araguan soldiers; no pickup.</note>
honduran troops on wednesday surrounded about 2,000 nicaraguan soldiers who entered the country chasing contra rebels, military intelligence sources told the associated press
they said the sandinista troops had crossed about 3 miles into the honduran border province of olancho, east of the capital of tegucigalpa, and had remained in the area for 24 hours
one official, who asked not to be identified, said the nicaraguan troops ``have been surrounded by our army ... and we are only waiting superior orders to enter into action.''
there really is tension and there is crisis, however we are acting with prudence but with strength in these affairs, and we hope that everything will stabilize in the next two days,'' he said
the honduran military went on alert, the sources said, speaking on condition of anonymity
foreign minister carlos lopez contreras said that honduras' president, jose azcono hoyo, contacted nicaraguan president daniel ortega to demand the withdrawal of the troops
ortega has not confirmed the presence of sandinista soldiers in honduras, and the nicaraguan foreign ministry has denied any incursion
in washington, presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater said the united states was dispatching 3,200 soldiers to southern honduras to carry out training exercises and to be ``a signal to the governments and the people of central america.'' he said they would not enter any combat zones
earlier, fitzwater said azcona had asked the united states for help in dealing with an invasion
intelligence officials said the sandinista troops apparently entered honduras to destroy a base camp of the u.s.-backed contras
we have done everything possible to avoid a confrontation that would drastically affect ... both countries,'' one source said
the superior council of the armed forces, the country's highest military body, was in session most of the day, the officials said. earlier wednesday, azcona met for about six hours behind closed doors to discuss the situation with top officials and the armed forces military chiefs
lopez contreras told reporters at a news conference that the military command was reviewing battle plans in case the sandinista forces continued occupying honduran territory
in managua, ortega refused to confirm or deny that nicaraguan troops had encroached on honduran soil
lopez contreras did not comment on reports that the reagan administration was dispatching u.s. troops to honduras
we don't want to create a national panic. we only ask our compatriots to have confidence in the government and in the armed forces,'' he said
the foreign minister added that azcona had demanded that ortega order the ``withdrawal of the troops because they are raising tensions and producing insecurity in the border.''
azcona also asked presidents of costa rica, el salvador and guatemala to appeal to ortega ``to abstain from bringing about aggressive military actions against honduras,'' lopez contreras said
the government and the army are ready to put into action the right of legitimate defense,'' the foreign minister declared
military intelligence sources said that at least 2,000 sandinista troops were inside honduras and that another 4,500 were near the border in the bocay region. denounces attack. picks up 7th graf pvs, the litle-known ...</note>
a man who fired guns and grenades from behind a tombstone killed three people and wounded 68 at an ira graveside service wednesday before enraged mourners cornered and beat him
young catholics rioted in the streets afterward
belfast police arrested the gunman at the end of a wild chase over graves in the milltown roman catholic cemetery during which he hurled grenades at the pursuing mourners and fired until his gun jammed. they identified him as michael stone, a protestant, but gave no other information about him
thousands of mourners screamed and dived for cover when shots shattered the silence of the cemetery in early afternoon, as the coffins of three unarmed ira members killed by british soldiers in gibraltar were being lowered into a single grave
a companion of the attacker fled in a van parked nearby, and police said they captured him in another part of the city. both men can be held without charge for seven days. police provided no details on the second man
mainstream protestant organizations disavowed the attack. the rev. ian paisley, leader of the protestant democratic unionist party, said all ``right-thinking protestants'' would condemn the attack ``without any ambivalence whatsoever.''
the british broadcasting corp. in belfast said an anonymous caller claimed responsibility wednesday night on behalf of the protestant action force, but gave no recognized codeword to establish authenticity of the claim
the little-known extremist group has claimed responsibility for numerous sectarian assassinations
catholic youths ignored government and church appeals after the attack and rioted through the evening. they burned hijacked buses and other vehicles and blocked streets with flaming barricades
palls of smoke hung over the catholic ghettos of west belfast
police said they fired plastic bullets at rioters who fired a shot and threw stones at a police patrol in the ardoyne district of west belfast. in londonderry, the province's second city, one car was hijacked and set ablaze in the catholic bogside district
police identified the three people killed wednesday as thomas charles mcerlean, 20; john murray, 26; and kevin brady, 30. all came from catholic areas of belfast
one of those wounded at the cemetery was in critical condition and four were in seriously wounded, said a spokesman for royal victoria hospital. most victims were shot or hit by shrapnel while scrambling for cover during the melee, which lasted about five minutes
sinn fein, the legal political wing of the outlawed irish republican army, blamed protestant paramilitary groups and accused britain of collusion
in london, aides of prime minister margaret thatcher said she was ``shocked and appalled.''
her government denounced the attack as ``insane and depraved.'' it appealed for calm, as did sinn fein, church leaders and the irish republic government in dublin
police, the british government and the ulster defense association, an umbrella organization of protestant vigilante groups, and the outlawed ulster freedom fighters denied involvement
the largely catholic ira is waging a guerrilla war to drive the british from protestant-dominated northern ireland, and protestant paramilitary groups have grown up to fight it
martin mcguinness, vice president of sinn fein, said: ``it's obvious it was an attack by loyalist (protestant) movements.''
sinn fein president gerry adams said: ``there was collusion between elements with the british crown forces, probably the royal ulster constabulary (provincial police).''
police said they deliberately kept away from the funeral because of assurances that the ira would not turn it into a paramilitary display
commandos in civilian clothes killed the guerrillas, mairead farrell, 31; sean savage, 24, and daniel mccann, 30, on march 6. british officials said the three were on a mission to bomb a military ceremony at the colony
mourners were lowering miss farrell's flag-draped coffin into the grave when a bearded man opened fire 15 yards away from behind a gravestone
young men yelled ``there he is! there he is!'' and the thickset gunman bolted
his cap fell off as he reloaded his pistol, and still dodging and weaving, he fired at the youths and hurled two grenades while taunting the pursuers to keep coming, witnesses said
i saw a young man throwing things from the back of the mourners,'' said the rev. alec reid, who was saying prayers beside the open grave. ``i thought they were stones, but it looks as if they were grenades. he was also firing shots into the crowd. there was absolute chaos.''
adams said the two men involved in the attack entered the cemetery carrying bags and cameras and were mistaken for journalists
the attack occurred after moderate andy tyrie was ousted as leader of the ulster defense association. hardliners accused him of weakening the armed fight against the ira
more than 2,600 people have been killed in northern ireland's sectarian violence since august 1969
a 9-foot-tall stained glass window that was headed for the trash heap after being found in a church garage here was made by louis tiffany, an expert says
there's no question in my mind whatsoever that it's tiffany,'' said dan oppenheimer, who owns a stained glass studio in memphis and is the author of numerous published articles about the craft. ``it's a glorious find.''
the window depicts the figure of jesus and features examples of drapery glass, a technique unique to tiffany about 1905 when the piece was made, oppenheimer said
he said the window's intricate leading and the plating of glass in multiple layers caused him to suspect right away it was by tiffany, who lived from 1848 to 1933 and was america's most famous stained glass artisan
the window, which measures 4{-by-9 feet, was found last week in a packing crate in a garage at grace st. luke's episcopal church, oppenheimer said
the maintenance people were going to throw it out. they thought it was a crate of broken glass,'' he said
oppenheimer said the value of the window has not been determined, but another tiffany window at the church was appraised 10 years ago at $132,000
in 1977, oppenheimer identified three of the church's windows as tiffany's and his findings were confirmed by sotheby parke bernet, the art auction house
oppenheimer said the crate with the newly discovered window apparently was stored in the church basement in the 1960s but was moved recently to the garage
he said the window is probably one of seven commissioned by the grace episcopal church, which merged with st. luke's church in 1944
tiffany co. records document at least three installations at grace church and sotheby's vouches for three others. all six windows are at grace st. luke's
oppenheimer said the newly discovered window is apparently the seventh work commissioned from tiffany
there are certain earmarks you look for, including the glass itself,'' he said. ``when you find all of them in one panel and it comes from a church that has a history of commissioning stained glass from tiffany, you just have to take a leap of faith and pronounce it tiffany.''
oklahoma officials say a vacation in their state is more than ok, and they hope a road campaign in south texas will persuade ``snowbirds'' to stop by on their way back north this spring
state and private tourism supporters opened up a two-day travel show in this lower rio grande valley city tuesday, hoping to reach the thousands of retired midwesterners and canadians who spend winter in the area
you have to try pretty hard coming to south texas not to go through oklahoma,'' oklahoma lt. gov. robert s. kerr iii, who traveled to mcallen
a tourism survey, however, showed that ``oklahoma doesn't have much of an image,'' kerr said
the state has launched a $1.2 million tourism promotion campaign, said eugene dilbeck, director of the oklahoma tourism and recreation department
state officials project they will get a five-fold return on their promotional investment
unlike miss americas of recent years, kaye lani rae rafko is not looking for movie contracts or modeling jobs after her reign ends
instead, she is anxious to return to her job as a registered nurse at a hospital in toledo, ohio, working with terminally ill cancer and aids patients
after another six months of this, i'll be ready to hang up the heels and the tiara and head back to work,'' she told nurses tuesday while visiting hospitals here
the 24-year-old former miss michigan is using her reign to maximize the image of her career, however, promoting the nursing profession rather than snipping ribbons to open new shopping malls or shaking hands at state fairs
the first months of miss rafko's reign, which began in september, were booked with appearances for the pageant's six sponsors, said pageant executive director leonard horn
but once people saw that kaye lani was a nurse, we cleared her schedule to make room for more public service appearances,'' said horn, in his first year as head of the pageant
this is what i want miss america to do more of anyway _ less commercial appearances and more living up to the role model that she really is.''
miss rafko has visited numerous hospitals and hospices and spoken to many nursing associations and medical groups. she has done a public service announcement for the nursing profession and appeared on the cover of a nursing trade journal
horn said that miss rafko's career fits in perfectly with public service appearances, acknowledging that future miss americas who sing or dance for a living might not have as much expertise in dealing with service-oriented groups
but we're going to emphasize the fact that any miss america has a beneficial interest when she speaks to any number of groups, whether it's the future farmers of america or the american cancer society,'' he said. ``you don't have to be a nurse to speak to those groups and make an impression. miss america can make a difference simply by promoting education.''
but this year, miss rafko is intent on hyping her career
a main focus of today's american people is health, and fortunately i know a lot about that,'' she said
at least one other miss america was inundated with special requests for speaking engagements. miss america 1984 vanessa williams, the first black miss america, addressed many black organizations until she relinquished her crown in a scandal over nude photographs
but most recent miss americas have followed a fairly routine round of promotional appearances
in the past few years, many miss americas have concentrated on entertainment careers. there's nothing wrong with that,'' miss rafko said. ``everybody has their own dreams and goals and that's what the miss america pageant is all about.''
saying a special investigation uncovered ``a massive network'' of corruption in city prisons, prosecutors tuesday announced charges against seven guards and two inmates and said there would be more
district attorney ronald castille said during a press conference outside the philadelphia detention center that arrests could reach into the hundreds before the 18-month investigation known as ``operation ferret'' is completed. officials said the investigation was prompted by widespread reports of corruption and complaints within the system
the investigation will potentially yield the largest number of arrests related to official misconduct by correctional officers in this country's history,'' castille said. he declined to give specifics
the city has five correctional institutions with between 8,500 and 9,000 inmates. the institutions are run by 1,700 employes, 1,400 of them are guards
the first charges stemmed from two incidents, an escape from laurel hall minimum security pre-release unit and an aggravated assault against a prisoner at a downtown ywca, another pre-release facility
those named in a grand jury presentment were charged with crimes ranging from aggravated assault to escape
in the laurel hill case, guard dennis tiest, prison cook stanley suder, and inmate kenneth lynch were charged with helping inmate john longendorfer escape last july. longendorfer was serving time for terroristic threats and indecent assault
in the other incident, which occurred feb. 16, six correctional officers were charged with an unprovoked assault on inmate william kennedy. kennedy was hospitalized for four days after the attack, castille said
castille said the beating was allegedly in retaliation for kennedy reporting a guard asleep at his assigned post
those charged were officers edward ricks, sammie rogers, clemon davis, christ taylor, charles favano and sgt. peter jones
