as he stripped and cleaned the ak-47 assault rifle on his desk, federal judge miguel angel izaguirre said he has good reason to try to stop latin american cocaine from reaching the streets of the united states
in 20 years, the youth that is taking all this cocaine will be running america and influencing latin america _ with the mentality of cokeheads,'' he said. ``north america's influence in this region is tremendous. so we latin americans have to try to ensure that american youth does not take cocaine.''
the 41-year-old izaguirre is the federal judge in this caribbean coastal town. he also is a weapons buff and student of military history
men, like arms, are proven on the field of battle,'' he said in an interview in his cramped and cluttered office that also contained an uzi submachine gun. ``and this is my field of battle.''
he has survived two attempts on his life, he said _ one with an incendiary bomb, the other a machine-gun attack on his home during which he returned fire with his soviet-made ak-47
i love the ak,'' he said. his arsenal of weapons, he explained, is ``to defend myself against the medellin cartel.''
the medellin cartel, named for the city in colombia where it is based, is believed responsible for more than 80 percent of the cocaine smuggled into the united states
they have tried to bribe me with money, women, airplanes and yachts,'' he said
leaning against the wall were five segments of hollowed out honduran redwood ostensibly intended for assembly into rustic doors. they are evidence from the biggest drug bust in u.s. history _ the confiscation in november of four tons of cocaine by u.s. federal agents in florida. the drug, shipped from the northern honduran coast, was hidden in the hollows
according to our information, the shipment was 8,000 kilos (almost 9 tons). so more than half of it got through,'' he said
u.s. authorities were greatly concerned when, over the past few years, honduras became an increasingly important transshipment point for colombian cocaine
izaguirre has been cited as a key man in joint u.s.-honduran efforts to reduce the flow
the judge said honduras, with its long and relatively unguarded coast and scores of clandestine air strips, provided the ideal midpoint for northbound shipments
when i came here in june 1987, i found a series of cases, all of which were being dismissed for lack of evidence. ... other judges had certain fears, some got sick, some left,'' he said. but within two months, he had handed down the first conviction and prison term for cocaine trafficking in honduran judicial history
he has convicted 10 others on drug charges, and has nearly three dozen suspected traffickers in jail awaiting judgment. two major traffickers based here, the colombian luis guerrero and the cuban-american rafael gonzalez, were extradited to the united states after being arraigned by izaguirre. they are both serving terms in u.s. prisons
izaguirre said he has given the maximum penalty under honduran law to all the drug traffickers he has convicted _ five years in prison and a 5,000 lempira ($2,500) fine. he complains, however, that the law is too lenient and would like to see penalties increased. he said the law provides the same penalties for cocaine trafficking as it does for marijuana trafficking
the judge _ divorced four times and the father of five children _ carries his weapons with him wherever he goes
if it befalls me to die in this post, then i'll die, without the slightest fear,'' he said
he keeps a .357 magnun revolver on his desk within easy reach
the judge insists he has no political ambitions, but maintains contact with a number of the country's political leaders
i tell them it is imperative that we verify the origin of the parties' funds. because if we don't, we're running the grave risk that the traffickers get their people elected to congress. then they reform the constitution in their favor, they gut the anti-narcotics law; they destroy us.''
though u.s. authorities have expressed concern that drug money has corrupted some officers in honduras' armed forces, izaguirre said the cooperation given him by the military has been ``total.''
he said his interest in the military began when he was 12 years old, with the reading of karl von clausewitz, the 19th century prussian general and writer of military strategy
i was two centimeters (about an inch) too short to get into the military academy,'' he said. ``but if i had, i'm sure i would have made general.''
the reporter rode on a bus with jewish settlers who were attacked by palestinians at night. the stone-throwing assault was one of the nightly incidents that are raising the level of tension in the occupied territories
rocks smashed through windows of bus no. 60, shattering the quiet murmur of hebrew as jewish settlers traveled home on a moonless night
israelis clutching frightened children in their arms ducked quickly into the aisle. several men leaped to their feet and fired shots through two broken windows. in the darkness, the voice of a young israeli boy rang out: ``get the arabs! get them!''
stop the bus!'' shouted another angry israeli woman
the driver, an israeli arab, hesitated and then pulled to a stop. three israelis ran from the front of the bus, firing shots, and two others went out the back door. but it was too late. the palestinian stone-throwers had disappeared into the night
in a 45-minute period monday night, arab attackers heaved stones through windows of three buses and five cars near this arab village on the outskirts of the settlement of kiryat arba, about 20 miles south of jerusalem. no arabs were caught
three israelis were treated for cuts at a nearby hospital, but there were no serious injuries
jewish settlers say, however, the assaults show this biblical land is increasingly becoming a battlefield and the arabs see them as the target
make no mistake. this is war,'' said one woman aboard bus no. 60, social worker rachel klein, 50
about 50 settlers, including a dozen children and three infants, were aboard when the bus was attacked about 9 p.m. most of the women wore headscarves and the men wore knitted yarmulkes, the head caps of observant jews
the red-and-white bus, marked with three hebrew letters denoting the eged civilian bus cooperative, was on a scheduled hour-long run from jerusalem to the west bank town of hebron. the trip on the winding narrow road took the settlers past several arab villages and refugee camps, including the city of bethlehem and the dheishe refugee camp, which is blocked by a 10-foot-high wire fence to prevent stone-throwing
settlers retaliated before dawn tuesday, setting fire to three arab-owned cars in halhoul and breaking the windows of several others, said yossi dayan, president of a newly formed kiryat arba security committee
dayan said a rising number of settlers who previously were inactive are being driven to fight back by the nearly nightly attacks, even if it means breaking israeli law
the latest leaflet signed by the palestine liberation organization and distributed in the west bank and gaza ordered arabs to step up their fight against ``the occupation (and) its settlers.''
arabs have not only thrown stones and firebombs at israeli vehicles, but also defiantly hang the outlawed palestinian banner from utility poles along roads used by settlers. the nationalist symbol acts like a red flag for many israelis
they don't have the same rights in this country as we do,'' said the london-born mrs. klein, who has lived 13 years in kiryat arba. ``how can we let them make us cower in fear on our own buses in our own country?
our government is diddling and afraid to take strong action,'' she said. ``but the arabs only understand a clear message. we should give them one.''
some settlers already have tried to send a message, damaging arab-owned cars, carrying out patrols along west bank roads and sometimes firing shots at palestinians
settlers are blamed for killing seven of the arabs who have died during the 14-week uprising
but, dayan warned: ``if the army doesn't move to stop acts of violence against us, we are going to take far more serious steps. we are discussing setting up some kind of _ i don't want to call them militias _ but some kind of patrols.''
the army maintains an around-the-clock presence in the west bank. but fewer soldiers are in evidence now than a month ago, and the settlers complain that even when troops are on the scene, they are prevented by defense ministry policy from adequately retaliating against the arabs
many people in kiryat arba prefer if the army doesn't come, because then they can respond in their own way,'' said baruch goldstein, a brooklyn, n.y.-born settler and also a member of the security committee
kiryat arba is breaking into two groups. one is of people who are frightened, tend to ride the buses less and will eventually leave,'' goldstein said. ``the other, larger group will stay and, sooner or later, take its own action to stop the violence.''
goldstein, a 31-year-old doctor who specializes in trauma cases, said about four times as many vehicles traveling between jerusalem and kiryat arba were stoned in the first three months of this year, compared with the first three months of 1987
on sunday, a 12-year-old girl from kiryat arba was struck on the face by a stone as she traveled on a bus to school. her nose was broken, her teeth chipped and her upper lip cut, said goldstein, who treated her
people know it is against the law for them to act against the arabs and they will be arrested if they do,'' he said. ``but as the violence against us increases, people are deciding they don't have too much to lose. they are realizing coexistence with the arabs is an impossibility.''
terry anderson, chief middle east correspondent for the associated press, today began his fourth year as a hostage in lebanon. here is a chronology of the 40-year-old american journalist's captivity:
march 16 _ anderson is abducted on beirut street. telephone caller says islamic jihad kidnapped him as part of ``continuing operations against america and its agents.''
may 16 _ first photo of anderson in captivity is released. islamic jihad warns of ``catastrophic consequences'' if kuwait does not free alleged terrorists
sept. 9 _ rev. benjamin weir is freed after 16 months in captivity. president reagan says he ``will not be satisified'' until remaining americans also are released
oct. 29 _ beirut television stations broadcast videotaped birthday message from relatives and friends to anderson, two days after he turned 38
nov. 8 _ in open letter, anderson and three other captive americans call on reagan to ``have mercy'' and negotiate with kidnappers
feb. 15 _ anderson's father, glenn r. anderson, dies of cancer at age 69
june 7 - anderson's 46-year-old brother, glenn richard jr., dies of cancer four days after making a videotape from his bed appealing to terry's captors
july 26 _ rev. lawrence martin jenco, freed after almost 19 months as hostage, says he was held with anderson and two other hostages for a year
oct. 3 _ in videotaped appeal, anderson and david jacobsen call on reagan administration to work as hard for their release as it did in winning release of journalist nicholas daniloff in moscow
oct. 31 _ beirut tv stations broadcast videotape showing anderson's 16-month-old daughter, whom he has never seen
nov. 2 _ jacobsen, freed after 17 months in captivity, says hostages ``are in hell.''
nov. 15 _ islamic jihad releases new picture of anderson
dec. 28 _ fourth picture of anderson is sent by captors to western news agency in beirut
jan. 16 _ islamic jihad distributes another picture of anderson
june 7 _ anderson's daughter is shown on lebanese tv on her second birthday saying, ``our hearts are broken. where is daddy?''
aug. 2 _ sixth photo of anderson is released by islamic jihad
oct. 21 _ islamic jihad releases another photo of anderson
oct. 27 _ as anderson turns 40, friends and family gather at jefferson memorial in washington and ap staff in beirut goes to his vacant office to mark day
nov. 26 _ jacobsen says he learned from sources in government and middle east that anderson being held again in chains and blindfolded 24 hours a day
dec. 10 _ anderson passes his 1,000th day as hostage in lebanon
dec. 14 _ london newspaper reports soviet intelligence officials told american officials at summit that foreign hostages were undergoing brutal treatment and drugging
dec. 24 _ anderson's captors release a videotape of anderson. appearing to read from a prepared text, anderson criticizes the reagan administration for failing to secure his and fellow prisoners' freedom and warns ``there's a limit to how long we can last.''
dec. 30 _ london newspaper reports cia analysis of videotape indicates anderson may be held in basta prison in west beirut, along with kidnapped anglican church envoy terry waite
march 10 _ anderson's sister peggy say and former hostage jenco accuse presidential candidates of avoiding question of american hostages in lebanon
march 16 _ anderson begins his fourth year as a hostage
here is a chronology of events in the panamanian crisis:

thursday, feb. 25 _ panama's president, eric arturo delvalle, announces he is dismissing gen. manuel antonio noriega, indicted on u.s. drug charges, as defense chief and replacing him with col. marcos justines, chief of staff. justines refuses job
friday, feb. 26 _ noriega-dominated national assembly votes to oust delvalle. education minister manuel solis palma named new head of state. noriega opponents call for general strike in protest. diplomats and economists say customers begin run on domestically owned banks
saturday, feb. 27 _ delvalle goes into hiding in panama, defying noriega's order that he leave country
sunday, feb. 28 _ organization of american states sidesteps panama issue by refusing to choose between two men claiming to be panama's ambassador
monday, feb. 29 _ general strike begins with mixed participation. panama's ambassador to united states, juan b. sosa, refuses to relinquish post to noriega designee
tuesday, march 1 _ general strike gains support in second day. locally owned banks close. international banks limit withdrawals. plainclothesmen wreck only remaining opposition radio station in panama city. security forces crack down on protests amid scattered violence. u.s. government officially denounces panama as deficient in fighting drug trade. delvalle outlines plans to freeze panamanian assets outside country. united states, still recognizing delvalle as president, supports action
wednesday, march 2 _ doctors join businesses in general strike. u.s. officials confirm they will ask u.s. banks to freeze panamanian government assets. more violence reported in panama city
thursday, march 3 _ organizers end general strike as support fades, saying money crunch will keep pressure on government. president reagan indicates he believes noriega must go. congressmen propose trade, air travel and currency embargo on noriega regime. u.s. federal courts temporarily block withdrawal of panama funds from u.s. banks
friday, march 4 _ national bank of panama says it cannot meet banks' cash demands because of freeze on bank deposits. international banks fearing a run on deposits close their doors. local banks remain closed
sunday, march 7 _ alliance of business and civic groups opposed to noriega calls for ``government of national reconciliation'' and ``authentic democracy.'' retired people unable to cash pension checks rally in streets
monday, march 8 _ riot police disperse demonstrators in panama with tear gas and birdshot
tuesday, march 9 _ government says banks can reopen but no one can cash checks or withdraw funds. few banks respond. two prominent panamanian diplomats break with noriega
wednesday, march 10 _ the u.s. house votes 367-2 for a non-binding resolution calling on reagan to ``consider seriously'' additional economic and political sanctions. libyan television reports noriega asked for libyan backing against ``american military aggression and economic threats.''
friday, march 11 _ reagan imposes economic sanctions, including eliminating trade preferences for panama and withholding panama canal fees from the noriega government by placing them in escrow. noriega government meets army payroll. miami federal judge grounds air panama, freezing its assets while he decides which panamanian officials should control the airline. spain tells ukkknited states it would accept noriega if he asked for asylum
saturday, march 12 _ panamanian cabinet meets in emergency session
sunday, march 13 _ solis palma calls cabinet into another emergency session
monday, march 14 _ public employees stage work stoppages and riot after government is unable to pay wages. riot police use tear gas and truncheons to disperse hundreds blocking traffic. reagan administration hints it may reassess demand for noriega's extradition in order to allow him to step down. u.s. sends 100 additional military personnel to beef up security around canal
tuesday, march 15 _ reagan says u.s. wants noriega ``out of there.'' at least a dozen are injured in demonstrations as civil servants take to streets to demand paychecks. panama orders u.s. embassy official to leave country, but u.s. rejects demand. government says it will make partial payments to public employees. employee union leaders reject plan and demand full salaries. bgng ``i am bumping...</note>
pat robertson met with the republican national chairman tuesday to discuss his faltering presidential bid and said later he is ``laying the foundation'' for 1992
robertson suffered another disappointing showing in illinois, collecting just 7 percent in tuesday's primary. though he insisted he will remain in the 1988 race, robertson appeared to be looking ahead
i am laying the foundation now and definitely talking to people about 1992. i will play a major role in the gop,'' he told reporters at his headquarters in chesapeake, va
robertson also talked with reporters after his meeting with republican national committee chairman frank fahrenkopf. he said he is approaching the $27 million limit that candidates are allowed to spend in the primary season. he said he is laying off staff and will be forced to discontinue the big spending that has characterized his campaign so far
i am bumping up against the limit. ... i have enough money to keep in the race through california and the convention. but i don't have enough to do telemarketing and television,'' he said. ``my own personal travel will continue but as far as a full-blown media campaign i can't afford that any more.''
election law restricts spending by presidential candidates who accept federal matching funds for their campaigns
the meeting with fahrenkopf took place at robertson's request, a party spokeswoman said
robertson said, ``we were discussing arrangements for the convention in august and also discussing ways where i could help republicans gain control of key state legislatures, for instance the legislature of california, so that we could achieve redistricting of a fair basis in the early 1990s and use that as a basis to gain control of the house of representatives and the united states senate for the republican party.''
rnc spokeswoman kathryn murray confirmed the meeting had focused on those two topics at the suggestion of robertson
she said robertson expressed a wish to campaign on behalf of republican candidates at all levels. fahrenkopf ``welcomes his support,'' she said
as long as he can continue to bring new voters into the republican party, that's a positive,'' murray said
robertson also met tuesday with israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir who was in washington for talks with u.s. officials
robertson said he and shamir were ``old friends.'' the christian broadcasting network that robertson founded broadcasts in the middle east
robertson endorsed shamir's stance against giving up israeli occupied lands to the palestinian people until after ``a period of palestinian self rule.''
any surrender of territory in the near future would seriously imperil the ability of israel to defend itself,'' he said, adding that he supports negotiations among the israelis, jordan and palestinians
on politics, he was pressed to explain how he could continue campaigning without spending money. robertson said that in illinois he spent only $20,000
i have tens of thousands of volunteers who are working ceaselessly night and day because they care for a cause, they care for principle,'' he said. ``its a movement to bring about conservative principles in america.''
a viewer never knows exactly what to expect from the lar lubovitch dance company but it's almost certain to be interesting. tuesday's opening night of a two-week season presented two very different premieres and a masterpiece from 1986, ``concerto six twenty-two.''
the opening, which attracted a formal-dress audience to the city center, marks the 20th anniversary of lubovitch's founding his own modern dance company to dance his choreography
musette,'' the premiere ending the evening, is set to poulenc's ``concerto for two pianos.'' lubovitch has six couples follow the music's moods, which often change. he doesn't repeat himself
early in the dance, though in bare feet, the dancers assume the leg and foot positions of ballet. lubovitch has, as he usually does, a time for humor. one man's solo ends, to his apparent surprise, when two men pick him up and carry him off stage. at one time, half the dancers stand still, while the rest dance in and out among them like skiers going around poles
when the music becomes lyrical, the men lift and carry the women so their colorful tulle skirts look like big candy canes going by. there is a section that looks like court dancing and one that looks like trained dancers' variations of america's folk version of court dancing, the reel. a romantic section of music has two men picking up one woman between them and gracefully swinging her. ``musette'' ends most satisfactorily with a courtly bow
of my soul,'' to a bach ``cantata,'' was danced at avery fisher hall last summer at the mostly mozart festival. the company considers this the ``official'' premiere. lubovitch incorporated some american sign language into the arm movements. it's an arresting idea which doesn't come off brilliantly
some of the arm movements translate what four people are singing in the orchestra pit. lubovitch has made them flow in and out of expansive arm reaches. that works but the whole thing doesn't seem to arise from the music like the evening's other two dances
concerto six twenty-two,'' premiered at carnegie hall in 1986, is danced to mozart's ``concerto for clarinet and orchestra.'' the dancers, wearing white, in the first and third movements, looked inspired and fresh. the middle movement, danced by sylvain lafortune and rick michalek, remains one of dance's most moving and dignified duets. in such simple things as one man leaning back against the other's hand, it shows human support and trust
the solisti new york chamber orchestra, conducted by ransom wilson, did a beautiful job with the mozart and bach music. the poulenc music was a recording
michael j. fox's acrobatic quest for a soft drink to satisfy an attractive apartment neighbor won three awards in an international competition for television and radio commercials
the tv commercial for diet pepsi was named sweepstakes winner, world's best live action 60-second english-language commercial and best humorous commercial at tuesday's 28th international broadcasting awards dinner
a series of three commercials for wine world was the radio sweepstakes winner. it also won the series trophy
the annual competition sponsored by the hollywood radio and television society attracted more than 5,000 entries from 60 countries
radio personalities casey kasem and gary owens were masters of ceremonies at the black-tie presentations at the century plaza hotel attended by an estimated 1,500 advertising and broadcasting executives from around the world
the society also honored bea arthur, rue mcclanahan, betty white and estelle getty of nbc's ``the golden girls'' as international ``women of the year.''
actress lillian gish has donated $10,000 to bowling green state university to enhance the film theater that bears her family's name
the gift is designated for the dorothy and lillian gish film theater endowment fund, which supports activities in the building that commemorates the gish sisters' contributions to the performing arts
the theater, dedicated in 1976, showcases the art of film by offering regular showings of classic movies
the theater is undergoing a $250,000 renovation of its seating, projection facilities, and gallery. the renovation is scheduled to be completed in may 1989
ms. gish also donated $10,000 in 1986 to advance and support the study of film at bowling green
ms. gish, 91, was born in ohio and made her acting debut at the turn of the century in the village of rising sun, about 20 miles from bowling green
the tv personality who calls himself the amazing kreskin looked into the future of entertainment and predicted that dinner theaters next season will offer more than just musicals
future dinner theaters will resemble the supper clubs of the 1940s with plush decor, outstanding meals and a wider variety of entertainment, kreskin said tuesday in a speech to the annual convention of the national dinner theater association
because television is offering a wider choice of entertainment, ``to survive in the next decade, you must offer more than the same old buffet and musical,'' he said
he said concerts, discos and festivals also have changed theatergoers' tastes. ``they want to participate in the entertainment rather than just sitting and watching a production.''
while kreskin made it clear he was available for such engagements, richard aikins, theatrical producer and chairman of the convention, said he thought kreskin's view was valid
kreskin, a 53-year-old self-styled ``mentalist,'' has performed extrasensory feats on his own syndicated tv show and in dozens of talk-show appearances
musicians from 10 western countries including david bowie, jennifer rush and irish rockers u-2 have agreed to perform along with soviet musicians in benefit concerts next month to fight drug addiction
the official novosti press agency said other foreign performers scheduled are level 42, supertramp, foreigner, tangerine dream and bon jovi
participating soviet groups are aquarium, bravo, brigade s, black coffee and others whose music ranges from heavy metal to traditional rock 'n' roll, novosti said
the press agency did not give a date, but said the three six-hour concerts will be held in late april at the 30,000-seat olympic stadium in moscow
sources close to the organizers said the concerts were postponed from this month because of bureaucratic red tape
the sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said former beatles george harrison and paul mccartney, as well as julian lennon, son of the late beatle john lennon, had been invited. it was unclear whether they would participate
the press agency said revenue from tickets costing about $16 each will be donated to the united nations fund for the struggle against drug addiction and to the soviet toxicology research center
laryngitis caused nancy reagan to cancel a trip today to a nashville, tenn., school that a snowstorm had prevented her from visiting once before
she can't talk. it's a bad case of laryngitis,'' spokeswoman wendy weber toler said tuesday. ``she started losing her voice last night.''
mrs. toler said the white house physician, dr. john hutton, had advised the first lady not to travel
it was the second time the first lady had been forced to cancel the visit to warner elementary school and a drug and alcohol abuse prevention program; a snowstorm had prevented mrs. reagan from visiting the city the first time
jeb stuart magruder, a former white house aide who served seven months in prison for his role in the watergate coverup, says he's well prepared to head the mayor's commission on values and ethics
i talk about these issues to the kiwanises and the rotaries around here, as well as deal with these issues through the church, so i would hope that my background would be helpful,'' magruder said tuesday
after his release from prison in 1976, magruder entered a seminary and was ordained in 1981 as a presbyterian minister
mayor dana rinehart appointed the 15-member volunteer commission, on which he also will sit, as part of the city's response to an incident last year in which passersby made off with bags of money that fell from an armored truck on a freeway
magruder, president nixon's deputy director of communications at the time of the 1972 watergate break-in, pleaded guilty to perjury and conspiracy to obstruct justice
the national aeronautics and space administration says the ozone shield is in fact thinning measurably due to chlorofluorocarbon compounds
a nasa panel said the shield thinned out by about 2.3 percent over a 17-year period ending in 1986 in the temperate zones of the northern hemisphere. the panel said the shield thinned by 0.5 percent to 1.8 percent over nine years ending in 1987 in the tropics and part of the temperate zones of both hemispheres
this means increased skin cancer around the world, largely unknown effects on fish and wildlife and increased pressure from environmentalists to go beyond the treaty approved by the senate to cut emissions of ozone-destroying chemicals
chlorofluorocarbons are used as refrigeration fluids, cleaning solvents and plastic foam blowing agents
at this point there is no other culprit to blame,'' panel member sherwood rowland of the university of california at irvine said tuesday. ``we have taken out all the natural phenomena that are believed to affect ozone.''
a massive 17-month effort by more than 100 scientists convened by nasa went through practically every ozone observation made in recent years, trying to correct for instrument errors and drift and to remove the effects of the 11-year solar cycle and the biennial oscillation of high-altitude winds
since 1985, there have been several reports of ozone decline worldwide in addition to the well-established ozone ``hole'' over antarctica _ a 50 percent decline in springtime, followed by recovery
environmental protection agency administrator lee m. thomas said the report ``will certainly be a part of the 1990 assessment'' called for in the treaty. ``the crucial first step, however, is speedy international ratification,'' he said
but sen. robert t. stafford, r-vt., said, ``the nations of the world should immediately reconvene to consider amendments'' to the treaty, and the united states should resume its advocacy of a complete ban. ``we've got to make deeper cuts in cfc emissions,'' said sen. max baucus, d-mont
kevin fay, executive director of the alliance for a responsible cfc policy, a group of producers and users, said the 1990 schedule ``is the framework to be followed'' because unilateral reductions won't help
the senate voted 83-0 on monday to approve a 31-nation treaty calling for 50 percent cuts by 1998 in production of chlorofluorocarbons
noting that cfc compounds over antarctica now were released at ground level about 10 years ago and that the antarctic hole could last 100 years even if the treaty is followed, rowland said, ``there's plenty of reason to re-open the ... protocol.''
ozone at high altitudes makes life on earth possible by blocking the harmful ultraviolet rays. the epa estimates that each percent decrease in ozone means a 4.8 percent to 7.5 percent increase in non-melanoma skin cancer and a 0.8 percent to 1.5 percent increase in the more deadly melanoma form
considering the incidence and death rates of both forms, this would mean 280 to 455 deaths per year on top of the 10,000 from skin cancer in the united states, or 640 to 1,050 deaths if a 2.3 percent decline were uniform across the country
the 2.3 percent is not uniform. nasa presented its 1969-1986 northern hemisphere estimates from ground obserations as averages over each of three bands: 30 degrees latitude (about the latitude of houston, cairo and shanghai) to 40 degrees (philadelphia and madrid), down 1.7 percent; 40 degrees to 53 degrees (edmonton, alberta, and berlin), down 3.0 percent; and 53 degrees to 64 degrees (fairbanks, alaska, and reykjavik, iceland), down 2.3 percent
no single estimate was presented for all three bands, but rowland said the average, a 2.3 percent decline, would be close. all the estimates have substantial uncertainty about them. each of the three band estimates has a 68 percent chance of being plus or minus 1.0 percentage point, at most, away from the number given
corrected satellite data show an ozone decline of about 2.5 percent in the band running from 53 degrees north to 53 degrees south from 1978 through 1987. but 0.7 percent to 2.0 percent of this results from the solar cycle, the report said
officials in natchez say they'll reluctantly permit a white supremacist protest march against a 14-week-old black boycott of white-owned businesses in exchange for dismissal of a lawsuit against the city
u.s. district judge william h. barbour announced the settlement tuesday in dismissing a lawsuit filed by jackson attorney richard barrett on behalf of the nationalist movement. the judge also ordered natchez to pay barrett's attorneys' fees in the case
the law of the land will prevail in natchez, not the law of the jungle,'' barrett said after the announcement. ``this is a victory for the red-white-and-blue people _ meaning red-neck, white skin and blue collar.''
boycott leaders are seeking, among other things, a black school superintendent and more black teachers in the adams county-natchez school district
i'm opposed to richard barrett and his movement, but as mayor of the city, you have to abide the by the laws and the courts. we just hope nobody will show up for it,'' natchez mayor tony byrne said of the march
byrne said officials decided to settle after the county board of supervisors said the city couldn't ban the rally scheduled for the county courthouse grounds saturday afternoon, the day barrett was seeking permission for the parade through city streets
barrett had contended in his lawsuit that the city was infringing on the group's constitutional rights by retroactively applying a parade ordinance adopted march 8
we'll see to it that mr. barrett comes to town, has his parade and rally, and leaves town as expeditiously as possible,'' byrne said
two years ago the reagan administration proposed selling its overseas private investment corp. to private interests. now it's urging that the government agency be allowed to buy shares in private companies
craig a. nalen, opic's president for more than seven years, told the house foreign affairs subcommittee on economic policy on tuesday that the agency wants to begin a pilot project that would put $10 million over the next five years into black africa and the caribbean
the money would be spent to take up as much as 30 percent of the shares in new american companies there. government bodies in japan, west germany, britain and the netherlands already help their private investors in this way
opic's main job is to sell insurance to american investors overseas, against what are called political risks: war, rebellion, civil strife, confiscation and official freezing of assets. it is one of the few federal agencies that makes money: $300 million over the past three years, nalen said
opic's strong financial position makes the agency a good candidate for privatization,'' said the president's budget proposal for the year that ended last september
there was considerable opposition to the idea, both inside and outside the agency, on grounds the insurance was sought precisely because it had the power of the u.s. government behind it. after some study, the president's office of management and budget decided that opic had better stay part of the government
the privatization plan was quietly dropped
opic also makes loans to u.s. companies setting up business in other countries _ $202.8 million worth of loans and guarantees last year
nalen said tuesday that buying shares as well as making loans would help small projects get started
it would allow these heavily indebted countries to borrow less for industrial development, he said. many are unable to borrow because banks have cut back their lending he said
nalen also argued that direct investment by his agency would help u.s. investors
opic's major ... counterparts all have the ability to invest equity, thus providing their clients with a significant advantage over their u.s. competitors,'' he said in his prepared testimony
if your idea of a good tax form is one with short sentences and short words, take heart
a group of students, venturing where government has been less than successful, vows to come up with a series of tax forms that are understandable even to the high school dropout. and the students say they will finish the job within less than six months
i don't say it's a simple task, but we're going to try,'' professor nicholas j. creme, director of the center for taxation studies in the akron university school of law, said in an interview tuesday
he said he wants the students to work with the internal revenue service on the project, although the irs has not yet embraced the idea
the students' interest was piqued by what they learned while representing low-income taxpayers in audits, collections and other actions involving the irs. they learned that on the average, only 11 percent of taxpayers with less than a high school education have the reading skills to comprehend instructions for filling out forms 1040 or 1040ez
the students concluded that if taxpayers can't understand how to comply with the tax laws, they probably won't. or as creme, a tax lawyer for 20 years, put it, ``when people can't figure out the right answer, they will take the answer that gives them the best break.''
high school dropouts aren't the only people having trouble with this year's tax forms. even tax professionals shake their heads at some instructions prompted by the more complex provisions of the 1986 tax overhaul, which was initially billed as tax ``simplification.''
this sentence is part of the form 1040 instructions for determining how much interest is deductible:
if all of your mortgage debt on your principal home was borrowed before august 17, 1986, (and you have not borrowed any new amounts on that debt); or, at all times in 1987, the total of your mortgage debts was less than or equal to what you paid for the home plus improvements (such as adding a room), the mortgage interest you paid is fully deductible on line 9a or 9b, whichever applies.''
creme says that about 20 students training in law, business or education will develop a more-readable w-4 withholding form; w-2 yearend wages-earned statement; 1099 interest-earned form and the basic 1040, 1040a and 1040ez forms
we're not saying we could bring it down to a second-grade level, but we certainly can make it simpler,'' he said. ``if you simplify the forms, people will be a lot less hostile toward the irs. and you'll raise a lot more revenue.''
creme and some of the students volunteered for the project monday while testifying before a senate finance subcommittee about irs penalties. the chairman, sen. david pryor, d-ark., welcomed the idea
creme and professor james w. childs, director of the university's tax clinic, said it is not difficult to figure out why the tax forms and instructions are difficult. ``the average sentence length of these publications exceeds 25 words,'' they said in written testimony. ``one-third of the words in these publications are multisyllabled words.''
creme's solution: ``by reducing the number of syllables and the number of words in a sentence we can make the forms and instructions significantly more readable. and we want to change how the forms look _ change the spacing so things don't look so crammed in.''
irs forms are developed in consultation with lawyers, accountants and educators. in changing its forms last year to reflect the new tax law, the irs hired a consultant and even went to some shopping malls for instant reaction from random taxpayers
as for the students' project, irs spokesman steve pyrek says, ``one-syllable words are nice, but what do you do about `dependents'?''
the irs estimates nearly half of taxpayers will pay professionals to fill out their returns this year
senate approval of a bill requiring the white house to tell congress about all covert actions within 48 hours after the operations start marks a major step toward avoiding another iran-contra affair, say the measure's sponsors
this will help immeasurably toward preventing the kind of mistakes that were made'' in the iran-contra affair, sen. david boren, d-okla., chairman of the intelligence committee, said late tuesday after the senate voted 71-19 in favor of the bill
the measure now goes to the house, where ``overwhelming approval'' is likely, according to both boren and sen. william cohen, r-maine, vice chairman of the intelligence committee
the house intelligence committee is considering a similar bill, but no date has been set for a vote by the panel or for floor action
president reagan has threatened to veto the legislation as an unconstitutional restriction on his ability to conduct foreign policy
but boren said, ``that kind of threat has been heard before and it hasn't come true.''
cohen noted that the 71 votes are four more than the two-thirds which would be required to override any presidential veto. ``and that 71 total is without some of our supporters here,'' he said
the bill arises from the iran-contra affair, when u.s. weapons were secretly sold to iran and some of the profits were diverted to the contra guerrillas in nicaragua
reagan withheld notification about the arms sales from congress for 10 months
current laws require only that the white house give congess ``timely notice'' about covert actions, but they do not define the term. the intelligence committees had been operating on the assumption that the phrase meant only a brief delay in notification
this bill clarifies what we thought was the procedure all along,'' cohen said. ``we believed timely meant a couple of days and we were surprised to find out that the administration was working under a different definition.''
the measure doesn't give congress a veto over covert operations, cohen noted
there's no piece of legislation that can weave a web of security around good or bad judgment,'' said cohen. ``i can't say for sure this would have prevented iran-contra, but it would mean that we can give the president the benefit of our advice. the function we serve is to have a second opinion outside the administration.''
boren said if the bill eventually becomes law, ``it will help'' prevent future problems because ``it clears up so many ambiguities that are in the existing law. it makes the notification process so much more clear.''
but he warned that ``you can never prevent absolutely any future iran-contras, anymore than a law against bank robberies will prevent bank robberies.''
in the wake of the iran-contra affair, cohen noted, reagan has promised to tell capitol hill about all future covert actions and has moved administratively to make many of the changes proposed in the law. ``this only writes into law what the president has already said he would do,'' cohen said
the bill also requires written ``findings,'' which are the presidential orders authorizing covert operations. some actions in the iran-contra affair were done under an oral finding which was open to misinterpretation, boren said
before passing the bill, the senate rejected, 60-32, a proposal by sen. john chafee, r-r.i., to allow notification within 10 days, instead of two days
chafee said the time period was long enough to permit actions, such as the rescue of hostages, in which lives might be endangered by leaks of information, but short enough to discover situations such as the iranian arms sale
earlier, the chamber voted 73-18 to limit debate. that was 13 more votes than needed to invoke cloture and block an attempt by conservative republicans to pass the measure
one opponent, sen. malcolm wallop, r-wyo., said: ``this bill is badly drafted, badly conceived, and the worst of its conceptions is that somehow you can legislate intelligence ... it's hard for me to believe that one piece of legislation can obviate stupid activity.''
defense secretary frank c. carlucci testified last week that reagan believed the bill was an unconstitutional restriction on presidential authority and would veto it. carlucci took over as reagan's national security adviser in the wake of the iran-contra affair
here is the 71-19 roll call tuesday by which the senate passed a bill requiring the president to tell congress about all covert actions within 48 hours after they begin
there were 71 votes ``for'' and 19 votes ``against.''
