federal reserve chairman alan greenspan easily fielded one complicated economic question after another from a congressional committee, but then one request stopped him cold
who was on the fed committee that charts national monetary policy when it held its most recent meeting last month?
that question, posed on tuesday by sen. john melcher, d-mont., a member of the house-senate joint economic committee, stumped greenspan and the six aides seated behind him, at least temporarily
at issue was a feb. 9-10 meeting of the 12-member federal open market committee, or fomc. it is made up of the seven members of the federal reserve board and five regional fed bank presidents
greenspan, shuffling papers and conferring with his aides, made a halting effort to name the five fed bank presidents on the panel in february _ and finally got four of the five right
you're a little bit fuzzy on just who voted in february,'' melcher said
i'm not fuzzy on who voted. i know who was on the committee. what i don't remember is which ones of them were on at that particular time,'' said greenspan, a former new york business consultant who took command of the fed last august
the committee meets every few months to chart the nation's monetary policy
melcher contends that the fed committee is unconstitutional because it holds vast power over u.s. economic policy even though five of its members are not appointed by the president nor do they undergo senate confirmation. so far, federal courts have not agreed with melcher's assertion
at that february meeting, the committee voted to widen the target range for the growth of the nation's money supply in 1988 _ an action that could bear on inflation and interest rates
greenspan told the committee he was confused because committee membership is rotated among the presidents of the 12 fed banks _ and ``we're in the process now of changing.''
joseph coyne, a spokesman for the fed, said the rotation of members onto the committee took place on march 1 _ after the last meeting
for the record, the five bank president members of the committee in february were gerald e. corrigan, president of the new york fed, a non-rotating position; edward g. boehne, philadelphia; robert h. boykin, dallas; silas keehn, chicago; and gary h. stern, minnesota
the one greenspan missed? stern. instead, he named st. louis fed chairman thomas c. melzer, not a voting member of the committee then or now. savings</head>
the reagan administration and democrats led by sen. edward m. kennedy agree that tax breaks must be provided to encourage parents to save early for college tuition costs that continue to skyrocket
rising costs threaten to put a college degree out of reach of average families'' as well as the poor, kennedy told the senate finance committee on tuesday. ``we must find a safe, convenient and simple way to help them meet tuition bills.''
the massachusetts democrat has drafted a plan that would encourage tuition savings by making interest on u.s. savings bonds tax free if the bonds are used for college tuition
families earning under $75,000 a year would receive the full benefit of the legislation. the tax break would be reduced for families earning more, decreasing until it is completely phased out at the $150,000 income level
there is an excellent chance that many families who are not saving now will do so, using this safe, convenient plan,'' kennedy said
assistant treasury secretary o. donaldson chapoton said the reagan administration's college savings bond proposal is similar to the kennedy bill, providing tax exemptions on interest for parents who save for college
but the eligibility is lower under the president's plan, which calls for a phasing out of the tax break for families earning between $60,000 and $80,000
the administration's proposal also would allow tax-free interest on savings bonds used to cover part of a student's living expenses in addition to tuition, books and other fees
chapoton said the administration version eventually would cost about $1 billion in lost revenues, but said the incentives are ``urgently needed'' as college tuition continues to skyrocket
we're coming perilously close to a time when only the wealthy can attend the university of their choice,'' said sen. robert t. stafford, r-vt., who is backing the kennedy bill
kennedy said his measure, also supported by sen. claiborne pell, d-r.i., is expected to cost about $300 million five years into the program. but he said because the government saves $60 million for every $1 billion sold in savings bonds, the plan eventually could be self-financing
chapoton warned that by the year 2007, the total cost of attending a four-year private university will be $200,000. today, it is more than $50,000, nearly doubling since 1980, he said. federal grants and loans, meanwhile, have stayed about the same
if we're going to continue to compete, we have to have a competitive education,'' said finance chairman lloyd bentsen, d-texas, who is supporting the kennedy bill
chapoton said the administration opposes legislation that would restore the interest payment deduction on college loans
in a related matter, officials from michigan complained about a proposal by the internal revenue service to tax michigan's guaranteed college tuition trust
wyoming, maine, florida, indiana and tennessee have adopted guaranteed tuition programs similar to michigan's
the michigan trust allows payment into a state fund in return for guaranteed tuition
the irs ruled that people buying trust contracts on behalf of children would have no additional tax liability, but that the trust itself is subject to federal taxes, michigan gov. james blanchard said tuesday at a washington news conference
federal taxes could add up to 20 percent to the cost of a trust contract, if the trust were to invest fully in taxable bonds, michigan treasurer robert bowman said
irs spokeswoman johnell hunter declined to comment on its ruling, or even to acknowledge a ruling had been made
we do not feel that it should be taxed,'' said herbert conley, director of the florida treasury division. ``we are basically setting up a trust where these are going to be state dollars, and at no time will the purchaser of a contract have any control of the monies once they are paid.''
the faces stare at you in unrelenting succession, none with a smile. they are faces of adults without hope and children without childhood
there is photograph after photograph of families being evicted, mother and children sitting outdoors on their piled-up belongings. they are pictures that have the impact of war, of the great depression, of children orphaned and victimized by fighting not of their making
these are the scenes in a new exhibit called ``homeless in america,'' that opened tuesday at the corcoran gallery, a block from the white house. the exhibit of 64 pictures will tour 32 cities in the coming years to act as, in the words of its sponsors, ``a centerpiece for public education.''
it's a national disgrace that in this country of plenty there are people who don't have a place to live,,'' said susie elson, immediate past president of the national mental health association, which joined in producing the exhibit along with families for the homeless, a group that includes congressional, administration and media families
tipper gore, wife of the senator from tennessee, headed the project
in america we have become adjusted to the image of poverty,'' she said. ``the half-clothed child in a shack in appalachia is what many people still think of when they think about poor people in this country,'' she said before the exhibit opened. ``today's realities far outstrip this outdated image and that is why we felt it was important to have top photojournalists communicate through the power of their images.''
simultaneously with the opening of the exhibit, a book of the photographs was published. many of the photographers represented in the exhibit and book were commissioned by michael evans, formerly president reagan's personal photographer
the exhibit will endure as a lasting work of art and that, too, is important,'' said mrs. gore. ``but the key component, the key element is using the photographs to ... drive home that there are maybe three million homeless people in this country, that they are families, that they are children, the elderly, that they are veterans, that they are mentally ill, that they are the most vulnerable people in our society and that they are growing.''
evans said the project cost $450,000. its principal funding was provided by triangle industries, inc
the photographs, all black and white, depict such urban scenes as a pair of legs sticking from a box that obviously served as a night's accommodations; a child eating from a metal bowl in her home, under an underpass; a small girl weeping as a humane society worker removes her cat in a cage, prior to her own eviction; families with their belongings in plastic bags
they show two young men scavenging through a metal trash container; a man and woman asleep on a park bench, his knee serving as her pillow; a food line, with the splendor of the dallas skyline as a backdrop
the honorary patron of the project is barbara bush, wife of the vice president. the board of directors includes susan baker, wife of white house chief of staff howard baker
subsidized sales are expected to account for more than 60 percent of all u.s. wheat exports this year, according to projections by the agriculture department
total wheat exports are forecast at a six-year high of 1.55 billion bushels in the marketing year that runs through may 31, up 54 percent from 1986-87
sales of subsidized wheat under the export enhancement program, or eep, have climbed rapidly this year, particularly since last october, says the department's economic research service
big sales have been made to the soviet union and china, the two largest wheat importers, as well as to poland, algeria, egypt, morocco and iraq, the agency said in a new outlook report
the program was started three years ago in selected overseas markets to counter subsidized exports by u.s. competiors, notably the european economic community. under eep, exporters get free government-owned surplus commodities as bonuses, or subsidies, so they can sell wheat _ or other eligible products _ to designated foreign countries
since june 1, 1985, according to the report, the united states has announced ``initiatives'' or offers to sell wheat to 30 countries for a total of 43.1 million metric tons. through feb. 11, the actual sales totaled 31.4 million tons, most of it since last fall
a metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels of wheat. the projected export total this marketing year of 1.55 billion bushels would be about 42 million tons, of which more than 25 million tons is expected to be shipped under eep
the brisk sales have boosted u.s. wheat export prices, the report said. the average price at gulf ports loaded aboard ship for hard red winter wheat of ordinary protein rose to about $130 per ton in january from $116 in november and $110 in january 1987
rising prices also meant that the eep subsidies increased. those averaged about $34 per ton during the 1986-87 marketing year but rose in november and december before easing off in january, the report said. for example, the subsidy for the soviet union rose to more than $40 per ton but later dropped to less than $30
the total value of wheat bonuses awarded from the first wheat offer through january 1988 is approximately $1.1 billion,'' the report said. ``nearly 40 percent of the total has been awarded since oct. 1, 1987.''
meanwhile, the eep subsidies and the rise in u.s. wheat exports has had an impact on world trade, the report showed
in the current 1987-88 marketing year, the united states produced about 11 percent of the world output of wheat, the same as in 1986-87
but the boom in exports _ to 1.55 billion bushels from 1 billion bushels the previous year _ is giving the united states an estimated 41 percent of the world's wheat exports, compared with only 30 percent in 1986-87
according to agency records, that puts the u.s. export share at its highest level since 1982-83 when it was 42 percent
fat-conscious consumers soon may be able to buy leaner hot dogs, bologna and other cooked sausages
the agriculture department has approved a rule change that will let processors make make leaner products by substituting water for fat, so long as there is no loss of nutritional value
the leaner products can be labeled as ``lite,'' ``light,'' or ``lower fat'' if they contain at least a fourth less fat than similar cooked sausage products on the market, officials said. the labels must include a comparison that explains the term
for example, the label for lower-fat hotdogs might say: ``this product contains 20 percent fat, while usda allows 30 percent fat in meat hot dogs.''
lester m. crawford, administrator of the department's food safety and inspection service, said tuesday the change in regulations will be effective on april 14 and ``reflects our desire to facilitate the marketing of lower-fat products.''
current federal rules for cooked sausages limit fat to 30 percent and ``added'' water to 10 percent. the new rule will limit the combination of fat and added water to 40 percent of the product
the maximum fat content in the finished product will continue to be limited to 30 percent, but the water restriction will be removed so that processors can substitute some of the water for fat _ and wind up with a lower-fat product, crawford said
protein content, which is indirectly controlled by the limits on fat and added water, will remain unchanged and will be comparable to other cooked sausages, he said
the rule change is being made at the request of the american meat institute, a private trade association, which asked usda to develop a standard for light frankfurthers and similar cooked sausages. the proposed change was announced by the agency on nov. 25, 1986
an 11-ton satellite in orbit three years longer than planned will be rescued by a space shuttle crew next year, just months before it would fall back to earth in pieces
the national aeronautics and space administration on tuesday included the retrieval of the satellite _ the long duration exposure facility _ in a new schedule of flights and cargoes. the rescue was added to a mission beginning july 13
the orbit of the satellite, which gauged the effects of space's hostile environment on metal coatings and on 13 million seeds, is decaying and officials fear it will crash through the atmosphere and break up if it is not recaptured by mid-1990
the new schedule makes no change in the date of the much-delayed first post-challenger flight, now set for aug. 4. there have been no american manned missions in space since the challenger _ the 25th shuttle mission _ exploded on liftoff jan. 28, 1986 and killed its seven-member crew
the six-sided long duration exposure facility _ ldef in space jargon _ was tossed overboard by astronauts in april 1984 to be hit by meteors, pelted by cosmic rays and corroded by oxygen atoms
the bus-size frame held 57 experiments, including one that tested 120 varieties of vegetables, fruits and flowers to see whether cosmic radiation caused useful genetic changes. the ldef was to have been retrieved by another shuttle mission 10 months later and brought back in the cargo bay
but delays in the space program combined with grounding of all shuttles after the challenger disaster kept the 11-ton satellite in its lonely journey around earth. the $14 million package has no on-board propulsion systems or ability to transmit signals
it is orbiting 292 miles above earth, according to the north american defense command
the nasa schedule also calls for six small and medium-sized expendable rockets to be launched this year, four in 1989 and seven in 1990
the shuttle schedule reverses the order of one military and one civilian flight early next year. this enables nasa to orbit a pair of huge communications satellites earlier than planned. they will be needed in june 1989 when the $1 billion hubble space telescope is launched from a shuttle
nasa places such emphasis on the two communications satellites that they will be the principal cargoes on the first and third flights in the new series. together they will provide communications with the shuttle 95 percent of the time it is in orbit and be a spaceborne switchboard for many satellites
nasa was forced to change its priorities for shuttle payloads in order to be ready to launch the magellan probe to map venus at a time when the least amount of fuel will be needed to traverse the 90 million miles
the magellan flight is scheduled for april 27 and it will be the first u.s. planetary mission since a pioneer probe was launched to venus in 1978
nasa has scheduled the launch of the hubble space telescope for june 1, 1989, and another important planetary flight _ galileo _ for oct. 8, 1989. galileo is a cooperative project with germany to survey jupiter and its moons
the first shuttle flight will have a five-man crew commanded by navy capt. frederick hauck
the next mission, scheduled on the atlantis for oct. 27, will launch two military communications satellites. the next flight, discovery again, will be on jan. 19, 1989 and the fourth, using columbia, will be march 2 _ a defense department mission to launch an advanced reconnaissance satellite
a spacelab mission _ so-called because a complete laboratory is carried in the shuttle's cargo bay _ was delayed in the new schedule to push the tdrs satellite ahead
nasa said the mission to study the universe in the ultraviolet spectrum is being reconfigured to enhance study of the brightest exploding star seen by astronomers in more than 200 years. the discovery of supernova 1987a has drawn attention of astrophysicists around the world
the new schedule also adds two spacelab flights in 1990, using the shuttle columbia. also, the gamma ray observatory has been moved forward in the schedule to march 1990. the ulysses mission to study the sun and its environment remains in an october 1990 launch date
senate sponsors of a bill to change the nation's legal immigration system say they'll begin negotiations with key house members, and push for final passage this year
despite the senate's 88-4 vote tuesday for the legislation, there is no indication that the house is ready to tackle the bil 16 months after congress enacted a landmark law to curb illegal immigration
the current immigration control bill took six years to pass congress, as large numbers of special interest groups prevented a consensus until the fall of 1986
in contrast, the new legislation was guided through the senate with a minimum of debate by democrat edward m. kennedy of massachusetts and republican alan k. simpson of wyoming. they had smoothed the way by holding extensive discussions with their colleagues
the bill deals with those who apply through normal government channels to come here _ not with illegal immigrants
the senate measure would establish a cap on legal immigration to the united states. it would maintain the current priority for applicants with relatives in this country, but vastly expand immigration visas for those with needed labor and professional skills
the most influential house member on immigration matters, judiciary committee chairman peter w. rodino jr., has said he wants to move slowly until congress has a better idea of how the 1986 law is working
that means no immediate action, but does not rule out approval of the legislation later this year
kennedy and simpson said they plan to initiate discussions with rodino soon
simpson's spokeswoman, mary kay hill, said the senator thinks house leaders ``can see the need to reform the (legal immigation) system.''
others expected to be part of the consultations include rep. romano mazzoli, d-ky., chairman of the judiciary panel's immigration subcommittee; rep. patrick l. swindall of georgia, ranking republican on the subcommittee; and rep. charles e. schumer, d-n.y., who has introduced a measure similar to the senate bill
the senate measure is expected to allow more western europeans into the country by expanding the number of visas for those without family members here
sponsors say the family preference system has resulted in 85 percent of the immigrants to the united states coming from asia and latin america
ninety percent of the people immigrating to the united states arrive under the family system. the remaining 10 percent come in under other categories including job and professional skills
rodino has expressed worry that any new bill would interfere with family reunification. simpson said that would not happen, because the senate's cap is 100,000 above the currrent figures
the maximum number of visas under the senate bill would be 590,000 annually
under this umbrella, 470,000 visas in each of the first three years (440,000 thereafter) would be reserved for family immigration, and 120,000 (150,000 after three years) would be for the new ``independent'' category
currently, spouses and minor children of u.s. citizens can enter the country without limitation
schumer's bill would have a more generous cap of 750,000, including refugees fleeing from persecution. the senate cap does not include refugees, who now are admitted under a separte law that sets annual limits. the current refugee cap is 68,500
schumer has said there may be attempts in the house to link a legal immigration bill with proposals to extend an amnesty program for some of those who came here illegally. the 1986 law grants legalization to those who have lived in this country since before jan. 1, 1982, but the program ends may 4
simpson opposes an extension, and conservative senators would be expected to filibuster if an extension were added to a legal immigration bill, according to simpson and kennedy staffers
rodino has favored an extension, but has not said whether he desires linking the issues
voting against the bill in the senate were democrat dennis deconcini of arizona, and three republicans: jesse helms of north carolina, pete wilson of california and mark hatfield of oregon
federal prosecutors fear that statements by nuclear regulatory commission officials may have jeopardized their investigation of a 1986 radioactive spill at an ohio military base, according to agency documents
the democratic staff of the senate governmental affairs committee released documents tuesday that include a memo from an nrc official who said other nrc representatives believed regulations governing the incident were ambiguous and open to interpretation
the memo also said christopher barnes, assistant u.s. attorney for the southern district of ohio, believed those statements may have ``significantly impacted'' on the chances for a successful prosecution of officials involved in the spill
the case involves a sept. 18, 1986, spill of highly radioactive americium-241 at wright-patterson air force base near dayton, ohio. the spill occurred when workers opened an unlabeled drum at a base storage facility
air force officials have said almost no radiation escaped from the building despite a second spill oct. 6 while a cleanup was under way. the building eventually had to be torn down at a cost of $1 million
an inspection by the nrc's region iii office in chicago determined that the air force's failure to report the incident promptly violated an nrc regulation requiring disclosure within 24 hours of any incident that threatens to shut down operations of a facility for one day or more or causes over $2,000 in property damage
the documents released by the senate committee included a january memo from eugene t. pawlik, director of the nrc's region iii investigations field office in chicago. pawlik's memo refers to a december 1987 meeting between two nrc officials at the agency's region iv office in arlington, texas, and barnes
pawlik said barnes met with jerry everett, nuclear materials safety section chief for the nrc, and charles cain, radiation specialist
according to the nrc memo, everett said the nrc regulations governing disclosure were ambiguous and the nrc had not communicated to the air force a full interpretation of how the regulations were to be implemented
and cain stated that the first spill was open to interpretation and not reportable and that in his mind the air force was not negligible in waiting to file a report
i think it is a fair assessment to say that the two recent interviews of everett and cain have at this late date placed most, if not all, of the ... investigation in jeopardy,'' pawlik said in the memo
everett and cain declined comment on the documents tuesday through a spokesman
americium powder is not considered dangerous on the skin, but small amounts can cause cancer if inhaled or otherwise introduced into the body. saved</head>
a southern baptist minister says he was fired from his denomination's regional mission board because he believes jews can achieve salvation without converting to christianity
the rev. george sheridan of the first baptist church here was regional director of interfaith witness for the southern baptist convention's home mission board for 12 years. the region runs from north carolina to maine and west to michigan
as director of the interfaith witness, sheridan was the southern baptist liaison with other religious groups, including jews
a statement from the mission board's atlanta headquarters said sheridan ``was not fired or terminated'' but ``declined transfer'' from new jersey to a position as an editorial assistant at the headquarters
but sheridan, 45, said tuesday he was fired, and has hired an attorney to counter any claims by the mission board that he resigned
the minister believes he was fired because he opposed southern baptist plans to begin a program aimed at converting jews. the program was discussed at a private meeting in new york last year
sheridan said he was asked in june to submit to the board a written statement about his theological views about jews
in the absence of any biblical contradiction, i believe that the jews of today, as ever, receive salvation through their having been chosen by god in covenant with abraham, moses and the prophets,'' sheridan wrote in his statement
he said board members grilled him about his views when he was summoned to a special meeting in atlanta in november. the board informed him in a letter dated jan. 9 that he was being assigned, he said
sheridan said he has not been able to determine if the board considered his views heretical, and added that the board had not given him a specific reason for removing him from his post
in 1987, the national convention of the united church of christ accepted the view that jews can achieve salvation without believing in jesus. opposition to attempts to convert jews often is based on this view
lawmakers may make a massive new farm subsidy program part of sweeping trade legislation, while its chief backer argues that u.s. trade negotiators want it despite the threat of a presidential veto
the subsidy plan known as a ``triggered marketing loan'' was included in the senate version of the 1,000-page trade bill. house and senate negotiators are working on a compromise
final action on the loan program was postponed when house agriculture chairman e. ``kika'' de la garza, d-texas, said tuesday that senate agriculture chairman patrick j. leahy, d-vt., had the votes but wanted a few revisions
under marketing loan programs, some of which already are in effect, producers receive the u.s. price for their crops, which are then sold at world market prices. the taxpayers make up the difference
the plan under consideration would create such provisions for wheat, corn and soybeans but only if current negotiations failed to produce an agreement among the nation's trading partners to reduce agricultural subsidies by the 1990 wheat marketing year
leahy said he was convinced of the need for a triggered marketing loan on a trip to geneva last week to get a progress report on negotiations aimed at reaching a new general agreement on tariffs and trade
he said european negotiators have been ``arrogant'' in their rejection of u.s. demands for an end to export subsidies. he said americans at the table in geneva favor the triggered marketing loan as a ``club'' to hold over the europeans and prod them on the issue
if you were talking to some of the people we have to negotiate with, then you might think we need it, too,'' leahy said
in other action, the panel approved expanding the 1985 export enhancement program by more than $1 billion to $2.5 billion. it provides bonuses in the form of government-held commodities to exporters to ship american commodities that they acquired at u.s. prices
critics of the triggered marketing loan program said that the sum involved could strain the budget
this is potentially a huge sum of money we're talking about in agricultural programs,'' said rep. sam gibbons, d-fla., whose home-state growers are often wary of anything that could prompt restrictions abroad against orange and grapefruit exports
rep. charles stenholm, d-texas, said the use of such a measure as a bargaining chip would not be credible now because it would require reshuffling budget priorities
stenholm did say he favored the objective. he said the united states should tell the european community: ``if they have unlimited supplies of money, it's going to cost all of it and we're going to raise you five.''
gibbons presented a letter from agriculture secretary richard lyng, u.s. trade representative clayton k. yeutter and other administration officials suggesting that attaching the program could prompt a presidential veto for the trade bill. bgng ``jackson voted...</note>
jesse jackson set aside his disappointment in finishing second in his home state primary tuesday night and focused on his overall strength, saying ``i am where every candidate wishes he could be tonight.''
jackson had predicted he would finish first in illinois and defeat another favorite son, paul simon. but the results showed just the opposite
i finished second, it seems, in illinois,'' jackson said. ``(but) i'm a winner. i am the leading contender for the democratic nomination. i am where every candidate wishes he could be tonight.''
a noticeably tired jackson told supporters at a downtown chicago hotel that both he and simon had reason to celebrate. illinois voters, he said, ``paid their respects on a sitting senator who focused on one state.''
jesse jackson voted near his south side home earlier in the day, accompanied by sons jesse jr., 23, and jonathan, 22, at the bryn mawr community church
the democratic candidate said his message to ``stop drugs from coming into our country, save our jobs, secure our farmers and invest in our children'' has touched voters and given them something to fight for
i have run all the way, and we've been winning all the way, and we'll keep winning,'' jackson said. jackson had hoped to add illinois to a string of successes over the last week, beginning with super tuesday and continuing over the weekend in south carolina. he and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis top the delegate count
jackson voted shortly after 9 a.m. in a small church room jammed with reporters, photographers and a handful of bewildered-looking voters
afterward, donning a topcoat on a chilly day, jackson said he was touched by ``the joy i see in my children voting. when i was their age, i did not have the right to vote.''
it says a lot about the greatness of america, the fact that we have the right to grow to our potential,'' jackson said. ``hope is going to prevail.''
the south carolina native said he has been the most effective and best managed candidate, despite relatively weak financing
if my opponents had my budget, they could not compete,'' jackson said. ``if i had their budgets, they could not compete.''
jackson, whose delegate total was second only to massachusetts gov. michael dukakis' going into tuesday's primary, said he has broadened his base of support since waging his first presidential campaign four years ago
expectations are higher; the experience factor is greater and i've had a chance to serve more people,'' jackson said. ``people who feel that the process was not working for them find hope in the campaign. ... now they feel there is a way out. there is hope.''
students who skip professor gerald m. phillips' opening lecture in his course on group decision-making may find themselves searching the campus in vain for any trace of him the rest of the semester
that's because the penn state university professor communicates with his speech communications 350 class only through the school's computer system, by electronic mail or ``e-mail.''
the class does get weekly lectures, from two graduate students, and other graduate students sit in on group discussions as ``consultants.''
we've got a real industrial model,'' said phillips, who this semester has 212 students enrolled in the course. ``what we've got here is a simulation of top management, middle management and employees.''
phillips considers himself the chief executive officer. as such, he monitors computer messages between student groups and the graduate students, and answers questions sent to him
i can monitor everything. they know i'm monitoring. i'm the ceo. i can get all the information on my company,'' phillips said
phillips, 59, doesn't go to his office on campus often. he prefers to stay home, a mile away, working from his cramped study filled with computer equipment
graduate students who have been there have dubbed his study ``the bridge of the starship enterprise,'' after the spaceship on the television series ``star trek.''
phillips said he is giving students a taste of the real world, adding that he is more accessible than most professors
last spring, in a trial run of the course, phillips said he answered 3,169 questions from students
you find me a professor anywhere in north america that can handle 3,169 questions _ and they weren't stupid questions,'' phillips said
students who miss phillips' lecture on the first day of class can only guess at the appearance of the professor known by his computer address ``gmp.''
one says she's going to track me down to see what i look like and talk to me face to face. i said `catch me if you can,''' said phillips
one student who asked that her name not be used said the course puts too much emphasis on computer communication
it's like e-mail is god,'' she said. ``it really shouldn't be like that. there has to be some communication that is one-on-one.''
others disagree
i don't think we've suffered any because we haven't seen him face to face,'' said michael guerin, a senior operations management major from rochester, n.y. ``he's readily available on the computer.''
phillips has a contract to write a book on the course, which he said has generated widespread interest
we've been visited by educators from norway, australia and japan. a lot of people are looking over our shoulder in this process,'' he said
warner burke, a professor at teachers college of columbia university, said phillips' emphasis on mimicking a corporate hierarchy hinders the students' understanding of how they come to their decisions
here our goals are understanding the group process, not just decision making,'' said burke, director of teachers college's graduate program in organizational psychology. ``the most important aspect of group processes is non-verbal behavior.''
