former mayor jane byrne's bid for a political comeback ended in defeat tuesday, but house minority leader bob michel, president reagan's point man in congress, easily overcame his first gop primary challenge in 32 years
michel's democratic arch-foe, attorney g. douglas stephens, won the democratic primary, setting the stage for a november rematch of the 1982 contest that almost cost michel his 18th district seat
with nearly three-quarters of the votes counted, michel defeated tazewell county board chairman james e. unsicker by 85 percent to 15 percent, while stephens beat an unemployed recent college graduate, justin z. west, 89 percent to 11 percent
the state board of elections said between 45 percent and 48 percent of the state's 5.9 million registered voters went to the polls
in chicago, mrs. byrne lost to aurelia pucinski in a race for the democratic nomination for clerk of the circuit court. with nearly three-quarters of the vote reported, mrs. puchinski had 53 percent of the democratic primary vote
it means that when the people spoke, they apparently shouted. ... i am very good at taking hints,'' mrs. byrne said. asked whether she would consider running for office again, she said, ``i'm not even thinking of it right now.''
ed vrdolyak, former democratic powerbroker who left the party, was unopposed on the republican side and will face mrs. pucinski in november
also back on illinois ballots were followers of political extremist lyndon larouche. at least 20 larouche supporters were candidates in races ranging from president to county register of deeds
in southern illinois, the retirement of veteran rep. melvin price, a democrat, set off a four-man scramble in the 21st district primary. vying for the party's nomination were st. clair county board chairman jerry f. costello, madison county auditor pete fields; former price administrative aide mike mansfield and perennial local candidate steve maragides
in the 22nd district, state sen. glenn poshard of carterville was unopposed in the democratic primary as he moved to succeed rep. kenneth gray, who is retiring after 12 terms. pete prineas of carbondale and patrick j. kelley of carbondale sought the gop nomination
chicago voters held a non-binding referendum on the training of illinois national guard troops in central america. with roughly three-quarters of the precincts reporting, those wanted to stop sending illinois troops to central america outnumbered those favoring the foreign-training program about 2-to-1
neighbors of chicago's wrigley field also opposed night games at the cubs' vintage ballpark, piling up 3-to-1 margin in early returns in a non-binding referendum. with four of 21 precincts counted, 692 voters opposed lighting wrigley for night baseball and 237 supported night games
chicago's city council in february approved lights at wrigley field, the only major-league ballpark without them, after years of controversy. the issue pitted neighborhood groups concerned about noise, litter and parking problems against the cubs' owners, tribune co., which argued the team was losing prime-time television revenues
the latest bid for office by mrs. byrne, who lost the mayor's office to harold washington in 1983 after one term, was made without the backing of the party, which supported her opponent, mrs. pucinski. vrdolyak became a republican after a failed third-party challenge to washington
michel defeated stephens six years ago with 51.6 percent of the vote after the toughest campaign fight of his career. his office attributed the tight race to redistricting
the larouche candidates were back two years after winning the democratic primary for lieutenant governor and secretary of state. illinois democrats tried without success this year to remove la rouche candidates from the party
in the 21st congressional district, the winner of the democratic fight will face republican robert h. ``bob'' gaffner, who was unopposed in the primary. in 1986, he came within 943 votes of upsetting price, who is leaving capitol hill after 44 years
gray held his 22nd district seat from 1955 to 1975, when he retired for health reasons, and in 1985 returned to congress for two additional terms
democratic presidential contender michael dukakis declared himself undaunted by a third-place finish in the illinois primary, saying ``the field is wide open'' in coming contests
now we move on to michigan where there are no favorite sons,'' a somewhat subdued dukakis said at a news conference tuesday night at a boston television station
two illinois home-state favorites _ sen. paul simon and civil rights leader jesse jackson, who has made chicago his home _ finished well ahead of the massachusetts governor. on the other hand, dukakis' showing was far better than that of sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee, who failed to demonstrate any appreciable strength outside his southern base
dukakis said his third-place showing in a state where he invested more than $350,000 was not a setback
i don't get disappointed. ... i was running against two citizens of illinois who had strong bases and a great deal of support from those who know them,'' dukakis said. ``we did what i can characterize was a respectable third.''
those around the massachusetts governor echoed his contention that his showing was good under the circumstances. leslie dach, a spokesman for the dukakis campaign, ``we did as well as we expected.'' campaign manager susan estrich added, ``we did beat all the non-favorite sons.''
during the illinois campaign, dukakis had said a vote for simon would increase the chances of a brokered democratic national convention, something he said would be a ``disaster.''
tuesday night, dukakis said, ``i've been making a number of calls around the country to key democrats and there is an overwhelming sentiment that we should get behind a nominee
i don't believe we have any front-runners; i don't think we're going to have a front-runner until the convention,'' dukakis said
the seven days between super tuesday and the illinois primary left dukakis too little time to attract strong support in illinois, he said
but he said effort and money expended in illinois will pay off later, if he is the democratic nominee
dukakis wasn't about to make any bold predictions on michigan's caucus march 26
i don't have to win any primary. i have to do as well as i possibly can. when you have a multi-candidate field, the vote tends to get split up,'' he said, adding that he hoped michigan would help winnow the field
dach said missouri rep. richard gephardt, the big democratic loser on super tuesday, would be competing fiercely with dukakis for labor votes in michigan
the nikkei stock average closed at 25,704.43 points, up 228.76 points, on the tokyo stock exchange on wednesday
investigators are trying to learn whether ferdinand marcos was behind a plot to ship weapons from the united states to forces loyal to him in the philippines, federal officials say
u.s. officials suspect the ousted philippines president may have been instrumental in abortive plans to supply automatic rifles and submachine guns for an 80-member force
marcos' chief american attorney, however, denies marcos was involved in any arms shipments. ``that's a dry well for you, my friend,'' richard a. hibey said friday in washington. ``there's no truth to that allegation.''
details of the planned arms sale surfaced here last fall during a federal trial of leon dicker, a disbarred hewlett, n.y., lawyer convicted of conspiring to export weapons illegally
at trial, the government said the arms were bound for thailand. but two federal officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said last week that authorities believe the weapons were for pro-marcos forces in the philippines
dicker, two men acquitted in the case and one who pleaded guilty and testified for the prosecution were arrested in a u.s. customs service ``sting.'' no arms were alleged to have changed hands
the officials said new york businessman robert l. steele is a focus of the continuing investigation. during the trial, the prosecutor said steele had worked with dicker on the arms deal, but steele was not charged
steele and dicker have been linked to orlando c. dulay, a marcos supporter and former provincial governor later linked by philippine military sources to an august 1987 coup attempt in the philippines
dulay, detained by authorities in august 1986 on the grounds of a marcos-owned estate near princeton university, said steel and dicker were his ``lawyers'' who had sent him to clean up the court-sealed property at marcos' request
a newspaper in manila reported last week that dulay was contacted by u.s. authorities who traveled there seeking his cooperation in the investigation of alleged arms shipments to pro-marcos groups
assistant u.s. attorney john peyton in honolulu on monday confirmed that he met with dulay last week, but said he could not comment further because of an ``ongoing criminal investigation.''
raul rabe, deputy chief of mission at the philippines embassy in washington, said dulay recently ``surfaced in honolulu and joined mr. marcos'' before being deported to the philippines, where he faces charges in the 1986 slayings of three campaign workers of president corazon aquino
marcos has been living in exile in honolulu since his 1986 ouster and the election of mrs. aquino as president. he has said he wishes to return to his homeland. marcos supporters failed in two 1987 coup attempts
last year, two u.s. businessmen testifying before a house subcommittee played secretly recorded conversations with marcos and said that marcos had sought to buy weapons for shipment to the philippines
the weapons discussed in the house testimony allegedly were to be used for a coup attempt in late june, four months after dicker's arrest. it could not be determined if the alleged june coup attempt, the dicker case and the honolulu investigation were related
a government source said u.s. authorities suspect a link between marcos and the new jersey arms case, but declined to provide specifics
abelardo morua, dicker's co-defendant who pleaded guilty, was questioned recently by federal authorities about a possible link between marcos and the weapons deal, said morua's attorney, chris franzblau. he said morua provided no information
several government officials with knowledge of the investigation, speaking on condition of anonymity, said that to discuss the case openly could jeopardize a prosecution
neither u.s. attorney samuel a. alito jr. nor richard mercier, head of the customs service's newark office, would comment on the case
our policy is never to confirm or deny any inquiry,'' said leonard s. walton, customs' director of illegal export investigations in washington
on monday, marcos issued a statement denying he was ``bent on taking control (of the philippines) through violent means.''
the news that authorities are pressing the investigation in this new direction surfaced last wednesday when u.s. district judge alfred j. lechner jr., in sentencing morua here, referred to a continuing probe
steele did not return repeated phone calls this week and last at his manhattan conglomerate, commonwealth group ltd., a private company
dicker, sentenced to four years, said he could not comment on the matter because he was appealing his conviction. about it</head>
an american, the first mountaineer to conquer north america's highest peak alone in winter, left a japanese flag atop mount mckinley to honor the man who tried _ and failed _ before him
vern tejas ended a monthlong ordeal of screaming winds and subzero temperatures on tuesday, picked up by plane on mckinley's flank and flown to anchorage, 130 miles to the south
during the climb tejas often thought about japanese climber naomi uemura, the only other person to reach the 20,320-foot summit in a solo winter climb but who disappeared during his descent in february 1984 and was never found
many times i was wondering, `is this where he slipped? is this where he lost it?' '' tejas said tuesday in anchorage
i think i figured out where he bought the farm up there. there was one area, on summit day, i was coming back down. it's very steep, very exposed, and you feel that if you make one mistake, you could die.''
tejas, a stocky 35-year-old with beard and shaved head, had climbed mckinley 12 times, usually as a guide during the may-june climbing season
even then, in relatively milder conditions, about a third of several hundred climbers who attempt the climb turn back short of the summit
snow-covered mckinley is infamous for hurricane-force winds that rage for days, temperatures that dip to minus 60, and whiteouts that make it hard to know up from down. tejas' planned two-week trek took a month
tejas, who lives in talkeetna, which is used as a staging area for mckinley climbers, was dropped off feb. 16 at the mountain's 7,200-foot level. on the second day, a storm came and kept him in his snow cave for three days. he eventually went onto half rations, then half rations every other day
i ended up working at my margin. it was around the edge of safety several times.'' twice, he found earlier climbers' food caches that helped him survive. on march 7, he waited out a storm and made a dash to the top during a whiteout
i couldn't see where i was going. after 12 times to the summit, i can feel my way up to it, but it wasn't as pretty or spectacular as i'd hoped for,'' he said
i took a few pictures, left a few mementos, turned around and headed down. i left a japanese flag in memory of naomi uemura, and i also left a can of spam. there was no meat in it. i ate it. i was very hungry.''
he made it back the same day to 17,000 feet and rested overnight. the next day, he contacted pilot lowell thomas jr. by two-way radio and started down. tejas appeared in good shape when he arrived tuesday in anchorage, but he said the mountain had pushed him to his mental, physical, and emotional limits
you go, `this is ridiculous. this is a hill, this is the middle of winter, i'm a lone guy out here. there are crevasses all around, there's danger. what am i doing here?' ''
safe on level ground, he answered his own question
to live in a very harsh environment, to do something very stressful and straining like that, is a challenge,'' he said. ``i was at the limits of my ability. it was a good test. i'd never spent a month by myself. i found out i really liked myself.''
republican pat robertson ran a distant third in the illinois primary but repeated his vow to continue his campaign to the national convention
i am in all the way to new orleans,'' robertson said tuesday night, insisting that he was ``not a bit in the world disappointed'' over the illinois results
robertson has spent nearly $25 million on a campaign that has gained 17 national convention delegates, according to the associated press tally. the federal spending limit for primary campaigns is $27 million
thus, robertson acknowledged, he must run a drastically scaled-back effort from here on
my own personal travel will continue but as far as a full-blown media campaign, i can't afford that any more,'' he said after meeting tuesday afternoon with republican national committee chairman frank fahrenkopf
but, he added: ``i have enough money to keep in the race through ...the convention.''
marc nuttle, robertson's campaign manager, said the exact amount that could be spent before hitting the limit would not be known before the next seven to 10 days
whether it's between $2 million and $3 million or less than $2 million it will be enough for the campaign,'' he said
richard pinsky, national field director for americans for robertson, characterized the new campaign as ``mean and lean. we have always been labor-intensive and have won on organization and grass-roots support from volunteers.''
robertson said he would campaign in california, which holds its primary june 7, to help local candidates with their races
we would like to see republican majorities enunciating major conservative causes by 1990 or 1992,'' he said
robertson said his meeting with fahrenkopf was mainly to plan the role of robertson delegates in the convention
we talked about housekeeping things,'' he said
nuttle said the talks were to ensure that the convention went smoothly, and that robertson's backers, many of whom have never attended a national convention, are included in the preparation for the event
our goal is to unify the party,'' robertson said. ``i am going to be the conservative champion.''
bob dole says his republican presidential campaign is still alive and ``we're just going to hang in there'' despite another crushing loss to george bush
but the kansas senator has been without a win for three weeks, and the primary calendar offers him little hope: the next gop contest is march 29 in connecticut, another one of the vice president's home states
dole returned home for a few days, flying into washington as the disappointing illinois results began unfolding. bush rolled up more than half of the popular vote, and more importantly, held a 3-1 ratio in distribution of the 82 gop delegates
despite the bleak news, dole told reporters, ``we're doing all right. we're just going to hang in there. there's a long way to go yet.''
pressed on whether he would continue his candidacy, he said, ``we're staying in, we're staying in.''
dole's campaign was stunned by bush's 16-state sweep on super tuesday, and he ordered massive staff layoffs and a halt to all advertising in illinois late last week. at the urging of some aides, dole considered giving up his white house hopes but decided to stay in
he campaigned in wisconsin and connecticut as illinois primary voters went to the polls, saying: ``i don't give up very easily.''
in hartford, he said, ``this is called a surprise state from time to time. we're ready for one. we could use it.''
dole hasn't had much to cheer about since feb. 23, when he won contests in south dakota and minnesota. a week before that, he was surprised by bush's come-from-behind win in new hampshire, the first signal of chaos in dole's campaign
little over a month ago, dole was the early leader with his impressive victory over bush in iowa. illinois win</head>
even as george bush rolled up a victory in the republican primary in illinois, exit polls indicated ``little chinks in his armor'' that could bedevil him in the general election, analysts say
bush on tuesday overwhelmed sen. bob dole in virtually all ideological and demographic groups of the republican electorate, cementing his huge lead in the gop race
it's a blowout,'' said abc news poll analyst doug muzzio
results were far less clear on the democratic side, where sen. paul simon cashed in on his favorite-son status and jesse jackson rode another huge wave of black support to finish first and second respectively in their home state
while bush swamped his republican opponents, his ratings on leadership and toughness were weaker than may be expected from a prohibitive front-runner, said nbc news poll analyst sheldon gawiser
additionally, bush failed to win the independents who voted in the gop primary
if bush is going to win the general election, he's got to start attracting independent voters,'' said cbs news poll chief warren mitofsky
the results did not foreshadow problems for bush within the gop; he even won among former television evangelist pat robertson's natural supporters, born-again christians and voters concerned about so-called ``morality issues.''
but among the 23 percent of republicans who said leadership was a key issue, dole and bush split the vote, abc found
a prohibitive front-runner should be showing some leadership, particularly given the fact that he holds the second-highest office in the land,'' muzzio said
in nbc's poll, 55 percent of gop voters said bush was tough enough to be a good president, but 24 percent said he was not and 21 percent were not sure. the 55 percent was ``a pretty small number,'' considering that it came among republican primary voters, said gawiser
thirty 30 percent of republicans told nbc that bush would be a very strong leader, 42 percent said he would be somewhat strong, 16 percent said not very strong, 6 percent said not at all strong and 6 percent didn't know. again, ``that's not a terrific standing among republican primary voters,'' gawiser said
in another measure, a plurality of republican voters, 41 percent, said bush had not fully disclosed his knowledge of the iran-contra affair, while 32 percent said he had and 21 percent were not sure, nbc found
while the issue has not been a significant one in the minds of republican voters, ``it's there,'' gawiser said. ``that's a tomorrow story,'' one that could gain significance in the general election
these bush results amounted to ``little chinks in his armor,'' not major campaign problems, gawiser noted. muzzio noted that the flaws spotted in the abc poll also were minor, with dole beating bush among the tiny number of republicans who rated ``honesty'' or ``getting things done'' as key
it doesn't tell us all that much about bush's electability,'' muzzio said. ``but it certainly indicates he's not a prohibitive favorite to beat a democrat.''
in the democratic race, weaknesses were demonstrated most strongly by sen. albert gore of tennessee, who failed to turn his super tuesday victories into a sizable showing, and rep. richard gephardt of missouri, who finished last
the g-boys just didn't show,'' said muzzio. ``they were squeezed by the hometown favorites.''
one favorite, simon, even drew voters who doubt he can succeed. abc said just 40 percent of simon's supporters gave him the best chance to win in november, and 35 percent named massachusetts gov. michael dukakis even though they voted for simon. nbc said only 35 percent of simon's voters thought he would win the nomination, while 39 percent picked dukakis to win it
jackson enjoyed his now-customary huge black support: he received 91 percent of the black vote, which was about a quarter of the democratic turnout, abc said. but he won only 8 percent of the white vote by abc's count, 7 percent by the cbs news-new york times poll
jackson still can't attract any white votes,'' said mitofsky. ``he got 7 percent. and that's not enough.''
though dukakis finished third, abc said a plurality of democrats, 35 percent, thought he had the best chance of winning the general election. jackson had 27 percent, simon, 18 percent
the margin of sampling error for the results was about 5 points for most subgroups
the house has given final congressional approval to legislation authorizing prime federal parkland in washington for a national monument to the 5,000 black patriots who served in the american revolution
the voice vote by the house on tuesday followed senate approval of the bill on feb. 26
the house is expected to approve similar, senate-backed legislation today that would authorize a choice washington site for a national memorial to americans who fought in the korean war
rep. james j. florio, d-n.j., said the korean war memorial, to be built on the mall that extends from the lincoln memorial to the capitol, will be ``a fitting and long-overdue monument to the 55,000 amricans who lost their lives in a forgotten war.''
private sponsors say they have raised $2.5 million toward a goal of $10 million for the korean war memorial. the black patriots monument, also expected to be built on the mall, will cost an estimated $4 million
both the black patriots and the korean war monuments previously were authorized by congress, and will be built with private donations. nixon</head>
a group of judges that makes policy for the federal courts is urging the house to consider impeaching u.s. district judge walter l. nixon of mississippi, who is scheduled to go to prison for perjury on march 23
the group, the judicial conference of the united states, on tuesday unanimously supported a resolution that says ``consideration of impeachment may be warranted.''
nixon, 59, was sentenced to five years in prison following his 1986 perjury conviction. he has remained a judge but has not been hearing cases since he was indicted in 1985 although he continues to be paid his annual salary of $89,500
nixon would forfeit his salary and his eligibility for a pension at age 65 if he is impeached by the house and removed from office by the senate
the recommendation that the house consider impeaching him was approved by a vote of 24-0 by the judges' group. three members abstained, including chief justice william h. rehnquist, who traditionally does not vote on such matters
nixon is the third federal judge ever to be indicted for crimes allegedly committed while in office
a federal panel has determined that the primary cause of a 1987 collision that killed 10 people in utah was an instructor's failure to keep his plane out of restricted airspace during a student training flight
the single-engine training plane collided with a skywest commuter plane near kearns, utah, on jan. 15, 1987, while making an approach to salt lake city international airport after a flight from pocatello, idaho
the national transportation safety board on tuesday absolved the air traffic controller handling the skywest plane. the other aircraft was flying under visual flight rules and was not under the direction of air traffic control
nevertheless, the ntsb said the accident might have been avoided if the private aircraft had equipment that would have provided the controller information on the plane's altitude. investigators said the single-engine mooney m-20c was on the radar screen, but without altitude information the controller would not have known the two planes were about to collide
the safety board put the primary blame for the accident on the instructor of the private aircraft's ``lack of navigational vigilance ... which led to the unauthorized intrusion'' into the restricted airspace that surrounds the salt lake city airport
a federal official is telling congress that states whose drivers ignore the 55 mph speed limit should not be penalized, but two senior lawmakers said they are writing bills that would do just the opposite
reps. james howard, d-n.j., chairman of the house public works and transportation committee, and glenn anderson, d-calif., who heads the public works surface transportation subcommittee, said they are working on measures that would extend the penalties to states that have adopted the 65 mph limit
states with 55 mph limits can lose up to 10 percent of their federal highway aid if monitors find that more than half their motorists are driving too fast. but when two laws were passed last year allowing 65 mph driving on many rural highways, the penalties were not extended to roads where states allow the faster speeds
the states are clearly in the best position to determine where speed enforcement is needed to enhance safety,'' diane k. steed, chief of the national highway traffic safety administration, said in a statement delivered tuesday to anderson's panel. ``they should be able to deploy enforcement personnel accordingly, without the threat of losing federal funds.''
lawmakers from the 11 states that have retained the 55 mph limit have complained that it is unfair for their states to face the loss of federal assistance while states that permit faster driving cannot be penalized for motorists speeding on 65 mph roads. status</head>
an independent study group says significant changes are needed in the way the veterans administration is being managed whether or not it is elevated to cabinet status
in its report to the senate governmental affairs committee, a panel of the national academy of public administration said it found ``little evidence'' in its study that cabinet-level status would materially improve the va's mission of providing for the present and future needs of veterans
the panel does not believe that such an elevation would significantly improve either access to the president, the adequacy of necessary resources, or the organization, management and delivery of high-quality services and benefits,'' the report said
the seven-member panel said it ``does recognize the potential political value of raising the public visibility of the needs of veterans and the programs designed to meet these needs by making va a department in the president's cabinet. however, given the broad political support which already exists for the va and its programs, the gain would be at the margin.''
the academy panel and the general accounting office, the investigative arm of congress, did not make recommendations on whether the va should become part of the president's cabinet. 3rd graf pvs bgng, volume in the ... deletes 6th graf pvs, in foreign exchange... to conform.</note>
the u.s. dollar rose slightly in tokyo trading wednesday, while stock prices rallied in heavy trading, ending the day sharply higher
on the tokyo stock exchange, the nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues, which climbed 42.16 points tuesday, closed the day at 25,704.43 points, up 228.76 points, or 0.90 percent, from tuesday's close
the u.s. currency closed at 127.49 yen, up 0.24 yen from tuesday's close, after opening wednesday at 127.38
volume in the first section was estimated at a heavy 1.1 billion shares, compared with 550 million shares traded tuesday morning
individual investors were active buyers of heavy industrials, helping to absorb some selling of those issues by institutional investors such as life insurance companies, traders said
the nikkei average's previous closing high since the oct. 19 market crash was 25,682.82 points on march 2
the yen is easing against the dollar...but everyone is waiting for the latest u.s. trade data,'' said an exchange dealer at a major commercial bank in tokyo, who spoke on condition of anonymity
the u.s. commerce department is scheduled thursday to release the nation's foreign trade figures for january
an american communications satellite that was launched last week has rocketed into geosynchronous orbit and should start operations early in april
the spacenet iii satellite owned by gte corp. was launched friday night by a french ariane rocket. on tuesday, the satellite fired its apogee kick motor, a small rocket engine, and moved into orbit 22,300 miles above the equator, gte officials said
since the satellite is moving at the same rate of speed as the earth, it will in effect hover over a point on the earth's surface
the 1,562-pound satellite provides a communications link between points in all 50 of the united states. clients include the associated press and the television groups of abc, cbs, cnn and gannett
the u.s. satellite and a french communications satellite were launched together friday from the european space agency launch site in kourou, french guiana
gte spacenet is the first american client of arianespace, the operating arm of the european space agency. moving on sports wires.</note>
susan butcher, bundled against biting winds and subzero temperatures, widened her lead and seemed assured of an unprecedented third straight victory in the 1,150-mile iditarod trail sled dog race
butcher, who left this checkpoint just as her closest competitor arrived tuesday, was expected to cross the finish line in nome today
if butcher wins, it will be the fourth consecutive year that a woman has won the 16-year-old race. libby riddles of teller won in 1985, and butcher won in 1986 and 1987, setting a course record each year
butcher left elim, 123 miles from nome, at 5:11 p.m. tuesday, after stopping in the eskimo village for two hours to feed and rest her dog team. martin buser of big lake arrived two minutes before she left
butcher, a resident of manley, took the lead early tuesday and has not yielded it. she left elim with 10 of the 17 dogs she started with march 5 in anchorage; the others were dropped at checkpoints along the trail
buser was traveling with 12 of his original 20 dogs still in harness
subzero temperatures and biting winds continued to hinder the leaders, and weather forecasters said the wind chill factor could sink to minus 70 degrees along the trail's final miles
in each of her two previous victories, butcher proved the strength and endurance of her team in the final, windswept miles along the barren bering sea coast. her elapsed time last year was 11 days, 2 hours
her closest rival last year was four-time iditarod champion rick swenson of two rivers, who ran neck-and-neck with butcher until his dogs refused to continue just 22 miles from the finish
this year, swenson was about six hours behind butcher at last report, leaving koyuk at 2 p.m. tuesday in third place. running in fourth was joe garnie of teller
herbie nayokpuk of shishmaref was fifth. seventy-year-old joe redington of knik, who took an early lead and held it for more than 400 miles, was sixth
redington, known as the ``father of the iditarod'' for organizing the first race in 1973, has run all but two races and placed as high as fifth, but has yet to win
the first musher to nome collects $30,000 of a $150,000 purse; the next 19 finishers split the rest. five of the 52 teams that started the race have dropped out

