the ap
until this week, almost no one had heard of kon yu-leung, reputed drug kingpin. he wasn't on any list of most wanted criminals and he'd never been the subject of a crime commission hearing or a newspaper story
today, kon is accused of leading a conspiracy to smuggle as much as 1,000 pounds of southeast asian heroin into the united states, far more than in such notorious cases as the ``pizza connection'' from sicily and the ``french connection'' through marseilles
authorities say they seized 570 pounds of the kon network's heroin. the head of the drug enforcement administration's new york bureau calls the amount ``almost mind-boggling'' compared with 200 pounds in the pizza connection and the 70 pounds in the french connection
considered equally mind-boggling is the fact that such a huge operator was not the agency's no. 1 target, as one prosecutor claimed, but just one of several large asian importers. they have, according to authorities, increased their share of the city's heroin business from 3 percent to 70 percent during the last five years, displacing the mafia
despite the enormity of the 44-year-old kon's alleged operation, his rivals are expected to have no trouble supplying new york's 225,000 heroin addicts _ half the national total
and there will be more drug lords
today's courier is tomorrow's king,'' robert strang, a dea spokesman, said tuesday. ``that makes it difficult for law enforcement. ... it's not like the traditional organized crime families, where there's an organization with an observable hierarchy.''
many people feel that because of this arrest we've solved the southeast asia heroin problem,'' he added. ``we haven't. he's only one of several major traffickers.''
kon, whom the police call johnny kon, was arrested sunday night outside the new york hilton. he was wearing a $25,000 diamond-studded piaget watch and a gold bracelet with a buddha charm, and carried $32 in a pocket of his dark business suit
kon told the judge at his arraignment he could not afford to hire a lawyer. he was held without bail in the federal jail in manhattan
kon admitted to the agents who arrested him he was a smuggler _ of gems and cigarettes, authorities said
investigators told a different story: that kon may have imported up to $1 billion in heroin into the united states between 1984 and 1987. he was described as a shadowy figure with a half-dozen counterfeit passports in as many different names, who may have bribed high officials in several nations
money, apparently, is not one of his problems. the new york post reported that on a recent night kon lost $1 million at a manila casino ``and walked out laughing.''
federal prosecutor catherine palmer described kon as ``a big spender. he enjoys big meals, good times and buying expensive things for people.''
kon came to the dea's attention in 1984, when a shipment of 250 pounds of heroin believed destined for the united states was seized in hong kong harbor. kon, a shanghai-area native living in the british colony, fled before he could be arrested, authorities said
prosecutors said he owns about $20 million in real estate in metropolitan new york and san francisco and controls companies that deal in furs, watches and tobacco
police also arrested john routollo, a former new york city policeman who is accused of helping kon distribute the drugs. strang said there was no evidence routollo was associated with any local crime groups
palmer said kon had been lured to the united states by a ``unique and highly creative'' ruse. but she would not elaborate and it remained unclear why a major asian trafficker would risk a u.s. trip
he has to be here as well as in southeast asia to run his business,'' strang said. ``major traffickers travel between hong kong and new york city all the time, on a regular basis. we're watching them.''
prime minister margaret thatcher's government has produced the most radical budget since it came to power nine years ago, driving home a capitalist revolution with big tax cuts for the wealthy
in parliament on tuesday, the rage of a frustrated opposition boiled over into an unprecedented uproar. one member was expelled and the session was twice suspended while chancellor of the exchequer nigel lawson battled to deliver his budget speech
labor party outrage at the slashing of the top tax rate from 60 percent to 40 percent and conservative government delight at producing the first budget surplus for nearly 20 years underlined the chasm between britain's two major parties
it also signaled that mrs. thatcher, at her most confident since winning a third five-year term last summer, does not plan on yielding an inch to the opposition, or to more widespread pressure to increase spending on the ailing national health service
mrs. thatcher gave what opposition leader neil kinnock called ``handouts to the rich'' in a society that critics charged is increasingly polarized between the better off and the poor, between depressed north and booming south
for the conservatives, tuesday was a high point and a vindication of rigorous policies: the day britain shrugged off years of budget deficits and demonstrated it has combined the fastest growth in western europe with low inflation and a budget funded by the generation of wealth, not borrowing
the united states was able to achieve tax reform, but it lamentably failed to achieve a balanced budget,'' said a jubilant lawson, the top treasury official who presented the budget to the house of commons
what is a substantial achievement is to do both ... what i have been able to tell you is a story of success. a story of the transformation of britain's fortunes.''
the package contained what were widely regarded as the most sweeping tax reforms in modern british history
lawson replaced the previous six brackets of income tax rates with just two, a new base rate cut to 25 percent from 27 percent, and the top 40 percent rate, which is payable on income over $35,700. the corporation tax was unchanged at 35 percent
in a single swoop, the british top tax rate fell to among the lowest in industrialized nations, apart from the united states
lower taxes are a cornerstone of mrs. thatcher's free-enterprise policy, basic to encouraging business, keeping talent from fleeing to tax havens and generating wealth and competitiveness
the government goal, lawson said, is a 20 percent basic tax rate
when mrs. thatcher won power from a socialist administration in 1979 the basic tax rate was 33 percent and top rate 83 percent
apart from doubling taxes on company cars, tuesday's budget was almost all good news for the well-off
for the briton on average earnings of $23,125 a year, tuesday's tax cuts meant an extra $9.25 a week
for big earners, on $185,000 and up, savings began at $462.50 a week
across the tv news programs tuesday night flashed the faces of the even richer, such as retail chain store boss sir ralph halpern who'll be taking home nearly half a million dollars more a year after the tax changes come into force in april
amid jeers from the left and cheers from big business, there were signs the thatcher recipe will work again to allay resentment
we're in the money, folks'' britain's biggest selling daily, the 4-million circulation sun, declared today. the times of london carried a banner headline, ``lawson's tax triumph.''
the budget announcement came just a month before a new tightening up on welfare comes into force
among others things, about 6 million low-income households will lose all or part of rent subsidies because they have savings of more than $11,100
and welfare payments to the poor for household items such as kitchen stoves will be switched to loans
there never was a more obvious example of the rich getting richer and the poor getting demonstrably poorer,'' said labor's finance spokesman, john smith. ``it's an outrageous and disgusting budget.''
retorted tory legislator peter lilley, a treasury spokesman: ``you don't make the poor richer by making the rich poorer.''
maureen johnson has covered british politics since 1980
an asteroid collision with earth may have released enough gas to heat the planet 65 million years ago, causing gradual extinction of dinosaurs and other species by destroying their food, researchers say
the study drew guarded praise from a critic of the theory, because the findings attempt to explain why only certain creatures became extinct and why the extinctions were gradual, not sudden
the asteroid impact theory differs from ones in which scientists said such a collision caused mass extinction by kicking up enough dust to block sunlight, plunging the planet into a freezing darkness that killed plants, a source of food
california institute of technology planetary scientist john o'keefe and geophysicist thomas ahrens reached their conclusion by analyzing experiments in which ahrens and geophysicist manfred lange shot steel bullets into rocks at 4,500 mph
based on the amount of carbon dioxide released by the shattered rocks, the scientists calculated that a 6-mile-diameter asteroid hitting limestone or other carbon-rich rocks on earth would have released enough carbon dioxide to increase the amount of the gas in the atmosphere two to five times
such an increase in the gas, which traps solar heat like glass in a greenhouse, could have caused a ``greenhouse effect'' that warmed the planet by 9 to 36 degrees fahrenheit for 10,000 years after the asteroid struck, ahrens said tuesday
the leafy plants which dinosaurs ate were selectively destroyed'' by the heat while other plants survived, ahrens said. ``so there was probably (increased) competition for available food, and eventually food supplies declined to a point where different species, including the dinosaurs, became extinct in a less-than-sudden manner.''
fossils show dinosaurs and other creatures became extinct gradually, while many species survived. many biologists and paleontologists argue the mass extinction 65 million years ago was caused by gradual climate change, not an asteroid or other sudden catastrophe
william clemens, paleontology chairman at the university of california, berkeley, and a leading critic of asteroid theories, said he was skeptical of the o'keefe-ahrens theory because the dinosaurs started to die earlier than 65 million years ago
but he called their study ``clearly a positive step'' because it is consistent with gradual, selective extinction
o'keefe will present the study thursday in houston at the 19th lunar and planetary science conference
scientists debating the dinosaurs' extinction fall into two main camps: those who blame gradual climate change and those who blame catastrophe. catastrophe theorists disagree on whether an asteroid or gigantic volcanic eruption was to blame
geophysicist charles officer of dartmouth college said he believes the o'keefe-ahrens theory does not have merit because geologic evidence supports the theory that volcanoes spewed enough ash skyward to block sunlight and cause mass extinction
geochemist frank kyte, of the university of california, los angeles, disagreed, saying the theory that the asteroid triggered greenhouse warming of the atmosphere is probably sound
while other scientists previously suggested the greenhouse effect caused the extinctions, they said the carbon dioxide was generated by volcanoes, changes in ocean circulation, or acid rain that dissolved carbon-rich rocks
it is important to learn what killed the dinosaurs because ``it behooves us to find out if we're just sort of sitting here awaiting another (asteroid) impact to seal our doom, or if some of the things we're doing to the environment might ... lead to the extinction of many species,'' clemens said
scientists believe rising levels of carbon dixoide and other greenhouse gases will warm earth 3 to 5 degrees by the year 2050, possibly causing crop-threatening droughts and partly melting polar ice caps to raise sea levels and threaten coastal cities
ahrens said an asteroid impact not only may have triggered greenhouse heating, but possibly caused chemical reactions that formed intense acid rain, which either killed many creatures directly or wiped out their food plants. clemens, however, wondered how birds and other surviving species could have hidden from the corrosive downpour. corruption</head>
hundreds of prison guards here have engaged in corruption including drug sales and aiding escapes, the district attorney said in announcing the first nine arrests from a continuing investigation
authorities say seven guards, one prison cook and an inmate were charged as a result of ``operation ferret,'' an investigation begun 18 months ago
the investigation will potentially yield the largest number of arrests related to official misconduct by correctional officers in this country's history,'' district attorney ronald castille told a news conference tuesday
we are gathering the evidence to present to the special grand jury that will lead to the arrest or discipline of hundreds of guards over the coming months,'' castille said
the crimes include selling drugs to inmates, bringing money and other contraband into the city's five prisons and providing handcuff keys to aid escapes, castille said
the investigation will lead to the exposure and elimination of a massive network of corruption and criminal activity among self-serving philadelphia prison employees and prison inmates,'' castille said
prison superintendent edward lyons acknowledged that employees targeted in the investigation will continue to guard inmates until charged. he said the situation will pose no security problems
we have a sufficient number of employees to handle the system,'' lyons said. ``we have stepped up recruiting activities. and as soon as charges are filed by the grand jury, we will suspend and fire.''
the prison system houses up to 9,000 inmates and employs 1,400 guards and 350 other workers
the two instances cited in the grand jury's report involved one guard, the cook and an inmate in an escape and six guards in a beating that hospitalized an inmate who reported a guard sleeping at his post
castille declined to say how many escapes guards allowed
police commissioner kevin tucker said a federally financed organized crime law enforcement network aided the investigation, which according to castille relied on undercover officers, cooperating inmates and guards and electronic surveillance
guard dennis tiest, 42; prison cook stanley suder, 37; and inmate kenneth lynch, 39, were charged with helping inmate john longendorfer escape from the laurel hall minimum-security unit in 1987
longendorfer, who was serving time for terroristic threats and indecent assault, cooperated in the investigation, allowing authorities to videotape the escape, according to court documents
suder accepted a $1,000 bribe and a 1987 pontiac grand am, castille said
the six other guards were charged with an unprovoked physical assault on inmate william kennedy on feb. 16
those charged were officers edward ricks, 32; sammie rogers, 41; clemon davis, 35; christ taylor, 50; charles favano, 44; and sgt. peter jones, 50
castille said the investigation of the assault uncovered other reports of brutality
there is no question there is a serious problem within the walls of the prisons, and with these arrests, starting now, we hope to send out two messages,'' said lyons
one, to those employees engaged in criminal activities that we will find them and arrest them, and to those employees who discharge their services with pride, we say to them that we need you.''
other corruption cases in philadelphia have resulted in the conviction of 34 police officers since 1983 on federal bribery and conspiracy charges. they included a deputy commissioner for extorting money from vice figures. twelve judges were suspended last year for allegedly accepting cash from roofers' union members. three of the judges have been convicted of bribery in recent months.  
sal piro has seen the rocky horror picture show 1,100 times. diane witt has auburn hair 10 feet long when straight _ tresses even rapunzel would envy
they, and the world's fastest talker, were among the guests at tuesday's official reopening of the guinness book of records' spruced-up museum of ``amazing feats and astonishing facts'' in the empire state building
since 1977, 250,000 visitors a year have slaked their curiosity at the museum, forking over an admission price of $3.50 for adults and $2.50 for children, director ken volk said
at the reopening, boxer thomas hearns of detroit was inducted into guinness for earning world titles in four weight classes
i'm a very proud man at this moment,'' he said. ``this is something that my kids can look upon.''
around him, guinness alumni toasted the renovation amid replicas of the world's biggest produce (carrot, 15 pounds 7 ounces, i.g. scott, new zealand, 1978) and videotapes of human feeding frenzies (100 yards of spaghetti, 27.75 seconds), complete with sounds of swallowing and belching
calliope music wafted from the circus exhibit as marilyn vos savant _ whose iq of 228 made her the world's smartest person _ fielded reporters' highbrow questions about intellect, intuition and upbringing
i really do enjoy the guinness book,'' insisted savant, who attended on the arm of her husband, artificial heart inventor dr. robert jarvik. ``i like the idea of somebody out there being able to be an authority without having any kind of message.''
savant and the others stood aside as ms. witt of worcester, mass., unleashed 9 feet, 2 inches of auburn hair. she didn't get the 30 minutes she needed to comb out the waves to reach her record length of 10 feet
fran capo of queens, fast talker extraordinaire, showed her stuff with a rapid-fire biblical passage. ``i save money on long-distance bills,'' she noted
bruce block of cincinnati, a record-holder for balancing 135 cigar boxes on his chin, gave a 5-second demonstration; and albert lucas of las vegas tossed around four tennis rackets to show how he seized the most guinness records for juggling
tom harrington of peekskill, leader of the world domino spectacular team, staged a topple. but gary stewart of reading, ohio, on record for 130 pogo stick jumps, was there sans stick
manhattan's piro, who has seen the rocky horror picture show 1,100 times, said, ``i only go twice a week. some people go to the same bar night after night.''
in his spare time, piro, a writer, goes to other movies, plays chess and watches tv. he's seen the soap opera ``all my children'' every day for five years
an air force captain's wife who is dying from breast cancer that went undiagnosed by military doctors for almost two years has won more than $1 million in damages from the government
u.s. district judge joseph h. young awarded sandra m. edwards, 34, of camp springs, and her husband, bryan, $550,000 in compensatory damages, $415,000 for lost earnings and $100,000 for medical expenses she is expected to incur
neither consoling words nor monetary damages can be expected to fully compensate the truly grievous injury mrs. edwards sustained and will continue to endure,'' the judge said in his opinion, which was issued friday
mrs. edwards, whose doctors have given her anywhere from a few months to a year to live, said in court that she ``would like other women to be aware'' of what happened to her
she said women who find breast lumps ``shouldn't be humiliated by their doctors and shouldn't be embarrassed to get a second or third opinion'' if they are unsatisfied with their diagnoses
mrs. edwards, a former civilian navy employee and the mother of a 3-year-old son, testified last month that she sought medical help from military doctors in 1984 and 1985 after she felt a lump in her right breast and experienced bleeding from the nipple
both times, her male doctors gave her mammograms and blood tests, but told her the lump was nothing to worry about, she said
one physician told her he thought she needed psychological help because of her fears of the disease, she testified
a biopsy, ordered by a female military physician in late 1985 showed that the lump was malignant. she underwent a radical modified mastectomy and reconstructive surgery in january 1986, at the national cancer institute in bethesda
she quit her job to recuperate and joined her husband in west germany, but the cancer reappeared. last december, her doctors said cancer had spread to her brain, liver and one lung
assistant u.s. attorney barbara s. sale said in court that she was not authorized by the justice department to admit liability, but she did not defend against the malpractice charge
william o.p. snead 3rd, the edwards' lawyer, accused the military doctors of ``conduct far outside minimally acceptable standards.''
a hearing is set for today on whether the delegate slates of republican presidential candidates pat robertson and sen. bob dole should be on the primary ballot in all of new york's 34 congressional districts
supporters of the two gop contenders filed a civil rights action at federal court in manhattan monday, claiming that state election laws violate the voting rights act by making it unfairly difficult for their candidates to compete for delegates in the april 19 new york primary
u.s. district judge leonard b. sand scheduled the hearing on a request by dole and robertson supporters that he should order delegate slates for their candidates placed on the ballot in every congressional district, pending the outcome of the lawsuit
under state law, candidates had to get 1,250 signatures on petitions from registered republicans in each of the state's 34 congressional districts to get their delegate slates on the ballot. all the signatures had to be gathered between jan. 5 and feb. 11, 1988
only vice president george bush's campaign was able to accomplish that and as a result, bush slates are running unopposed in about half the districts, according to the lawsuit. caucuses</head>
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis holds a strong lead over jesse jackson according to results released from last week's democratic presidential precinct caucuses by washington state party officials
with about 68 percent of the precincts reporting the results of last tuesday's balloting, dukakis had 45 percent, jackson 35 percent, and 14 percent were uncommitted
all the other candidates were well off the pace, with illinois sen. paul simon a weak fourth at 4 percent, tennessee sen. albert gore jr. at 2 percent and rep. richard gephardt of missouri with 1 percent
the democratic party made no effort to collect results statewide on caucus night, gathering precinct returns slowly by mail instead
republicans say it will be at least another week before county chairmen submit the names of gop delegates elected in last week's precinct caucuses
tennessee sen. albert gore jr.'s bid for the democratic presidential nomination has been endorsed by new york state assembly majority leader james tallon
in making his announcement tuesday, the binghamton democrat and former chairman of the assembly's health committee stressed gore's work on the federal organ transplant act and his grasp of new technologies
the legislature's no. 1 democrat, assembly speaker mel miller of brooklyn, has yet to endorse any of the democratic candidates although his wife is running in the state's april 19 presidential primary as a prospective gore delegate
i've been speaking to the gore people more frequently than anybody else, but i've not finally made a decision,'' said miller
also not taking sides yet is new york's top democrat, gov. mario cuomo. cuomo has said he doesn't know when, or even if, he will endorse any of the democratic candidates
cuomo has bridled at suggestions that he's holding off an endorsement because he's hoping a deadlocked national convention would turn to him as a candidate. while cuomo has said he won't seek the nomination, he's refused to rule out accepting a draft for the nomination if there's a deadlocked convention
a gubernatorial task force has proposed that new yorkers be allowed to register and vote on election day
issuing a 94-page report tuesday, the governor's task force on encouraging electoral participation noted that maine, minnesota and wisconsin had ``experienced a substantial increase in voter turnout'' after switching to such a system
the 17-member commission included officials from gov. marion cuomo's administration, the state legislature, the new york state and city boards of elections, college student representatives and private citizens
the task force conducted a poll of 3,500 new yorkers and talked to focus groups. cuomo said it had done all of that for ``less than $20,000.''
in the end, the task force came up with 30 recommendations to get more new yorkers to the polls by, among other things, allowing college students to register to vote in their college communities when they register for classes
the group also recommended that elementary and secondary schools be required to offer classes that stress the importance of voting, that public employees be allowed to assist new yorkers in filling out voter registration cards, and that the state create a permanent state primary day. the state primary day has varied from summer to fall during recent elections. it is scheduled for sept. 8 this year
apathy often is blamed for low voter turnouts, but the real reason people don't go to the polls may be found in examining voter registration laws, says a university of michigan researcher
many states have voter registration laws that discriminate against the electorate by making it difficult to register, contends political science professor steven j. rosenstone, who is coordinating a nationwide study of registration laws
rosenstone said preliminary research suggests that modified voter registration laws would increase overall voter turnout by about 9 percent, bringing about 16 million more people to the polls
blacks, hispanics and the poor would benefit the most from the changes,'' said rosenstone, who is coordinating the nationwide project funded by the ford foundation
in most states, voters have to register weeks before interest peaks on election day, leave work early or travel an inconvenient distance to the registration office, and finally, stand in a long line, rosenstone said
almost half the 180 million eligible u.s. voters, including more than half of the 20 million eligible black voters, aren't expected to go to the polls in november, rosenstone said
contrast this situation to canada, where registration officials go door to door to make sure every eligible voter is on the rolls. their election-day turnout averages about 68 percent _ about 15 percent higher than in the united states,'' he said
a jury awarded $1.45 million to a man left paralyzed from a 1985 wasp sting at an inn
the jury tuesday awarded the money to joseph febesh, 68, after finding the the fox hollow inn of woodbury liable for the sting that within an hour put him into a three-week coma
febesh, former manager of the golf program at the doral country club in miami beach, is unable to talk, feed himself or use his arms and legs in any way at all, according to his lawyer joseph napoli
febesh's wife, shirley, was awarded $250,000 for loss of her husband's companionship and services
the febeshes were at a 50th wedding anniversary party in the garden of the inn when they noticed yellow jackets around the garbage and the food. they told the head waiter, who shrugged off the situation, napoli said, and about an hour later febesh was stung in the hand
napoli said the wasp's venom attacked febesh's brain stem and part of his spinal cord, putting him in a coma. he said febesh, paralyzed since regaining consciousness, is undergoing physical therapy at a miami hospital
the jury, after a 10-day trial before state supreme court justice harold baer, awarded $3.4 million to the febeshes. the court reduced the verdict by half after the jury found the couple 50 percent negligent
lawyers for the inn argued that the febeshes should have left the area if they were worried about the yellow jackets
a cruise ship crew battled an engine fire early today in the gulf of mexico, and u.s. coast guard cutters and planes were steaming to the vessel, officials said
the scandinavian star was about 35 miles off isla mujeres, a mexican island north of the tourist resort cancun in the yucatan peninsula, coast guard lt. jim mazzonna said from the agency's miami office
the cruiseliner's skipper was unsure at 4:20 a.m. est if his crew had been able to douse the flames, said mazzonna, who wasn't sure how many passengers were aboard the ship or if any injuries had occurred
we're waiting for details,'' he said
besides coast guard cutters, the canada star cruiseliner was en route to evacuate scandinavian star passengers if needed, mazzonna said
