former south korean president chun doo-hwan will visit the united states for three weeks as a guest of president reagan, chun's aides said today
chun is scheduled to meet reagan next wednesday to discuss regional and world affairs. he will remain in the united states for talks with former presidents richard nixon and gerald ford, former secretary of state henry kissinger and defense department and cia officials, the aides said
chun, who left office feb. 26, heads the advisory council of elder statesmen, a presidential advisory group
last month's transfer of power was the first peaceful one in modern south korean history. chun was replaced by his chosen successor, roh tae-woo, who won last december's presidential elections against a divided opposition
gov. buddy roemer, elected on the promise of ending waste in government and changing louisiana's image of cronyism, dove headfirst into the state's financial problems by ordering budget cuts and calling the legislature into special session
during his first full day in office tuesday, roemer also huddled with legislative leaders, visited with foreign dignitaries and took time out to pose for his official portrait
roemer went to work on measures to solve the fiscal crisis immediately after his oct. 24 election victory over gov. edwin edwards and said tuesday included ``more of the same.''
i really feel like i've been doing this for 100 days,'' he said at a news conference. ``i feel the same. i'm still feel excited about it after 24 hours. i feel good getting into the substance of it.''
just hours after he was inaugurated monday, roemer turned down a stay of execution for wayne felde, convicted of killing a shreveport police officer in 1978. felde died in the electric chair shortly after midnight
while roemer settled into his new job, former officials of the edwards administration jammed the three main elevators in louisiana's skyscraper capitol, moving out boxes of personal belongings
roemer ordered $7.9 million in immediate spending cuts and summoned the legislature into a 10-day special session next monday to consider government reorganization and giving him emergency power to cut spending through the rest of the fiscal year without lawmakers' approval
the largest of the new cuts include $2.6 million from the department of health and human resources, $2.2 million from the department of public safety, and about $1.1 million from the vocational education system
louisiana faces an accumulated four-year budget deficit and cash shortfall of $1.2 billion
the governor can cut up to 20 percent from any budget unit without legislative approval. roemer said one idea under consideration was asking for the power to cut up to 20 percent from an entire agency and eliminate entire state programs
the governor also said he was developing other executive orders to save the state 10s millions of dollars, primarily through budget cuts that edwards refused to impose at roemer's request
we are in a position in this fiscal year where the numbers drive the policy and not the policy driving the numbers,'' roemer said. ``when this state is busted, broke, when the deficit is approaching a number too large to comprehend, the numbers are driving this now.''
to alleviate a cash-flow deficit that threatens to shut down state government, about $156 million in additional cuts from the state's $5.3 billion budget will have to be found, roemer said
edwards approved about $36 million in reductions before leaving office and roemer's budget team plans to delay state payments to retirement systems, hold up income tax refund checks and push one state payday into the next fiscal year to conserve cash
roemer has said new taxes probably will be needed to overcome the budget deficit. however, he said that topic would not be considered during the special session
roemer met tuesday with representatives of the government of taiwan about the possibility of building an industrial plant in louisiana. after monday's inauguration, the governor met with business representatives from japan and nigeria
