confusion and fear generated by aids has created an unlimited audience for quacks who are expected to take in $1 billion this year, speakers at the national health fraud conference said
many persons who have aids will try anything to defeat it; many who don't have aids will try anything to avoid it,'' said dr. john h. renner, director of the national health information center in kansas city. ``that makes it easy for quacks to convert every trick in their repertoire into an aids treatment or preventative.''
dr. robert e. windom, assistant secretary for health of the u.s. department of health and human services, called tuesday for health professionals to join in an anti-fraud effort
renner said he's seen fraudulent aids remedies that include processed pond scum, hydrogen peroxide injections, the food preservative bht, pills derived from aids-infected mice and ``herbal'' capsules containing poisonous metals
we've even discovered a phony doctor who, for a $100 fee, was injecting his patients with a processed byproduct of their own urine,'' he said
about 400 people attended the two-day conference on health fraud, including representatives of law enforcement agencies, consumer groups, medicine, insurance companies and business
michael r. botwin, a california deputy attorney general, said it was understandable that people faced with aids would try any treatment, and that it some cases quack treatments provided a psychological boost
however, many so-called aids treatments are sold with scare tactics, pose health hazards, or carry the risk of substantial financial loss,'' he said. gun</head>
tape recordings indicate president corazon aquino's husband was killed with a gun other than that which officials claim was the murder weapon, a japanese sound expert testified today
based on the tapes of voices, footsteps and gunfire, matsumi suzuki also identified four soldiers as the ones who shouted the tagalog words ``this is it,'' ``let me do it'' and ``shoot'' seconds before former sen. benigno aquino jr. was shot and killed on aug. 21, 1983
suzuki, president of the japan acoustics institute of tokyo, made the statements at the trial of 34 soldiers and three civilians accused of murdering aquino and rolando galman, an alleged communist agent initially tagged as the assassin
aquino was killed as he walked down the stairway from a china airlines plane to the tarmac at manila airport under military escort. he was returning to the philippines from three years' exile in the united states. galman was shot and killed by soldiers immediately after aquino fell
suzuki, speaking in japanese through an interpreter, said he reached his conclusions after analyzing sounds picked up by journalists' tape recorders during the assassination and the test firing of various types of guns in studios in japan and the united states
chief prosecutor raul gonzales told reporters that suzuki's testimony supports the prosecution's claim that aquino was shot on the stairway, where only soldiers were in a position to shoot him in the back of the head
the military under deposed president ferdinand marcos claimed aquino was shot by galman on the tarmac with a .357-caliber magnum revolver
in his testimony, suzuki said an analysis of the tape recordings show that the first shot, which has been established as the one that killed aquino, could have come only from a .45-caliber pistol
the sound of the gunshot was close to the sound of a .45-caliber automatic pistol,'' suzuki said. ``the sound was quite different to a great degree from the sound coming from a .357 magnum.''
suzuki said the sound of the footsteps of aquino and his four soldier escorts were clearly picked up by two boom microphones extended over the top of the stairway, as the party began descending
we can clearly analyze the sound of the first step to the eleventh step,'' suzuki said referring to the stairway, which had 21 rungs. ``after the eleventh step ... the sound of gunfire was heard.''
suzuki said he could not pinpoint the step where aquino was shot but calculated it was between the 11th and 15th rungs
the tapes also picked up the words ``eto na'' (this is it), followed by ``ako na. ako na'' (let me do it. let me do it) and ``pusila. pusila.'' (shoot. shoot
suzuki said the words ``eto na'' were uttered by lt. jesus de castro, chief of the security detail assigned to aquino, who remained at the top of the stairs while aquino was led down
the words ``let me do it'' were said by sgts. claro lat and arnulfo de mesa one after the other, suzuki said
he said the fatal gunshot came after both castro and constable 1st class mario lazaga shouted ``shoot!'' one after the other
suzuki said he identified the voices by comparing voice prints on the tapes with tape-recorded statements made by soldiers during a formal investigation shortly after the murder. a five-member board had required all the soldiers who escorted aquino to say those words
a texas businessman and prominent democratic party fund-raiser with ties to house speaker jim wright has been indicted by a federal grand jury in an alleged land fraud
thomas merrill gaubert of desoto, texas, was accused tuesday of pocketing $5.6 million of $8 million he persuaded the capitol federal savings and loan association into investing in a condominium project he was developing in texas
the mount pleasant, iowa, savings and loan was closed in may, when federal regulators said its texas investment and other poorly secured loans had left the company with a negative net worth of $65 million
gaubert, 48, former owner of the independent american savings association in irving, texas, contributed $7,000 to two wright political committees in 1985
in the fall of 1986, wright, d-texas, then house majority leader, arranged a 2{-hour meeting between federal home loan bank board chairman edwin gray and gaubert to air gaubert's complaints about his s&amp;l's treatment by the board
wright said he was simply encouraging gray to ensure that his agency was being fair to one of wright's constituents
gaubert is accused of using the s&amp;l to finance a ``land flip'' in a dallas county, texas, condominium project he was developing in 1982 and 1983
gaubert bought about 44 acres of land about 11 miles south of downtown dallas at less than 50 cents per square foot, then sold it the same day through a middleman to 22 buyers at $5.25 per square foot, the indictment alleged
he is accused of not telling capitol federal officials that he owned the land and planned to sell it to investors at inflated prices
the indictment charges gaubert with three counts of wire fraud and one count of making false statements to a federally insured financial institution
i am confident that i will be vindicated,'' gaubert said tuesday. ``the transaction in the indictment occurred five years ago and all of the funds initially borrowed from capitol savings were repaid in 1985.''
no arraignment date has been set for gaubert
the s&amp;l industry in texas, which leads the nation in losses and failures, is the focus of a huge federal criminal investigation that has led to a number of indictments of prominent businessmen
the maximum penalty for wire fraud is a $1,000 fine and five years in prison. making false statements to a federally insured financial institution carries a maximum $5,000 fine and two years in prison
voters in the illinois primary stopped a political comeback by former chicago mayor jane byrne and set up a congressional rematch between house minority leader bob michel and his 1982 challenger
mrs. byrne lost her race tuesday for the democratic nomination for clerk of the circuit court in cook county to aurelia pucinski, who was endorsed by the county party organization. with 92 percent of the vote in, mrs. byrne trailed mrs. pucinski 53 percent to 38 percent
it means that when the people spoke, they apparently shouted. ... i am very good at taking hints,'' said mrs. byrne, loser of two previous bids to regain the mayor's office she lost in 1983 to harold washington
asked whether she would consider running for office again, she said, ``i'm not even thinking of it right now.''
edward vrdolyak, a former democratic power broker who left the party, was unopposed on the republican side and will face mrs. pucinski in november
