southern illinois democrats chose a nominee who never finished college and doesn't hold a law degree for an illinois supreme court vacancy. appellate justice horace calvo of glen carbon, who attended college and law school but never earned a degree, won the nomination with 34 percent of the 49,817 votes cast
chicago voters in precincts around wrigley field, the only major league stadium without night baseball, voted three-to-one in a non-binding referendum against the city council's decision to add lights to the historic home of the cubs
in a citywide non-binding referendum, voters advised against sending illinois national guard troops to train in central america
michel, president reagan's point man in congress, easily defeated tazewell county board chairman james e. unsicker. with 96 percent of the votes counted, michel had 86 percent to unsicker's 14 percent
stephens coasted through the democratic primary, receiving 88 percent of the vote to justin zachary west's 12 percent
in the 21st congressional district, where retiring democratic rep. melvin price has served for 44 years, st. clair county board chairman jerry f. costello won a four-man race for the democratic nomination. he'll face republican robert h. ``bob'' gaffner in november
in the 22nd district, state sen. glenn poshard of carterville will carry the democratic standard in november against republican patrick j. kelley of carbondale. the two are vying to succeed retiring rep. kenneth gray, who served 12 terms in two capitol hill stints since 1955
tuesday's primary also saw the return of followers of political extremist lyndon larouche on the ballot for a range of positions from president to county register of deeds. unlike two years ago when two larouche candidates were nominated for lieutenant governor and secretary of state, none of the candidates succeeded
here is sulome, our daughter, wishing you a safe return home, daddy. she often asks about you. wondering which of all the planes she is seeing will be the one bringing daddy home....'' _ madeleine anderson, whose letter to her husband, terry anderson, was printed in two lebanese newspapers on the third anniversary of his abduction in moslem west beirut
