many times i was wondering, `is this where he slipped? is this where he lost it?''' _ vern tejas, who became the first mountaineer to conquer mount mckinley alone in winter, referring to naomi uemura, the only other person to successfully reach the 20,320-foot summit solo in winter but who disappeared during his descent
voters soundly defeated a proposal to change the town's name to sleepy hollow, a historic moniker made famous by the washington irving story of the headless horseman
the vote tuesday was 1,322 against the name change and 794 in favor, said alison fine, a village trustee
sleepy hollow was the 17th century dutch description of the hudson river area north of new york city
advocates of the name change said the village of 8,000 was too often confused with neighboring tarrytown and needed a new image to attract business and tourist money. opponents said changing the name would cause more confusion and might cost more than $50,000
stacy kelly, a member of the sleepy hollow committee, said she was disappointed, but added, ``we raised the consciousness of people here that we need a long-term vision for the village.''
a university of texas astronomer has observed the first ghostly light ``echoes'' from supernova 1987a, an exploding star that lighted the southern skies in february 1987, the university announced
arlin crotts made the observations at the carnegie institution of washington's las campanas observatory in chile, the university announced tuesday
theories predict that when a supernova explodes, some light from the flash would light up or reflect off dusty clouds of gas and show up as faint arcs of light long after the peak brightness of the supernova
until now, however, no supernova has been close enough and bright enough to test this prediction, ut spokesman danny ewald said
crotts found two arcs of light corresponding to echoes from supernova 1987a. the echoed light should be that which was emitted when the supernova was at its brightest, some 80 days after the explosion was detected
crotts said the discovery of the light echo from supernova 1987a was confirmation of a basic prediction on how a supernova should behave
the echo is useful for mapping the clouds of gas and dust that surround the supernova, much as terrain-mapping radar gives information on and contours, ut said in a statement announcing the discovery
according to scientists, previously observed supernovae have been so far distant from earth that light echoes were undistinguishable from the source, and the later-arriving light was misinterpreted as slower decay of the supernova. rally</head>
authorities today announced the release of eight opposition leaders jailed while 10,000 anti-government demonstrators marched through budapest in hungary's largest street protest since the 1956 uprising
the state news agency mti said writer miklos haraszti and the other seven were detained for ``intenting to disturb'' tuesday's ceremonies commemorating the 140th anniversary of hungary's rebellion against austrian rule
after a communist party-organized demonstration on tuesday, the protesters marched down the capital's main boulevards shouting ``democracy'' and chanting slogans demanding a free press and free elections
police turned out in force but did not disturb the march
speakers at a rally after the march criticized the soviet system
the time is over for self-appointed governments,'' leading dissident gabor miklos tamas told the crowd, referring to the nation's communist authorities. ``a modern democracy has to be created with a new constitution and free elections.''
haraszti, reached by telephone from vienna today, said he and the other dissident intellectuals were taken to the gyuejtoefoeghaz prison outside budapest, where imre nagy, premier during the 1956 revolution, was executed
i was picked up by police at 5 a.m. and set free around midnight,'' haraszti said. ``we were all held in separate cells.''
haraszti said that, in days preceding tuesday's anniversary, authorities launched a campaign to try to discourage young people from taking part
in an attempt to keep the number of demonstrators low, he said, police searched houses, seized underground literature and visited high schools, apparently to intimidate students
he said he did not think any of the dissidents detained tuesday had been fined or charged
the others are sociologist ottilia solt, publisher gabor demszky, artist tamas molnar, gyoergy gado, jenoe nagy and two lesser known dissidents, sandor racz and robert palinkas
on tuesday, the crowd marched to monuments to national heroes, paying particular tribute to firebrand poet sandor petoefi, whose name is symbolic of resistance to foreign domination of hungary
a 1948 rebellion in hungary was put down a year later with the help of russian troops. in 1956, soviet troops again helped suppress a nationalist uprising
hungarian dissidents have staged unofficial demonstrations on march 15 every year since 1973. police generally have shown restraint, although dozens of officers clashed violently with protesters in 1986
roza demszky, wife of the detained publisher, read her husband's speech to the crowd. the soviet system has led hungary into a crisis ``and does not show any way out,'' she said
hungary recently has imposed an austerity program to try to reverse economic stagnation
a former auto-parts salesman whose collection of orchids was among the world's largest has died, leaving his $5 million estate and its nearly 12,000 orchids to the american orchid society
lewis vaughn died monday at age 92
it's just kind of special to see a man's life turned into such beauty and love,'' said pat pepper schwab, the city's vice mayor
he was our best friend, there's no doubt about it,'' said lee cooke, executive director of the society. ``he's going to be very sadly missed.''
vaughn and his late wife, varina, bought their first orchid about 50 years ago. he became a leading amateur grower _ one of the first to develop the yellow phalaenopsis _ and his private collection is among the world's largest
somebody said, `try an orchid,' and i bought one in a pot, and the blame thing bloomed. that was a cattleya, c. bowringiana. and i still have a cutting from it on the mango tree by the office,'' vaughn said in a 1987 interview
on tuesday, about 9,000 of vaughn's orchids were blooming
it's a little bit of heaven here,'' cooke said
vaughn, who was childless, is survived by six nieces and nephews. funeral services were scheduled for friday afternoon here
olive carey, veteran actress of hollywood's golden age and wife and mother to a pair of famous harry careys, has died. she was 92
born olive golden on jan. 31, 1896, she came from a performing family headed by her father, famed vaudeville entertainer george fuller golden
mrs. carey died of natural causes at her home sunday
the actress destined to wed actor harry carey appeared on screen with him in the 1914 silent movie, ``the sorrowful shore.'' she later worked with director d.w. griffith
while the careys worked under contract for universal studios, she introduced her husband to a 21-year-old prop man, john ford. she persuaded carey to allow the unknown ford to direct his first two-reel western, ``the soul herder.''
ford went on to rank among the top directors in film history
they became lifelong friends along with another budding young western actor, john wayne
mrs. carey made several films with ford, wayne, her husband and their son, harry carey jr
when carey died in 1947, mrs. carey came out of retirement to act in such films as ``the searchers,'' ``the alamo'' and ``two rode together.''
she has appeared with other hollywood greats such as jimmy stewart, richard widmark, vera miles and natalie wood
mrs. carey is survived by a sister, mignonne, her son, harry carey jr., a daughter, cappy carey, six grandchildren and seven great-grandchildren
she was to be memorialized today in a private ceremony at her home about 75 miles northwest of downtown los angeles
ranchers whose rangeland was devastated by a wildfire that killed about 200 head of cattle are receiving gifts of about 350,000 pounds of hay daily to keep their operations going, officials say
many cities around the state are conducting hay drives for ranchers affected by the fire, said alan heirman of the federal soil conservation service
we have received a tremendous response to the hay program,'' heirman said tuesday. ``today, we received about 100 different donations of hay, with promises of close to 15,000 square bales and 500 to 1,000 round bales.''
the wildfire charred an estimated 350,000 acres of rangeland before it was declared under control monday afternoon. weary firefighters who had fought the blaze since last thursday were sent home tuesday
a frost helped cool the ground and extinguish the blaze, said mahlon hammetter, a spokesman for the texas forest service. but rain is needed to help rejuvenate the scorched ground, he said
we are saving a lot of cattle,'' said heirman. ``if we can get some rain, we may see them continue to live. everybody's praying for rain right now.''
about 200 cattle died on 53 ranches in shackelford county, he said, and about 500 head were injured
