the afghanistan peace talks resumed today with no new target date for their completion and growing impatience in moscow, which renewed charges that the united states and pakistan were blocking the pact's progress
afghan foreign minister abdul wakil, speaking at a news conference, also said that pakistan was delaying progress on a settlement but said afghanistan sees no reason to suspend the talks, now in their sixth year
in moscow, soviet foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze told u.s. ambassador jack matlock that the kremlin wants the united states and pakistan to stop ``artificially procrastinating'' on an agreement, the tass news agency said
the soviets offered fresh assurances, however, that it would still remove its estimated 115,000 troops two months after a settlement is signed. soviet troops intervened in afghanistan in 1979 and are helping the marxist government fight u.s.-backed moslem guerrillas
at issue were pakistan's demand for a broad-based transitional government to replace the current, soviet-backed adminsitration in kabul, and for a simultaneous end to military assistance to the warring sides
pakistan argues that only a government replacing the present administration of president najib could guarantee that a peace settlement would be put in place and ensure the safe return of more than 5 million refugees
pakistan, where most of the afghan refugees live, has been representing the guerrilla movement during the u.n.-sponsored talks
the importance of a simultaneous cut-off of superpower military aid has been particularly stressed by washington. it would mean that soviet aid to its allies in kabul would have to end at the same time as aid to the guerrillas who get the bulk of their supplies from the united states
an official soviet statement issued tuesday in moscow condemned attempts ``to dictate to the u.s.s.r and afghanistan how they should build their bilateral relations.''
the soviet statement confirmed, however, that the decision to pull out the troops still stands and that the withdrawal would begin two months after the signing of a geneva settlement
in moscow, tass said the discussion between shevardnadze and matlock dealt mostly with the afghanistan issue
u.s. embassy spokesman richard gilbert confirmed that matlock had a meeting with shevardnadze that included a discussion on afghanistan, but said it is embassy policy not to disclose details of diplomatic exchanges
the ambassador's attention was drawn to the soviet government's statement of march 15, which contains a principled assessment of the unsatisfactory situation at the afghan-pakistani talks in geneva, and also contains a clear-cut qualification of the actions of pakistan and the united states which are artifically procrastinating the signing of actually agreed-upon accords,'' tass said
in geneva, wakil told reporters that pakistan's stand amounted to a ``unilateral suspension'' and would get the talks nowhere
wakil spoke shortly before a new session with u.n. undersecretary general diego cordovez, the intermediary in the talks. it was the first meeting since the talks failed to meet the target of march 15 set by soviet leader mikhail gorbachev for their conclusion
he charged that pakistan had organized the war which had already led also to ``tragic events'' on pakistan's side. he warned that allowing the conflict to continue would pose a threat to the entire region. graf pvs, ``i'm running ...''</note>
jesse jackson's best week in the 1988 campaign brought seven victories in seven days, but his streak ended with a disappointing second-place finish in illinois that highlighted the obstacles he faces in the big-state primaries to come
jackson drew less than 10 percent of the white vote in tuesday's primary
nevertheless, jackson said today that he has broader support than any other candidate. ``when you get second place in idaho and in florida, and minnesota, vermont, maine, you're getting white vote,'' he said on nbc's ``today'' show
when it's all said and done, it's just democratic votes. i have the most democratic votes. i expect to have the most democratic delegates.''
jackson is locked in a tight race with massachusetts gov. michael dukakis for the lead in the delegate count
i'm running no. 1 in popular votes and in delegate votes,'' jackson said after the illinois results were known tuesday, overstating the delegate situation a bit. ``illinois has been good to two favorite sons today. it has also given me the lead for the party.''
sen. paul simon of illinois easily won the primary
if i have the most democratic votes and i have the most delegates, i will be the nominee. that is my preoccupation,'' jackson declared
taking a third of the popular vote in illinois, jackson was close to amassing 3 million votes in the first 20 primaries of 1988
before the home-state primary, he had trailed massachusetts gov. michael dukakis slightly in total primary votes, 2.61 million to 2.57 million. dukakis was winning less than 20 percent of the vote in illinois, boosting his total to just over 2.8 million votes
in delegates before the illinois returns, dukakis held the lead over jackson, but his margin was almost wiped out by the illinois returns. dukakis was being shut out in the direct election of delegates in illinois
jackson has proven that he can win votes. and on super tuesday he proved he can win state primaries, taking the top spot in alabama, georgia, louisiana, mississippi and virginia. later in the week he won the caucuses in south carolina and, surprisingly alaska
the calendar now forces him to prove again that he can win primary victories, this time in states not nearly as friendly to his hopes as those in the past week
jackson's showing in his home state of illinois on tuesday illustrates his problem
he swept the black vote in chicago and added less than 10 percent of the white vote to put together a second-place finish to fellow favorite son simon
jackson decried any emphasis on the racial division of the vote, saying ``there is a preoccupation with the ethnic breakdown'' of the balloting
but to win in the states to come, jackson must do better among the white voters while holding the great bulk of a high-turnout black vote
in the major states holding primaries in the next six weeks _ michigan, connecticut, wisconsin, new york and pennsylvania _ there are substantial black populations to give jackson a core of support. but the relative size of the potential black voting bloc is smaller in each of the coming states than it was in the south, where jackson won his primary victories
and, in the industrial states to come, those black voters are heavily concentrated in a few congressional districts
jackson will do quite well in the delegate contests there _ as he did in three districts in illinois _ but without substantial white backing in other districts, his delegate count will not add up as fast as his opponents'
the jackson campaign didn't win any victories in the early going of the presidential season, but he did have some surprisingly powerful showings in states outside his traditional strongholds
he was fourth in iowa and new hampshire. but then he came in a surprising second in the minnesota caucuses on feb. 23. he was second as well in the maine caucuses on feb. 28 and in the vermont primary on march 1
the victory march for jackson began in the region that was his birthplace, the south. jackson won five states across the region on march 8, super tuesday. on saturday, he returned to the state of his birth _ south carolina _ for a big victory in that state's caucuses. he then took first place in the alaska caucuses
looking to the upcoming events, jackson faces the illinois problem again
in michigan, with its caucuses march 26, about 12 percent of the population is black. but only four congressional districts out of 18 had more than 10 percent black population in the 1980 census
in connecticut, only about 7 percent of the population is black, although three of the six congressional districts have substantial minority populations in the march 29 primary
in the wisconsin primary on april 5, the black population is centered in milwaukee, adding up to only about 4 percent statewide
in the big new york contest on april 19, about 14 percent of the population is black. and some 13 of the 34 congressional districts have more than 10 percent minority residents
in pennsylvania _ with an april 26 primary _ the black population is about 9 percent, heavily concentrated in four of the state's 23 congressional districts. and move up reference to yugoslav-moscow break. edits throughout. no pickup.</note>
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev today said the kremlin will find democratic solutions to the recent ethnic unrest in his country, but he stressed there could be no secession from the soviet union
gorbachev, who has been critical of some of his predecessors, indirectly attacked former kremlin leader josef stalin when he referred to yugoslav leader josip broz tito's break with moscow in 1948
the soviet leader also said the superpowers should reduce their naval forces in the mediterranean, and he accused nato of slowing the pace of nuclear disarmament
in his address to the yugoslav parliament, gorbachev said ethnic relations are ``one of the most important and delicate issues'' in the soviet union and that it would be unnatural to think they were `once and for all resolved.'''
yugoslavia itself is an ethnically diverse nation of six republics and two autonomous regions _ kosovo and vojvodina _ and is plagued by rising ethnic tensions as the economic situation worsens
there are both ``certain difficulties inherited from the past'' and other ``problems created by the passage of time and the changes in the economic life of society,'' gorbachev said
he made no mention of riots that killed at least 32 people in the azerbaijani city of sumgait in february, nor of recent mass protests by armenians demanding the return of a largely armenian region put under the administration of azerbaijan in 1923
but he said that on ethnic problems, ``we are determined to reach democratic solutions which would correspond to the interest of each and every nation ... and our entire socialist society.''
gorbachev indicated, however, there could be no question of secession, saying that each region within soviet borders has ``indissoluble links'' with the rest of the country. the soviet union is comprised of 15 republics
in the baltic states of the north, some activists want independence from moscow
gorbachev's itinerary does not include kosovo, yugoslavia's most ethnically troubled area, but he will travel to slovenia, the most developed republic
in a wide-ranging 40-minute speech, gorbachev said the 1948 rupture in soviet-yugoslav relations ``inflicted grave damage on yugoslav-soviet relations and ... on socialism as a whole.''
ties between moscow and yugoslavia were mended after stalin's death in 1953, when nikita s. khrushchev and tito agreed on bilateral relations in 1955 and 1956
now, gorbachev said, ``both sides are eager to raise our interstate and interparty relations to a new level, to give them a new quality'' and expand ties
a new declaration on yugoslav-soviet relations adopted tuesday is to be published friday, when gorbachev returns home
gorbachev also outlined new proposals for mediterranean security. he enlarged on previous suggestions for reducing the superpowers' naval presence in the waterway by proposing the united states and the soviet union freeze the number of warships they have there on july 1
washington and moscow should then agree on the number of warships they maintain in the mediterranean, with the eventual aim being a withdrawal of soviet ships if the united states follows suit, gorbachev said
in addition, he said, the superpowers should give each other advance notice of all ship movements and naval maneuvers in the mediterranean
gorbachev stressed that for the soviets, the mediterranean ``is no remote area'' because it is the passage to and from the black sea ports of the southern soviet union
naturally, we are interested in routes of peace and not those of war passing here,'' he said
gorbachev also attacked what he said were efforts by unidentified politicians in the nato alliance to block total nuclear disarmament and to respond to the removal of medium-range nuclear missiles from europe by building up conventional weapons
these contradictions, not to say absurdities, have quite definite political convictions behind them,'' gorbachev said
such politicians want to paint moscow in a bad light at any price, he said
they keep harping on the lie of the soviet union's and warsaw pact's war image'' when moscow is working on ``weeding out for good the cold war sprouts'' in east-west relations, gorbachev said
a 10-year-old girl, frustrated in efforts to get information for a class report on mississippi, flew there for a five-day visit there as a guest of the southern state
melissa montgomery, a fifth grade student at john swett elementary school in martinez, was greeted by classmates when she returned tuesday night to oakland international airport
she said the strangest part of the trip was when people laughed at her accent
i said `you guys,' they said `you all,''' she said
her mother, kathryn montgomery, said all expenses except plane fare were paid by an anonymous person
the mother said she called the mississippi secretary of state's office and was told the office was out of reference works. she was half-seriously told to send the girl to mississippi
i said, `great, i will,''' she said. the next morning she got a call from a mississippi mother who was wiling to take care of melissa
the girl even met ray mabus, the mississippi governor
he was nice,'' she said
melissa said she toured museums, battlefields, mansions and rode a pony
there are a lot of museums,'' she said, adding that the favorite part of the trip was a visit to the impressionist gallery
it had neat stuff in it,'' she said
the 5-to-10 page class report is due march 23
a 128-year-old exclusive private club has admitted its first two black male members but continues to ban women
the two men broke the color barrier at the olympic club, where membership costs $12,500 plus monthly dues and greens fees
i've played golf for years with olympic members,'' said roy clay, president of a company that makes electronics testing equipment. he said he applied and was interviewed last fall and was accepted last week
i'm not a golfer,'' said jessie knight, vice president of marketing for the san francisco newspaper agency. ``i joined strictly because of the athletic facilities. the club is close by, and it's good place to work out.''
a city ordinance that went into effect in december bars private clubs with more than 400 members from discriminating against minorities and women
however, club spokesman jim myers said the ban on women members will remain pending the outcome of a court battle with the city and an appeal to the federal courts on constitutional grounds of freedom of association
three vietnamese freighters were burning today after chinese warships attacked them, and chinese were blocking efforts to rescue the crew, an official vietnamese broadcast said
china said today that some chinese were wounded in the exchange of gunfire in the south china sea
the voice of vietnam radio said the freighters have been on fire since they were attacked monday near disputed islands claimed by vietnam, china, the philippines and taiwan
vietnam calls the islands the truong sa archipelago. they are known in china as the nansha islands. they also are called the spratly islands
the broadcast said nguyen phuong vu, head of the china department of vietnam's foreign ministry, made the accusations in a meeting today with li shuchin, beijing's ambassador to hanoi
the vietnamese side sent lifeboats flying red cross flags to rescue those freighters, but they were obstructed by chinese warships,'' said the broadcast, monitored in bangkok
it added: ``the vietnamese side urged the chinese side to order its warships to move away from this area and not to prevent the vietnamese ships from coming to the rescue of the crews on these freighters. the vietnamese side wishes a favorable and early reply from the chinese side.''
the broadcast repeated earlier claims that the clash began when the chinese warships without provocation opened fire on two vietnamese freighters. it said that warships nos. 502, 506 and 531 then fired on other vietnamese freighters that had come to the rescue
vietnam's foreign ministry on tuesday delivered an official protest to china's ambassador to hanoi, li shuchin, the official radio hanoi reported earlier
the note called the alleged chinese attack a military provocation and attempt to grab vietnamese territory. it said vietnam will ``resolutely apply all necessary measures to protect (its) independence, sovereignty and territorial integrity.''
in beijing, the foreign ministry disclosed today that china had suffered casualties in the skirmish
ministry spokeswoman li jihua gave china's version of the clash, saying vietnamese naval ships fired on chinese vessels conducting a scientific survey on a reef in the chain of 500 uninhabited islands and reefs
the chinese side was forced to make a limited counter-attack in self defense,'' ms. li said
ms. li refused to disclose how many chinese were wounded, whether they were civilians or military personnel, or other details of the clash
large oil deposits are believed to be in the vicinity of the archipelago, which is more than 310 miles south of hainan island
vietnam has stationed troops on a few of the islands since the early 1970s, while china has troops on a few islands of a second disputed group, the nearby xisha or paracels
the clash monday was the first reported exchange of gunfire between vietnam and china over the islands, although the two governments periodically have verbal skirmishes
china was an ally of vietnam's communist party during the vietnam war but relations cooled after the communist vietnamese victory as vietnam drifted closer into the soviet orbit
china and vietnam fought a brief border war in 1979. states since iowa</note>
it seems there are people out there who actually want george bush to become president of the united states. that novel notion may explain why the primary election count is now bush 20, sen. bob dole 1
that simplest of explanations is about the only one that has not been advanced by the political sages during the remarkable month-long string of victories that leaves bush the all-but-certain gop nominee
more popular explanations for bush's lopsided success run this way:
as vice president, he has the benefits of president reagan's popularity. his organization is strong, dole's is weak. he has the biggest campaign bankroll by far. he has had the support of governors in key states: new hampshire, south carolina, illinois
each of those factors certainly helped. in addition, the trappings and status of the vice presidency have so far served bush well, overcoming the disadvantage no. 2 men always have had in running for the top job _ they can't argue with the boss and they must defend what's already in place
but all those elements combined could not produce the kind of landslides bush has been gaining unless the vice president had a constituency to call his own, and was strengthening it
just a month ago today, bush won his first significant victory in new hampshire. on tuesday, he trounced dole, the most credible rival still standing, in the illinois primary
since opening day in iowa, dole has won just one primary _ in south dakota _ and caucuses in minnesota and his home state of kansas
the total popular vote in the 21 gop primaries held so far this year is bush 3.3 million, dole 1.6 million
bush already has 772 of the 1,139 delegates needed to win the gop nomination in new orleans next aug. 17. dole has 180
all of that has wiped away the memory of embarrassment in iowa, where bush ran third to dole and the rapidly vanishing pat robertson, and of the week he then spent on the political critical list
since then he has been winning big, with only minor setbacks
dole complains that the primaries are ending up as a referendum on reagan, not a contest with bush. ``if i hit him directly, i get ronald reagan first and then they say, oh, oh, he's out there attacking ronald reagan,'' the kansas senator said. ``it's pretty hard to reach bush except by phone.''
he found plenty to hit bush with earlier in the contest, and he still taunts the vice president as a man who got where he is ``without ever doing much.''
he also calls him a loser. ``sooner or later, the voters in one of these states are going to say `hold it, we're about to nominate a candidate who can't win,''' dole said after losing 16 primaries to bush on super tuesday
but recent polls conducted for usa today, time and newsweek show bush leading potential democratic nominees. besides, at this point no one can say who's a likely winner in the fall. the tickets aren't known, the issues aren't set, and the odds are subject to wide swings. in fact, the pollsters said bush trailed several of the potential democratic nominees just before his super tuesday sweep
the dole camp has not managed to zero in on a state likely to reverse the trend; in contests over the next month the polls point to bush
accepting defeat in illinois, which he had said would be his comeback state, dole said he would keep campaigning
we're just going to hang in there,'' dole said. in washington, the pundits thought dole was waiting to see if any of the upcoming iran-contra indictments might reflect badly on the vice president
but against a runaway delegate leader, dole doesn't have much else to hang in for, nor does he have a limitless bankroll with which to do it
dole argues that it is too early for the competition to end, and says that he has been encouraged by other republicans, including former president richard m. nixon, to stick with the race
that was not one of his themes after iowa, when there were suggestions that a new hampshire defeat would doom bush and trigger a dole runaway. nor did nixon value competition for its own sake 20 years ago, when he drove george romney out of the running even before new hampshire, and sailed through the primaries without real opposition
for all that, the script isn't completed, and the convention is five months away. there could still be damaging disclosures about iran-contra, or about cia links with panamanian boss manuel noriega when bush headed the agency, a question dole has been posing lately
bush has shown himself capable of saying the wrong thing and hurting his own cause. to guard against that, he's avoided saying much of anything lately
veteran political writer walter r. mears is executive editor of the associated press
the uss john hancock's disbursement office was robbed of $120,000 in cash and the battered body of the ship's paymaster was found stuffed in a locker aboard the destroyer, navy officials said
the body of paymaster lt. ratish prasad, 24, of park forest, ill., was found tuesday, said chief petty officer art riccio
he'd been bludgeoned,'' said the spokesman. ``he was beaten up pretty bad.''
the destroyer's disbursement office safe was found open and $120,000 in cash plus an undetermined number of blank checks were missing, riccio said
an audit of the ship's funds is pending and alternate arrangements have been made to pay the crew,'' said riccio
tuesday was payday for navy personnel, who are paid the 1st and 15th of each month, said riccio, adding that navy and jacksonville sheriff's investigators were working on the case
access to the hancock, which was tied up at its home port here, is strictly controlled, said riccio. people trying to board the ship must pass checkpoints at the base entrance, the pier area and the ship itself, he said
only family members and friends of the crew who have been previously cleared are allowed aboard the ship in port, he said. even naval personnel who do not have business on the ships cannot board them, he said. picks up 7th graf pvs: `the almost...'</note>
five explosions erupted today as the coffins of three irish republican army guerrillas killed by british troops were being lowered into graves
thousands of mourners clustered in the roman catholic milltown cemetery in west belfast flung themselves on the ground as organizers appealed for calm. there were no immediate reports of injuries and it was not clear what caused the explosions
several mourners grabbed a man evidently suspected of setting the explosions. hundreds of others rushed from the graveside toward where the explosions took place
the explosions erupted after more than 4,000 mourners had followed the flag-draped coffins of mairead farrell, 31, sean savage, 24, and daniel mccann, 30, to the cemetery
several mourners shouted out they believed the explosions were set by protestant paramilitary groups
police and troops, in an evidently deliberate policy, had kept out of sight during the funerals, which began with a requiem mass in a packed parish church, st. agnes
the mourners had followed the coffins, draped in the irish tricolor, through somber streets, with shops shut, to the cemetery
at the mass in st. agnes, mourners listened silently as the priest charged that the unarmed trio, ambushed on a bombing mission, were murdered
shortly before the funeral began, a bomb exploded on a street more than a mile from the church, slightly injuring a british soldier on foot patrol, police reported
earlier, about 150 mourners watched, with no sign or police or troops, as relatives and members of sinn fein, the ira's legal political wing, carried the coffin of mccann from his parents' two-story row house to be driven to the church
the almost exclusively catholic irish republican army is fighting to push the british out of protestant-dominated northern ireland, join it with the republic of ireland and set up an all-ireland socialist state
in his funeral oration at st. agnes, the rev. tom toner called the march 6 shootings in gibraltar ``murder'' and accused british authorities of ``gloating'' over them
more than 1,000 mourners listened in silence broken only by a the crying of a baby
we have a mounting, accumulated anger at the treatment of irish people by britain over the past weeks and months,'' he said
britain says the guerrillas were shot by commandos while preparing a car bomb attack on the changing of the guard outside the governor's residence in the colony on the southern tip of spain
the three were unarmed, but britain said they made movements that led the soldiers to believe their lives were in danger. the irish government has complained that the soldiers should have tried to arrest the trio, who the ira said were on ``active service.''
outside the chapel, a crowd of about 3,000 gathered to accompany the coffins to milltown, the burial ground for many other guerrillas killed in nearly 20 years of sectarian strife which has claimed more than 2,600 lives
in the tense buildup to the funerals, protestants stoned hearses that brought the ira bodies home tuesday on a 100-mile route from dublin. the coffins had been flown from gibraltar on a plane chartered by sinn fein
hooded ira gunmen fired a three-shot volley, the ira's traditional salute to guerrillas killed in its bomb and bullet campaign against british rule, to coincide with the arrival of the coffins on irish soil
two catholics, including ira member kevin mccracken, 33, shot by british troops near savage's home on monday, were fatally wounded in belfast over the past two days
another catholic, charles mcgrillan, died when unidentified gunmen opened fire as he arrived for work tuesday. police said they suspected a sectarian attack by protestant militants
fallen television evangelist jim bakker has sued a new york attorney who formerly represented the ptl ministry, charging that the attorney tricked him into resigning and turning the ministry over to the rev. jerry falwell
in the suit, which seeks more than $10,000 in damages and was filed this week in york county, bakker and his wife, tammy faye, say they did not know that roy grutman also represented falwell when he advised the bakkers to step down
what the bakkers are really saying in the lawsuit is that mr. grutman tricked the bakkers into resigning from office to open the way for mr. falwell to take over the leadership of the ministry,'' said jim toms, one of the bakkers' attorneys
grutman said tuesday the allegations were ``utterly meritless,'' adding that he was never bakker's attorney
i didn't tell him to resign. he made that decision,'' grutman said
bakker left the fort mill-based ministry last march amid a sex scandal involving a church secretary, jessica hahn. falwell took over the ministry for several months. ptl now is undergoing reorganization in bankruptcy court
grutman told the bakkers, according to the suit, that television evangelist jimmy swaggart, now beset by a sex scandal himself, was heading a conspiracy to take over ptl
the bakkers claim that grutman and falwell advised them to ``turn the leadership of the ministry over to mr. falwell, who, it was said, would lead the ministry as a caretaker until such time as the (bakkers) could return to the ministry,'' the suit said
the suit also charged that ``grutman either knew or should have known that the alleged conspiracy to seize control of ptl by mr. swaggart, either was not truthfully reported or was impractical of attainment.''
bakker resigned as ptl president on march 19; a month later, falwell took the bakkers off the ptl payroll
the suit said the bakkers left ptl ``severely damaged financially and diminished as a christian ministry'' and accused grutman of giving the bakkers incorrect advice to resign, resulting in damage to the bakkers' reputations
the sister of the longest-held american hostage in lebanon said today that the reagan administration, once obsessed with securing freedom for the captives, no longer cares about their fate
i think it's rather interesting to look back and see the concern expressed by the administration, by president reagan, vice president bush, and their rationale for the iran-contra scandal that they were so obsessed with the fate of the hostages that they made this move,'' peggy say, sister of hostage terry anderson, said of the arms-for-hostages deal
and for the past year, silence. that obsession seems to have been overcome and the fate of the hostages no longer seems to be of great concern to anybody in this administration,'' she said on nbc-tv's ``today'' show
anderson, 40, chief middle east correspondent for the associated press, is the longest-held of 22 foreign hostages in lebanon. he was kidnapped on march 16, 1985, in beirut as he was returning from a tennis game
services to mark the third anniversary of his abduction were scheduled in anderson's hometown of batavia, n.y., as well as buffalo and rochester, and in california and florida, mrs. say said
in washington, democratic presidential candidate jesse jackson was taking part at an afternoon service at holy trinity roman catholic church where prayers for anderson and the other hostages were to be offered by christian and islamic clergy
participants, including three former hostages _ the rev. lawrence jenco, the rev. benjamin weir and abc news correspondent charles glass _ were to read passages from the bible and the koran
marilyn langston, daughter of american hostage frank herbert reed, said today she hopes the service ``puts an awareness in everyone's mind that this hostage situation is going on continually and until they're all out we can't forget it.''
ms. langston said, however, that she feared the captives have been forgotten by the u.s. government
i feel they've been put on the backburner, that the concern for the hostages _ i don't know if there is any any more,'' ms. langston said on the nbc program
reed, director of the lebanon international school in beirut, was kidnapped sept. 9, 1986. he is among the nine americans held captive in lebanon, including thomas sutherland, joseph james cicippio, edward austin tracy, jesse turner, robert polhill, alaan steen, and marine lt. col. william r. higgins
the federal aviation administration is investigating continental airlines' pilot testing procedures following comments made last week at a hearing into a november crash that killed 28 people, officials said
daniel beaudette, manager of the faa's air transportation division in washington, said tuesday that the investigation was set off by one pilot's report that he made deliberate mistakes in wing settings to test pilots
i can't see how they could safely do that in passenger-carrying operations,'' beaudette said. federal regulations prohibit pilot training on flights that carry passengers
the inquiry follows testimony by continental capt. kenneth watson last week before a national transportation safety board hearing into the nov. 15 crash of a continental dc-9 that killed 28 and injured 54 as it was taking off from denver's airport
on a flight last october, watson said he made incorrect adjustments to an aircraft before takeoff in order to test pilot frank zvonek, who died in the november crash
as is my common practice, i advised frank that i would intentionally make several mistakes,'' watson told the hearing
i intentionally misset flaps, (stabilizer) trim and weight cards for takeoff. he caught and corrected me on them,'' he said
if a violation is found, continental could be issued an administrative warning, fined, or watson's license could be suspended, beaudette said
continental spokesman bruce hicks said the procedure watson reported using is not a company policy
but hicks said he didn't know whether the technique has been used by other continental pilots and said the airline has not yet decided whether to permit that kind of pilot testing in the future. with report iran cut ties to security council. pick up 6th graf pvs: ``iraq on...''</note>
iran said it fired five missiles into baghdad today, and iraq said it shot seven into tehran. the iranians said 52 civilians were killed in tehran and in iraqi warplane raids on other cities
iran also said its warplanes bombed other iraqi cities today, and its troops pushed into northeastern iraq overnight and seized the border town of khurmal, iran's islamic republic news agency said. irna said 1,150 iraqi troops were killed or wounded, but iraq had no comment on the reported offensive
also today, foreign ministers of the gulf cooperation council met in saudi arabia to discuss the 7-year-old iran-iraq war and its implications for the oil-rich region
on tuesday, iran accused the u.n. security council of wasting time on an arms embargo instead of ending the missile duel, in which scores of civilians have been killed or wounded
in switzerland, the prestigious newspaper neue zuercher zeitung today quoted senior iranian charge d'affaires mohammed hussein malaek as saying his country had cut all ties to the security council
malaek also was quoted as saying only a military solution could end the persian gulf war, and that iran no longer felt obligated to respect international conventions, presumably including the geneva convention on the conduct of nations at war
iraq on tuesday reiterated the claim that iran broke a two-day truce in the ``war of the cities'' and said it would continue to attack tehran until iran stopped shelling border cities
the iraqi news agency said warplanes tuesday night bombed iranian towns and attacked a ship in the persian gulf. maritime sources had earlier reported an iraqi attack at around the same time on the 249,223-ton trade fortitude
the iranian agency said revolutionary guards fired five missiles into baghdad in retaliation for an air raid tuesday that killed 25 students and teachers at a high school in al-eshtar in western iran
the iraqi agency confirmed three of the hits on baghdad and said ``many'' civilians were killed. iraq said it fired seven missiles into tehran
iran said an unspecified number of missiles hit the capital of tehran today and said iraqi warplanes also bombed bakhtaran and other cities in western iran. the iranian agency said a total of 52 civilians were killed
iraq says it has fired 22 missiles into tehran since the tenuous truce broke down late sunday. iran has reported launching seven into baghdad
neither side has given an overall casualty count
iran's news agency said iranian jet fighters bombed the northern iraqi oil city of kirkuk and other cities today, ``inflicting heavy casualties and losses on the enemy.'' it said the jet fighters also shot 16 air-to-ground missiles into kirkuk
it said nine short-range missiles were fired into the southern basra province, the area surrounding iraq's second-largest city
it said revolutionary guards pushed farther into sulaymaniyah province in northeastern iraq, inflicting ``heavy losses.'' earlier in the week iran said its fighters seized villages and hills in the region, 160 miles north of baghdad
iranian forces took the town of khurmal a few miles from the border after a ``pitched battle,'' the agency reported today
it said residents of ``liberated villages'' in the area ``warmly welcomed the attacking iranian combatants,'' and iranian forces seized 95 square miles of iraqi soil, including 21 villages
announcing today's iraqi missile strike on iran, an iraqi military spokesman was quoted by the official iraqi news agency as saying:
we will continue our destructive hits into the nest of vice and ugliness.''
it also said revolutionary guards pushed farther into sulaymaniyah province in northeastern iraq, inflicting ``heavy losses'' and that khurmal had fallen
earlier in the week, iran said its fighters seized villages and hills in the region 160 miles north of baghdad
the iraqi and iranian reports were monitored in cyprus
the attack tuesday on the trade fortitude raised the possibility of revived attacks on shipping in the gulf, where the u.s.-flagged kuwaiti tanker gas prince was heading north in the 17th u.s.-escorted convoy this year
since feb. 15, there have been two confirmed iraqi attacks on tankers in iranian shipping lanes
police investigating the death of a man who was crushed between a truck and his porch ended up arresting two people after they found out the truck was loaded with stolen chickens, authorities said
officers said joshua horton, 50, was pronounced dead at mississippi baptist medical center after he was crushed between the truck and a porch at his home about 11:35 p.m
investigators said patricia tucker, 33, of jackson, the victim's step-daughter, was attempting to back the truck into horton's driveway to unload the frozen chickens when the brakes failed
the truck contained 20 boxes of chickens allegedly taken from a jackson firm where tucker's husband, edgar tucker, 36, was employed, officers said
a police spokesman said tucker, who was at work when the accident occurred, was arrested on an embezzlement charge while his wife was charged with accessory to embezzlment
syria will become an oil exporter for the first time because of new discoveries, officials said today
james audu, a spokesman for the vienna-based organization of petroleum exporting countries, said that syria produced 240,000 barrels per day during the fourth quarter of last year
with local demand estimated at about 220,000 barrels a day, the country would become a net exporter on an annual basis for the first time this year, helping it to cope with a foreign debt of at least $3 billion
the small amount of oil to be sold abroad will not qualify syria for membership in the oil cartel, audu told the associated press in vienna. but it is expected to make that arab nation a net exporter in 1988, he said
syria, with 10 million people, is not expected to become a big exporter. but the modest 1.8 billion barrels of estimated oil reserves should help alleviate the economic burden
president hafez assad announced in a speech to the nation last week that there have been new oil discoveries but he did not elaborate
the damascus government currently gets millions of tons of cut-price oil from iran each year
syria is persian iran's main ally in the 7-year-old persian gulf war against arab iraq. but damascus has come under growing pressure from other arab countries to stop supporting iran against a fellow arab nation. sub 4th graf to correct `our' rights sted `are'</note>
like an electronic sneeze, a rogue computer program known as a ``virus'' has spread to a major software company's commercial programs, a frightening ``infection'' that the experts once thought was impossible
on march 2, a ``message of peace'' created by the publisher of a canadian computer magazine appeared on as many as 350,000 macintosh computer screens in north america and europe, apparently spread like an epidemic through the network of electronic bulletin boards' free or low-cost software
the message became the first known contamination of an off-the-shelf program when it cropped up in freehand, aldus corp.'s latest software, forcing the company to recall or rework about 5,000 copies of the program
it ``was a very benign incident,'' but aldus officials ``are talking with our attorneys to understand what our legal rights are in this instance,'' said laury bryant, a spokeswoman for the seattle-based software company
viruses are small, secret programs created by programmers as jokes or acts of vandalism, then secretly inserted into other programs. viruses can spread from computer to computer by operators sharing ``contaminated'' software
at their most benign, viruses will cause only a message to pop up on a computer screen, as apparently happened here. at their worst, as ``tapeworms'' or ``logic bombs,'' they can destroy information stored in computer memories
richard brandow of the montreal-based computer magazine macmag told the associated press in a telephone interview tuesday that he wrote the virus, but intended only to show the dangers of software piracy, or unauthorized copying
the full message, said brandow, read: ``richard brandow, the publisher of macmag, and its entire staff would like to take this opportunity to convey their universal message of peace to all macintosh users around the world.'' beneath that was a graphic of the globe
ms. bryant said fewer than 5,000 copies of freehand were contaminated by a an infected disk that was copied for three days by a disk duplicating machine, and only half the infected disks were distributed to retailers
until now, personal computer viruses were thought to reside only in noncommercial ``freeware'' or ``shareware'' legally distributed on computerized bulletin boards or on software disks shared by computer users
experts had thought viruses could be avoided if users didn't freely distribute software, but only used off-the-shelf programs
the incident rocked the computer industry because the nation's three largest software companies _ microsoft corp., ashton-tate, and lotus development corp. _ are clients of macromind inc. of chicago, the company that inadvertently gave the virus to aldus
ashton-tate declined comment, but officials at microsoft, apple and lotus said none of their software was infected
macromind president marc canter said in a telephone interview tuesday that to the best of his knowledge, none of his other customers received the virus and that the program has erased itself
ms. bryant and brandow said the virus died out after march 2, the anniversary of the introduction of apple's macintosh se and macintosh ii models
canter said the peace message apparently was in software he obtained from brandow during a visit to montreal. the packet included a game program called mr. potato head, a computerized version of the popular toy
unaware of the ``infection,'' canter ran the game program once and then used the same computer to work on a disk to teach macintosh users how to use freehand
that original disk became infected, and then contaminated other freehand teaching disks when it was copied by aldus, he said
canter, upset with brandow, also said he was considering legal action. brandow said he met canter, but denied giving him the software
brandow said the idea for the message program was written and tested for a year, then left for two days in december on a macintosh at macmag's offices, a frequent gathering place for macintosh devotees
the publisher said he expected pirated programs from the machine would spread the peace message in the montreal area and a few other areas of canada and the united states
instead, he said, he was shocked to find that, by his estimate, 350,000 people in north america and europe had the message pop up on their macintoshes on march 2
whoever said one vote doesn't count isn't following sand lake politics, such as they are
in a somewhat less than spirited election for a vacant village trustee's seat, bob vandenberg, ralph boerman and earl thomas finished in a three-way tie _ each receiving precisely one write-in vote
a winner will be chosen at 9 a.m. march 21 under kent county's official tie-breaking method, a drawing at the county clerk's office in grand rapids. two slips of paper marked ``not elected'' and one marked ``elected'' will be put in a box and drawn by the candidates or their representatives
the village council in this community of about 400 people will appoint a trustee if the winner declines the job, something that appeared to be more than a remote possibility
thomas, 40, served 14 years as village clerk but didn't run this year, saying his night job prevented him from attending council meetings. ``i was a clerk for 14 years, so i did my time,'' he said
vandenberg, 51, chose not to run for re-election as village president this year after six years in local politics. ``i figured it was time for the young ones to take over,'' he said
boerman, at 22 a political neophyte, could be considered one of vandenberg's ``young ones.'' but boerman said he didn't know he was in the running until a reporter telephoned him with news of the three-way tie
i haven't ever thought about it,'' boerman said. ``no one has approached me or asked me or anything.''
thomas said he'd like to know who wrote in his name
i'll kill `em, whoever it was,'' he joked
a couple collecting aluminum cans found the remains of the sixth body discovered in the desert since last fall, and police said they needed an autopsy to determine the victim's age, sex and cause of death
however, police chief john scagno said tuesday the discovery of the exposed, bleached bones on the outskirts of el paso wasn't cause for panic
the sixth body was found monday afternoon northeast of el paso, a few hundred yards from where the bodies of five young women were unearthed
no one has been charged in the desert deaths, which police have said could be the work of a serial killer. however, police have identified a suspect who has been jailed on unrelated sexual assault charges since oct. 14
police took two days to unearth the latest skeletal remains, sifting buckets of excavated dirt
scagno would not comment on whether clothing or a weapon was found at the scene
the only detail we're going to tell you is ... the body had (dental) braces,'' scagno said. ``the body itself is just skeletal remains.''
skeletons were all that remained of the first five victims
scagno said he didn't know when the autopsy results would be released
the search for the desert killer began in september, when a utility company employee found the first body while digging a hole near several highways
although police concluded their search of the area in january, scagno said they now plan to start looking again
the remains of maria rosa casio, 24, and karen baker, 20, were found buried close together sept. 4. the bodies of desiree wheatley, 15, and dawn smith, 14, were found oct. 20, about 200 yards from the first two bodies. the body of angelica frausto, 17, was found nov. 3, between the first two pairs of graves
ms. casio, from a dallas suburb, had been here visiting a relative when she disappeared. the other victims were from el paso
the sixth victim's grave was found a few hundred yards away from the other five graves, deputy chief gus massey said
after tearfully telling his lawyer ``there was still some good in him,'' a rape defendant pleaded guilty so he could spare his 16-year-old victim the trauma of testifying
terry lee buckholtz was charged with raping the teen in november 1986 when he was in a prison work-release program, and then trying to kill her and her brother with a meat cleaver
the brother and sister survived their wounds, and were to take the witness stand tuesday in court here
he called me this morning totally out of the blue,'' defense attorney john voigt said tuesday. ``he was in tears. he said that even though nobody thought so, there was still some good in him
the only good thing left for him to do was not make (the victims) testify,'' voight said
circuit judge stanton s. kaplan asked buckholtz to explain
i didn't want to put them through any more,'' replied buckholtz, 20
under a deal with the prosecutor, buckholtz was sentenced to 40 years in prison followed by 15 years of probation. in return for the guilty plea, prosecutor kate kearney agreed to drop charges of armed kidnapping and aggravated battery
kearny said buckholtz had rejected that plea-bargain offer a week ago
it's been an exceptionally traumatic experience for the family,'' she said. ``the state offered this to avoid having the victims exposed to mr. buckholtz.''
an organized crime informant who rejected an offer to enter the federal witness protection program has been found murdered in a california parking lot, authorities said
the body of george peter yudzevich, 46, was found near a business-industrial center in irvine, calif. he had been shot at least three times in the head, police said
irvine police said they did not know the motive for his murder, which was discovered saturday
yudzevich turned down an offer for federal protection before testifying last fall at the racketeering trial of joseph n. gallo, 76, the reputed former consigliere of the gambino crime family; joseph armone, 70, the reputed gambino underboss, and two other gambino associates, according to edward mcdonald, head of the brooklyn-based organized crime strike force
his testimony against armone and the two associates was ``critical'' in the trial, which ended in december with the conviction of all the defendants, mcdonald said tuesday
we sponsored him for the program and even went so far as to prepare necessary paperwork, but for his own reasons he chose not to enter the program,'' mcdonald said
yudzevich admitted to being an fbi informant from 1980 to 1985, mcdonald said. he refused to speculate about the motive behind the slaying
yudzevich also testified in california last fall against alleged organized crime figure robert (fat bobby) paduano of newport beach, calif., who was arrested in february and charged with 73 felony counts of robbery, burglary, assault and extortion, said orange county deputy district attorney wallace wade
paduano's lawyer, alan may, said his client denied any knowledge of or involvement in yudzevich's murder
yudzevich also had been awaiting a judge's decision on whether he should be tried for allegedly bilking orange county investors out of about $350,000 in a money laundering case, authorities said. newspaper says</head>
undocumented aliens seeking amnesty despite misdemeanor criminal records may be eligible if the convictions are more than a year old, a newspaper reported today
but amnesty rights activists said the proposed change in immigration-law standards comes too late
immigration has been very lax in coming forward to publicize this major change,'' said susan alva, director of a legalization appeals project for the legal aid foundation
under the existing u.s. immigration and naturalization service policy, immigrants who have been convicted of three or more misdemeanors, or any felony, are not eligible for amnesty
the proposed change would allow immigrants to expunge misdemeanors from their records and be eligible for amnesty, according to a report published today in the los angeles herald examner
alva estimated that thousands of people, many of whom have been told by officials that they weren't eligible for legalization, would be affected by the reported policy shift
but duke austin, an ins spokesman, disagreed
i don't think this would dramatically affect the numbers of people in the program,'' he said
in a letter dated jan. 18, joe thomas, director of the ins western region processing facility for amnesty applications, explained to an immigrants' rights attorney that ``an expungement will not remove ineligibility for criminal convictions.''
however, attorneys from the immigration committee of the national lawyers' guild and the los angeles county public defender's office said the ins is now accepting expungements, though too late to be of use to many immigrants
the amnesty deadline is may 5, and ray santana, a deputy los angeles county public defender, said it takes a month or longer to get an expungement
city health officials say 25 people became ill and two had to be hospitalized following a corned beef and cabbage dinner sponsored by the ancient order of hibernians
richard wilberg, chief inspector for the city department of public health, said tuesday that the meat served at the saturday dinner was apparently contaminated during preparation with staphyloccus, which produced a toxin creating food poisoning
he said that 160 people had attended the pre-st. patrick's day dinner at the city's irish club and the two people hospitalized have been released
among those hospitalized was edward f. o'connell, president of the local chapter of the hibernians
it's a tough situation,'' o'connell said. ``we rented the caterer and they brought everything in cooked.''
an arab-american who advocates non-violent resistance to israel's occupation was detained today for allegedly taking part in an illegal gathering, police said
mubarak awad, 44, was being held at a city police station and his case was under investigation, police spokesman rafi levy told the associated press
levy said the illegal gathering took place on the main road between jerusalem and the west bank city of nablus, but he had no further details
we do understand that mr. awad has been taken into custody, but our understanding was that he was stopped for a traffic violation,'' said a u.s. consulate official who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``we have consular officers seeking access to him at this time.''
last year, israeli officials confiscated awad's israeli identity card and ordered him out of the country in november, when his three-month tourist visa expired
on monday, israel's supreme court ordered the interior ministry to show within 60 days why awad had not been expelled
awad, a palestinian who also has homes both in jerusalem and wapakoneta, ohio, came under fire after the publication in hebrew of his book entitled ``non-violent resistance: a strategy for the occupied territories.''
the book urged the 1.5 million palestinians in the west bank and gaza strip to refuse to pay taxes, lay down in front of bulldozers to prevent land confiscation and boycott isreli products. victory</head> subbing grafs 27-28 pvs, with nearly ... no delegates</note>
the democrats are searching anew for a presidential front-runner after the home-state revival of sen. paul simon, who declared today he has ``as good a shot as anybody'' after his victory over jesse jackson in the illinois primary. george bush won easily in the republican contest, although he still had to contend with a battered but dogged bob dole
the candidates went on spring break today after a grueling month that featured 20-odd primaries and caucuses in both parties
this is the state, it will be remembered, which locked it up for george bush,'' gov. james thompson said after illinois shattered dole's comeback bid and brought bush two-thirds of the way to a gop nominating majority
the democrats had no luxury to talk of locking up anything. the race for a nominating majority of delegates was a dead heat between jackson and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis with kansas and michigan next up on the calendar
however, dukakis was expecting to pick up about 100 uncounted delegates from caucuses already held in minnesota, texas and washington state
now we move on to michigan,'' said dukakis, ``where there are no favorite sons. the field is wide open.''
jackson, in an interview on nbc-tv today, congratulated simon on his victory but in almost the same breath seemed to dismiss it as illinois voters paying ``respects to a sitting senator'' who had focused on his home state while jackson was competing in the super tuesday states
simon, on the other hand, said on abc-tv that his illinois win showed he is in the thick of a battle that will go all the way to the democratic national convention this summer
i don't know who out there will emerge, but i think paul simon has as good a shot as anyone,'' he said
simon said in several interviews that his relative lack of campaign money wasn't a big problem, though he concluded his appearance on cbs-tv by saying with a smile, ``any of your viewers who want to send in a contribution, i'll be happy to accept it.''
i don't believe we have any front-runners,'' dukakis said after finishing what he described as ``a respectable third'' in illinois. he said in his discussions with democratic party leaders around the country ``there is an overwhelming sentiment that we should get behind a nominee.''
jackson finished second in the duel of favorite sons, and said, ``jesse jackson, in popular vote and delegates, is on top of the race.''
in fact, the associated press delegate survey showed dukakis with 464.5 and jackson with 460.55. sen. albert gore jr. had 354.8; rep. richard gephardt 145, and simon 171.5 delegates
the big losers in illinois were republicans dole and pat robertson and democrats gore and gephardt
we're staying in,'' said dole after absorbing another beating at the hands of the vice president
illinois has spoken loud and clear and strong,'' said bush, who now has won 18 straight primaries _ 16 of them one week ago on super tuesday
there was relatively little campaign activity today, after five frantic weeks in which nearly half the delegates to the democratic and republican conventions were chosen
gephardt was campaigning in michigan and gore was in kansas. dukakis had an appearance scheduled in new york, but the rest of the candidates were off the campaign trail
kansas democrats hold caucuses this weekend and both parties have primaries scheduled saturday in puerto rico
next tuesday, the only event in the presidential struggle is a primary to select the seven delegates allocated to democrats abroad
the next major battleground for the democrats was michigan, which holds party caucuses on march 26
gephardt made little effort in illinois, pinning his hopes on michigan with its strong union vote
but gore spent about $200,000 on advertising in illinois and ended up with only 5 percent of the vote. yet, he insisted, there would be better days ahead. ``this race has a long way to run yet,'' said the tennessee senator
for the republicans, the next big test was connecticut, with a primary on march 29. that should produce another big win for bush, who grew up in the state, which his father represented in the u.s. senate
there were two presidential votes in illinois _ a non-binding popularity contest and the election of convention delegates
bush and simon were the big winners in both
with nearly all the votes counted, bush was getting about 54 percent of the popular vote and winning 66 delegates. dole was receiving 36 percent of the vote, and winning 16 delegates. robertson was getting 7 percent of the vote and no delegates
simon, running stronger than expected, was getting 43 percent of the popular vote and picking up 136 delegates. jackson was receiving 31 percent of the vote and 37 delegates, while dukakis was getting 17 percent of the vote, but no delegates. gore and gephardt trailed with 5 percent and 2 percent of the vote respectively, and no delegates
good news for dukakis came from far-away washington state, where democratic officials released results from 65 percent of their march 8 caucuses. dukakis led with 45 percent of the vote, to 35 percent for jackson and 14 percent uncommitted. simon had 4 percent. overall, washington will send 65 delegates to the national convention
robertson said he'd have to reassess his candidacy _ the political euphemism for preparing to drop out _ if he got less than 5 percent of the vote in illinois. he got 7 percent, but has stopped talking about being the 1988 gop nominee
simon declared, ``this is a new beginning for the paul simon candidacy.''
lawyers for the ``sharpeville six'' today filed an appeal with the supreme court for a stay of execution for the six blacks, whose scheduled hangings have prompted worldwide cries for clemency
attorney prakash diar filed the request on the basis of new evidence relating to allegations that police assaulted and pressured a state witness into giving false evidence against two of the defendants
the hearing was scheduled for thursday morning. the executions are scheduled at dawn friday at pretoria central prison
a finding of new evidence is the only grounds available to stop the hangings, since president p.w. botha said tuesday he had turned down the last appeal to save the five men and one woman
the six were convicted of murder in connection with the sept. 3, 1984 mob killing of black township councilor jacob dlamini in sharpeville, about 40 miles south of johannesburg
the attorneys submitted documents stating that joseph manete, a black trial witness, was forced by police to say in a sworn affidavit that he had seen two of the defendants at the scene, when he really did not
manete testified in the non-jury trial under protection of anonymity. the attorneys tried to question him during the trial about his allegations, which were made to his attorney. the court refuthe sharpeville riots were provoked by the local council's decision to raise rents
george bush, with another republican primary victory under his belt, celebrated his ``great and convincing'' win in illinois, while backers proclaimed he has the gop presidential nomination sewed up
this is the state, it will be remembered, which locked it up for george bush,'' said james thompson, illinois' four-term republican governor. thompson served as bush's state chairman and campaigned with him all over illinois
who says nice guys finish last?'' a buoyant bush asked supporters at a victory celebration in this northwest chicago suburb
thank you, illinois,'' he said
the vice president was returning to washington today for a campaign hiatus
bush resoundingly beat his nearest rival, kansas sen. bob dole. former television evangelist pat robertson ran a distant third with 7 percent
illinois has spoken loud and clear and strong, and so now we go on, right down to the wire in november, and with your help we'll win illinois in november,'' he told supporters who waved red, white and blue balloons and chanted ``bush '88.''
with a victory in the first big industrial-state primary on top of his super tuesday sweep, bush said his campaign themes had won nationwide approval
wherever there's a primary, i am going to be there taking the illinois message,'' he said. ``ours is a national message for a national campaign.''
backers said bush was virtually assured of winning the nomination
i think the race is going to be wrapped up when bob dole decides to drop out, but the numbers certainly would indicate that it's all over,'' said ed murnane, deputy director of the bush campaign in illinois
a prominent soviet adviser warned the kremlin less than a month after soviet troops entered afghanistan that the action would derail efforts to curb the arms race, he said in a letter published today
economist oleg t. bogomolov said he sent a report in 1979 to the communist party's ruling politburo that outlined the potential dangers to soviet foreign policy and public opinion
in a situation report delivered to the appropriate levels on jan. 20, 1980, the hopeless and detrimental aspects of that action were stated,'' bogomolov wrote in a letter published in the weekly literary gazette
bogomolov has been head of the institute of economics of the world socialist system for nearly 20 years and is a respected adviser on development in kremlin-allied nations
soviet troops entered afghanistan in december 1979 to replace one pro-moscow leadership with another and to back it against an anti-communist moslem insurgency. an estimated 115,000 soviet soldiers remain in afghanistan to support the kabul government now headed by president najib
the soviets have said they will withdraw their troops if pakistan, which represents the afghan rebels, agrees to a peace proposal with kabul. the two sides have been meeting for u.n.-sponsored peace talks in geneva
for the first time since world war ii emerged the possibility of a military conflict in which, unlike in korea or vietnam, we would have to fight with our own troops,'' bogomolov quoted his report as saying
the report stated that as a result of that action detente was blocked and political efforts to limit the arms race were liquidated,'' bogomolov wrote. ``there occurred a considerable consolidation of the anti-soviet front in governments surrounding the ussr from the west to the east.''
the intervention in afghanistan damaged kremlin relations with developing countries, especially in moslem nations, the economic theorist said he warned in the report
the letter gave no indication what, if any, response bogomolov received from the kremlin leadership
a church of england theologian committed suicide after writing a controversial article accusing the archbishop of canterbury of weakness and indecision, a coroner ruled today
the rev. gareth bennett, a traditionalist figure in the church, wrote the traditionally unsigned preface to ``crockford's clerical directory 1987-88,'' the church's own reference book listing anglican clergy
the article, published dec. 2, started a furor in the state church because it was widely interpreted as the opening shot in a campaign to pressure archbishop robert runcie, 66, into retiring early and to block the appointment of a liberal to replace him
runcie is spiritual head of the church and the world's 70 million anglicans
bennett, 58, wrote in a diary four days before his dec. 7 death that ``i should be lucky to weather this business through without disaster.''
he was found dead in his fume-filled car at his home in oxford, western england. bennett had purchased a hose pipe on dec. 5 that was used to siphon fumes into his car from the exhaust, the inquest heard
oxfordshire coroner nicholas gardiner said the tenor of bennett's diary entries ``changes dramatically in the last few days of his life'' and there was ample evidence to suggest bennett was under extreme pressure
he decided that he had only one course of action open to him and took that course of action fully aware of what the results would be,'' gardiner said. ``accordingly, my verdict must be that he took his own life.''
negligence and dereliction of duty have caused the deaths of 11,700 people over the past three years, a top chinese official was quoted today as saying
the official china daily quoted an official of the supreme people's procuratorate, the nation's top prosecutor's office. he was not identified by name
the official said accidents resulting from ``rampant bureaucratic bunglings'' and negligence cost the state $378 million in direct economic losses over the same period
he said there had been an unexpected rise in the number of serious cases of negligence involving criminal liability over the past two years
he gave no reason for the increase. previous reports have linked china's serious problem with industrial accidents to both inept bureaucracy and economic reforms which have decentralized industry and encouraged the establishment of hundreds of thousands of small, often poorly regulated factories
the official said most criminal cases are in the fields of construction, mining and transport, forcing the resignation of several senior government leaders
the head of the forestry ministry was forced from office last year because of his poor handling of a disastrous forest fire and the railways minister stepped down earlier this month to take the blame for three fatal train accidents in january
the official said the procuratorate will impose stricter punishment for people who have committed crimes of derelection or have caused major accidents due to negligence of duty
organizations caught trying to cover up such crimes or which delay reporting them will also face severe criminal punishment, he said. comments. picks up 11th graf pvs, `inside, the ...</note>
u.s. defense secretary frank c. carlucci and soviet defense minister dmitri yazov today held the first such high-level military talks in an atmosphere characterized as friendly and non-pressured
the tone has been very positive and cooperative throughout,'' said pentagon spokesman dan howard. ``we are pleased with the way things are going.''
the two discussed the strategic arms limitation talks, implementation of the treaty to eliminate medium-range superpower nuclear missiles, and the size of the respective armed forces, said howard
they also discussed u.s. allegations that the soviets violated the 1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty by building a phased-array radar far from the soviet border in siberia, said howard. the pact requires such radars to be along the border
howard declined to give full details of the talks, saying that carlucci and yazov reserved that right for news conferences both plan at the end of the talks thursday
opening the morning session at the u.s. embassy, said howard, yazov ``commented that the room ... was a very small room, and said there is a saying in russian that although we have close quarters, we shouldn't quarrel.''
everyone got a laugh out of that,'' said howard
the main point that mr. yazov made in the beginning was that he wanted to have useful discussions without having the pressure of negotiations ... to arrive at some sort of agreement,'' howard said
carlucci welcomed yazov to the opening round
inside, the two men, flanked by about 10 aides apiece, faced each other across a long table at the end of which stood a relief map of europe, the area defended by the opposing forces of the north atlantic treaty alliance and warsaw pact
the two men exchanged greetings, but made no public remarks. it was the first ever business meeting between u.s. and soviet defense secretaries
reporters and photographers were ushered out of the room as the first, three-hour session began
carlucci and yazov ate lunch at the residence of u.s. ambassador faith ryan whittlesey before the afternoon session at the soviet embassy
on thursday, carlucci and yazov were to eat breakfast at the residence of soviet ambassador zoya novozhilova before their third and concluding session. carlucci told reporters earlier that he hoped yazov could give him concrete evidence of a highly publicized new soviet military doctrine
despite extensive soviet press commentary on the kremlin doctrine of reasonable or defensive sufficiency, he said he had seen seen ``absolutely no practical change.''
if anything, their military continues to grow. they continue to modernize,'' carlucci said tuesday
yazov said before he left moscow that he hoped for ``frank, constructive discussion'' on arms control issues including strategic arms, nuclear testing, chemical and conventional weapons
carlucci emphasized that he did not want the meeting to open a ``parallel channel'' to on-going superpower arms negotiations in geneva
soviet journalists covering the session said they had been told it was likely to produce no dramatic announcements, but to serve as an ``impulse'' to other negotiations
here are excerpts from soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev's speech wednesday to the yugoslav parliament:
we will have to thoroughly examine the question of improving inter-nationality relations, one of the most important and delicate issues in a multinational country such as ours. basic positions here are firm
recently, when the 70th anniversary of the great october revolution was formally celebrated in moscow, we spoke with a justified sense of gratification of the results of the leninist nationalities policy of how much had been done in the country to upgrade the economy and culture of the many peoples inhabiting our land, so that they might live in friendship and accord
whatever constituent or autonomous republic or region we take, it is now bound by thousands of threads to all other parts of the sountry, and it has indisoluble links within the integrated economic and political complex ... it would be a mistake, however, to regard the life of nations and relations of nations as something settled once and for all
there are certain difficulties inherited from the past. there are problems that emerged in the course of time prompted by changes in economic life and social relationships and in the consciousness of people
we are determined to secure democratic solutions to these problems which would correspond to the interests of each and every nation and in the family of soviet nations and our entire socialist society
i should like to stress that the changes in our society are closely linked with the activity of the communist party. the communist party of the soviet union is the initiator of perestroika (change). in the current crucial stage, its role as the soviet people's political vanguard is particularly great. and we are convinced that the party can carry out the current responsible tasks it is confronted with, not by methods of command and administration, but by putting itself at the head of the mass movement for a revolutionary renewal of society, and by consolidating two-way connections with the working class, the farmers, the intelligentsia and all social strata.''
we are implementing our perestroika in keeping with the conditions and needs of our own country, and we have no intention whatsoever to palm it off as a universal model or recipe that would be good for all
today, the mediterranean is one of the most explosive regions of the world, an intricate knot of conflicting interests abounding in huge military arsenals which are continuing to grow. there is no other enclosed sea with the same concentration of naval forces
for us, the mediterranean base is no remote, out-of-the-way area. it is close to our southern borders, and it is crossed by the only sea route linking our southern ports with the world's oceans
naturally, we are interested in routes of peace, rather than those of war, passing here. in this connection, i would like to declare that we fully support the program of security measures advanced by the mediterranean nonaligned states at their (brunei) meeting. it is a sound basis for broad and fruitful dialogue on the problems of the region
along with the earlier soviet proposals to reduce military potential in the mediterranean area, we would like to advance additional proposals for consideration to the international community
reaffirming our readiness to withdraw the soviet naval forces along with those of the united states, from the mediterranean. we suggest that this should not be put off indefinitely ... and that as a first step, the number of ships in the two countries' naval potential here should be frozen as from july 1 this year. thereafter, ceilings would be set for them
second, even before general confidence-building measures are agreed upon in the spirit of the stockholm accords, the soviet union and the united states could give each other and all the other mediterranean countries advance notice of any redistribution of warships and of naval exercises. they could also invite observers to them
third, our country will fully support the elaboration by mediterranean and other interested countries of principles and methods assuring the security of intensive shipping, especially in international straits.'' 22-24 pvs, the results ... state there. ^by david espo</note>
the five democratic presidential contenders all made it out of illinois alive, with jesse jackson declaring today that ``illinois voters were quite generous to both favorite sons'' and paul simon claiming momentum for the primaries still to come
simon's victory over jackson has rendered talk of a nationwide democratic front-runner meaningless and given new boost to discussion of a brokered national convention next summer
both simon and jackson said today that they would participate if democratic chairman paul kirk called a summit to close ranks behind a probable nominee if no one emerged from the primaries with enough delegates to win
but simon said on abc, ``i am not optimistic that it will provide answers.''
he said that after his victory in illinois, ``i think i'm going to do well'' in the contests yet to come
jackson, appearing on nbc, acknowledged that simon was ``back in the race.''
the field is wide open,'' said massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, the national leader in delegates but a third-place finisher in illinois
we're about halfway home. all sorts of things can happen,'' new york gov. mario cuomo, a non-candidate, said tuesday night in an interview on abc's ``nightline.''
illinois marked a turning point in the nominating calendar, out of the south and into the northern and midwestern states. after michigan's caucuses on saturday (138 delegates), connecticut, wisconsin (81), new york (255) and pennsylvania (178) all cast their votes in primaries over a six-week period
winners and losers alike hailed the results of tuesday's primary that gave simon the gift of political life and elevated fellow-favorite son jackson to within a few votes of wresting the national delegate lead from dukakis
dukakis, however, is expecting to reap some 100 delegates from uncounted caucuses already held in minnesota, texas and washington state
this is a new beginning for the paul simon candidacy,'' said the senator as he celebrated his triumph. ``i intend to do well in succeeding states.''
i think i will do respectably well in michigan, then in wisconsin and new york i think i will do very well.''
in a dig at dukakis, he said the massachusetts governor ``spent more than $500,000 and didn't wind up with a single delegate.'' simon has his own vulnerability of course; he couldn't win next-door iowa and bypassed the entire south and more on super tuesday
jackson said, ``i finished second, it seems in illinois.'' but he took a look at the overall popular vote for the states to hold primaries and caucuses thus far and said, ``i'm a winner. i am the leading contender for the democratic nomination. i am where every candidate wishes he could be tonight.''
jackson is hoping to maneuver around detroit mayor coleman young _ one of the few prominent black officials to endorse dukakis or any other non-jackson democrat _ to build his michigan support
dukakis, the leader in delegates nationwide, finished a distant third in illinois. he failed in a $250,000 advertising campaign designed to siphon off enough of simon's white support to drop the illinois senator into second place and force his withdrawal from the campaign
i don't get disappointed,'' dukakis said. ``we did what i characterize as a respectable third.'' he added, ``now we move on to michigan where there are no favorite sons.''
the massachusetts governor has several dozen staff aides in michigan, and is counting on the friendship of gov. james blanchard, mayor coleman young and former united auto workers union president douglas fraser to aid his cause
albert gore jr. finished fourth in illinois, and aides said despite his strong super tuesday showing a week ago, he has yet to decide where to concentrate his efforts in the north and midwest. ``the outcome means that this race is even more wide open than ever before,'' said the tennessee senator
rep. richard gephardt of missouri was last in illinois and went to bed without talking to reporters. but he was first on the air with television commercials in michigan in what aides said was a make-or-break contest for him. gephardt hopes his appeal for tougher trade policies will appeal to the state's large unionized automobile labor force and is counting on picking up agricultural support as well
i feel we did as well as we could in illinois. i just didn't feel it was worth the effort to go in and put in a lot of resources to get votes in their favorite-son situation,'' gephardt said today in kalamazoo
the race is wide open. it has been right along. i think if i can get a good result in michigan, which i think i can, i'm going to be back in the middle of this thing and have a great chance to be the nominee,'' he said
said gore: ``the outcome means this race is even more wide open than ever before ... the results ... make it more likely we will go to a second ballot'' before picking a winner at the convention
but dukakis, the best-financed and best-organized contender, shuddered at the talk. ``i've been making a number of calls around the country to key democrats and there is an overwhelming sentiment that we should get behind a nominee.''
relatives and close friends attended memorial services today for 17 soldiers killed last week in the collision of two helicopters during a night training exercise
soldiers and dignitaries, including gov. wallace wilkinson, filled the 450-seat main post chapel. an opened bible rested on a simple altar
i have flown personally with each of these men. i can tell you without reservation that they truly loved what they were doing,'' said lt. col. joseph a. fucci, commander of the 101st aviation regiment's 5th brigade
we all share in the loss of these men. and though all the grief that we feel does not begin to compare with the sorrow being felt by their wives and their families, our hearts and our prayers go out to you.''
seven aviation flight helmets mounted atop sabers and m-16 assault rifles standing next to seven pair of boots to represent those victims from the fort's aviation brigade
over the last week we have expressed our sympathies to families, friends and fellow soldiers with our heads down, unable to find the right words, if any at all, and an emptiness felt within,'' said maj. paul j. pozorski, sr, acting commander of the aviation regiment's 1st battalion
one service was held for members of the 101st aviation brigade, a second for members of the 502nd infantry regiment. both units lost members in the crash
thirteen infantrymen and helicopter crew members died when their craft, returning to campbell army airfield from a night training exercise in a formation with two other helicopters, was struck broadside by a second copter on a separate mission, army spokesmen said
all four soldiers on the second craft also died, in what the army said was its worst aviation accident since 248 fort campbell servicemen were killed in a jet crash in canada in 1985. the two other helicopters flying in formation were not damaged and landed safely
an investigation by the army safety center at fort rucker, ala., was to finish its work at the crash scene six miles from the airfield by friday and reconvene at fort rucker, officials said
the safety center's report on the accident is expected within three months
one crash investigator has said initial findings indicated that ``human and environmental factors'' _ and not mechanical failure _ were suspected as responsible for the collision
the body buried in the police chief's front yard turned out to be that of his wife's former husband, and now authorities are trying to find out how the man died and how the body ended up where it did
state pathologist dr. roger fossum was to continue an autopsy today, according to gregory swope, senior assistant attorney general
dental records identified the remains as those of russell bean, swope said tuesday. bean disappeared 10 years ago; his wife, sylvia, married the police chief, robert chambers, a year after bean's disappearance
sources close to the investigation told the associated press that police began digging in chambers' front yard following revelations by his father, clifton chambers, who died last wednesday
police discovered the bones on monday after three days of digging
the keene sentinel reported that police investigators learned the elder chambers confessed to his daughter that bean died accidentally in a fist fight after hitting his head on a rock. clifton chambers also told his daughter that he helped bury bean's body, the newspaper said
the attorney general's office, which has handled all news releases in the case, has declined to comment on the source of its information
swope said only that the dig ``was undertaken when allegations arose that a corpse was buried at that location approximately 10 years ago.''
no charges have been filed in the case
chambers, 36, and his wife, sylvia, about 35, have been secluded at a friend's home and have not spoken with reporters
chambers, who has lived in the town of 600 most of his life, three years ago took over as part-time chief. he also is part-time chief of nearby gilsum. he took an indefinite leave of absence from the marlow job on saturday
sylvia chambers is the town welfare director and has worked with the girl scouts and the cancer society
the couple lives in a five-room, 1{-story cabin with their four teen-age children by previous marriages
this is the second time in five years that marlow has been shocked by a criminal investigation
in 1983, audrey hilley, who became known as the ``black widow,'' was arrested in marlow. she had been convicted in alabama of poisoning her husband in 1975 and later trying to poison her daughter
while a fugitive, she married a man in florida, moved with him to marlow, left on a trip to texas, faked her death and returned to him posing as her twin sister. she died last year of exposure after failing to return from a furlough from a women's prison in alabama
a panel of theologians has ruled the unexplained healing of a youth's hearing impairment was a miracle attributed to mother katharine drexel, advancing efforts to have the heiress-turned-nun declared a roman catholic saint
the panel's decision will be reviewed by the 19 cardinals of the congregation for the causes of saints, which will take up the case after easter and recommend any further action to pope john paul ii
a group of doctors said in december they could find no medical explanation for the healing in 1974 of robert j. gutherman, now 28, of bensalem, after an infection had destroyed the hearing in his right ear
he regained hearing after his family and members of the order miss drexel founded, the sisters of the blessed sacrament for indians and colored people, prayed for her intervention
miss drexel, who died in 1955 at the age of 96, was declared ``venerable'' on jan. 26, 1987. if the theologians' decision is upheld by the cardinals and the pope concurs, she would be declared ``blessed,'' the final step before sainthood
before she could be declared a saint, a second miracle would have to be credited to her
miss drexel founded the sisters of the blessed sacrament in 1891 and gave $20 million toward helping blacks and american indians
i am elated,'' said sister faith okerson, executive secretary of the cornwell heights-based order. ``it's a real gift to us and our nation.''
but sister patricia lynch, a spokeswoman for the order, said miss drexel would have been happier to learn about the appointment tuesday of eugene a. marino as archbishop of atlanta
marino, who will be the first black american archbishop, attended an elementary school founded by the sisters of the blessed sacrament in biloxi, miss
she was not one for a lot of fuss about herself,'' sister lynch said. throughout. no pickup.</note>
israeli police today detained an arab-american peace activist and a palestinian was killed in clashes with troops in the occupied territories, where israel banned travel and long-distance phone calls
defense minister yitzhak rabin defended israel's move tuesday to cut telephone links between foreign countries and the west bank and gaza strip, and to ban travel by palestinians in the occupied territories
the restrictions were aimed at hampering palestine liberation organization activists, whom israel blames for keeping alive unrest that has claimed 97 arab lives since dec. 8
the army said one palestinian died and six were wounded in protests near tulkarm, 40 miles northwest of jerusalem. the army said the circumstances of the death were under investigation and that no other details were available
the arab-owned palestine press service identified the victim as 60-year-old salim al yehyeh and said he died after soldiers threw tear gas into his home in a refugee camp on the outskirts of tulkarm
hospital officials said israeli soldiers shot and wounded eight palestinians, six of them in the gaza strip and two in the west bank
arab-american mubarak awad, 44, was being held at a city police station after he was arrested for attending an illegal gathering, police spokesman rafi levy said. levy said the illegal gathering took place on the main road between jerusalem and the west bank city of nablus, but he had no further details
last year, israeli officials confiscated awad's israeli identity card and ordered him out of the country in november, when his three-month tourist visa expired. on monday, israel's supreme court ordered the interior ministry to show within 60 days why awad had not been expelled
awad, a palestinian who also has homes both in jerusalem and wapakoneta, ohio, came under fire after the publication in hebrew of his book entitled ``non-violent resistance: a strategy for the occupied territories.''
the book urged the 1.5 million palestinians in the west bank and gaza strip to refuse to pay taxes, lay down in front of bulldozers to prevent land confiscation and boycott isreli products
in other developments, a plo-ordered general strike entered its second day today, keeping most arab workers from their jobs in israel
rabin told high school students that nightly curfews in gaza were necessary to ``reduce their (the arab activists') capability to move by night, to prepare explosives ... to obstruct roads that carry workers to israel.''
according to army estimates, about 2,600 palestinians have been arrested on riot-related charges, most for throwing stones
the telephone and travel restrictions have a two-fold purpose: to demonstrate israel's determination to regain control of the streets and to keep palestinian activists from receiving telephone instructions from abroad or from moving freely between the west bank and gaza strip. israel seized the territories in the 1967 middle east war
the ban on direct-dial overseas telephone calls was not likely to be completely effective, however, since it excluded arab neighborhoods in east jerusalem, where 130,000 palestinians live
the army-run territorial government will lift restrictions when authorities feel a change and the situation calms, informed sources said
the sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, also held out the possibility other steps would be taken, including the closing of west bank bridges to jordan. the bridges are an avenue for trade and travel, and israeli officials estimate more than 1 million people cross annually
the daily hadashot newspaper today said authorities were considering cutting off electricity to some areas, banning export of some products and closing markets
in recent days, the focus of the plo campaign has shifted from street confrontations to civil disobedience, such as the resignations of arab police and tax collectors
israeli authorities each day this week have imposed new restrictions on palestinians
three children died today when a van ran off a coastal road and plunged into the chilly waters of weeks bay, where it remained submerged for three hours, state troopers said
a woman driving the van escaped and was taken by helicopter to the university of south alabama medical center, where she was being questioned byb authorities
the driver was identified as 29-year-old aimee dees of chatom. the children were not immediately identified
state troopers said the van apparently ran off a county road between 1 a.m. and 1:30 a.m.the road dead-ends into the secluded bay, about seven miles south of point clear
a group of people on the beach near the county road were huddled around a campfire when they saw the van run into the water. they pulled mrs. dees out, but didn't know the children were still in the vehicle
mrs. dees was dazed and in shock and unable to immediately describe what happened, authorities said
rescue workers searched in 30-degree weather for three hours before locating the vehicle
burt lancaster was the fast-talking tough guy, james stewart his drawling partner with homespun common sense as they rode into town to fight for a principle _ only this time it was real life, not a movie
the two hollywood legends began a two-day whirl of lobbying in congress and on television talk shows tuesday to plead for the preservation of their film classics against modern moguls out to ``make a buck.''
lancaster shook his finger at a packed room of reporters, arguing passionately for a halt to the controversial coloring of black and white films
media entrepreneur ted turner has led the colorization field, releasing computer-colored versions of such classics as ``casablanca'' and stewart's ``it's a wonderful life.''
all of this is done for them to make a buck,'' said lancaster. ``let them go out and make an honest buck.''
stewart told reporters in his halting cadence that he agreed with lancaster, ``but for me to say the same thing would take so very much longer, i better not say it.''
the two were joined in their rounds by directors peter bogdanovich, fred zinnemann and several other top american filmmakers. the hollywood push for legislation included testimony before a congressional committee two weeks ago by directors steven spielberg and george lucas
stewart said he came to washington because he was appalled by the colorization of frank capra's ``it's a wonderful life,'' after turner bought the rights to the movie
as frank's health deteriorated, he found to his horror that `it's a wonderful life' was one of the first films that was colorized. it broke his heart,'' an emotional stewart said
i am determined to do whatever i can to make things right for frank capra,'' he said
the directors and actors want congress to expand the nation's copyright laws to give directors and writers perpetual ``moral rights'' over what can be done to their works
under a plan supported by the directors guild of america, those who hold exhibition rights to completed movies would not be allowed to make changes _ such as adding color _ without the filmmakers' permission
i see myself today in movies where the story has been distorted and the movie chopped up,'' said lancaster. ``yet, my name is on it. i think, `what are they doing to me?'
they don't own me. they're using my name as a kind of draw. that's felonious, really.''
although he was passionate before the news cameras, drawing memories of his roles as a tough guy dating back to the 1940s, lancaster said he toned down his private performance before members of congress
we're dealing with politicians _ we have to be a little political too,'' he said. affect network ratings. picks up 3rd graf, `with only ...'</note>
nbc's ``aaron's way'' made it into the top 10 in the a.c. nielsen co. ratings as the television season winds down and the networks begin giving spring tryouts to potential series
last week's ratings were skewed by pre-emptions for college basketball and the rev. billy graham's televised fund-raising, but nbc still won, taking the top five places
network analysts estimate that about a quarter of the country's network affiliates pre-empted network shows for the graham crusade on friday night, lowering the networks' ratings. graham's show is syndicated, so its ratings aren't included in the weekly nielsens
with only five weeks left, abc is holding onto second place in the season-long ratings race, thanks to high ratings for its winter olympics coverage
nbc won the week that ended sunday with an average, prime-time rating of 15.9. cbs had a 12.7 and abc 11.8. the season-to-date averages are nbc 16.3, abc 14.0 and cbs 13.6
to make up the 0.4 point it lags behind abc, cbs would have to beat abc by two points each of the remaining five weeks of the season, an unlikely prospect
cbs, however, has rebounded in news ratings. for the week that ended friday, the ``cbs evening news'' had an average rating of 11.1, its second-straight victory. abc's ``world news tonight'' had a 10.2 and ``nbc nightly news'' had a 9.4
the rating is the percentage of the nation's 88.6 million households with televisions
after a lengthy reign at the top of the news ratings last summer, nbc is now struggling in third, although the close rankings make the news race virtually a three-way tie
nbc analyst gerald jaffe said results of the november sweeps showed nbc with a disadvantage in local news lead-in. nbc affiliates had an average rating of 11.5, which ``nightly news'' improved on, to 11.9
cbs had the best advantage. its affiliates had an average rating of 12.9, and the network newscast improved that to 13.1. abc affiliates averaged a 12.0 rating and the network broadcast was a 12.3
network news is an island in a sea of local news,'' said jaffe. ``if the local news is going down, there's not much you can do to keep the network news from going down, too.''
nbc continued to dominate prime time. ``the cosby show'' was no. 1 even though the episode was a repeat. next was nbc's ``cheers,'' ``a different world,'' ``night court'' and ``golden girls.'' the rest of the top 10: ``murder, she wrote'' cbs, ``the people's choice awards'' cbs, ``60 minutes'' cbs, ``growing pains'' abc. ``aaron's way,'' a new nbc series starring merlin olsen as the patron of an amish family trying to cope in california, made its debut at no. 10, the best showing of the crop of new series getting spring tryouts
the premiere movie of abc's new series ``probe'' did well, landing in 28th place, but its regular time period on thursday didn't make a dent in the ratings and was ranked 60th of 68
abc seems to have successfully transplanted ``growing pains'' from tuesday to wednesday, where it was strong enough to pull ``head of the class'' into 11th place
katharine hepburn proved she is still a ratings draw. her nbc movie ``laura lansing slept here'' was 12th
cbs did make headway against nbc's thursday's lineup with the debut of ``48 hours'' in its new time period opposite ``cosby.'' last week's documentary on runaways ranked 34th with a rating of 22.9
the lowest-rated shows of the week were: ``buck james,'' ``probe,'' ``ohara,'' ``west 57th,'' ``hotel,'' ``barry manilow, swing street,'' abc's super tuesday coverage, ``the thorns,'' cbs' super tuesday coverage and ``the redeye express.'' rioting; edits to tighten. no pickup</note>
attackers fired pistols and hurled hand grenades at a graveside service for three slain irish republican army guerrillas today, killing three people and injuring 34, police reported. one man was arrested
thousands of mourners threw themselves to the ground as the explosions ripped across the milltown roman catholic cemetery, while hundreds of others raced across the graves pursuing a suspected attacker
one attacker, weaving and dodging between gravestones, flung a hand grenade at the pursuing mourners
organizers of the funeral for the guerrillas, who were shot by british troops in gibraltar, immediately blamed protestant paramilitaries for the attack
police moved in to surround the cemetery and a dozen ambulances ferried the 34 injured, including several young children hit by gunfire, to the nearby royal victoria hospital
the three dead, all men, were not immediately identified. a hospital spokeswoman said one of the injured, a woman, was in serious condition and three men also were gravely wounded
it's obvious it was an attack by loyalist (protestant) movements,'' martin mcguinness, vice president of sinn fein, the outlawed ira's legal political front, told reporters in the cemetery
the violence erupted about 15 yards away as the flag-draped coffins of mairead farrell, 31, sean savage, 24, and daniel mccann, 30, were being lowered into a single grave. the unarmed trio were shot march 6 by british troops in gibraltar, and british authorities alleged the three were on a bombing mission
within hours of the cemetery attack, youths hijacked and set fire to a bus in the ardoyne area in nearby catholic west belfast, despite sinn fein appeals for calm. it roused fears of renewed rioting in the west belfast, already tense because of the funerals
at the cemetery, mourners screamed as at least five explosions rang out. mcguinness said that witnesses had spotted four men getting out of white van and slip into the cemetery just before the attack
amid scenes of chaos in the cemetery, several hundred youths gave chase to one attacker who fled, still firing and throwing a grenades, witnesses said
i saw maybe 300 youths chasing this one gunman who turned every 15-20 yards, threw a hand grenade and loosed off a shot before running again,'' said cab driver aidan o'reilly
the mourners were gaining, but bunched up and he threw another grenade into the middle of them, then got out on to the motorway. ... he was egging them on to come and get him when he threw the grenade.''
at the cemetery, sinn fein organizers completed the funeral while priests comforted the wounded
the rev. alec reid, who was saying prayers next to the graveside as the last of the coffins draped in the irish tricolor was being lowered, said he saw a young man throwing something from the back of the crowd
i thought they were stones, but it looks as if they were grenades. he was also firing shots into the crowd.''
in london, british officials said prime minister margaret thatcher was immediately informed
the mourners had followed the coffins through somber streets to the cemetery
at a mass earlier in st. agnes, mourners listened silently as the priest charged that the three ira men were murdered
shortly before the funeral began, a bomb exploded on a street more than a mile from the church, slightly injuring a british soldier on foot patrol, police reported
the almost exclusively catholic irish republican army is fighting to push the british out of protestant-dominated northern ireland, join it with the republic of ireland and set up an all-ireland socialist state
britain says the slain guerrillas were shot by commandos while preparing a car bomb attack on the changing of the guard outside the governor's residence in the colony on the southern tip of spain
the three were unarmed, but britain said they made movements that led the soldiers to believe their lives were in danger. the irish government has complained that the soldiers should have tried to arrest the trio
in the tense buildup to the funerals, protestants stoned hearses that brought the ira bodies home tuesday
soldiers today battled more than 100 communist rebels who burned a town hall and kidnapped three policemen. at least four rebels and three soldiers were killed, the military said
before dawn, about 120 rebels entered san juan, and most took over the municipal building while others searched homes, maj. wilmur panabang told repoters. san juan is 210 miles north of manila
panabang, the philippine constabulary assistant provincial commander, said troops arrived at daybreak in trucks and an armored personnel carrier from the provincial capital of bangued, about 20 miles away, and attacked the rebel positions
the troops were backed by three helicopter gunships, but panabang denied they fired rockets at the rebels in the town hall
we wanted to do that but we were afraid to miss and hit houses instead because the town hall is in the middlle of town,'' he said
provincial governor vicente valera ordered the evacuation of residents from san juan and nearby villages during the fighting and military pursuit operations to prevent civilians from getting hit in the crossfire
at least four rebels and three soldiers were killed before the guerrillas broke off the engagement about five hours later, set fire to the building and retreated to the nearby mountains, panabang said
only seven bodies were recovered following the fighting, including those of two soldiers whose remains were charred in the fire. but panabang quoted witnesses as saying the rebels loaded nine bodies on a commandeered jeep as they departed
he said the rebels ``may very well have suffered up to 13 dead'' in the raid
one trooper also was wounded in the fighting, panabang said
the retreating guerrillas took three police hostages with them, including san juan police chief alejandro arcanghel, he said
more than 100 troops backed by the three helicopter gunships and the armored personnel carrier pursued the rebel force into the hills around san juan until midday, panabang said. he said the military planned to resume pursuit of the rebels shortly
the attack was the bloodiest in northern luzon this year and was the second in abra province
two crane operators at a plutonium production plant were contaminated with a low level of radiation, and one of the men carried the radiation into his home, a plant spokesman said
investigators found radiation in the cab of a crane at the plant but the source of the contamination has not been determined, said bill whiting of westinghouse hanford, which operates the plutonium-uranium extraction plant at the hanford nuclear reservation under government contract
contamination was found on one of the men when he reported to work monday and a check of his home determined he had spread the contamination there, whiting said
radiation was found on the other employee's hands and clothes monday as he prepared to leave for the day, whiting said
the level of radiation was extremely low and posed no health threat, he said
both operators were decontaminated and given clearance to return to work
a radiation team checked the homes of the two crane operators and two other employees monday night, whiting said. they removed a wash cloth, electric razor, towel and undershirt from the home of the employee who registered contamination when he arrived at work, he said
the maximum contamination level in the crane operator's home was 3,500 counts per minute, or less than half the radiation present in the glowing part of a lighted gas lantern, whiting said
you can buy higher levels of radiation at the store,'' he said
it wasn't known how radiation on the operator who contaminated his home had been missed in daily checks of employees leaving the plant
the contamination was isolated at the plant in the area surrounding the crane, he said
investigators' preliminary report will be issued within 10 working days, whiting said
an explosion in a chemistry lab injured a teacher and a student today and forced officials to close newton county high school
both the 34-year-old teacher and the 16-year-old student were reported in stable condition, but a georgia baptist medical center spokeswoman said the teacher was expected to undergo plastic surgery
the teacher was taken by helicopter to the atlanta hospital with burns, bruises, hand injuries and minor facial injuries, said spokeswoman colleen nowak
the student suffered cuts on her arms and was expected to be kept overnight at newton county general hospital, said a spokeswoman there, kathy klauss
the explosion occurred during a chemistry experiment about 8:45 a.m., said herb burnsed, assistant superintendent of the newton county school system
fumes spread into hallways and prompted officials to dismiss classes for the day, he said
the victims were not identified pending notification of relatives
a small group of people dedicated to terry anderson's release from captivity in lebanon today hoisted an american flag and tied a yellow ribbon to the flag pole at city hall
the ceremony marked the third anniversary of the capture of anderson, who was born in lorain and spent the first seven years of his life in this northern ohio city
anderson, 40, chief middle east correspondent for the associated press, was abducted march 16, 1985. he is the longest-held of 22 foreign hostages in lebanon. there has been no word of him for three months
a dozen people, including some of anderson's relatives, attended the ceremony in cold, dry weather
jack lavriha, chairman of the town's free terry anderson committee, spoke briefly and accused the reagan administration of dragging its feet and doing little on behalf of anderson and oher hostages in lebanon
gwen jones, anderson's aunt, said after the ceremony that the family is ``finding it very hard and frustrating.''
anderson's sister, peggy say, will be speaking at the lorain veterans council's 42nd annual banquet on saturday. mrs. say, of batavia, n.y., was in washington today for a ceremony for anderson and other hostages
in beirut, two lebanese newspapers today published letters addressed to anderson and his pro-iranian captors, along with pictures of his 2-year-old daughter
mrs. jones said she hadn't thought her nephew would be held this long. she said that if she could talk to him, she would ``tell him to keep praying. i'm sure the lord is going to answer those prayers.''
swarms of desert locusts have been sighted on the tunisia-libya border, and a government committee has been set up to battle the agricultural pests
government sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said authorities have begun spraying in the areas of bir-pasteur, north of bourje el-khadra near the frontier
a committee comprised of governors from the affected regions, primarily in eastern and southern tunisia, is working with the tunisian army in fighting the infestation
locusts also have been reported in northern mauritania, southern morocco and algeria. morocco has mobilized 35 airplanes and land vehicles to fight the infestations, according to the official map news agency
in late february, the u.n. food and agriculture organization said northern africa and the sahel region were threatened by swarms of locusts
the taiwan government will allow foreign films shot on the china mainland to be shown here, an official said wednesday
government spokesman shaw yu-ming told reporters the government decided to lift the ban on the films because taiwan citizens have been allowed since last year to visit the chinese mainland for family reunions
officials of the government information office's motion pictures department said applications to import the movies will be accepted effective wednesday
shaw said, however, that the new policy won't apply to mandarin-language films shot in china by companies in the british colony of hong kong, which, together with domestic films, are governed by a more restrictive law. this restriction will be reviewed in may
shaw said taiwan film companies still will be banned from going to china to shoot movies
the public repeatedly has urged the government to ease the restrictions on foreign films, especially since ``the last emperor,'' a movie shot in beijing, won nine oscar nominations last month
here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers throughout the nation
march 9
westerly (r.i.) sun on nuclear reactor safety:
the cumulative effect of frequent censure of the nuclear regulatory commission for lax enforcement of safety standards is to bolster a where-there's-smoke-there's-fire conclusion
this time ... the nrc's apparent (desire) to ok relicensing of reactors closed for safety flaws in 1985 by the tennessee valley authority brought testy comments at a house committee hearing
the projected restarts are planned although the justice department has not completed its investigation of charges that the tva's nuclear power manager, steven a. white, made ... false assertions as to the reactors' compliance with safety rules
rep. sam gejdenson of connecticut ... zeroed in on the conclusion of the commission ... that white ``intentionally lied to the nrc.''
he spoke for many ... when he said: ``the thing i am concerned about is that the justice department could decide that mr. white is guilty of lying ... and the nrc would have ordered a restart of that reactor.''
a fair question: what's the big hurry?
march 15
baltimore evening sun on the execution of willie darden:
as florida authorities prepared for the ritual of taking willie jasper darden's life ..., they maintained that his conviction for a 1973 murder was based on ``irrefutable evidence.''
in fact the evidence is refutable _ refutable by at least two witnesses who were not called at darden's trial more than a decade ago. but what is irrefutable is that darden, a black man, was tried before an elected white judge in an inflamed predominantly white community in rural florida, prosecuted by a white district attorney, ... convicted by an all-white jury drawn from friends and neighbors of the murder victim, and sent to the electric chair by a white governor. ..
is there anyone of any color, creed, ethnic background or religious or ideological persuasion who truly believes he could get a fair trial for his life under such circumstances?
march 15
the kansas city (mo.) times on aid to the contras:
if congress has behaved schizophrenically over contra aid, part of the reason may be that deception by the administration has made it hard to tell reality from phantasm in nicaragua
the administration has put lawmakers in the unfortunate position of having to question the leadership of their democratic government while simultaneously trying to fend off communist leadership in another
that helps explain why lawmakers have over time voted for and against contra aid, and why it is difficult now for military aid to be approved
march 11
riverside (calif.) press-enterprise on budget deficit projections:
there is a white house budgeting ritual. call it fiscal chicken. ..
the white house budget office issues its spending plan. the spending is all geared to impossibly high economic growth predictions. in six or eight months, it becomes apparent that there just isn't that much steam in the economy
shame might compel most people to concede, but this is where this budget office gets tough. ..
only when evidence of this impossible optimism becomes just mountainous do the president's men back off a bit in their predictions. and as it retreats, the office of management and budget is required to observe that there's a new economic boom coming, just around the corner
recently president reagan's fiscal 1989 budget was issued. ... a deficit of $130 billion is foreseen
to make all these figures come out so serendipitously, the white house budget office underlaid them with a forecast of 2.4 percent economic growth in calendar 1988 and 3.5 percent growth in calendar 1989
the congressional budget office has now come out with its own economic forecast. it envisions growth of 0.6 percent less in '88 and 0.9 percent less in '89. run the white house budget numbers off that base and it produces a fiscal 1989 deficit of $165 billion
under the usual rules, the white house wouldn't admit its optimism before about september. but this being the year of transitional election, it may never admit it
it is ronald reagan's last chance to set a new record for rosy optimism. he'll probably want to have a run at it
march 8
the commercial appeal, memphis, tenn., on state-federal relationships:
state and local governments have long had a love-hate relationship with washington. they gladly accept federal subsidies, but resent conditions on how to spend the money
now they are getting the worst of both worlds: burdensome mandates without the funds to pay for them
the national governrs' association has voted to make this issue its highest priority for 1988
the governors _ along with mayors, city councils and school boards _ believe they deserve far more credit for honesty, good will and competence than the federal rulemakers are willing to give them. they are right
in many areas, such as education and welfare reform, these officials have shown themselves to be more innovative and effective than washington. ..
the governors have 163 specific proposals to lighten the regulatory load. congress should pay close attention
march 15
albuquerque (n.m.) journal on drug testing of transportation employees:
the discovery of cocaine in the system of the pilot of a commuter airplane that crashed near durango, colo., in january highlights a troubling dimension of the debate over who, if anybody, among american workers should be subjected to mandatory random drug testing
it was in january that the national transportation safety board disclosed a conrail engineer had used marijuana prior to a january 1987 collision between an amtrak passenger train and a conrail freight train, in which 16 passengers were killed
the personal rights of individuals employed in the transportation industry may have to give way to the right to safety of those who depend upon them to give alert, drug-free service in preparing and crewing commercial airliners and trains
if there is a group in our society in which mandatory, random testing would have potential for saving lives, the public transportation industry is it
march 14
san antonio (texas) express-news on trading with the soviet union:
of all the cabinet departments, the department of commerce is probably the least conspicuous to the average american, but beware
commerce secretary c. william verity wants to increase trade with the soviet union. selling levis, fords and coca-colas to 250 million soviets is tempting, but caution should be exercised
the soviets won't allow their market to be bought for a pittance. they want high-tech products more than blue jeans and cola
the pentagon opposes any trade in sensitive military gear. it should
getting a corner on soviet markets is enticing, but these are the same people who trample the civil rights of their citizens, who use slave labor to manufacture some of their goods, and who, in parts of the world, look down rifle barrels at u.s. troops
in summary, it's ok to boost trade in some areas, but don't give away the store
march 9
the news tribune, woodbridge, n.j., on masters and johnson's aids research:
in their new book ... so-called sex experts drs. william masters and virginia johnson have suggested that one in 20 men who have had at least six sexual partners for five years are infected with the aids virus
they say the rate is slightly higher among women
previous studies have shown the undeniable link between intravenous drug use and aids, and homosexual behavior and aids
what masters and johnson have done is suggest the link between casual heterosexual sex and aids may be greater than previously thought
time will tell who is right. we want to believe masters and johnson's scary scenario is wrong. but who knows?
aids is such a mystery that it is difficult to offer reliable statistics. the debate really isn't how, but how much
we could dismiss masters and johnson's methodology as wrong. what would be worse would be to dismiss the risk, and be dead wrong
march 9
medford (ore.) mail tribune on jesse jackson:
jesse jackson says he plans to be the democratic party's presidential nominee. ... with all due respect, we beg to differ. ..
jackson cannot survive a close examination. his record includes too many radical stands, too many blanket condemnations of the united states and too many associations with foreign leaders of questionable character. ..
in practical terms, jackson's best hope is that his delegate strength will force the party's leaders to make sure that the presidential platform features issues of concern to the people who have supported him
expecting much of anything beyond that is wishful thinking
march 10
brainerd (minn.) daily dispatch on postal rate increases:
dear postmaster general:
we're writing to you now, before postage rates rise next month
so you want to raise the price of the common, first-class stamp to 25 cents? that's only a jump of 14 percent, or three cents
trouble is, that's just part of the problem
you also want to raise the rates for second-class mail by 18 percent and for third-class mail by 25 percent
and guess who is going to help offset the increase. yep, the consumer
affected businesses will be forced to charge higher prices. magazines and newspapers will be forced to charge higher rates for advertising and subscriptions
we're afraid that higher postage rates will impose hardships on postal patrons whose only consolation will be a probable decline in the amount of junk mail
march 11
the hutchinson (kan.) news on college admissions standards:
mediocrity may be just so-so in most places, but in the kansas house of representatives, medocrity is excellent
with a vote so lopsided that it could never be described as average, the house spurned the idea of setting some (rather low) admissions standards for entrance to the state's top universities. ..
kansas students would have responded well to the modest challenge outlined in the educational admissions bill
no conscientious student would have been prevented from getting a college degree, and a series of higher educational standards would have led to more valuable degrees. ..
mediocrity is not nearly the superlative value that politicians think it to be
march 11
the milwaukee (wis.) journal on anti-drug legislation:
barely two weeks before the current state legislative session is to end, the omnibus drug bill promoted by gov. thompson and several lawmakers appears ready for action
the massive bill, which sets out an $11.6 million drug-fighting program, is the state's broadest attack on drug abuse in years and deserves bipartisan support
apparently, the only danger the bill faces is the possibility of getting hung up over one of its more controversial features _ the so-called ``len bias'' provision
named for a university of maryland basketball player who died in 1986 after taking cocaine, this provision would allow prosecution of drug suppliers on charges of second-degree murder if a client died of drug use
while that provision likely would have a deterrent effect on drug dealers and should be retained in the bill's final version, it is by no means the heart of the legislation
debate over its inclusion should not be permitted to hold up legislative approval of the omnibus bill
more important are the bill's (1) stiffer criminal penalties for the sale and use of a broad class of drugs and (2) needed funds for drug and alcohol treatment programs. ..
the bill strongly deserves approval before the legislature adjourns. sentence</head>
a woman charged with keeping an 8-year-old boy in a coffin-like box for two years said she confined the boy to protect her possessions and pleaded guilty to unlawful imprisonment
i restrained (the boy) during my sleeping hours in order to keep him from destroying property. my judgment may not have been proper, but my judgment as to the amount of restraint seemed proper to me under the circumstances,'' said retha skyles in a handwritten statement
ms. skyles, 54, entered her plea tuesday in pierce county superior court before judge thomas swayze jr., who set sentencing for april 26
in exchange for the plea, the prosecution agreed that ms. skyles be sentenced under provisions for first-time offenders, said deputy prosecutor barbara corey-boulet
that means a judge could sentence the woman to up to 90 days in jail plus two years' probation and counseling
ms. skyles was charged with keeping the son of her step-granddaughter in a playhouse-sized box from may 1, 1985, to may 1, 1987. the box often was locked and contained a jar in which the boy was expected to urinate, the charges said. the boy was not allowed to attend school
an anonymous referral tipped off state child potective services workers on april 29, 1987, and they took the boy and his 11-year-old sister into custody. the siblings have lived with foster parents and are doing well, ms. corey-boulet said
one of ms. skyles' adult sons said the confinement was a temporary way to handle the tantrum-prone boy
he said the family believed he was brain-damaged because of his mother, who the son said abused drugs and wouldn't take proper care of the boy. the natural mother denied she was a drug abuser
when sidney moncrief graduated from the university of arkansas, he left behind a sterling record as a basketball player and $8.31
the milwaukee bucks' star is one of the 2,494 arkansans who have money in accounts that have been inactive for seven years. state auditor julia jones is trying to track them down through a publicity campaign beginning this month
the booty is more than $750,000 in wages, bank accounts, insurance payments, utility deposits and other monies
nancy l. thornton, who heads the auditor's unclaimed property division, said that in some instances, the owners simply had not touched their accounts for seven years and the money is not actually unclaimed
moncrief's $8.31? seems he forgot about a electric utility deposit from his school days
most of spain's 270,000 public school teachers on wednesday began a second two-day strike for higher pay, forcing cancellation of classes for more than 5 million students, union and education ministry officials said
the ministry said it won't negotiate while the threat of strikes continues
the nation's two largest unions, the socialist-led general workers union and the communist-oriented workers commissions, called the strike
the unions said 92 percent of teachers backed their march 9-10 strike. the education ministry estimated teacher participation at 60 percent
negotiations broke off last month over public elementary and secondary school teachers' demands that they receive pay equal to that of similarly qualified civil servants
a union spokesman said primary school teachers earn an average of about $929 a month and want it raised to about $1,170, while secondary and technical school teachers want about $1,380 a month
education ministry undersecretary joaquin arango said teachers last year received the biggest raises _ 13 percent _ among civil servants. the rest of the civil servants received raises of 5 percent. spain's 1987 inflation rate was 4.6 percent
a seed company has developed a poppy with a reduced content of opium, a spokesman said wednesday
the white poppy is popular in denmark for its seed, traditionally used in bread. the plant's juice contains opium, which can be refined into morphine and heroin
we are doing this so that drug addicts will not feel tempted to pick or cut the poppies to get the drug, and so that farmers will continue to be allowed to grow poppies,'' said christian petersen of daehnfeldt, the biggest seed producer in europe
drug addicts have been known to plunder poppy fields in denmark. in other countries, including the united states, great britain and west germany, poppy cultivation has been banned
we ... have been able to reduce the opium content by half. in a couple of years, we expect to have more or less eliminated it completely,'' petersen said
a west virginia physician has filed consumer fraud complaints in all 50 states charging four major publishers with selling achievement tests that give a misleadingly rosy picture of student progress
the complaints were filed by john jacob cannell, who gained prominence last november as a test gadfly with a 26-page report accusing publishers of the iowa test, the metropolitan achievement test and similar tests of giving ``children, parents, school systems, legislatures, and the press misleading reports on achievement levels.''
the november report led officials of the u.s. department of education to summon 40 test experts and publishers to a closed-door meeting last month to discuss possible actions
cannell, who is from daniels, w.va., filed his complaints wednesday with the 50 state attorneys general, and distributed them to reporters. but he said he had not provided copies to the publishers named in the complaints
three of the four publishers said they had no comment because they hadn't seen the complaint. but a spokesman for ctb@mcgraw hill, publisher of the california achievement test and comprehensive test of basic skills, said cannell's work was ``full of fallacious statements.''
cannell's complaint claimed ``that 90 percent of school districts and 70 percent of children in america's public elementary schools are presently testing above average in elementary grades on one of the six commercial tests used in the u.s.a.''
thirty-eight of the complaints named ctb@mcgraw hill; 36 named the psychological corporation, which publishes the stanford achievement test and the metropolitan achievement test; 31 cited riverside publishing co., which publishes the iowa test of basic skills, and 26 listed science research associates, publisher of the sra exam
the complaints ask that publishers be required to identify school districts using their tests, provide free annual updates of the norms that determine how students score, and provide new test questions for free each year to ensure that schools cannot ``teach to the test.''
cannell, founder and head of the 700-member west virginia education watchdog group friends for education inc., also called upon each state to analyze standardized tests to determine if they have gotten easier over time
he also demanded that test publishers supply new, more accurate tests at no charge to ``compensate consumers for any misrepresentations received from previously deceptive tests.''
in september, cannell filed similar consumer complaints in his home state and in kentucky. he withdrew them last month after mcgraw hill announced it would provide annually updated norms
paul williams, director of research and management of ctb@mcgraw hill, said cannell condemned standardized tests generally for giving too rosy a picture of student progress, but ``he only looks at half the pie'' because cannell omits the fact that test scores for high school students have declined
responding to some of cannell's specific complaints, williams said publishers would probably resist demands to identify school districts using their tests. ``we have a responsibility to protect the confidentiality of our customers,'' he said
williams said his company already updates test norms annually, but he rejected cannell's demand that that service be provided free
he said it would be possible for testmakers to provide states with new questions each year, ``but it's also expensive. if our customers want it, we would respond.''
he added that the technical manuals that publishers routinely provide school districts using their tests already provide much of the information cannell demanded, such as how difficult the tests are
hopes for an end to the war in afghanistan have focused attention on talks in geneva this week, but more is at stake than the soviet union's military withdrawal from the 9-year-old conflict
the kremlin's apparent willingness to extract its estimated 115,000 troops may signal a broader policy change in the superpower's role in foreign revolutions
should an acceptable retreat be found from afghanistan and the conflict between pro- and anti-communist forces be left to the afghans, soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev would heal one of his nation's most visible foreign policy sores. he also could improve relations with the united states, china, the indian subcontinent and the moslem world
perhaps most importantly, some observers suggest, the kremlin might be rethinking its role in promoting socialist revolution in nations such as nicaragua and angola, where soviet aid bolsters government forces against tenacious opposition
the afghan revolution is the only struggle in which the soviet union acknowledges its troops are fighting
since the kremlin announced last year that it had taken the ``political decision'' to withdraw its troops from afghanistan, the state-run media and officials have hinted that policies that led to the dec. 27, 1979, intervention are under close scrutiny
oleg t. bogomolov, a leading economist who heads the institute of economics of the world socialist system, said in a letter published wednesday that he warned the kremlin less than a month after the intervention that sending soviet soldiers to afghanistan damaged relations with the united states, china and moslem nations
while marxist doctrine forecasts the spread of socialist revolution worldwide, gorbachev has made it clear that his first priority is getting his own nation's economy on its feet
the government has indicated it will fulfill its contractual agreements, even in afghanistan
foreign ministry spokesman gennady i. gerasimov told reporters tuesday that military aid to afghanistan was not subject to negotiation in geneva because it was part of longstanding cooperation with kabul
however, some american sovietologists and veteran foreign policy experts see in the military withdrawal the possible emergence of a policy of improving relations with other nations and directing resources to domestic needs
i see them moving toward a different approach to regional conflict,'' former u.s. defense secretary robert mcnamara said in an interview. ``i get the distinct impression they are changing substantially their view of the projection of power, in part on the basis of their experience in afghanistan, as in the united states we were affected by our experience in vietnam.''
mcnamara, in moscow this week for a conference on soviet reforms, served as defense secretary in the 1960s during the height of the vietnam war under presidents john f. kennedy and lyndon b. johnson
if gorbachev's stated sentiment for focusing time and money on improving the soviet lifestyle is genuine, mcnamara suggested, he will find it expedient to reduce soviet involvement in struggles between pro- and anti-communist forces
he pointed to civil warfare in nicaragua and angola as examples where gorbachev may be willing to step out if the united states did
robert legvold, director of columbia university's harriman institute for advanced study of the soviet union, accompanied a u.s. senate delegation to a three-hour meeting with gorbachev last week
he said he is convinced gorbachev and his advisers have made a commitment to ``cut their losses'' in afghanistan and have already begun a serious analysis of how the mistake of intervening was made
there is a feeling it was a lousy decision in all contexts _ in u.s.-soviet relations, in relations with arab countries, in sino-soviet relations,'' legvold said
the key move in working toward an afghan peace accord was an end to soviet insistence that the postwar government retain its current socialist character, said legvold
stephen cohen, a princeton university professor and author of several books on the soviet union, said the war in afghanistan could teach the kremlin ``the constraints of power'' and that losing a conventional war in the nuclear age does not necessarily threaten their security
carol j. williams has reported on soviet foreign policy and other issues from moscow since 1984. she visited afghanistan in october 1986
parents say they would be willing to pay higher taxes to give their children more education in the arts, according to pollster louis harris
seventy percent of respondents said they would pay an extra $10 in taxes for that purpose, and 56 percent would pay an extra $25, harris said
the american people are nothing less than outraged at the cuts that have been made in the arts in the curricula of public schools,'' harris said tuesday
he said nine of 10 people polled said, ``it's highly important for children of school age to be exposed to theater, music and dance, exhibitions of paintings and sculpture and similar cultural events.''
fifty-eight of those polled believe their children are being deprived of that experience, harris said
two of three give the arts as important billing as math, science, english, languages and social studies,'' harris said. ``this is a powerful mandate _ one that's gone too long unheeded by the school establishment in this country.''
however, despite support for arts in the schools, people are going to performances less
harris said decreases of 12 percent in attendance and 3 percent in participation were the first declines sustained since 1973, when he began regularly sampling national attitudes about the arts
although 33 percent of those polled said lack of time was the reason they didn't go to more arts performances, 32 percent said not enough performances were offered where they live and 29 percent said ticket prices are too high
no doubt price is an important element,'' harris said, but he called time more important
until the current poll, the amount of time devoted to the arts had grown _ despite a decline in leisure time from a median of 26.2 hours a week in 1973 to 18.1 hours in 1984
in the poll, a telephone survey of 1,501 adults conducted for philip morris companies inc. in march and april 1987, leisure time slipped to 16.6 hours a week overall, with women, blacks and hispanics below the median. the survey group, harris said, represented a national cross-section
the survey showed that hispanics have 13 hours a week of leisure time, and blacks, although gaining nearly three hours a week since 1984, still have only 15
women, increasingly combining jobs and homemaking, report having 14 hours a week for leisure time, while men have 19 hours, harris said
when people have lost leisure time, they have turned to vcrs,'' said harris. he said that ``44 percent of owners of vcrs report that they are increasingly watching a movie or some other performance on videotape instead of watching regularly scheduled programs on television.''
people want to be able to pick and choose precisely what they'll be doing with their precious but limited leisure time,'' he said. ``if they have an hour and 10 minutes _ and people are measuring it that way _ they're highly likely to pick out a videocassette that appeals to them and make a date with themselves to enjoy it.''
the air force academy grounds will be opened to limited deer hunting this fall for the first time in 18 years because of a burgeoning deer population and dwindling forage
without the hunting season, some of the estimated 1,500 to 2,000 deer could starve to death
the oct. 15-nov. 13 season for antlerless deer will be limited to 80 hunters _ 40 from the public and 40 academy personnel, said tom seamans, regional state wildlife manager
only rifles may be used
many of the deer who roam the academy appear to have little fear of people, but while they have been shielded from hunters for nearly two decades, their lives have not been risk-free
mike babler, academy resources officer, said about 100 deer are killed by motorists each year on academy reservation roads and adjoining interstate 25. in 1986, there were 186 collisions between cars and deer on or near the academy, he said
a man convicted of buying lsd with $20,000 he received from a state fund for crime victims has been sentenced to four years in prison and fined $14,000, federal court officials said wednesday
james b. miller, 29, of south charleston, pleaded guilty in january to two counts of distributing the hallucinogenic drug, admitting he sold 3,300 ``hits'' of lsd to police agents in 1986
he appeared tuesday before u.s. district judge john t. copenhaver jr
compensation fund records show miller was awarded the maximum personal-injury payment of $20,000 in 1985 after he was shot in 1983. miller apparently had just arrived at a beach party when he was shot in the right arm by someone using a .30-caliber rifle, police records show
miller lost his arm and incurred about $38,000 in medical bills, according to state officials
