a paris art gallery filed federal lawsuits accusing a dealer of operating a $32.5 million nationwide forgery network specializing in the works of surrealist painter salvador dali
t.r. rogers, whose beverly hills gallery was raided in august when forgery allegations surfaced, was named with four others in the $145 million package of suits filed last week in los angeles and new york on behalf of galerie furstenberg of paris
also named were wholesalers philip coffaro, thomas wallace and carol convertine and art authenticator julien aime, all of new york
the new york suit accuses all five of running an ongoing criminal enterprise in violation of federal racketeering laws
rogers' attorney, david steiner, called the lawsuits ``preposterous,'' and arnold ross, a new york lawyer representing coffaro, said, ``there doesn't appear to be any basis to it at all.''
i'm sure there will be substantial cross-complaints filed against them for the outrageous claims they're making,'' steiner said
beverly hills detectives began an investigation into rogers' gallery last summer after jean argillet, owner of galerie furstenberg, told police the originals of some of the works in rogers' gallery represented as dalis were actually in his own gallery in france
the case has since been turned over to the major frauds section of the los angeles county district attorney's office
the international dali market has long been the subject of an authenticity controversy because the artist made numerous copies during his youth and now refuses to come out of seclusion in spain to authenticate disputed canvasses
ms. convertine pleaded guilty to felony fraud and grand larceny charges in new york last year
a grand jury is now contemplating criminal charges against a honolulu gallery. another criminal case was begun in new mexico, and the federal trade commission is taking civil action against a gallery in arizona
according to the galerie furstenberg lawsuits, the defendants reproduced photos of dali originals, and through photomechanical means engraved the images on copper plates and ran off multiple copies
