no individual contracts will be signed during the writers guild of america strike, meaning the ``tonight show'' and other daily programs will get no new material until the walkout ends, the guild announced wednesday
the vote by the guild council reverses the position taken in earlier strikes, when individual waivers were approved for certain programs, including johnny carson's ``tonight show.''
the stance also reiterates the guild position that none of its writers will work on next month's academy awards broadcast
the council has decided to table all consideration of independent contracts until a future time,'' said mona mangan, executive director of the writers guild east, in a statement released after the vote
the strike by the 9,000-member guild against the alliance of motion picture and television producers began march 7. striking writers in hollywood and new york city have been walking picket lines
the writers had rejected an offer from the producers a day earlier. it marks the fourth walkout since 1973 by the wga; the longest, in 1981, lasted 17 weeks
the guild also announced wednesday that the canadian and british writers guilds have asked their members to support the walkout unless they had contracted for work prior to the strike
u.s. industrial production edged up 0.2 percent in february as reductions in output at auto factories and coal mines offset gains in other areas, the government reported wednesday
the federal reserve said that the february advance, which followed a 0.3 percent january gain, was the poorest showing since output actually declined by 0.2 percent in september
but private economists said the gains, even at a much slower pace, represented good news for the economy, especially given fears that production would have to be cut back sharply in the early part of 1988 in order to work off high levels of unsold goods
there is nothing here that signals anything dangerous for the economy,'' said maury harris, chief economist at painewebber. ``we are slowing down, but we are not slowing all that much.''
industrial output had surged ahead with monthly increases of 1.1 percent in october and 0.5 percent in both november and december. however, much of that production went into inventories of unsold goods as consumer spending fell during the final three months of the year
economists had worried that factories would cut back production so much in the early part of 1988 that it could topple the country into a recession
but recent business statistics, including the continued advances in production, rising consumer spending and strong gains in employment, have eased those fears
the industrial production figures depict an economy that is growing less rapidly but really looks pretty healthy,'' said jerry jasinowski, chief economist of the national association of manufacturers
u.s. manufacturers have enjoyed a significant rebound in output over the past year as the weaker dollar has boosted export sales. forecasts of continued economic growth this year are relying heavily on those advances to cntinue
jasinowski said a recent survey of the association's members found that a significant 20 percent of the companies were looking forward to higher sales this year
they see a lot of strength in their markets and very little probability of a recession,'' he said
the february increase included a 0.2 percent rise in production at manufacturing plants, identical to the gain in january
auto production fell 0.9 percent in february and now stands 8.5 percent below where it was in october. the output of passenger cars was 6.1 million units at an annual rate, a small improvement over january, but this was offset by a drop in production of light trucks
factories making durable goods, items expected to last three or more years, saw output rise by 0.2 percent last month while output at plants making nondurable goods edged up 0.1 percent
output in the mining industry dropped 0.8 percent in february, the third consecutive monthly decline. the setback last month was blamed on a drop in coal production
output at the nation's utilities rose 0.7 percent in february following a 1.8 percent january increase
the various changes left industrial production at 134.4 percent of its 1977 base of 100. starting sunday, sted monday; originally moved in advance for wednesday pms as b0175</note>
filming a documentary inside the soviet union cannot occur without omnipresent government officials, state-selected interviewees and limited access to certain areas
despite the restrictions, executive producer ira miskin said he didn't believe his seven-hour documentary, ``portrait of the soviet union,'' was compromised
many of the soviets who appear in the film, to be shown in installments on sunday, monday and tuesday on ted turner's superstation tbs, are members of the communist party, hand-picked by the government to appear in the film. officials from gostelradio, the state broadcasting committee, accompanied his crews on nearly every shoot
at the end, we had to rely on our own judgment,'' said miskin. ``and you also see the pictures. you can say anything you want over pictures, but the pictures _ what's going on the frame _ don't lie.''
nevertheless, the result is a flattering depiction of life in the soviet union _ an official portrait, beautifully photographed, showing only the occasional wart
the series does mention the soviet union's problems, but only those that have been raised in the state-controlled media: bureaucratic sluggishness, shoddy workmanship, complaints about consumer goods and housing
larger problems are inexplicably absent, given the briefest of mentions, or left for viewers to discern for themselves. these include the struggles over jewish emigration and human rights, the explosive nature of the nation's more than 100 nationalities, the issue of who really wields kremlin power, and the massive military budget and the war in afghanistan
i think the films do look to some degree pro-soviet,'' miskin said in an interview. ``i think that our intention was for certain aspects of it to look pro-soviet. not pro-soviet government, but pro-soviet people.''
the first episode, which is about the ethnic russians, is fairly typical. there is poet yevgeny yevtushenko, the one-time rebel who is now part of the establishment, reading a few lines from his epic work about the holocaust, ``babi yar.'' that's the only reference to anti-semitism in the soviet union in the entire seven hours
miskin, who is of russian extraction and jewish, said he could not ``in good conscience'' overlook the problems of soviet jewry, but he added that ``it's a much more complicated story than can be done in this kind of survey piece. it's a story that deserves its own hour
so to the extent that we ignored jewish emigration, we could not ignore the fact that anti-semitism existed and exists in the soviet union. it is a fact of life. you gotta mention it. we did,'' he said
what gets more than a mention is music and dancing
there's dancing by leningrad ballerinas and russians dressed as cossacks; by teen-agers in discos and old men straight from a yogurt commercial; by the georgian state dance troupe and bemedaled red army veterans
so much foot-stomping and high-kicking is in the series that some viewers may get the impression the biggest name in the soviet union isn't lenin or stalin, but danskin
miskin, who also did the upbeat ``portrait of america'' series for tbs, said he wanted to draw in the general audience with the music and dance, then give viewers an understanding of the soviet lifestyle, politics and economy
such an overemphasis on dance weakened the segment that profiled the peoples of georgia and armenia, miskin said
one troubling part comes in the episode on central asia, in which an official involved in the restoration of mosques is allowed to deliver the statement: ``times change. islam is not so popular now.''
the documentary allows the statement to go unchallenged, even though there are 45 million moslems in the soviet union _ 16 percent of the population _ and many practice their faith regularly despite kremlin oppression
miskin replied that ``our perception was ... the general consensus seems to be that islam is a mile wide and an inch deep, rather than a mile deep and an inch wide. ... so, we couldn't find a way to challenge it, essentially.''
the strongest of the segments by far is the sixth hour, a moving piece on how world war ii affected the soviet union. miskin does a good job of blending historic war footage and poignant interviews with elderly widows and veterans
other episodes look at life in siberia and the baltic republics. the final hour summarizes the series and features a lot of footage from the goodwill games, the international sports competition that turner conceived with the soviets
elsewhere in television:
cable estimates _ nielsen says its surveys show cable continuing to grow rapidly across the country, up to 51.1 percent penetration in february 1988, compared to 50.5 percent last november _ which was the first time cable penetration was found in over half of u.s. television homes. the february figure translates into 45.5 million television households
a federal grand jury today indicted former national security adviser john poindexter, lt. col. oliver north, and two arms dealers on conspiracy charges in the diversion of iranian arms sales profits to the nicaraguan contra rebels
the long-awaited 23-count indictment _ which in addition to north and poindexter also named retired air force maj. gen. richard v. secord and his business partner, albert hakim _ culminated a 14-month grand jury investigation into the arms-for-hostages deals with iran and the diversion of funds to the contras
the grand jury said the four men ``deceitfully and without legal authorization'' organized, directed and concealed ``a program to continue funding of and logistical and other support for military and paramilitary operations in nicaragua by the contras'' at a time u.s. law barred such action
the four defrauded the government ``by deceitfully exploiting for their own purposes'' u.s. arms sales to iran, ``rather than pursuing solely the specified governmental objectives of the initiative, including the release of americans being held hostage in lebanon,'' the grand jury said
one count said the defendants embezzled and converted to their own use proceeds generated by the weapons sales to iran. it was reported in the indictment that the arms sales generated approximately $30 million, while the u.s. government was paid only $12.2 million for the weapons
the indictment stated the conspiracy began in late spring or early summer of 1985 and continued through at least december 1986
the central conspiracy count charges that poindexter, north, secord and hakim ``together with others known and unknown'' conspired to defraud the united states by obstructing lawful government functions
the indictment variously charged the defendants with conspiracy, theft of government property, obstruction of justice, false statements, falsification, destruction and removal of documents
the indictment said the conspiracy deprived the government ``of the honest and faithful services of employees'' by using the positions of poindexter and north to generate funds for secord and hakim
north was named in nine counts charging him with obstruction of congress, making false statements, obstructing the presidential inquiry into the iran-contra affair in november 1986, and concealing, falsifying or destroying official documents
poindexter was named in two counts of obstructing a congressional inquiry and two other counts of false statements
the three counts in which all four were charged _ conspiracy to defraud the united states and commit offenses against the government, theft of government property and wire fraud arising from the diversion of the arms sale proceeds _ carry together maximum penalties of 25 years' imprisonment. each charge carries a maximum fine of $250,000
each of the obstruction and false statement charges against north and poindexter carries a five-year sentence and $250,000 fine
the destruction of documents charge against north carries a three-year term
hakim and secord, among other things, were charged with conspiracy to pay illegal gratuities to north and his family to further the sale of arms to iran so that secord and hakim ``would continue to receive opportunities for substantial revenues and profits'' from ``lucrative activities referred to them by north and facilitated by him.''
this charge listed a series of two payments totaling $16,000 to security expert, glenn robinette, who installed a security system at north's home in great falls, va
the indictment also charged that hakim created an investment account containing $200,000 in a swiss bank for the financial benefit of the north family
secord and hakim were also charged with offering an illegal gratuity to north in return for his support of the private supply network for the contras and iran arms sales
north was charged with receipt of an illegal gratuity stemming from the installation of the security system. the charge carries a two-year sentence and a $250,000 fine
north was also charged with pocketing at least $4,300 of the $90,000 in traveler's checks from contra leader adolfo calero. the charge alleged that calero had given the traveler's checks to north for efforts to help release u.s. hostages in lebanon and to help support the contras
north was also charged with conspiracy to defraud the government in connection with the use of a tax-exempt foundation that raised several million dollars in private donations to help arm the contras. two conservative fund-raisers, carl r. ``spitz'' channell and richard miller, pleaded guilty last spring to the same charge and identified north as a co-conspirator
independent counsel lawrence e. walsh and several of his top prosecutors made a final presentation to the panel
last week, former national security adviser robert c. mcfarlane, pleaded guilty to misdemeanor charges that he withheld information from congress in 1985 and in 1986 about covert administration efforts to help the contras during the ban on direct u.s. military aid
the 1985-1986 sales to iran were part of an effort to trade arms for u.s. hostages being held in lebanon by pro-iranian terrorist organizations
congressional investigators determined that of the $16 million in profits from the arms sales, $3.8 million went to the contras when the congressional ban on direct u.s. military aid to the nicaraguan rebels was in effect
the nicaraguan rebels on tuesday accused the sandinistas of being totalitarian for refusing to allow opposition political parties to be represented at cease-fire talks planned for next week
presidential press spokesman manuel espinoza said monday night that the leftist government vetoed the rebel request last week
one of the reasons is space,'' espinoza said. ``there's just not room for a mountain of people.''
the first face-to-face talks in nicaraguan territory between the government and rebels, known as contras, are set to begin monday at sapoa, a border post near the costa rican border. the meeting had been set for last week, but the government canceled it after the contras at the last minute insisted on a preliminary meeting to work out the topics for discussion
the rebels backed off that demand and both sides agreed to an open agenda. one issue the contras want to include in the discussions is a proposal by roman catholic cardinal miguel obando y bravo that calls for political amnesty and a revision of the military draft law, among other things. the rebel delegation will be headed by its top political leader, adolfo calero
the sandinistas are insisting that the talks center only on the mechanics of working out a cease-fire in line with a regional peace plan the five central american presidents signed last august
the government group will be led by defense minister humberto ortega, the brother of president daniel ortega
a contra statement tuesday said nicaraguan resistance, as the rebels are formally called, ``puts special importance and utility on the participation by the respresentatives of the internal opposition in the talks, considering its protaganist role in the nicaraguan conflict and its participation in a national solution to the national conflict.''
the rebel communique, read over the telephone to the associated press, said the rejection of the presence of opposition party members as well as the dismissal of the cardinal as mediator of the negotiations confirmed the sandinistas' ``totalitarian tendencies.''
president ortega on march 2 said obando y bravo's mediation no longer would be needed because the talks would be direct. the move was seen here as retaliation for the cardinal's proposal, which included political themes that the government said it would not discuss
president ortega on tuesday said he did not ``discount that at the last minute the mercenary forces will come up with pretexts so the meeting would not take place.''
an esimtabed 50,000 people have been killed and wounded in the war that has continued for more than six years
president ortega also proposed monday the renewal of talks with the internal political opposition, also a condition of the peace plan. those talks broke off last december when the political parties insisted on discussing a change in the constitution
the peace outline was signed in august by the presidents of nicaragua, el salvador, guatemala, honduras and costa rica. it seeks to end wars here, in el salvador and guatemala
it calls for cease-fires, political amnesties, democratic reforms and an end to logistic or strategic support for insurgencies
president reagan's former national security adviser, john m. poindexter, and fired white house aide lt. col. oliver l. north were indicted wednesday along with two arms dealers on charges they conspired to divert iranian arms sales profits to the nicaraguan contras
the long-awaited 23-count indictment, which also named retired air force maj. gen. richard v. secord and his business partner, albert hakim, culminated a 14-month grand jury investigation into the arms-for-hostages deals with iran and the diversion of $4 million in profits to the contras at a time when congress banned direct u.s. military aid to the rebels
the indictment variously charged the defendants with conspiracy, theft of government property, obstruction of justice, false statements, falsification, destruction and removal of documents
all four were named in three counts that charged conspiracy to defraud the united states and commit offenses against the government, theft of government property and wire fraud arising from the diversion of the arms sale proceeds
north was named in nine counts charging him with obstruction of congress, making false statements, obstructing the presidential inquiry into the iran-contra affair in november 1986 and concealing, falsifying or destroying official documents
poindexter was named in two counts of obstructing a congressional inquiry and two other counts of false statements
the three counts in which all four were charged _ conspiracy to defraud the united states and commit offenses against the government, theft of government property and wire fraud arising from the diversion of the arms sale proceeds _ carry together maximum penalties of 25 years imprisonment. each charge carries a maximum fine of $250,000
each of the obstruction and false statement charges against north and poindexter carries a five-year sentence and $250,000 fine
the destruction of documents charge against north carries a three-year term
the federal election commission certified almost $3.5 million in new federal matching funds on wednesday for 11 presidential candidates, including nearly $900,000 for pat robertson whose republican campaign is winding down
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis continued to lead the democratic money race, qualifying for more than $600,000 in new matching funds and raising his matching total to more than twice that of his competitors for his party's nomination
vice president george bush, who has a big lead in the republican contest, got in line for a new quarter of a million dollars in federal funds, keeping his edge in the category
in all, the new funds raise the total certified thus far for 14 candidates to $45.44 million
presidential candidates qualify for matching funds by raising at least $5,000 in individual contributions of $250 or less in at least 20 states. after qualifying, every individual contribution of $250 or less is matched dollar-for-dollar by federal funds. the money comes from the voluntary $1 checkoff on federal tax returns
candidates lose eligibility for matching funds for new contributions by withdrawing from the race or by failing to win at least 10 percent of the vote in two consecutive primaries in which they compete
here are the republican presidential hopefuls, the amount of new money certified wednesday and the total certified thus far:
bush, $247,118.92, $6,859,448.66
sen. bob dole of kansas, $380,928.96, $6,604,354.65
former gov. pete du pont of delaware, who has withdrawn, 0, $2,300,502.23
former secretary of state alexander haig, who has withdrawn, $45,237.64, $484,622.29
rep. jack kemp of new york, who has withdrawn, 0, $4,506,454.78
robertson, $896,551.91, $8,138,333.65
among the democratic candidates, here are the figures:
former arizona gov. bruce babbitt, who has withdrawn, 0, $870,133.58
dukakis, $621,098.39, $5,684,114.11
rep. richard gephardt of missouri, $161,107.89, $2,340,696.53
sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee, $336,312.04, $2,540,541.74
former sen. gary hart of colorado, who has withdrawn, $5,399.68, $1,122,281.67
jesse jackson, $330,189.60, $1,047,538.32
sen. paul simon of illinois, $397,839.29, $2,637,867.28
independent candidate lenora b. fulani qualified for $44,548.96, raising her total in federal matching funds thus far to $307,225.19. company, other comments.</note>
at least 10 firefighters have become ill after battling a weekend fire that destroyed a warehouse containing thousands of chemicals, authorities said wednesday
several residents of a nearby mobile home park also reported rashes and other adverse health effects after saturday night's fire in the town of seabrook, which was the worst accident involving hazardous materials in state history
until we take a look at specifically what compounds were involved, it's difficult to evaluate the seriousness of the health implications,'' said brian strohm, deputy director of the state division of public health. he was unaware of anyone being hospitalized
state fire marshal bill toland said some of the 75 to 80 firefighters called in to extinguish the fire have reported nausea, tightness in their chests and other symptoms
toland said exeter's fire chief ordered his firefighters to go to a hospital for blood tests _ and the chief himself wasn't feeling well
strohm estimated that 10 to 14 firefighters have fallen ill. he said the state became aware of the illnesses tuesday. he said he was not aware of any new illnesses since then
the firedestroyed an 8,000-square-foot warehouse of the aesar division of johnson matthey, an international precious metals company with u.s. headquarters in malvern, pa
johnson matthey officials did not immediately return a telephone message wednesday afternoon
the warehouse contained about 3,000 chemicals, including heavy metals and inorganic chemicals, the company said in a statement
officials said the fire caused millions of dollars in damages and will cost millions more to clean up. johnson matthey has hired clean harbors inc. of kingston, mass., to conduct the cleanup
federal and state investigators on wednesday continued trying to determine the cause of the fire. toland said investigators from the federal bureau of alcohol, tobacco and firearms believe it was accidental
another fire broke out in seabrook at the same time saturday night, at an abandoned lumber yard. that fire caused an estimated $500,000 damages. toland said its cause also remains unknown
about 80 residents of a trailer park were evacuated when wind shifted and blew a plume from the chemical fire in their direction
fearing that radioactive materials could have been stored in the warehouse, some firefighters were tested for radiation exposure but the tests were negative. officials from the stalled seabrook nuclear power plant provided testing assistance
strohm said determining possible health risks from the warehouse fire is difficult because some of the chemicals' properties may have changed when mixed with each other and with water and when they burned
barbara curtis, johnson matthey's manager for environmental affairs, said clean harbors workers have finished cleaning the warehouse parking lot and are building a temporary cover over the fire site to prevent any precipitation from seeping through
state hazardous-waste officials have said they are conducting laboratory tests of the runoff but have not received results.  ever</head> national...</note>
the democratic presidential race was as scrambled as the republican contest was clear wednesday after sen. paul simon's illinois victory enhanced the chances the democrats would met this summer without an obvious nominee
on the republican side, the biggest question appeared to be merely whether _ or when _ george bush's rivals, trounced in primary after primary, would drop out
bush, donning his leader-at-work mantle, lunched with president reagan and played dinner host to israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir while savoring his 55 percent majority over bob dole's 36 percent and pat robertson's 7 percent in tuesday's illinois primary, the one that dole once said would start his turnaround
dole tended business in the senate and pondered his future. in the face of defeat, he met with supporters in washington
they're all very friendly, very positive, very upbeat, saying `hang in there,''' dole said
robertson, a big loser tuesday, went home saying he would have to scale back his effort. he has spent within $2 million of the $27 million allowed by law for the primaries
republican national chairman frank fahrenkopf signaled it was time for the gop race to end. he said dole and robertson should ``start thinking past the convention and start thinking about november'' and the need to win the white house
but among the democrats, the talk was of a brokered convention, which simon says is inevitable, and of the steps that some party leaders said must be taken to prevent so publicly divisive an event this summer
simon, aglow in the winner's circle at last, said the nomination in a deadlocked convention could easily come to him because ``i'm probably the second choice of as many people as anyone else.''
at the same time, he all but conceded the next big bloc of delegates _ michigan's 138, to be awarded in a primary march 26 _ and concentrated on another state he thought he could win, wisconsin, on april 5
home-state voters pumped up simon's political adrenaline with his 43 percent showing in tuesday's illinois primary, against jackson's 31 percent, dukakis' 17 percent and a weak 5 percent for albert gore jr. and 2 percent for richard gephardt. but simon conceded he still must prove himself
i have to win outside the great lakes region,'' simon said, ``and i will.'' he flew directly to milwaukee and told reporters, ``you are going to be seeing a lot of paul simon.''
but the debate among democrats was whether they should search for a formula to avoid a deadlocked convention. paul kirk, the democratic national chairman, has proposed a meeting after the primaries at which party leaders and the candidates would close ranks around the front-runner. he said a brawl at the convention would damage the democrats' chances in the election
new york gov. mario cuomo, often pictured as the beneficiary of a brokered convention, seconded kirk's motion
i think it would be a mistake to go to atlanta, have a divisive convention, have a contention over a canddidate, have deals cut practically in public,'' cuomo said
jackson said he would attend a post-primary season summit, but only to talk about fair play and fair rules at the july convention
my base of support is broader than any other candidate,'' jackson said, contending the nomination could go to him outright
simon, acknowledging he won't be the front-runner, said there was nothing wrong in the image of a convention deal selecting the nominee
brokered conventions produced franklin roosevelt, harry truman, john f. kennedy,'' he said. ``we didn't do too badly for this country in those brokered conventions.''
gephardt struck an underdog posture, saying ``the odds are against me here in michigan.''
they say i'm the underdog. i like being the underdog because the underdog usually does well,'' he said. the missouri congressman said he would duplicate a campaign gimmick that drew publicity just before iowa's long-ago caucuses: several dozen of his house colleagues will stump michigan for him on friday. 82nd airborne to honduras, quotes from howard baker that no decision yet made; deletes redundant 13th graf bgng, `fitzwater said that'</note>
president reagan said today that nicaraguan troops had attacked contra rebel positions in neighboring honduras and officials said he is considering sending the 82nd airborne in response
a senior u.s. official said the use of the 82nd airborne, based in ft. bragg, n.c., was one of a ``few options'' being considered by the administration to confront the new situation in central america
however, white house chief of staff howard baker, asked on capitol hill whether any military action was being taken in central america, said, ``that is absolutely not true....''
the president has made no decisions,'' baker said. ``he is identifying his options. he has not acted on them. we are keeping very close touch with the situation. it is a fluid and developing situation.''
baker and national security adviser colin powell briefed congressional leaders for more than an hour on what baker called ``an incursion'' by sandinista forces into honduras to eliminate contra supply locations in that country
it is clear the sandinistas ... have crossed the border into honduras and are mounting a major offensive,'' baker said. ``the outcome is uncertain.''
the white house said the president of honduras, jose azcona, asked for american assistance in trying to repel the nicaraguan forces, but white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said he could not say whether that request included a plea for military help
the honduran ambassador put the number of nicaraguan troops in his country as in the thousands, but nicaragua today strongly denied that its soldiers had entered honduran territory
we have never invaded honduras and we have never invaded any neighboring country,'' said maj. rosa pasos, a nicaragua defense ministry spokeswoman. ``so we totally deny those declarations made this morning by the white house.''
reagan, asked whether he was considering any use of u.s. military forces, replied, ``we've been in consultation with the honduran government but i can't comment on anything.''
he said that ``the information we have is that nicaragua has crossed the border into honduras. obviously we're concerned.''
speaking separatel, the honduran ambassador, roberto martinez, said that here a had been a ``penetration into honduran territory of a number, ... definitely in the thousands, of sandinista troops
at this moment, we are trying the utmost to obtain a clearing of the area, ... a total withdrawal, immediate withdrawal, of the sandinista troops from our territory.''
but he said his government hoped to avoid military action
presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater said reagan, his national security adviser, the secretary of state and others ``have conferred at length in the last 24 hours concerning the nicaraguan invasion of honduran territory.''
fitzwater did not spell out what options were being considered, except he did say that ``the organization of american states will be asked to consider the issue, and the presidents of guatemala, costa rica and el salvador, will present their views.''
he said the administration no longer is thinking of working with congress on an aid package to simply provide the resistance forces with food, medicine, and other supplies, but not arms
house speaker jim wright said he could not immediately evaluate reports that sandinista troops had crossed into honduras
if true, that would be a very serious matter and would introduce an element of gravity that could profoundly alter the situation,'' including the willingness of congress to vote for further aid of some kind for the rebels, he told reporters
but wright said he still does not believe support exists in congress for any kind of renewed military aid for the rebels, and repeated that congressional democrats remain willing to talk about a further package of purely ``humanitarian'' aid
fitzwater said that 1,500 nicaraguan troops were inside hondruas and that an additional 4,500 appeared to be in a staging area to cross the border
fitzwater told reporters that ``all options are under consideration. at this moment, everything is being considered short of (u.s.) invasion.''
fitzwater commented one day after reagan met with democratic and republican congressional leaders. he failed to persuade the democratic leaders to get behind a new package of humanitarian aid for the contras
congressional sources, declining to be named, said at the meeting reagan pounded the table and said, ``there are some people around this table who don't seem to know who the bad guys are down there.''
today, fitzwater said, ``more than 1,500 sandinista troops are now inside honduras, attacking freedom fighter camps in an effort to destroy their remaining supplies.''
he added:
there are nearly 4,500 sandinista forces with strong helicopter support moving into the bocay valley, which is just below the honduran border. they've established a new base for this operation ... 
in the last several hours, the united states government has been in contact with the presidents of the other three democratic governments in the region,'' he said. ``we've had discussions concerning their response to this incursion and its meaning for the guatemala peace plan.''
the united states government today is examining its options,'' he said
when first word of the sandinista operation came monday night, democratic sources in congress portrayed it as a nicaraguan attempt to strengthen their position in advance of cease-fire talks with the contras, scheduled to begin monday
today, one senior administration official, speaking on the condition of anonymity, said the sandinista drive appeared to be aimed at a contra camp complex and supply depot
if the depot is knocked out, ``there will be nothing left'' of the contra war effort, the source said
that official said that contra commander enrique bermudez is in the bocay region and may be in ``serious trouble'' because he and his forces are surrounded by sandinista troops
nicaragua did not report the offensive until tuesday evening, when a defense ministry spokesman said it was under way but denied contra claims that sandinista troops crossed into honduras, where the rebels have bases
the army has undertaken major offensive operations. ... reports that the army has penetrated honduras are not true,'' the spokesman said
today, however, another official of the defense ministry would neither confirm nor deny that its troops had invaded honduras
we're looking into the reports,` an officer said. ``it's serious and that's why i can't say yes or no.'' both nicaraguans would not be identified
the honduran defense ministry said that 43 people had been killed in the sandinista initiative
heavy fighting was reported throughout nicaragua's 5th military region, which includes boaco, chontales, rio san juan and zelaya south. the contras said sandinista troops had overrun some rebel positions
fitzwater was peppered with questions about whether the administration was considering any use of u.s. military forces stationed in honduras and in nearby areas
the president has said many times that he does not plan to introduce invasion forces in central america,'' fitzwater said. ``we have said in the past, and it still holds true, that we do not plan to invade. ... that certainly hasn't changed.''
but fitzwater also said, ``at this moment, everything is being considered, short of invasion.'' but later he said ``nothing is ruled out at this point.''
i'm trying to be as restrained as possible,'' the spokesman said under intense questioning about u.s. military intentions. ``i'm telling you not to draw that signal (of direct u.s. military involvement), but we're in the midst of discussions.''
fitzwater said that administration officials had consulted by telephone late tuesday with congressional leaders and their representatives
the prosecutor in the ``preppie murder'' trial suggested in closing statements wednesday that the defendant strangled a teen-age woman after a bitter central park argument about his alcohol-induced impotence
perhaps he couldn't perform because he had too many tequilas and beers,'' assistant district attorney linda fairstein said of 21-year-old robert chambers
whatever the exact words were, only two human beings know what triggered the fight. it was an argument that escalated and became physical,'' she said
earlier, chambers' attorney ridiculed the prosecution version of the death of jennifer levin and said his client accidentally killed her during rough sex in the park
what he was doing was reacting to the pain. he was trying to stop her,'' lawyer jack litman said during his four-hour summation. ``he used force to repel the pain that was being caused to him.''
chambers is charged with second-degree murder. a former drug abuser who is under indictment on burglary charges in another case, chambers admits he killed the victim but says it was an accident after she attacked him sexually and hurt him
fairstein repeated her charge that chambers brutally beat and murdered miss levin, 18, while in a rage in the early morning of aug. 26, 1986
he squeezed her neck until her young life expired in his deadly hands. ... she struggled against death. she was in intense pain,'' fairstein said. ``she writhed and squirmed to free herself.''
holding a photo of miss levin taken in a bar hours before her death, fairstein told the jury: ``one can't help but look at that photograph and pray for time to stand still, for time to grab her and say, `don't go with robert chambers.'''
litman, in his summation, repeatedly told the jury in state supreme court in manhattan that the evidence supported chambers' version of the woman's death
litman reminded jurors that miss levin had pursued chambers in a bar on the upper east side of manhattan the night of her death because she wanted to have sex with him. a friend of miss levin testified the slain teen had said her previous encounters with chambers had been ``the best sex'' she ever had
that's why she pursued him, and that's why _ unfortunately _ this wound up the way it has,'' litman said
to convict chambers in the highly publicized case, ``you must exclude to a moral certainty every inference except one of guilt _ and you can't do that,'' he said
there are 20 different explanations that are as consistent with reality as the one they're (the prosecution) going to try to give you,'' said litman
following the summations, the jury is to receive its instructions in the case thursday before beginning deliberations. charges</head>
the very authority by which independent counsel lawrence e. walsh brought indictments wednesday against four major participants in the iran-contra affair is being challenged in a constitutional battle before the supreme court
but a supreme court decision striking down the so-called special prosecutor law would not necessarily invalidate the indictments returned against former national security adviser john m. poindexter, fired white house aide lt. col. oliver l. north, retired air force maj. richard v. secord and his business partner, albert hakim
attorney general edwin meese iii had given walsh a back-up appointment in the justice department in an attempt to shield the iran-contra inquiry from legal attacks that the special prosecutor law improperly takes power from the president and confers it upon the federal judges
however, the status of walsh's investigation is further blurred because he began his work before the back-up authority was conferred. the targets of the investigation are expected to argue that the initial absence of the supporting authorization taints the entire inquiry
the supreme court will hear arguments april 26 in the constitutional challenge to the special prosecutor law. eight justices will decide the outcome. justice anthony m. kennedy has removed himself from consideration of the case without explanation. a decision is expected by july
a panel of the u.s. circuit court of appeals in washington ruled, 2-1, in january that the independent counsel provision of the ethics in government act of 1978 is unconstitutional
the law authorizes a federal court to appoint a special prosecutor when the attorney general recommends an independent investigation of a high-ranking administration official accused of a crime
the appeals court ruling came in the investigation of former justice department official theodore b. olson on charges he lied to congress
alexia morrison, the independent counsel investigating the olson case, appealed to the supreme court. ms. morrison did not receive back-up authority from meese and her investigation would be ended if the high court declares the special prosecutor law unconstitutional
two other inquiries by independent counsels also could be affected by the court's ruling
the perjury conviction of former white house aide michael k. deaver could stand or fall on the outcome. the investigation that led to the illegal lobbying conviction of former white house aide lyn nofziger had back-up authority similar to that conferred in the iran-contra case
here, at a glance, are developments in the economic picture wednesday:
production at u.s. factories, mines and utilities rose 0.2 percent in february, following a 0.3 percent january gain. it was the fifth consecutive increase and left american industry producing at a level 5.8 percent higher than a year ago, although the gains are below advances registered in late 1987
the february increase included a 0.2 percent rise in manufacturing, identical to january's gain. in both months, auto assembly lines were shut down as automakers worked to reduce a high backlog of unsold new cars
auto production fell 0.9 percent in february and now stands 8.5 percent below where it was in october
housing construction increased sharply in february, by 8.9 percent, the biggest monthly gain since a 12.7 percent rise in december 1986
it follows declines of 1.9 percent in january and 15.8 percent in december. all regions posted increases except the west, where starts fell 9 percent
many economists had predicted a housing rebound, since mortgage rates have fallen since the first of the year and are again in the single-digit range
job prospects for production and service workers are the brightest they have been in three years but are declining slightly for technical, professional and office workers, according to a survey by the bureau of national affairs, a private publisher of business research
twenty-one percent of the 398 corporations and organizations surveyed said they anticipate expanding production and service work forces from april through june. a year ago 15 percent expected an increase in hiring
but only 19 percent of the companies surveyed said they plan to increase technical and professional staffs, down from 21 percent for 1987's first quarter
stock prices climbed in late trading, putting on a show of strength in advance of thursday's monthly report on the nation's balance of trade
the dow jones average rose 16.91 to 2,064.32
the market had been in a holding pattern since the start of the week as traders await the figures on the trade balance for january
in tokyo, the nikkei stock average closed at 25,704.43 points, up 228.76 points. the dollar closed at 127.49 yen, up 0.24 yen, on the foreign exchange market
the results of the illinois primary were just what the delegate counters for democratic candidates paul simon and jesse jackson expected, including michael dukakis's third-place finish without a single delegate
simon spokesman terry michael predicted early tuesday that the favorite son senator would claim 135 delegates in the direct-election primary. simon captured 136 of the 173 delegates at stake
steve cobble, delegate counter for jackson's campaign, expected his candidate to finish with close to 40 delegates based on his forecasts for various counties in illinois. jackson gained 37 delegates
the last-minute advertising blitz launched by dukakis failed to translate into delegates for the massachusetts governor
dukakis never made any headway,'' said cobble. ``he had four days of banging his head.''
michael, who contends that after all the primaries and caucuses the democrats will be ``gridlocked,'' said the illinois results solidify his theory of no clear winner heading into the convention
not only does it further assure the likelihood that no one claims a first-ballot victory on the morning of june 8, it pokes big holes in dukakis attempt to claim inevitability,'' michael said
the last big primaries _ new jersey and california _ are held june 7
dukakis still maintains a slight edge in total national convention delegates, according to the associated press survey. the massachusetts governor has 464.5 delegates with jackson second at 460.55 and gore third with 354.8. simon stands in fourth place with 171.5 delegates and gephardt is fourth with 145
there are 272.65 uncommitted delegates
on the republican side, vice president george bush _ to no one's surprise _ picked up 69 delegates out of the 82 at stake in illinois. kansas sen. bob dole finished a distant second and gained 13 delegates
bush has a commanding lead in the ap delegate count with 774 of the 1,139 needed to nominate. dole is second with 178 delegates and former television evangelist pat robertson is third with 17. there are 72 uncommitted delegates in the republican race
david sparks, delegate counter for the bush campaign, said the total was slightly higher than the delegates the vice president expected, and the campaign immediately started looking to the future
in puerto rico, we have a terrific organization. in connecticut, that's yet another home state of george bush and wisconsin has a good organization,'' sparks said. liability</head>
the senate on wednesday rejected an attempt to make private contractors at least partially liable for any future accidents caused by negligent work at the nation's nuclear weapons plants
the chamber voted 53-41 against a proposal by sen. howard metzenbaum, d-ohio, after senate energy committee chairman bennett johnston said that subjecting private contractors to potentially huge damage claims while they are performing ``the most important and sensitive function of this government'' would merely drive them away from the nuclear weapons business
rather than attracting the big companies with the reliability and the expertise, we'd wind up with fly-by-night operators running these plants,'' said johnston, d-la. the senate's vote came on johnston's motion to table the metzenbaum proposal
metzenbaum, citing a long list of problems in the department of energy's nuclear complex, argued that ``unless we hold the contractors responsible, there is absolutely no incentive for them to operate these facilities as safely as possible.''
most of the doe's nuclear facilities, which produce the components for nuclear warheads, are operated by private companies, whose contracts total an estimated $100 billion
the debate over contractor liability occurred as the senate neared passage of a bill to renew the price-anderson act, the government's 30-year-old system of no-fault insurance covering nuclear accidents
the key feature of the measure is a tenfold increase, from $700 million to $7 billion, in the maximum amount of money that would be available for quick disbursement to victims of any single accident involving nuclear reactors
in the case of nuclear utilities, each commercial reactor would be required to continue to carry the maximum amount of private insurance available _ about $160 million. if any given accident cost more than that to compensate victims, the additional money _ up to $7 billion _ would be assessed equally among all 110 nuclear plants now operating
once that pool was exhausted, it would be up to congress to provide additional money to victims from taxpayer funds
the government, meanwhile, would continue to self-insure its own nuclear plants, offering the same $7 billion maximum that could be disbursed quickly in the wake of an accident. the system, for both commercial and government operations, shortcuts the usual legal requirements for damage claims by eliminating the necessity for victims to bring individual suits in court
since the legislation was first passed in 1957, doe contractors have been virtually absolved of any responsibility to share the financial burden in the event of an accident at a government plant
the senate did approve, 94-0, an amendment offered jointly by johnston and metzenbaum which provides for stiff fines, ranging to $100,000 per day, for violations of safety rules by doe contractors. additional fines, and prison sentences ranging up to five years, could be imposed on corporate officials who commit ``knowing and willful'' safety violations
but metzenbaum fell short on his bid to have contractors share the financial burden caused by accidents, even though, in a last-minute bid for additional support, he watered down the amendment to stipulate that a company could be held financially liable for no more money than its profit on its contract at the plant where an accident occurs
johnston noted that several companies have threatened to withdraw from bidding on future contracts unless they continued to be exempt from liability
the energy department already has shut down one weapons production reactor, the hanford facility in washington state. the others, at the savannah river plant in aiken, s.c., are being run at partial levels because of safety and environmental problems. dupont announced last year it will not seek to renew its contract to run savannah river. westinghouse is considered a front-runner to take over that plant. bail, details. picks up 10th pvs: `he must ...; deletes 15th graf pvs, ``israeli officials ... as redundant.</note>
an arab-american who advocates non-violent resistance to israeli occupation of the west bank and the gaza strip was arrested wednesday and may be expelled, officials said
mubarak awad, 44, was charged with participating in an anti-israeli demonstration. awad said he was questioned for four hours about taking part in a women's sit-in in isawiya, an arab village incorporated into jerusalem after israel captured the area in 1967
he said he was released by city police on $2,000 bail and ordered to appear before a judge, but no date was set for the hearing
awad, a palestinian born in jerusalem, is an american citizen with homes in jerusalem and wapakoneta, ohio. he was in israel on a three-month tourist visa that expired in november
awad said he told police investigators the protest began peacefully
the women were demonstrating with olive branches to protest the ransacking of five houses by police. i went there, i saw the broken furniture and smashed windows,'' awad told the associated press after his release
he said he left the village when police ordered him out, then watched from a hillside as police fired tear gas to break up the sit-in. he said arab youths responded by throwing rocks
awad said he was stopped a short time later by traffic police for failing to signal a right turn
he said they ordered him detained when he was unable to present either his israeli identity card or his u.s. passport, which were seized last november when awad defied an expulsion order
during the questioning, ``the police mentioned expulsion. they said it could be this time for you,'' awad added
a senior government official who spoke on condition of anonymity said the charges could lead to awad's deportation
he must be investigated. the charges against him will be checked, according to that we will decide,'' said the official
i'm not saying he is definitely going to be expelled, but this (investigation) may affect it. everything depends on what the investigation shows.''
on monday, israel's supreme court ordered the interior ministry to show within 60 days why awad had not been expelled
u.s. officials have repeatedly urged israeli officials to allow awad to remain
we've been in touch with him and a consular officer visited him at the police station,'' said david good, a spokesman for the u.s. consulate. ``we are following the case closely.''
awad came under fire after the publication in hebrew of his book titled ``non-violent resistance: a strategy for the occupied territories.''
the book urged the 1.5 million palestinians in the west bank and gaza strip to refuse to pay taxes, lay down in front of bulldozers to prevent land confiscation and boycott israeli products
although awad has played only a minor role in the current uprising, some of his passive resistance ideas have been adopted, such as boycotting jobs in israel and refusing to pay taxes
gunmen on bicycles ambushed and killed auto speed king mickey thompson and his wife in their driveway wednesday, days after he told a friend he had received several death threats and feared for his life
the 59-year-old racing promoter and his wife, trudy, 41, were found dead at dawn, said sheriff's deputy doug gatlin. two male assailants fled on bicycles, investigators said
it was a double homicide, an assassination,'' said deputy richard dinsmoor
thompson became famous as the ``speed king'' in the 1950s when he set the first of his nearly 500 auto speed and endurance records. longtime friend carroll shelby described him as ``one of the greatest hot-rodders we've ever had'' and ``the dominant figure in off-road racing.''
as recently as sunday, thompson expressed fears for his life after receiving numerous death threats, friends and associates said
he was a little concerned,'' family friend ernie alvarado said. he said he talked to thompson early sunday and thompson mentioned the death threats
i don't know why trudy had to be involved,'' alvarado said. ``everybody loved her.''
neighbors heard six or eight shots and deputies found the bodies about 6 a.m. in the driveway of the couple's gated, spanish-style estate in an area of $1 million-plus homes 20 miles from downtown los angeles, investigators said
we don't know a motive,'' said deputy dan cox, who wouldn't divulge the type of weapon used. several bullets struck each of the thompsons in the upper torso, he said
mike difilippo, a building contractor who lives across the street, said he was awakened by shots
i heard yelling, `don't shoot.' that was trudy,'' said difilippo. he said thompson had voiced concern for his life after winning a series of multimillion-dollar lawsuits against another racing promoter
promoter and one-time partner mike goodwin lost a series of lawsuits to thompson, and goodwin's stadium motorsports corp. assets were ordered liquidated last year by a judge to settle the matter
at one point, thompson hired a guard, difilippo said. ``he told me around christmas they had threatened to kill him,'' difilippo said
the thompsons apparently were ambushed as they were getting into their van, cox said. the van, its passenger window shattered, rolled down the sloping driveway into a block wall
doug stokes, spokesman for thompson entertainment group in anaheim, said the thompsons were apparently leaving the house for work when the shooting occurred. he didn't know of any threats against thompson
thompson in 1960 became the first to travel over 400 mph on land when he drove a four-engine streamlined car 406.6 mph at the bonneville salt flats in utah
he later turned to drag racing and indianapolis car racing, and was a top competitor in road racing and off-road championships in the united states and mexico
thompson's other sports activities included stunt flying and management of prizefighters
racing put him in the hospital 27 times, including a seven-month stay when he was paralyzed from the waist down after a boat racing accident. it was two years before he walked again
here is what the presidential tower commission and the joint congressional investigating committees said about the four men indicted wednesday in the iran-contra arms scandal: former national security adviser john m. poindexter, marine lt. col. oliver l. north, and arms dealers richard v. secord and albert hakim
the tower commission, in its feb. 26, 1987, report to president reagan, depicted north as a backstage manipulator who carried out both the arms sale to iran and the diversion of profits to the contra rebels in nicaragua in an ``unprofessional'' manner that invited kickbacks and scandal
the tower commission said poindexter, a vice admiral who first was the deputy national security adviser and later held the top post in the national security council, ``failed grievously'' to consider the gravity of the diversion of proceeds from the arms sale to the contras
poindexter ``apparently failed to appreciate or ignored the serious legal and political risks presented,'' the tower panel said. ``his clear obligation was either to investigate the matter or take it to the president _ or both. he did neither.''
it said north ``conducted the operation through mr. (richard) secord and his associates, a network of private individuals already involved in the contra resupply operation.''
north cut himself off from resources and expertise within the government'' and relied on private businessmen and brokers with ``questionable credentials and potentially large personal financial interests in the transactions. this made the transactions unnecessarily complicated and invited kickbacks and payoffs.''
the use of mr. secord's private network in the iran initiative linked those operators with the resupply of the contras, threatening exposure of both operations if either became public. the result was a very unprofessional operation,'' the tower report said
the tower panel said that on one or more occasions, poindexter may have misled secretary of state george p. shultz about the initiative
the report quoted north as once saying, ``it's going to be just fine ... as soon as everyone knows that ... the ayatollah is helping us with the contras.''
the report said north ``misrepresented his access to the president and attributed to the president things the president never said'' during october 1986 meetings in frankfort, west germany, with iranian representatives
north reportedly told the iranians that reagan had said he wanted an end to the iran-iraq war on terms acceptable to iran, and that the persian gulf states had to be convinced saddam husain of iraq was ``causing the problem.''
reagan told the tower commission those statements were ``absolute fiction.''
the report said north once threatened the president of costa rica with a cutoff of $80 million in u.s. aid if he publicized the existence of a secret costa rican airfield used to resupply the rebels
secord, who retired from the air force as a major general in 1983 and became a private arms dealer, controlled swiss bank accounts under the name of lake resources into which $20 million in profits from the sale of u.s. weapons to iran were placed, the tower report said
hakim is an iranian immigrant and naturalized american who was secord's business partner in stanford technology trading group, a vienna, va., company. hakim helped open the channel of communications to the regime of ayatollah ruhollah khomeini in iran
the house-senate iran-contra committees in their report last nov. 18 faulted reagan for allowing a ``cabal of zealots'' to seize control of foreign policy and skirt the law
the report said that even when north became skeptical that the arms sales would free u.s. hostages being held in lebanon or lead to a new relationship between the united states and iran, ``he believed that the prospect of generating funds for the contras was `an attractive incentive' for continuing the arms sales.''
the decision to designate private parties _ secord and hakim _ to carry out the arms transactions had other ramifications,'' the committees reported. ``first, there was virtually no accounting for the profits from the arms deals. even north claimed that he did not know how secord and hakim actually spent the money committed to their custody. ..
second, by permitting private parties to conduct the arms sales, the administration risked losing control of an important foreign policy initiative.''
the committees determined that of the $16 million in profits from the arms sales, $3.8 million was earmarked for the contras when the congressional ban on direct u.s. military aid to the nicaraguan rebels was in effect in 1985 and 1986
the congressional committees said: ``in the iran-contra affair, administration officials holding no elected office repeatedly evidenced disrespect for congress' efforts to perform its constitutional oversight role in foreign policy.''
they called north ``the central figure in the iran-contra affair,'' but emphasized he ``did not act alone. ... north's conduct had the express approval of admiral john poindexter.''
police on tuesday occupied the campus of a technology institute and detained a number of students suspected of being involved in battles with villagers that left one student dead
authorities barred reporters from the rangoon institute of technology in west gyogone, seven miles north of downtown rangoon, following the weekend fighting
burma broadcasting service, the government radio station, said tuesday the violence began at a tea shop saturday night when students and villagers quarreled over the playing of a cassette tape. five villagers were arrested, it said
on sunday, larger groups of both students and villagers resumed the fighting and some 200 students set fire to seven buildings, according to the broadcast
it said police quelled the rioting with volleys of tear gas but 13 students were injured and one, maung phone maw, was fatally wounded. the report did not say how he was killed and added the government was investigating and would take ``necessary action'' against those involved
a resident of west gyogone told the associated press that police and army units were seen leaving the campus tuesday night escorting three police vans carrying an unknown number of students
the witness, who spoke with the condition he not be identified, said there was no violence as police occupied the campus and picked up the suspects. 15th graf pvs, sen. alfonse, with more comment from senators</note>
sen. bob dole came under increasing pressure on wednesday to give up his faltering presidential campaign as republican party chairman frank fahrenkopf said it was time to ``start thinking about november.''
a dozen of dole's senate supporters openly debated the merits of his continuing a candidacy that seemed doomed to failure _ although none of them advised dole to get out of the race. in any event, dole said, ``they're not going to decide. i decide what i'm going to do here.''
dole's campaign manager, william brock, said: ``we're in business.'' asked for how long, he said, ``until bob wants to change it.''
with vice president george bush marching with seeming inevitability toward the nomination, dole's aides said the senator had decided to stay in the race until the wisconsin primary on april 5. they said no decision has been made for beyond that date
bush's aides gave the kansas senator wide berth. ``we're prepared to accept whatever decision bob dole makes,'' said rich bond, the vice president's deputy campaign manager. he said bush was ready to match dole dollar for dollar in any primary state where he chooses to compete, and another spokesman said the vice president has a $4.5 million campaign treasury at his disposal
the other aide, pete teeley, said he believes bush will have enough delegates to claim the nomination by the end of april or early may in any event
fahrenkopf's comments seemed a broad hint to dole that the time is approaching to abandon the race. he stressed his campaign neutrality, but added that he has a responsibility as chairman ``to ask them (the candidates chasing bush) for some self-reflection.''
fahrenkopf said dole and former television evangelist pat robertson should ``start thinking past the convention and start thinking about november'' and the general election
he said either of the two would have to win roughly 75 percent of the remaining delegates at stake to have a chance at the nomination, and he called on them to assess ``realistically'' why they are still in the race
bush has won 774 delegates in the associated press count, compared with 178 for dole and 17 for robertson. it takes 1,139 to win the republican nomination at the party convention this summer
none of the three active candidates was campaigning during the day. dole was in the senate, bush attended to vice presidential duties and robertson was at home in virginia
but there was an extraordinary public airing of dole's prospects by his supporters in the wake of bush's illinois primary landslide on tuesday
sen. nancy landon kassebaum, dole's senate colleague from kansas, said, ``i guess the general feeling among some of us is he should go on through wisconsin.''
she added, ``if there's a way to stay in all the way and speak to the issues ... it benefits the party and benefits him, and it keeps the campaign on a positive level,'' she said. ``but i'm not sure it can be done that way. maybe it's not worth the strain of continuing on.''
sen. warren rudman, r-n.h., ``if he wants to stay in for a few more weeks he can do it. he's staying in because he's invested three years of his life.''
sen. alfonse d'amato of new york, who told cbs news on tuesday that it looked ``pretty clear and convincing'' that bush would be the nominee, said dole's chances are ``very very difficult, if not impossible. but that's all right. it's not over till it's over.''
sen. paul trible, r-va., said the meeting was of dole's ``best friends interested in his best interest and that of the party,'' adding: ``this is a decision for bob dole to make, and we will support that decision.''
sen. charles grassley, r-iowa, said ``no conclusions were drawn'' in the meeting, but ``i think there was a general consensus, more than a general consensus, that now the campaign ought to go forward.''
i believe that he should stay in,'' grassley said, adding that at the meeting, there was ``absolutely not'' anyone urging dole to get out
grassley said wednesday's iran-contra indictments were not discussed in the meeting, but said: ``there's going to be some reagan baggage that george bush has to contend with.''
that view was echoed by sen. dave durenberger, r-minn., who was not at the meeting but advised dole to stay in the race. ``george can't duck the (iran-contra) issue,'' he said
dole said his colleagues were `'very friendly, very positive, very upbeat, saying, `hang in there.''' bush's aides were careful not to gloat, but said it was as good as over
teeley said dole's ``got to do what's best for him.'' but he added that connecticut, which holds the next gop primary on march 29, ``is going to be a very strong state for us, there's no question about it.''
bush enjoys the support of several republican elected officials in the state. sen. lowell weicker, nominally neutral in the presidential race, is writing a newspaper article praising the vice president and is considering a formal endorsement at a bush campaign function being planned for a few days before the primary, sources said
beyond that, teeley said bush is in a strong position in primaries in wisconsin, new york and pennsylvania. he said he believes the vice president will clinch the delegates needed for the nomination either on april 26 when pennsylvania votes or a week later, with primaries in ohio and indiana
robertson, who met with republican party chairman fahrenkopf on tuesday, says he won't compete in either connecitcut or wisconsin, but will concentrate his efforts in caucus states. robertson says he is now concentrating on expanding his political base for the 1992 campaign
fahrenkopf said robertson indicated in the meeting that he intends to remain a candidate until the nominating convention
gov. michael s. dukakis' highly touted universal health care plan has been streamlined since it was raised a year ago, its deadlines extended, its bureaucracy reduced and its funding expanded by millions of dollars
but the proposal's basic premise, making massachusetts the first state to guarantee health insurance protection for all its residents, remains intact
the plan, which dukakis has held up as an example to the nation in his democratic presidential campaign, awaits final action by a legislative conference committee
senate ways and means chairman patricia mcgovern, the chief architect of the bill, said wednesday the house and senate proposals are so similar that ``there are no major sticking points'' that would prevent passage
universal health care in massachusetts first came to the attention of the legislature in a position paper issued by mcgovern in february 1987
in my wildest dreams, i didn't think a year later we'd be almost on the verge of accomplishing it,'' she said. ``i thought it would take much, much longer.''
dukakis wasn't an initial supporter of universal health care, considering it too costly. in his original proposal in august, the governor did not suggest any state spending for the plan, maintaining that employers should shoulder the cost
mcgovern is credited with getting the governor to support the present plan, which would phase in health care until all residents are insured by 1992
the present plan retains dukakis' proposed unemployment surcharge tax on employers who don't provide coverage by 1992. but it also contains a state commitment of $500 million or more over the next four years to make sure everyone is covered
the governor has taken the issue on the campaign trail, talking as much about the 600,000 uninsured in massachusetts as the 40 million uninsured nationally
only hawaii has anything comparable to what's been proposed in massachusetts. the state has required employers to provide workers with insurance coverage since the early 1970s
the federal employee retirement income security act was passed after hawaii's law took effect to prevent other states from imposing similar mandates on employers, and questions remain about how massachusetts' proposal will fare under federal review
massachusetts' small businesses lobbied hard and successfully against dukakis' bill last year
this year, although some small business groups still oppose it, the measure has been reshaped to reflect their concerns
state-brokered pooled insurance for small employers was added. so were tax breaks and a ``hardship trust fund'' in which the state agrees to help employers pay insurance costs that exceed 5 percent of their revenues
the house also passed an amendment exempting employers of nine or fewer workers from the 1992 deadline for providing employee coverage. the senate version has no such exemption, and the issue is expected to be a focal point of the conferee negotiations
other major changes since dukakis first proposed the bill include allowing more time to put the system into effect and scrapping a plan to create a ``super agency'' to oversee the universal health care system. iranian claim of 3,100 sted 1,150 iraqis dead</note>
iran and iraq blasted each other's capitals with missiles, hammered other cities with air raids, and fought ground battles along the front wednesday
the u.n. security council called for an end to the carnage
hundreds were reported killed in the air and ground exchanges, the latest in more than two weeks of almost daily attacks on the two nations' heaviest population centers
tehran's official islamic republic news agency said iran's revolutionary guards fired five missiles into the iraqi capital of baghad after 70 iranian civilians were killed in iraqi missile attacks on tehran and warplane raids on seven iranian cities
the state-run iraqi news agency confirmed only three hits on baghdad and said ``many civilians were killed or wounded.'' the agency, also monitored in nicosia, did not give a casualty count but reported seven missiles fired at tehran
iran confirmed that missiles hit the capital and said iraqi warplanes bombed bakhtaran, shiraz and other cities in western iran. the iranian agency said 25 civilians were killed and more than 100 wounded in shiraz alone
iraq says it has fired 22 surface-to-surface missiles into the iranian capital since a two-day truce in the so-called ``war of the cities'' broke down late sunday. iran has reported launching seven into baghdad
the iranian agency also said revolutionary guards pushed into sulaymaniyah province in northeastern iraq and seized 95 square miles, including 21 villages, in heavy battles with iraqi troops
it said more than 3,100 iraqis were killed or wounded and 800 taken prisoner in the fighting in the mountainous region, 160 miles north of baghdad
the agency said iranian troops were in control of the town of khurmal, near the border, and that the residents in the ``liberated'' area ``warmly welcomed the attacking iranian combatants.''
in switzerland, the newspaper neue zuercher zeitung quoted iranian charge d'affaires mohammed hussein malaek as saying his country had cut all ties to the security council
malaek also was quoted as saying only a military solution could end the persian gulf war, and that iran no longer felt obligated to respect international conventions which are supposed to protect civilians and prisoners in wartime and ban the use of chemical weapons
the u.n. security council, meanwhile, demanded an end to the missile attacks on baghdad and tehran. it also endorsed another round of negotiations by secretary-general javier perez de cuellar on implementing the council's july 20 cease-fire resolution and peace plan for the 7{-year-old war
a statement issued by the council president said the 15 nations on the panel ``strongly deplore the escalation of hostilities between these two countries, particularly the attacks against civilian targets and cities ...''
a presidential statement is the mildest form of council action. it falls short of the resolution and the appointment of a special negotiator the soviet union had been seeking
the united states said the soviet idea would divert attention from the july resolution. the resolution demands an immediate cease-fire and withdrawal to international boundaries as the first steps for negotiating an end to the war
iran's news agency said jet fighters bombed the northern iraqi city of kirkuk and other cities, ``inflicting heavy casualties and losses on the enemy.''
the iraqi agency reported that warplanes tuesday raided a ``large maritime target,'' a reference to an oil tanker, that night. gulf-based marine executives had reported a raid on the liberian-flagged trade fortitude at around the same time
lt. col. oliver north, his face drawn and gray, his voice breaking, said wednesday he was caught in the cross-fire of a bitter dispute between congress and the president and that ``it is a shame the new battleground for such a fight will be in a courtroom.''
the marine officer talked to reporters a few hours after a federal grand jury indicted him and three others on conspiracy charges
i did not commit any crime. i intend to fight allegations of wrongdoing for as long as necessary,'' said north. he said the fight will entail enormous costs, personal and financial, but ``nevertheless, i can assure you, i will never give up, we will win.''
north's eyes clouded and his voice quavered as he thanked the american people ``who have shown so much love and concern these past 16 months by their millions of telegrams and letters and prayers and support.''
beside him was his lawyer, brendan sullivan, who also represented north at last summer's hearings before joint committees of the senate and house. sullivan, whose spirited defense of his client was one of the highlights of the hearings, said that seeking wednesday's indictment ``was one of the worst prosecutorial decisions in the history of our country
it is a decision of an unaccountable prosecutor who came to washington determined to allege that some crime, any crime had been committed,'' sullivan said
sullivan added that lawrence e. walsh, the independent counsel ``presents an indictment after 15 months (of investigation) based on mistaken facts, novel and sometimes ridiculous legal theories
the return of an indictment under these circumstances presented here is an abuse of the criminal process,'' sullivan said. ``everyone must seriously wonder about a decision to indict a man like oliver north, a highly decorated marine corps officer, based on his tireless effort in the interests of his country.''
for his part, north said it was a sad irony that the decision to indict should occur on the fourth anniversary of the abduction in lebanon of william buckley and the third anniversary of the kidnapping of terry anderson, the associated press' middle east correspondent
the indictment is also sad for our country,'' north said. he said that as a marine officer he had always done his best
unfortunately, i have now been caught in a bitter dispute between the congress and the president over the control of foreign policy, the power of the president to deter communism in central america and the president's duty to protect our citizens against terrorist acts abroad,'' north said
it is a shame that the new battleground for such a fight will be a courtroom,'' north said
after he read his statement, north turned to leave. a reporter asked ``who authorized you to conduct u.s. foreign policy?''
i'm not going to take any questions,'' said north. damage</head>
separated siamese twin patrick binder may have suffered new brain damage after choking during a routine feeding, johns hopkins hospital said tuesday
patrick had been left unattended briefly late sunday afternoon when he choked on formula fed to him through a nasal tube, according to lisa hillman, spokeswoman for the hopkins children's center. since then, he has had some seizures, she said
a nurse making a routine check on the room patrick shares with his brother benjamin, found he had stopped breathing, called for emergency help and began mouth-to-mouth resuscitation
patrick was rushed to the pediatric intensive care unit, where a ventilator was attached to mechanically aid his breathing
the child awakened an hour later, an indication that his breathing had not stopped for very long, ms. hillman said
doctors believe ``there may be some damage,'' ms. hillman said, because ``he has had, since the incident, some mild seizures.'' she described them as ``jerking movements of the face'' and said they had been stopped by medication
the twins had been doing well since surgery last month to implant titanium mesh plates in the opening at the back of their heads, created by a complex, marathon operation last september to separate their joined skulls
doctors said both boys sustained slight brain damage during the separation procedure, and the long-term effects remain uncertain
benjamin remained in good condition tuesday, while patrick was listed in stable condition and showing slight improvement in the intensive care unit
doctors had hoped the 13-month-old twins would be going home to ulm, west germany, by the end of march, but ms. hillman said patrick's setback could cause a delay
investigators wednesday were trying to determine when and where the uss john hancock's disbursement officer was strangled, shot and robbed of the ship's payroll, a navy spokesman said
the body of lt. ratish prasad, 24, was found tuesday inside a locker on the destroyer. about $94,000 was missing from his office safe, the navy said, revising the amount downward from tuesday's estimate of $120,000
he was shot at close range, and also strangled,'' said chief petty officer art riccio
there was no indication prasad also was bludgeoned, as first reports indicated, riccio said. ``with all the blood and everything, that's the way it looked,'' riccio said. ``the bullet apparently passed right through the head.''
final autopsy reports have not been released, riccio said
the time of death and where prasad was shot had not been determined, navy officials said. no bullets or casings were found, and the caliber of the weapon was not known, riccio said
riccio said the twice-monthly payroll, due for disbursement tuesday, was $70,000, and about $20,000 in cash usually is kept in the safe
no information was available on suspects from navy investigative service officers working with duval-jacksonville sheriff's deputies, riccio said
people trying to board the destroyer or other navy ships must pass checkpoints at the base entrance, the pier area and the ship itself, riccio said
only family members and friends of the crew who have been previously cleared are allowed aboard the ship in port, he said. even naval personnel who do not have business on the ships cannot board, he said
prasad, who was single and came from park forest, ill., had enlisted three years ago
lt. cmdr. tim taylor said prasad normally would have been met at his office about 8 a.m. by an armed master at arms, a member of the ship's security force. prasad himself normally would not have been armed, taylor said
prasad and the master at arms then would have gone to the officer's quarters, chiefs' quarters, then crew messes to pay crew members, taylor said
when the disbursing office door was discovered open, a search was mounted for prasad, who had gotten off duty at midnight then spent the night on board, taylor said
prasad's body was found in an isolated storage area one deck below his office, taylor said. 03-16 0851</first> fitzwater comment.</note>
the white house remained silent wednesday on the question of whether president reagan would pardon key figures indicted by a federal grand jury for their involvement in the iran-contra affair
under the constitution, a president holds immense power when it comes to granting pardons. the question now looms whether reagan will choose to use it
on wednesday, a federal grand jury indicted reagan's former national security adviser, john m. poindexter, along with fired white house aide lt. col. oliver l. north and two arms dealers on conspiracy charges in the diversion of iranian arms sales profits to the nicaraguan contras
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said reagan was informed of the indictments by kenneth duberstein, his deputy chief of staff. speaking of reagan, fitzwater said, ``he had no response.'' he said there was no white house comment because ``it's a matter before the courts.''
since the iran-contra scandal erupted in november 1986, reagan has refused _ in public at least _ to entertain any discussion of pardons
this is a subject i have not and will not discuss at this time,'' reagan said last november
reporters tried _ at least four times that day _ to persuade him to discuss it, but reagan repeatedly refused to do so
in the intervening months, reagan has been careful not to rule out the option
he has made it clear _ particularly in his description of north as an ``american hero'' _ that he is giving the former national security council aide the benefit of the doubt
i'm going to wait until he's had his day in court,'' reagan said last summer when queried about north's testimony before the joint congressional committees investigating the matter. reagan added that he was ``not going to pre-judge'' north based on his televised appearances before the committees
and after congress completed its investigation, reagan said in a national broadcast that he thought north and poindexter ``believed they were doing what i would've wanted done.''
although contending he was as ``mad as a hornet'' about the damage inflicted on his administration, the president has never criticized his aides for lying to congress, shredding documents or participating in a cover-up
reagan, questioned at one time about the series of laws in 1985 and 1986 barring direct or indirect military aid to the contras, responded: ``i don't think that the law was broken.''
in fact, if reagan choses to grant pardons to anyone connected with the affair, he would not have to list a specific crime that is being pardoned
such sweeping power amounts to a legal grant of absolution, enshrined in the constitution. the founding fathers borrowed the concept from english common law
it allows a president virtually unlimited authority covering ``offenses against the united states, except in cases of impeachment.''
he's really very free,'' said c. thomas dienes, a professor of constutional law at george washington university
a president is able to grant a pardon involving a federal crime solely on his own initiative _ he need not consult anyone or even wait for an indictment or conviction before taking action, dienes said
dienes cited an 1867 supreme court case, ex parte garland, which states the effect of such a presidential decision: ``in the eye of the law, the offender is as innocent as if he never committed the offense.''
during his nearly eight years in office, reagan has granted 333 pardons out of 1,894 requests, according to the justice department
normally, the process begins with a four-page application submitted to the justice department's pardon attorney. since virtually all the applicants have been convicted of crimes, the department's guidelines require that applicants wait five years to seven years after the completion of their sentences
but presidents are allowed under the constitution to avoid that route
two months into his first term, reagan ignored the formal procedure and granted pardons to two former fbi officials convicted of sanctioning warrantless break-ins
that was the path president ford took to pardon richard nixon on sept. 8, 1974, for any wrongdoing connected with the watergate scandal
ford's pre-emptive pardon sent his popularity ratings into a tumble. it also contributed to his loss of the 1976 elections
although reagan is barred from running again, his decision in this case could affect vice president george bush's chances in the presidential election this fall and those of other gop candidates, according to stephen hess, a senior fellow and specialist in presidential affairs at the brookings institution in washington
hess predicted that if reagan decided to pardon any iran-contra figures, he would wait until after the november elections
since ford's action cost him the election, i doubt we'll see reagan move before november,'' hess said
he added: ``i would be stunned if there isn't a pardon between election day and january 1989. as outgoing president, reagan is in the best position to take the heat.''
protests that began months ago with allegations of criminal conduct by gen. manuel antonio noriega have turned into public rage over unpaid salaries in an economy without money
the largest demonstrations in nine months of turmoil, accompanied by strikes, took place wednesday. they started at about 10 a.m. and riot squads managed to disperse the crowds by mid-afternoon. by early evening the streets were deserted except for police patrols
people were reported injured, but there were no confirmed figures. there were reports of widespread looting and several stores were set ablaze
noriega, who rules panama as chief of the 15,000-member defense forces _ the military and police _ has been indicted in florida on narcotics charges and president reagan said tuesday he wants the general ``out of there.''
economic pressure applied by the united states includes a freeze on panamanian government accounts in u.s. banks and withholding panama canal revenues. this has dried up the supply of u.s. dollars, panama's national currncy
wednesday's protests began soon after young officers led by police chief leonidas macias mounted an unsuccessful coup
shops and other businesses closed early. reporters saw protesters at a barricade stop and open a refrigerated truck and empty it of frozen chickens
electric power went off throughout the country at about midday, soon after workers of the national power company walked out to protest not being paid
government workers were sent home after waiting all morning for biweekly paychecks that did not arrive
public transportation stopped because employees were not paid
in lower-income neighborhoods, burning barricades appeared at street corners. many protesters identified themselves as ``civilistas'' _ members of the national civic crusade, a coaliton of about 200 business, professional, labor, student and opposition groups
the crusade was formed last june, after the first reports that noriega was involved in drug dealing, corruption and allegedly even political murder. its stated purpose was to force him out
protesters at many street corners wednesday stoned the few buses that were running and any cars suspected of being from the government. those carrying journalists were allowed to pass
it is time for the gringos to come in,'' a demonstrator shouted at a carload of reporters, using the slang for north americans
carlos gonzalez de la lastra, a crusade leader, said: ``the fight will intensify tomorrow.''
one large group of protesters was made up of health workers from social security hospitals. they yelled that they have not been paid and many fought riot police with rocks and sticks
soldiers went to social security institutions wednesday morning and disarmed hospital security guards, also members of the defense forces
they probably do not want the people to take the guards' guns away,'' a hospital employee said
a nurse said of noriega: ``he must go. look what he is doing to this country.''
the second late-winter storm in a week dumped up to a foot of snow in mountain areas of utah, wyoming and colorado on wednesday and moved into the plains states, while record cold gripped the southeast
a winter storm warning was posted in northwestern kansas, and storm watches went up in parts of texas, missouri and oklahoma. up to 8 inches of snow were forecast for parts of kansas and missouri
the wintry weather comes on the heels of a storm that brought heavy snow to the area last weekend
parts of utah and western colorado got heavy snow wednesday morning, with more than a foot at fillmore and clear creek canyon, in central utah, 10 inches at lander, wyo., about 4 inches at red mountain pass, colo., and colorado springs, colo., and 2 inches at goodland, kans
blowing snow cut visibility at laramie, wyo., to an eighth of a mile
heavier snowfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. est included 5 inches at roosevelt, utah, 4 inches at goodland, kans., and milford, utah, and 2 inches at russell, kans
record lows were set in 18 cities in the southeast on wednesday morning, including apalachicola, fla., 31; calico rock, ark., 16; charleston, s.c., 28; el dorado, ark., 26; greer, s.c., 25; hollywood, fla., 44; hot springs, ark., 25; key west, fla., 55; meridian, miss., 23; miami, 44; miami beach, 45; mobile, ala., 30; new orleans, 38; tallahassee, fla., 24, and west palm beach, fla., 43
a frost and freeze warning was in effect overnight for south carolina
rain dampened south-central and southeast texas, and scattered light rain was reported in the texas panhandle and southwest oklahoma
heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. est included 0.38 inch at corpus christi, texas; 0.31 inch at alice, texas; 0.30 inch at palacios, texas, and 0.26 inch at corpus christi, texas
snowshowers occurred from vermont across much of new york, western pennsylvania and eastern ohio to the mountains of west virginia
temperatures at 2 p.m. est ranged from 16 degrees at limon, colo., to 72 degrees at wink, texas, and palm springs, calif. the nation's morning low was 12 degrees below zero at west yellowstone, mont
temperatures dropped to near freezing wednesday morning in the pacific northwest, where yakima, wash., tied a record low of 23 degrees
thursday's forecast called for snow from southern michigan across the middle mississippi valley, kansas and much of oklahoma to parts of northwest texas; rain mixed with snow from the lower ohio valley across southeast missouri and northwest arkansas to eastern oklahoma; rain across portions of the lower mississippi valley and much of texas, and thunderstorms scattered over southern and eastern texas
high temperatures should reach the upper 20s or 30s from northern new england to new york and from michigan across the upper half of the mississippi valley and all of the great plains to the central rockies, the 60s or 70s from the south atlantic coast across the gulf coast to southern texas and from the desert southwest to the pacific northwest, and the 40s or 50s elsewhere
president reagan's former national security adviser, john m. poindexter, and fired white house aide lt. col. oliver l. north were indicted wednesday along with two arms dealers on charges they conspired to divert iranian arms sales profits to the nicaraguan contras
the long-awaited 23-count indictment, which also named retired air force maj. gen. richard v. secord and his business partner, albert hakim, said the four men ``deceitfully and without legal authorization'' organized, directed and concealed ``a program to continue funding of and logistical and other support for military and paramilitary operations in nicaragua by the contras'' at a time u.s. law barred such action
the indictment charged that proceeds from the the $30 million worth of u.s. arms sales to iran were diverted illegally to foreign bank accounts controlled by secord and hakim for their personal financial gain
only $12.2 million from the arms sales was turned over to the u.s. government, according to the indictment
hakim and secord also were charged with conspiring to pay illegal gratuities to north by arranging the installation of a security system at the marine officer's home and by creating a $200,000 fund for his family in a swiss bank
outside the u.s. courthouse, iran-contra independent counsel lawrence e. walsh told reporters the investigation was continuing but declined to say whether there would be any more criminal charges brought in the case
the grand jury is not finished,'' walsh said. ``this is simply an interim report.''
north, who was fired from his job as a national security council aide in late 1986, said: ``i did not commit any crime. i intend to fight the allegations of wrongdoing for as long as necessary.''
his voice breaking, north said the months ahead will be difficult. but, he added: ``nonetheless, i can asure you, i will never give up, we will win, i just cannot tell you how soon.''
north's attorney, brendan v. sullivan jr., told repoorters it will be necessary to call high-ranking officials to north's trial
sullivan said the indictment was an abuse of the criminal process and said a criminal court is not the place to solve a dispute between the president and congress
it is mind-boggling to consider a protracted trial,'' sullivan said
a secretary in secord's office said he was out of town and had not commented on the indictment
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said reagan was informed of the indictments by kenneth duberstein, his deputy chief of staff. speaking of reagan, fitzwater said, ``he had no response.'' he said there was no white house comment because ``it's a matter before the courts.''
just hours before the indictment, reagan was asked if he still stood by his assertion that no laws were broken in the iran-contra affair. ``i have no knowledge of anything that was broken,'' he replied
asked why he felt that way, he replied, ``because from all of the investigation and everything else, we don't know where that money came from and we don't know who had it and we don't know where it went. all i know was that we got the purchase price we had asked for.''
but the indictment, among other things, charged that north and secord conspired to divert millions of dollars from the sale of u.s. government arms to the alleged ``enterprise.''
among other things the indictment charged that north persuaded the cia to lower its price from $6,000 to $3,469 for each of the 1,000 tow missiles sold to iran in february 1986 even though the iranians were paying $10,000 apiece
as a result, the ``enterprise'' kept more than $6 million and turned over only $3.7 million to the u.s. government, the indictment said
in may 1986, only $6.5 million of the $15 million that iran paid for spare hawk missile parts was turned over to the u.s. government, leaving nearly $8.5 million for the ``enterprise,'' the indictment said
the indictment culminated a 14-month grand jury investigation into the arms-for-hostages deals with iran and the diversion of nearly $4 million in profits to the contras
all four defendants were charged with conspiracy to defraud the government and commit criminal offenses against it, theft of government property and wire fraud arising from the diversion of arms-sale proceeds
the these charges together carry maximum penalties of 25 years imprisonment. each of the three charges carries a potential $250,000 fine
north was named in nine counts charging him with obstruction of congress, making false statements, obstructing attorney general edwin meese iii's nov. 21-23, 1986, inquiry by making false statements and concealing, falsifying and destroying classified government documents in nsc files
meese's weekend inquiry uncovered the diversion of arms-sale profits and led to poindexter's resignation and north's dismissal from the nsc staff
poindexter was named in two counts of obstructing a congressional inquiry and two other counts of false statements
poindexter was accused of lying to the house and senate intelligence committees on nov. 21, 1986, by saying he did not learn about the november 1985 shipment of hawk missiles to iran until three months later
the indictment also charges that poindexter, a computer buff, deleted from the nsc computer system all stored messages that he had sent or received
poindexter and north are also charged with lying to house committees in the summer of 1986 by falsely stating that north was not helping raise money for the contras or providing military advice to the rebels
the obstruction and false statement charges against north and poindexter each carry five-year sentences and a $250,000 fine
after a full day of deliberations, walsh was called to the grand jury room at 3:54 p.m. and told the panel was ready to return an indictment. the 21 members of the grand jury then filed upstairs to a courtroom where the 101-page indictment was formally returned to u.s. magistrate jean dwyer
the case was assigned to u.s. district judge gerhard gesell, 77, who was appointed by president johnson and presided over one of the watergate trials
last week, poindexter's predecessor as national security adviser, robert c. mcfarlane, pleaded guilty to four misdemeanor charges that he withheld information from congress in 1985 and in 1986 by denying that members of his staff, particularly north, were helping raise private money to arm the contras during the contra aid ban
the indictment also charged north with obstructing the independent counsel's investigation of the security system at his great falls, va., home by creating false documents to conceal the fact that secord had paid $16,000 for it installation. he was charged with illegally accepting the security system as a gratuity
the indictment also charged that north pocketed $4,500 of $90,000 in travelers checks that he received from contra leader adolfo calero to cover expenses related to the rebel cause and the efforts to obtain release u.s. hostages in lebanon
in a statement, hakim's lawyer, n. richard janis, said: ``we believe strongly that mr. hakim has committed no crimes and that ths indictment is unfair and unwarranted.''
sen. daniel k. inouye, d-hawaii, who chaired the senate iran-contra committee, said, he believed ``justice will ultimately be done.''
while i personally remain convinced that they exhibited insufficient sensitivity to the rule of law, and to the fact that under our system of government the congress makes the laws, we must await the verdict of a jury of their peers as to whether this insensitivity was criminal in nature,'' inouye said
but sen. orrin hatch, r-utah, another member of the senate panel who was one of the administration's strongest supporters during the congressional hearings, said the investigation was ``a colossal embarrassment to our whole government.''
it's going to be a very tricky trial to try to prove these charges in an open forum,'' hatch told reporters
i'm not white-washing this. there were serious mistakes made here,'' hatch said
last spring, two conservative fund-raisers, carl r. ``spitz'' channell and richard miller, pleaded guilty to felony charges that they conspired with north to illegally use a tax-exempt foundation to raise $3.2 million for the contras
the indictment also charged north with participating in that conspiracy
the security council unanimously urged south africa on wednesday to commute the sentences of the ``sharpeville six,'' sentenced to be executed for a 1984 death by mob violence
its resolution asked for a stay of the executions, scheduled for friday, and said south africa's ``practice'' of executing opponents of apartheid has harmed the search for peace
on tuesday, president reagan issued a personal appeal for the lives of the six
they were convicted in the 1984 mob killing of a black township councilman stoned and burned to death in the sharpeville township south of johannesburg. an appeals court judge ruled that they did not kill him personally but had common purpose with the mob
dragoslav pejic of yugoslavia, security council president for march, said death sentences for the ``african patriots'' had caused ``undivided international condemnation and uproar.'' he also said thousands of innocent black south africans have been detained and tortured
secretary-general javier perez de cuellar sent a telegram to president p.w. botha of south africa asking mercy be shown the five men and one woman on humanitarian grounds
he said clemency would help reduce tensions in south africa, where 5 million whites control the government and the 26 million blacks have no voice in national affairs
the council resolution spoke of the ``pretoria racist regime's decision to execute the sharpeville six ... in defiance of worldwide appeals.''
ambassador a. leslie manley of south africa issued a statement criticizing the council, which frequently condemns his country
he said the government ``strongly objects'' to council action that interferes ``not only in an internal south african matter but also a matter which is the result of the due process of law.''
south africa ``is not insensitive to the feelings aroused by capital punishment but must respect the independence of the country's judicial system,'' his statement said. ``murder is a common law crime. it has nothing to do with the color of a person's skin.''
it said south african courts ``are highly respected'' and that there are few countries ``if any, where the courts enjoy a higher degree of independence from the executive authority.''
this was the council's second action in a week of a resolution condemning apartheid, the official south african policy of race discrimination. last tuesday, the united states and britain vetoed a resolution that would have imposed economic sanctions
wednesday's resolution said the executions would ``further inflame an already grave situation in south africa.''
it urged south africa to commute the sentences and asked all countries and organizations to ``use influence and take urgent measures to save the lives of the `sharpeville six'.''
the united states, soviet union, britain, france and china are permanent members of the council, with veto power. other nations currently serving are algeria, argentina, brazil, italy, japan, nepal, senegal, west germany, yugoslavia and zambia
a japanese sound expert testified wednesday that tape-recordings show president corazon aquino's husband was killed on an airport stairway in 1983 by a gun other than previously claimed, and that soldiers shouted ``let me do it!''
matsumi suzuki, president of japan acoustics institute of tokyo, testified at the trial of 34 soldiers and three civilians accused of murdering former sen. benigno aquino and rolando galman, a purported communist agent originally accused as aquino's assassin
aquino's murder led to a groundswell of opposition to then-president ferdinand e. marcos that culminated in a february 1986 popular revolt which deposed marcos after 20 years in office and swept mrs. aquino to power
suzuki identified four soldiers as the ones who shouted ``this is it!,'' ``let me do it!'' and ``shoot, shoot!'' seconds before aquino was murdered at manila airport on aug. 21, 1983. he said the soldiers shouted in tagalog, the main filipino language
aquino was shot as he left a china airlines flight under military escort on his return from three years self-exile in america to lead the opposition to marcos. the soldiers shot galman on the tarmac seconds after aquino fell
suzuki, speaking in japanese through an interpreter, said he analyzed sounds picked up by journalists' tape-recorders during the assassination and from test-firing various types of guns in japanese and u.s. studios
chief prosecutor raul gonzales later told reporters suzuki's testimony supports the prosecution's claim that aquino was killed on the stairway, where only soldiers were in a position to shoot him in the back of the head
the marcos government claimed galman shot aquino on the tarmac with a .357-caliber magnum
suzuki said his analysis of tape-recordings show the first shot, which has been established as the one that killed aquino, could have come only from a .45-caliber pistol
he said the sound of the footsteps of aquino and his four soldier escorts were clearly picked up by two boom microphones extended over the top of the 21-step stairway as the party began descending
we can clearly analyze the sound of the first step to the 11th step,'' he said. ``after the 11th step ... the sound of gunfire was heard.''
the tapes picked up the words ``eto na'' (this is it), followed by ``ako na. ako na'' (let me do it. let me do it) and ``pusila. pusila.'' (shoot. shoot
suzuki said that from a study of voice prints, he concluded the words ``eto na'' were shouted by lt. jesus de castro, chief of the security detail who remained at the stop of the stairs while aquino was led down
the words ``let me do it'' were spoken by sgts. claro lat and arnulfo de mesa one after the other, he said
suzuki said the fatal shot came after both castro and constable 1st class mario lazaga shouted ``shoot'' one after the other
defense lawyer rodoldo jimenez objected that ``voice analysis is not an exact science.''
but suzuki and gonzalez claimed that like fingerprints, a voice print is unique and cannot be duplicated
judge regino hermosisima, one of the three judges trying the case, said the court was accepting suzuki's testimony as ``part of the evidence although this is not an exact science.''
an earlier trial acquitted 25 soldiers and one civilian implicated in the aquino-galman murders. but soon after mrs. aquino became president, the supreme court ruled marcos had influenced the decision and ordered a retrial
black anglican archbishop desmond tutu on wednesday canceled a meeting with leaders of the white dutch reformed church after they described his challenge of government policy as ``impious.''
tutu, a prominent foe of apartheid and winner of the 1984 nobel peace prize, had planned to meet the leaders in pretoria thursday for the first formal talks between the two churches since 1960. president p.w. botha and most other government officials belong to the dutch reformed church, the largest denomination of the dominant afrikaner white minority
tutu said he canceled the meeting because of an ``abusive attack'' on his church in a statement issued tuesday by dutch reformed leaders and published wednesday. he said the leaders ``deliberately sabotaged the talks.''
later wednesday, botha issued a statement asking tutu to repudiate the outlawed african national congress guerrilla movement. tutu says he does not endorse the anc's use of violence but shares its professed goal of a non-racial democracy
the question must be posed whether you are acting on behalf of the kingdom of god or the kingdom promised by the anc and the sacp (south african communist party),'' botha said
are you in favor of the establishment of a marxist dictatorship in south africa under the rule of the anc and the sacp, to the detriment of the church?''
tutu later met with botha to urge clemency for the ``sharpeville six'' _ a group of blacks scheduled to hang friday for complicity in a 1984 mob killing during anti-apartheid unrest
tutu said botha scolded him for taking a confrontational stance toward the government
the archbishop said his decision to cancel the church meeting was influenced by a ``background of unease'' related to the scheduled hangings. he urged dutch reformed leaders to join anglican clergy in prayers for condemned prisoners
the dutch reformed leaders' statement referred to comments by tutu and the rev. allan boesak, a mixed-race minister, at a church service sunday in cape town
tutu and boesak were protesting a recent government ban on political activity by 19 organizations
boesak, president of the world alliance of reformed churches, and tutu used strong language in responding to law and order minister adriaan vlok's warnings that he will act against the clergymen if they did not stop ``preaching revolution.''
boesak said the government ``signed its own death warrant. ... no government can challenge the living god and survive.''
tutu said, ``if it is revolution to say i work for a south africa that is truly democratic ... i am for that.''
the dutch reformed church objected to the clergymen's ``language, convictions and veiled threats that do not breathe the spirit of the gospel.''
it said it was ``not unsympathetic to the problems that churches in this country have to contend with.'' but the statement called on boesak and tutu ``to divorce themselves from this impious road and to discuss their problems openly'' with vlok and botha ``who are both avowed christians.''
botha issued a statement wednesday through the south african broadcasting corp. saying the churches had to recognize ``certain limitations in the execution of their prophetic task outside the ecclesiastical field.''
one major point of boesak's and tutu's sermons was to dispute vlok's statement that they were preaching revolution instead of the christian message
the dutch reformed statement appeared to agree with vlok and botha
in exceeding these limits they have confronted the state, and cannot equate themselves with the church in the face of state retaliation,'' it said. ``the church of jesus christ cannot be used as a means for a revolutionary change of government.''
by law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services
a woman who pleaded guilty to keeping an 8-year-old in a playhouse-sized box for two years says she was trying to prevent the boy from destroying her property while she slept
retha skyles, 54, pleaded guilty to unlawful imprisonment tuesday. sentencing was set for april 26
the child, who was kept in the box from 1985 to 1987, is the son of ms. skyles' stepdaughter. when the boy was removed from the skyles home, he said he was surprised to learn that all little boys weren't kept in boxes, court papers said
in a handwritten statement, ms. skyles said, ``i restrained (the boy) during my sleeping hours in order to keep him from destroying property
my judgment may not have been proper, but my judgment as to the amount of restraint seemed proper to me under the circumstances,'' she said
the box often was locked and contained a jar in which the boy was expected to urinate, police said. he was not allowed to attend school, but did attend church. when he was removed from the home, he had a severe case of head lice
the law provides for a maximum sentence of 90 days in jail, two years' probation and a requirement that the woman pay indefinitely for counseling for the boy, deputy prosecutor barbara corey-boulet said wednesday
however, a judge can declare the case exceptional and impose a stronger sentence
the prosecutor declined to comment on whether she thought the sentence contained in the law would be appropriate, adding only that the boy is ``going to be needing a lot of counseling as he adjusts to a more normal life and she's (ms. skyles) going to be paying for that. that's the kind of punishment that will benefit the child.''
larry fehr, executive director of the non-profit washington council on crime and delinquency, said: ``one can't help but be struck by the discrepancy ... in regard to a child being confined for a much longer period of time than the person who pleaded guilty to the crime.''
ms. skyles' attorney, wallace cavanagh, did not return messages left with his office wednesday
an anonymous tip led child protective services workers to the skyles home, where they took the boy and his 11-year-old sister into custody. they are living with foster parents and are ``thriving,'' said frank mendizabal, dshs spokesman
more than 2,000 ferry workers voted overwhelmingly wednesday to continue a six-week strike against a ferry line, despite a company ultimatum to sign new contracts or lose their jobs
in an outdoor meeting in this southeast england port, all but two of the ferry workers from the national union of seamen raised their hands in favor of maintaining the strike
roger wilkins, deputy general secretary, and other union leaders urged members to step up picketing and fight what they said were moves by p and o european ferries to hire non-union foreign workers
the strike has halted sailings of p and o's 11 vessels between dover and the french ports of boulogne and calais across the english channel and zeebrugge, belgium, across the north sea
peter ford, chairman of the ferry company, denied the company planned to use foreign workers and said he was disappointed with the vote
i hope they will opt for the new contracts,'' he said
the ferry workers struck after the company announced plans to reduce the number of crews for each vessel
pay for a deckhand ranges from $23,125 to $33,300 a year
the union agreed to fewer jobs to maintain profitable operations against the challenge of the channel tunnel project, but wanted the cuts spread over three years
the underwater rail tunnel now being built between england and france is scheduled to open in may 1993 at a cost of $9 billion and is expected to cut into ferry profits
the company's ultimatum followed the collapse of five days of talks with the union, which were convened by the government's arbitration service. each side accused the other of intransigence
six hundred ferry masters and officers will decide whether to settle a dispute with the company at a meeting saturday
the company wants to cut 200 of their jobs because of redundancies and new work patterns. the officers have not been on strike. 03-16 0882</first> `embarrassment'</head> jackson comment. adds three grafs at end of group calling for presidential pardon for north.</note>
a republican senator said the investigation that led to indictments wednesday of four people in the iran-contra scandal was a ``colossal embarrassment'' to the government, while democrats said the charges vindicate last year's congressional inquiry into the arms and money affair
the charges were announced by lawrence e. walsh, the independent counsel whose investigation began about the same time that committees of both the house and senate began looking at the secret sale of u.s. weapons to iran and the diversion of some of the money to the nicaraguan contras
sen. daniel k. inouye, d-hawaii, chairman of the senate committee, said he believes that ``justice will ultimately be done.''
inouye added that ``i personally remain convinced that they (the four men) exhibited insufficient sensitivity to the rule of law, and to the fact that under our system of government the congress must make the laws,'' but he said, ``we must await the verdict of a jury of their peers as to whether this insensitivity was criminal in nature.''
rep. lee hamilton, d-ind., chairman of the house iran-contra committee, noted that the indictments closely paralleled the conclusions of the congressional committees, although the panels made no attempt to assess criminal blame
i don't think there are any major surprises,'' he said, although ``there was more of an emphasis on the misuse of federal funds ... than i might have anticipated.''
they are very serious charges, obviously, and quite extensive,'' hamilton told reporters. ``they cover a lot of misconduct.'' he added that walsh probably developed more information than the committees were able to get on financial records
sen. george mitchell, d-maine, another member of the senate panel, said, ``it is a serious matter when any citizen is charged with a crime, and it is even more serious when a former high government official, and close adviser to the president, is charged.''
mitchell said ``no one should prejudge the case,'' but said he had heard nothing in the indictments which had not come out during last summer's iran-contra hearings
sen. orrin hatch, r-utah, another member of the senate panel, was one of the administration's strongest supporters during the congressional hearings and he was critical of the indictments
the investigation was ``a colossal embarrassment to our whole government,'' hatch told a news conference. ``it's going to be a very tricky trial to try to prove these charges in an open forum.''
i'm not white-washing this. there were serious mistakes made here,'' hatch said
you may very well be able to get convictions under technicalities of the law,'' he said, speaking of the indictments, but ``these indictments are choking on the nits of the law.''
rep. henry hyde, r-ill., a member of the house investigating committee and another strong administration supporter, said, ``these indictments aren't any surprise. but this is only the beginning of what will be a very long legal process that will question the sufficiency of the indictments and the constitutionality of the laws.''
for example, he said, ``i believe the indictments are premised on some assumptions that may or may not be true, like title to the money. the prosecutors believe the money from the sale of weapons to iran belonged to the u.s. treasury and therefore it was misappropriated for the contras, but i think a very good argument can be made that the proceeds of the sale don't belong to the treasury.''
rep. richard gephardt, d-mo., a candiate for the democratic presidential nomination, said, ``whatever the outcome of these prosecutions, i think the special prosecutor has given us fresh evidence that the reagan administration generally has put the constitution of the united states through the shredder.''
this will be an important issue in the campaign,'' gephardt said, particularly the role of vice president george bush, who is the front-runner for the republican presidential nomination
jesse jackson, another presidential candidate, said the indictments were ``a source of embarrassment to this administration and a disgrace to our country,'' but called those indicted ``the fall guys.''
they were, in fact, implementing this administration's policy,'' he said
lt. col. oliver l. north, the fired white house aide who was one of the four men charged, was supported wednesday by andy messing, head of the national defense council, a private, conservative organization. messing is a friend of north
it's a difference between persecution and prosecution that walsh is going to have to explain to the american people,'' messing said. ``after 15 months and $10 million and almost 300 people at his disposal, judge walsh is going to have to convince the american people that is not persecution but a prosecution.''
robert grant, president of another group that supports north, the american freedom coalition, issued a statement calling on the president to pardon north
col. north is a man of principle, honor and commitment. his patriotic, pro-american values are a tremendous asset to the well-being of the united states,'' grant said
this is hardly the definition of a criminal,'' grant said. ``he should be pardoned immediately.''
a soldier in one of the units involved in a helicopter collision that killed 17 servicemen said at a memorial service wednesday that the loss was magnified by ``the bond between us soldiers.''
military and civilian dignitaries, including gov. wallace g. wilkinson, joined family members and other mourners in the 450-seat post central chapel for two services
the first half-hour memorial honored the seven army aviators flying the helicopters when they collided march 8; the second paid homage to the 10 foot soldiers on board
an open bible rested on a simple altar, flanked by banners representing the the 101st airborne division and flags pinned with colorful streamers representing battles in which units of the 101st fought
the seven helicopter crewmen were represented in front of the altar by seven flight helmets placed atop sabers for the officers and m-16 rifles for the enlisted men. infantry helmets were used to represent the foot soldiers
the 17 were killed when a uh-60 black hawk helicopter, returning from a night mission, was struck by another copter on a separate mission at fort campbell
army investigators said they have not determined the cause of the crash
during the toughest of times we find ourselves wondering why we choose to be infantrymen,'' said spec. 4 colin cannon, whose unit included 10 of the victims. ``it is a job that is at best difficult and at its worst fatal.''
the loss was magnified by ``the bond between us as soldiers, which brought us closer to each other in a way that so many others can never know; something that only people who serve in a profession such as ours can ever understand,'' cannon said
i have flown personally with each of these (helicopter crew members). i can tell you without reservation that they truly loved what they were doing,'' said lt. col. joseph a. fucci, commander of the 101st aviation regiment's 5th brigade
we all share in the loss of these men. and though all the grief that we feel does not begin to compare with the sorrow being felt by their wives and their families, our hearts and our prayers go out to you,'' he said. arrival in ljubljana. picks up 7th graf pvs, gorbachev said ...</note>
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev proposed wednesday that the superpowers freeze their naval forces in the mediterranean as a first step toward reducing tensions in the region
he described the mediterranean as ``one of the most explosive regions in the world'' and recommended that the freeze begin july 1
in a wide-ranging speech to the yugoslav parliament, gorbachev also indirectly criticized the late soviet dictator josef stalin, who imposed an economic blockade of yugoslavia after president josip broz tito set his own foreign policy course in 1948
the kremlin leader also discussed the ethnic unrest in his own country, saying he was determined to resolve it democratically but would not allow independence for nationalist groups
yugoslavia itself is an ethnically diverse nation of six republics and two autonomous regions and is plagued by growing ethnic tensions as the economic situation worsens
gorbachev later flew to ljubljana, capital of the northern slovenia republic, one of the most prosperous regions in the communist world
plans for the soviet communist party chief to visit a private farm in the area were canceled because he arrived late, officials said
gorbachev will meet slovenian leaders thursday as he continues his five-day visit here
gorbachev said his country was concerned about the military presence in the mediterranean because it is provides soviet ports on the black sea their only access to the world's oceans
in addition to the naval freeze, gorbachev called on the superpowers to set a limit on the number of vessels they maintain in the mediterranean, and he suggested they give each other and nations in the region advance notice when they redistribute their forces or conduct military exercises there
gorbachev also proposed that military observers be permitted to watch such maneuvers
he made no direct reference to ethnic rioting in the soviet republic of azerbaijan, in which at least 32 people were killed, nor did he mention mass demonstrations in the armenian capital of yerevan
but he said the state of relations between the more than 100 nationalities within the soviet union is ``one of the most important and delicate issues in a multinational country such as ours.''
there are certain difficulties inherited from the past,'' gorbachev said, apparently referring to a 1923 decision to put an aremenian-controlled region under control of azerbaijan
armenians' demands for annexation of that region are believed to have been at the root of the sumgait riots
we are determined to secure democratic solutions to these problems,'' gorbachev said, but he served notice that he would not tolerate nationalists' demands for independence. that theme has been kept alive by exile groups from the baltic republics of lithusania, latvia and estonia
whatever constituent or autonomous republic or region we take, it is now bound by thousands of threads to all other parts of the country,'' gorbachev said. ``it has indisoluble links within the integrated economic and political complex.''
gorbachev said the 1948 rupture in relations between his country and yugoslavia ``inflicted grave damage on yugoslav-soviet relations and ... on socialism as a whole.''
but he assured his hosts he wants improved relations with yugoslavia and does not intend to try to press his ideas of perestroika, or restructuring, on them
we are implementing our perestroika in keeping with the conditions and needs of our own country, and we have no intention whatsoever to palm it off as a universal model or recipe that would be good for all,'' gorbachev said
the soviet leader blasted unnamed leaders in the nato alliance for ``harping on the lie'' of a soviet threat to prevent nuclear disarmament and build up nato's conventional forces in europe
these contradictions, not to say absurdities, have quite definite political convictions behind them,'' gorbachev said
thousands of yellow ribbons adorned trees, traffic signs and lapels on terry anderson day in the journalist's hometown wednesday, the third anniversary of his kidnapping by moslem extremists in lebanon
the most sacred experience is to be remembered by frends, loved ones and by god,'' said the rev. jack wolter of st. james episcopal church, where prayer services were held for anderson
we pray that terry will be remembered today and soon delivered from his tormenters,'' wolter said
anderson, the chief middle east correspondent for the associated press, was kidnapped in beirut and has been held longer than any of the 22 foreign hostages in lebanon
the activities in batavia coincided with a national observance in washington, d.c. the anniversary also was marked in anderson's birthplace, lorain, ohio, where a group including relatives hoisted an american flag and tied a yellow ribbon to the flagpole at city hall
may this be a day of miracles,'' the rev. thomas vickers, who has acted as personal chaplain to anderson's family in recent months, said in batavia. ``please lord, set him free.''
journalists outnumbered the handful of churchgoers at an early morning service at st. james. vickers asked reporters to put down their notebooks to join hands and pray for a colleague
at the church's midday service about 30 people heard a service by vickers and wolter, who said christians had a duty to speak up for those who suffer injustice
anderson's younger brother, jack, who grew up in batavia and works as a prison guard in ocala, fla., urged those attending to write their congressmen to press the government to do more to win the release of the hostages
i'm sure terry is thinking of batavia today,'' he said. ``i know he wants more than anything to be able come back here and be with his family and friends.''
several florists in the small city of 17,000 donated more than two miles of yellow ribbon, which was tied in bows and handed out to residents. nearly every tree, sign post and railing along main street sported yellow ribbon
we always knew people were concerned about terry,'' jack anderson said. ``but in the past they didn't turn out and make an effort to show it.''
anderson's sister, peggy say of batavia, has fought to free her brother since his kidnapping, but her activities did not win widespread support in her hometown until recently
people didn't know how to react,'' said terry fritts, a talk show host on radio station wbta. ``i don't think many people opposed what peggy was doing. they just didn't know if it was the best thing to do.''
mrs. say, who was in washington on wednesday, and other family members have said they hope the attention will force the administration to develop a new policy. indictments; adds 2 grafs with later event</note>
jesse jackson said wednesday he's counting ``the number of votes, not the color of votes'' in the wake of his second-place showing in his home state of illinois where he garnered less than 10 percent of the white vote
jackson also said the four men indicted wednesday on conspiracy charges in the iran-contra affair _ lt. col. oliver l. north, fired national security adviser john m. poindexter, retired air force maj. gen. richard v. secord and secord's business partner, albert hakim _ were ``fall guys.''
they were in fact implementing this administration's policy,'' jackson said, calling the iran-contra affair `` a source of embarrassment to this administration and a disgrace to our country.''
back on the subject of the illinois contest, jackson was upbeat
we came in a strong second in illinois,'' he told reporters. ``i am gratified with the response to my campaign in illinois yesterday.''
we did well. illinois did well by both of its favorite-son candiates,'' he said, when asked about pre-election polls that had showed him virtually dead even with home state sen. paul simon. jackson ended up with 31 percent of the vote, to simon's 43 percent
exit polls showed jackson overwhelming won the state's black vote, but pulled only 7 to 8 percent of white voters into his camp. that was less than the 10 percent he garnered across the super tuesday states on march 8, and a represented an apparent setback from his strong showings in northern states that have black populations of 1 percent or less, including minnesota, maine, vermont and alaska
when asked if that spelled trouble in the states yet to come as he tries to attract crucial white support to his campaign, jackson replied, ``let's count the number of votes, not the color of votes.'' he noted he is first in the cumulative popular vote count of states that have held primaries so far, and is a close second in the delegate count to massachusetts gov. michael dukakis
of 30 contests now i have come in number one or number two ... we have reason to celebrate in my campaign. we are where every campaign wants to be.''
jackson made the comments following an observance at holy trinity church of the third year of captivity for american hostage terry anderson, chief middle east correspondent for the associated press who is being held in lebanon
earlier he had a chance meeting at national airport with rival sen. albert gore jr., of tennessee, who was leaving as jackson was arriving. the two spoke briefly, and according to jackson talked about party unity
organizers of the hostage memorial said all the presidential candidates were invited to the service, which included remarks by former hostages and family members of anderson and others still being held. jackson, who helped gain release of downed navy pilot lt. robert goodman from syria in 1983, was the only one who attended
at a news conference afterward, jackson said he has ``done everything i can'' to make contacts that might secure the hostage release, but that the situation is complicated because he does not know who is holding the hostages
he criticized the administration, however, saying that the u.s. intelligence operations should be put to work finding the location of the hostages and the identity of the captors so that negotiations for their release can begin
they can be found, through our intelligence network,'' he said, adding that negotiations should begin ``either directly or through our allies.''
outside the church in the posh georgetown neighborhood of washington, jackson caused a stir among holy trinity elementary school students, georgetown university students and passersby who rushed out to shake his hand
the school children squealed in delight as he raced across a cobblestone street to greet them, then went to the other side to shake hands with college students who rushed out on the balconies of their brownstone homes to cheer him
i don't think i'd want him to win, but i think i might vote for him. he's the only one bringing out the important issues,'' said erich vaden, 19, a georgetown student
later, jackson went to one of washington's most well-known drug-trafficking neighborhoods, where he and district of columbia mayor marion barry addressed a rally. jackson made a strong anti-drug statement, telling 300 people, ``we must stop drugs or drugs will stop the people.''
you must be sober and free of drugs whether you have a job or not,'' he said. jackson also said drugs are a foreign policy issue that has been dealt with inadequately by the reagan administration. private aid to public aid.</note>
president reagan vetoed a major civil rights bill wednesday, saying it would ``vastly and unjustifiably extend the power of the federal government over the decisions and affairs of private organizations.''
reagan also proposed an alternative that he said would ``protect civil rights and at the same time preserve the independence of state and local governments, the freedom of religion and the right of america's citizens to order their lives and businesses without extensive federal intrusion.''
the veto was immediately criticized by civil rights and other groups, and congressional democrats predicted a quick override
the legislation, which had bipartisan support, passed the senate 75-14 on jan. 28 and the house 315-98 on march 2. both votes are more than the two-thirds majority necessary to override a presidential veto
sen. edward kennedy, d-mass., chairman of the senate labor and human resources committee, called the veto ``a kick in the teeth of civil rights. it is the most regrettable and least justifiable of all the reagan vetoes.''
the bill the president vetoed was designed to undo the effects of a 1984 supreme court ruling that, in cutting off federal funds because of illegal discrimination, the government could treat each specific ``program or activity'' separately
that meant that other parts of the institution involved could still receive federal funds
under the bill, federal aid to the entire institution would have to be cut off in such cases
in his veto message, the president said he supported legislation to ``strengthen the civil rights coverage of educational institutions'' that were affected by the high court's decision
he said he had already endorsed legislation to do this but his new bill ``goes further than the legislation previously endorsed.''
reagan's bill is similar to one rejected by the house by a vote of 266-146
the president said his bill would:
_``prohibit discrimination against women, minorities, persons with disabilities, and the elderly across the board in public school districts, public systems of higher education, systems of vocational education, and private educational institutions which receive any public aid
_``extend the application of the civil rights statutes to entire businesses which receive federal aid as a whole and to the entire plant or facility receiving federal aid in every other instance
_``prohibit discrimination in all of the federally funded programs of departments and agencies of state and local governments.''
reagan said his bill ``complements well our body of existing federal civil rights laws.''
congress, on the other hand, has sent me a bill that would vastly and unjustifiably expand the power of the federal government over the decisions and affairs of private organizations, such as churches and synagogues, farms, businesses, and state and local governments,'' he said. ``in the process, it would place at risk such cherished values as religious liberty.''
rep. augustus hawkins, d-calif., chairman of the house education and labor committee, said he was confident the house will override the veto. ``i don't think many members will be so weak-kneed that they will change on the basis of lobbying that is now going on,'' hawkins said
house speaker jim wright said in a statement that ``president reagan may want to turn the clock back on civil rights, but the american people do not... i am confident that the senate and house will move swiftly to override this unfortunate and shortsighted veto.''
a senate leadership aide said the chamber would vote thursday on overriding the veto. the house was not expected to act before tuesday
ralph g. neas, director of the leadership conference on civil rights, and benjamin l. hooks, chairman of the organization, issued a statement denouncing the president's action and predicting that it would be overturned
while we are confident that huge bipartisan majorities in both houses of congress will vote to override a presidential veto, we believe strongly that this veto is not in the best interests of the country because it sends a terrible signal to the nation, especially in this bicentennial year of the constitution,'' the statement said
the president sometimes expresses wonder that anyone can criticize him on his civil rights record,'' the two leaders said. ``in fact this administration is compiling the worst civil rights record of any administration in half a century.''
the afl-cio issued a statement wednesday calling the veto ``a strong message of retreat from enforcement of laws intended to prevent discrimination based on race, sex, age and handicap.''
the united states catholic conference, an association representing the nation's roman catholic bishops, issued a statement saying the conference was
deeply disappointed that the president saw fit to veto one of the most important pieces of civil rights legislation to come along in many years.''
it said the bill would have done much to ``strengthen federal civil rights protection while safeguarding vital concerns about human life and religious liberty.'' the conference vowed to work ``actively'' for an override
the white house, in a statement accompanying reagan's veto message, said the administration alternative would protect religious liberty by limiting coverage to the part of a church or synagogue that participates in a federal program. the statement said the reagan bill would provide that when a religious secondary or elementary school receives federal assistance, only that school, and not the entire religious school system, would become subject to federal regulation
the statement said the measure would ``ensure that the reach of the federal regulation into private businesses extends only to the facility that participates in federally funded programs, unless the business as a whole receives federal aid, in which case it is covered in its entirety.''
it said the administration bill also states explicitly that farmers will not become subject to federal regulation by accepting federal price support payments and that grocers and supermarkets would not be afgfected because they accept food stamps from customers
it said the independence of state and local governments would be preserved because federal regulation would be limited to the part of a state or local entity that receives or distributes federal assistance
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said tuesday he believed the bill would attract the support of ``a large number'' of senators and representatives
more soviets are applying to visit or live abroad and fewer of them are being refused permission, a soviet official said wednesday
sergei apatov, head of the moscow police department's visa office, told soviet journalists that 82 percent of soviets who apply to go to israel are granted permission
about 200 people have been turned down, he said. he did not break the number down into travel and emigration requests or provide an overall figure
the government newspaper izvestia and the official tass news agency carried reports on apatov's briefing
apatov said citizens were refused permission either because of their access to state secrets or because they could not satisfy their relatives' financial demands
he said those not allowed to leave because of their alleged access to state secrets can reapply, usually after six months
many soviet jews say officials abuse the law that says people can not leave if they know state secrets or are needed by their families for financial reasons
western sources say more than 8,000 soviet jews were allowed to emigrate in 1987, after several years when emigration was held to about 1,000 a year. emigration reached its peak in 1979, when more than 51,000 people left
apatov said a reduction in the paperwork needed to travel abroad also prompted more soviets to apply for permission for trips
the number of people applying to travel to capitalist countries increased 93 percent in the first two months of 1988, apatov said. the number of people refused such permission fell 44 percent in 1987 from the previous year, he said, without providing specific figures
a fee imposed on those leaving for capitalist and developing countries has been halved to 200 rubles (about $320), apatov said. money</head> image, trusting aides, allegation of protecting aide accused of death threat, rescinding martin luther king holiday. no pickup.</note>
gov. evan mecham took the stand at his impeachment trial wednesday and said that he did not protect an aide accused of making a death threat and did not sell appointments for campaign contributions
the governor, portraying himself as a naive victim of political enemies who skewered him with bad publicity, said the public never saw him as ``the nice guy i really am.''
i've learned a lot,'' he said in his first appearance at the senate trial, which opened feb. 29. the first-term republican was scheduled to return to the stand on thursday
mecham, 63, is the first u.s. governor to face an impeachment trial in six decades. wednesday's session was his first return to the seat of state government in more than a month
he is accused of trying to obstruct an investigation of an alleged death threat against a former aide who was about to testify in an investigation of mecham's finances. he is also charged with concealing a $350,000 campaign loan and misusing $80,000 in state money by loaning it to his auto dealership
mecham has denied wrongdoing
the 192-seat senate gallery was jammed as mecham took the stand. senators remained standing as he took an oath to tell the truth
defense attorney fred craft asked whether mecham intended to protect the aide accused of making the death threat, lee watkins
protect him from what?'' mecham asked. ``i've heard those allegations. i wish somebody would tell me what i protected him from.''
craft mentioned a conversation in which mecham was alleged to have ordered the state's top law enforcement officer to resist the attorney general's investigation of the alleged threat
were you intending to do anything to protect lee watkins (in that conversation)?'' asked craft
not in the least,'' said mecham
mecham has claimed he was inadequately informed about the death threat allegation
he has acknowledged he may have told the state's top police official, department of public safety director ralph milstead, to resist the attorney general's efforts to investigate. milstead has said he cooperated with the attorney general
mecham on wednesdsay also denied allegations that he rewarded fund-raisers with jobs. ``money was never an object and it was never used as a criteria to get a job,'' he said
the governor also denied that watkins was his biggest fund-raiser, saying watkins ``brought in some loans'' but not a huge amount in contributions
last week, donna carlson, a former mecham aide, had testified that watkins was protected by the mecham administration because of his fund-raising
she said that when she once complained about watkins' position in the governor's inner circle she was told by the governor's then-chief of staff: ``we have to take care of lee. he raised a lot of money for the campaign.''
earlier wednesday, sam udall, mecham's former appointments secretary, had testified that campaign contributions were a criterion, although not a major one, in making appointments to state boards and commissions
udall also testified that he did not immediately realize that two proposed appointees to the housing finance review board had been recommended by barry wolfson, who provided a $350,000 campaign loan to mecham
mecham, a millionaire auto dealer, said wednesday that he himself was his biggest campaign contributor
unfortunately i always have been,'' he said of his political career, which included four previous runs for governor before his successful 1986 campaign
mecham also seized the opportunity to complain of being misunderstood on one of his first official acts, elimination of the state's martin luther king holiday. he said that his action was mandated by the attorney general and that he replaced a paid state holiday with an unpaid ``recognition day.''
what we did was tell peoiple we in arizona believe in civil rights for all people,'' he said
shortly before mecham appeared, the senate resoundingly voted down a motion to dismiss the charges. the senators also defeated defense motions to declare a mistrial or to hold a hearing on defense claims of witness tampering
robert usdane, house republican majority leader, noted that claims by mecham's lawyers that the state police were intimidating witnesses were under investigation by law enforcement agencies
mecham, a perennial political outsider who won election in a three-way race, has been staying at suburban glendale offices he calls his ``government in exile.'' he retains his salary and is referred to as governor during the impeachment proceedings, but mofford has gubernatorial power pending the outcome of the trial
it would take a two-thirds vote of the 30-member senate to convict mecham and remove him from office. the senators could then take another vote and bar him for life from holding state office
mecham also faces a criminal trial april 21 on charges he concealed the $350,000 loan, and a recall election is scheduled for may 17
reputed druglord carlos lehder rivas interrupted his smuggling trial wednesday to say he had evidence the chief prosecutor was blackmailing the judge, an allegation the prosecutor called ``high comedy.''
u.s. attorney robert merkle said the man who sent the letter to lehder had ``mental problems'' and had made similar allegations about authorities in tampa, where he had been convicted on extortion and racketeering charges
u.s. district judge howell melton read the letter and said he had also received previous letters from the man
lehder, 38, charged with smuggling tons of cocaine into the united states, rose as the court was breaking for a mid-morning recess
your honor, i would like to disclose that i have received evidence that mr. merkle is blackmailing judge melton and i'd like to present it,'' he said
this is high comedy,'' merkle said as melton said he'd like to hear any such evidence
the statement apparently was unexpected even by lehder's attorneys. it resulted in quick recesses so they could confer with their client. the letter-writer's name was not revealed in court
this individual is familiar to me. he has mental problems,'' said the prosecutor
i do not intend for the integrity of this court, nor the prosecutor to be impugned,'' the judge said of the allegations. ``i would categorically say that at this time, they are absolutely untrue.''
the judge gave the defense until thursday morning to file any motions they might want to make concerning the material
lehder said the information had been filed by the letter writer with a federal appeals court and the senate judiciary committee. ``i wanted to just call it to the judge's attention so that something can be done about it,'' said lehder
defense attorney edward r. shohat said his client had no personal knowledge about the source of the information
lehder, reputed to be one of the leaders of colombia's medellin cocaine cartel, is on trial on charges he and others conspired to import some 3.3 tons of the drug into the united states from colombia via the bahamas
co-defendant jack carlton reed, 57, of san pedro, calif., is charged with being a part of the smuggling conspiracy. update with thiokol response; deletes 16th graf pvs, `three violations ...' to conform.</note>
a state agency cited morton thiokol inc. for six safety violations and fined the aerospace company $31,700 wednesday in a fire in an mx missile motor assembly building dec. 29 that killed five workers
the victims' presence in the building and failure to use remote-control equipment instead at the time of the fire were among the most serious violations alleged by the utah division of occupational safety and health
the penalties represent the maximum that could be imposed, said doug mcvey, uosh administrator
the contractor has 30 days to appeal the citations and penalties to the independent utah uosh review commission. three violations were deemed willful and serious, two were deemed serious and one was ``other than serious.''
in a statement late wednesday, chicago-based morton thiokol said that it is ``confident that the facts will not substantiate any conscious or knowing violation of the act'' and that it will challenge the citations
morton thiokol described many of the alleged violations as ``random instances unknown to company management, which reflect a failure of some employees to follow all rules established by the company.''
the company said increased supervision and stricter enforcement of the company's discipline program have been instituted as a remedy
the workers were withdrawing the core from a casting of the first stage of an mx missile when 100,000 pounds of solid fuel ignited in a fireball. the blaze caused $6.2 million in damage to the plant 25 miles west of brigham city
morton thiokol makes the missile's four stages, and also makes the space shuttle's solid-fuel rocket boosters, which failed when the challenger blew up in january 1986
the fire at thiokol's wasatch division has held up production of the mx missile until the cause of the fire can be determined and corrected
air force investigators, in a briefing wednesday, blamed either static electricity or friction, perhaps from grit, as the probable cause of the fire, said art kingdom, a spokesman for rep. wayne owens, d-utah
another theory is that as the propellant was compressed, its chemistry changed, making it more volatile, kingdom said
mcvey said state investigators agreed with the air force's findings, although his division's investigation focused on safety regulations, not the cause
results of the air force's investigation were scheduled to be made public thursday, but members of utah's congressional delegation were briefed a day in advance
uosh alleged that workmen were removing the core from an engine manually rather than by remote control. the cores, or metal forms, are removed after the propellant has been poured into the casing and allowed to harden
the agency also said protective walls and barricades were not provided, and proper precautions against static electricty weren't taken
in addition, it said, dual controls for a hydraulic system were not interlocked to prevent unintentional operations, and employees entering the explosive material area did not turn over all prohibited articles, such as coins and keys
also, an unauthorized crowbar was in a restricted area, uosh said
kingdom said the air force recommended better electrical grounding, increased humidity and more care in withdrawing cores from engines
the air force said the fire destroyed one of three missile engine cores. investigators said two completed castings are awaiting withdrawal of the cores before the engines can be shipped to the air force in california, kingdom said
kingdom said the air force had indicated it needed the engines within the two months to continue its mx test program. loss</head> comment from byrne.</note>
former mayor jane byrne kicked in the door of chicago's fabled backroom politics nearly a decade ago, unsmiling and unafraid of mixing it up with the democratic machine's big boys
but after her third straight electoral setback, this one for clerk of the cook county circuit court and viewed by many political observers as the first step in a comeback bid, mrs. byrne apparently is calling it quits
when we say the people spoke,'' mrs. byrne said of tuesday's primary defeat, ``they apparently shouted
and therefore,'' she added, ``i'm very good at taking hints.''
i truly believe that politically it's all over for me,'' mrs. byrne said wednesday before leaving for phoenix, ariz
she headed west for ``some rest and relaxation,'' said joe pecor, her campaign manager. asked whether she would run again, he said, ``where she is concerned, one should never say never.''
she has demonstrated time and again that she has a very solid core of support running somewhere between 35 (percent) and 40 percent of the democrats in chicago and the county.''
but that wasn't enough to stave off the late harold washington's upset bid in the three-way 1983 democratic mayoral primary, and it wasn't enough when she tried to avenge that loss against washington last year
it turned out be too little again tuesday when she lost to aurelia pucinski, endorsed by the party organization that mrs. byrne once held, vise-like, in her grip
and this latest loss came in a race rich with resonance and names _ pucinski, byrne and edward ``fast eddie'' vrdolyak _ that speak to the past, present and perhaps even the future of cook county's quirky democratic politics
mrs. byrne, a former debutante with a flair for the dramatic, became the city's first woman mayor in 1979, scoring a rags-to-riches victory after campaigning against the political machine of the late mayor richard j. daley
she defeated the machine's candidate, then-mayor michael bilandic, with the help of much of the city's machine-weary blacks, but later made peace with the regular democrats
included in that group were several aldermen mrs. byrne had railed against as members of ``an evil cabal,'' most notably vrdolyak and roman pucinski, aurelia pucinski's father and one of the machine's most loyal servants
but she paid dearly for cozying up to the old guard, as well as for several other moves _ replacing blacks with whites on the school board, then handing out hams at public-housing projects as the 1983 election neared
washington, galvanizing the black vote, turned her out of office and became the city's first black mayor
he spent the next four years retooling the party machinery to fit his needs, then became the first two-term mayor since daley by handily beating back successive challenges from mrs. byrne last february in the primary and then vrdolyak, running as a third-party candidate, in april
after washington's death in november, alderman eugene sawyer became mayor
vrdolyak, saying the party under washington had become untenable, completed his move away from the democratic organization last year. running as a republican, he was unopposed in tuesday's primary for court clerk
in the meantime, ms. pucinski, an attorney and metropolitan sanitary district commissioner, stepped out of her father's shadow and was welcomed into the washington camp
so much so that she may have beaten byrne in tuesday's race on the strength of her showing among chicago's blacks, who helped propel her to a 52 percent to 38 percent victory over mrs. byrne with nearly all the votes counted. two other candidates, thomas fuller, and janice hart, a follower of political extremist lyndon larouche, split the rest of the vote
ms. hart defeated ms. pucinski in the 1986 democratic primary for the illinois secretary of state's office, won that november by republican jim edgar
byrne's defeat spoiled an anticipated byrne-vrdolyak struggle in the fall, a match of two former titans for an obscure office both hoped would lead to bigger things
kim dae-jung resigned thursday as leader of his party in an attempt to unite the opposition before national assembly elections expected in april
he said he was stepping down because his presence as head of the party for peace and democracy was blocking unification and because he failed to win the dec. 16 presidential elections
i have keenly felt guilty,'' kim dae-jung said in a statement read by a party vice president, park young-sook, who said she would be acting party president
the statement made no mention of kim dae-jung's future plans. he did not make the statement himself because he was ill, party officials said
efforts to unite peace and democracy with the rival reunification democratic party collapsed last week when kim dae-jung refused the other party's demand that he resign
it was not clear if his resignation thursday would clear the way for the opposition to unite. the reunification democratic leadership met after kim dae-jung's announcement to consider its response
kim dae-jung acted after the reunification democrats moved to unite with three smaller opposition parties
many opposition supporters are angry that the two main opposition parties have failed to join together, and party leaders fear a major loss of support
kim dae-jung and his supporters split from the reunification democratic party to form the peace and democracy party late last year after he and kim young-sam, the reunification democrats' leader, failed to agree on who should run for president
both kims ran and were defeated by the government party's nominee, roh tae-woo, who became president feb. 25. opposition supporters blamed the two kims for the defeat because they split the opposition vote
kim young-sam resigned as reunification democratic party president in february to clear the way for the two parties to unite. unity talks ran into problems over leadership and political goals and collapsed
the opposition is concerned it will suffer a major defeat in the national assembly elections expected april 26
the security council unanimously urged south africa on wednesday to commute the sentences of the ``sharpeville six,'' sentenced to be executed for a 1984 death by mob violence
its resolution asked for a stay of the executions, scheduled for friday, and said south africa's ``practice'' of executing opponents of apartheid has harmed the search for peace
on tuesday, president reagan issued a personal appeal for the lives of the six
they were convicted in the 1984 mob killing of a black township councilman stoned and burned to death in the sharpeville township south of johannesburg. an appeals court judge ruled that they did not kill him personally but had common purpose with the mob
dragoslav pejic of yugoslavia, security council president for march, said death sentences for the ``african patriots'' had caused ``undivided international condemnation and uproar.'' he also said thousands of innocent black south africans have been detained and tortured
secretary-general javier perez de cuellar sent a telegram to president p.w. botha of south africa asking mercy be shown the five men and one woman on humanitarian grounds
he said clemency would help reduce tensions in south africa, where 5 million whites control the government and the 26 million blacks have no voice in national affairs
the council resolution spoke of the ``pretoria racist regime's decision to execute the sharpeville six ... in defiance of worldwide appeals.''
ambassador a. leslie manley of south africa issued a statement criticizing the council, which frequently condemns his country
he said the government ``strongly objects'' to council action that interferes ``not only in an internal south african matter but also a matter which is the result of the due process of law.''
south africa ``is not insensitive to the feelings aroused by capital punishment but must respect the independence of the country's judicial system,'' his statement said. ``murder is a common law crime. it has nothing to do with the color of a person's skin.''
it said south african courts ``are highly respected'' and that there are few countries ``if any, where the courts enjoy a higher degree of independence from the executive authority.''
this was the council's second action in a week of a resolution condemning apartheid, the official south african policy of race discrimination. last tuesday, the united states and britain vetoed a resolution that would have imposed economic sanctions
wednesday's resolution said the executions would ``further inflame an already grave situation in south africa.''
it urged south africa to commute the sentences and asked all countries and organizations to ``use influence and take urgent measures to save the lives of the `sharpeville six'.''
the united states, soviet union, britain, france and china are permanent members of the council, with veto power. other nations currently serving are algeria, argentina, brazil, italy, japan, nepal, senegal, west germany, yugoslavia and zambia
federal authorities in at least two states are investigating whether ferdinand marcos tried to arrange an arms shipment to philippine forces loyal to him, according to federal officials and other sources
marcos' chief american attorney denied the former philippine president was involved in any arms shipments. ``that's a dry well for you, my friend,'' richard a. hibey said friday in washington. ``there's no truth to that allegation.''
word that authorities were pressing such an investigation surfaced here last week when u.s. district judge alfred j. lechner jr., in sentencing a defendant in an arms smuggling case here, referred to a continuing probe
chris franzblau, an attorney for the defendant, abelardo morua, said tuesday that federal agents had asked his client about marcos
they asked a lot of times about if whether we had anything to tie up marcos to this transaction,'' he said, adding that morua was unable to provide such a link
morua was charged with three others in a customs service sting operation stemming from the alleged arms deal
no arms were alleged to have changed hands. however, officials said the shipment would have supplied automatic rifles and submachine guns for an 80-member force
leon dicker, a disbarred hewlett, n.y., attorney, was convicted of conspiring to export weapons. the two others were acquitted. dicker was sentenced to four years in prison. morua received a two-year term
during the trial, the government said the arms were destined for thailand, but two federal officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said last week that the weapons were believed headed for pro-marcos forces in the philippines
pro-marcos elements failed in at least two coup attempts in 1987
during dicker's trial, the prosecutor said new york businessman robert l. steele had worked with dicker on the proposed arms shipment
steele, who was not charged, and dicker have been linked to orlando c. dulay, a marcos supporter and former provincial governor later connected by philippine military sources to an august 1987 coup attempt against the government of marcos' successor, corazon aquino
dulay was questioned by police on the grounds of a marcos-owned estate in lawrence township in august 1986. he said steele and dicker, whom he identified as his lawyers, told him to clean up the estate. he was not arrested
a newspaper in manila said last week that dulay was contacted by u.s. authorities who traveled there seeking his cooperation in an investigation of alleged arms shipments to pro-marcos groups
assistant u.s. attorney john peyton in honolulu on monday confirmed that he met with dulay last week, but said he could not comment further because of an ``ongoing criminal investigation.''
raul rabe, deputy chief of mission at the philippines embassy in washington, said dulay joined marcos in honolulu before being deported to the philippines, where he faced charges in the 1986 slayings of three presidential campaign workers for mrs. aquino
marcos has been living in exile in honolulu since his 1986 ouster. he has said he wishes to return to his homeland
last year, two u.s. businessmen testified before a house subcommittee that marcos had sought to buy weapons for shipment to the philippines in june, four months after dicker's arrest. they played for the panel secretly taped conversations with marcos
it could not be determined if the alleged coup attempt, the dicker case and the honolulu investigation were directly related
neither u.s. attorney samuel a. alito jr. nor richard mercier, head of customs' newark office, would comment on the case. leonard s. walton, customs director of illegal export investigations in washington, also would not comment
on monday, marcos issued a statement denying he wanted to resume power ``through violent means.''
steele did not return repeated phone messages left this week and last at his commonwealth group ltd., a company in new york city. major u.s. pipeline interrupted. picks up 6th graf pvs, washington has ... with minor editing</note>
soldiers tried to overthrow gen. manuel antonio noriega on wednesday but they were overpowered, and thousands of people poured into the streets in the largest protest yet of his continued rule
many workers are broke in a country that uses u.s. dollars as its currency but has almost none of them. street corners in poor neighborhoods were dotted with burning barricades wednesday
the nation's defense forces said the coup attempt apparently was led by col. leonidas macias, head of the national police. he was arrested along with three majors, a captain and some civilians, the communique said
maj. edgardo lopez, head of the military press office, said ``no more than eight or nine'' officers were involved in the revolt. he said there were no casualties but did not say what happened to officers not listed among those arrested
it was the first sign of trouble within noriega's defense forces, which had kept a solid front through nine months of civil unrest caused by accusations that noriega was involved in crimes ranging from drug trafficking to political assassination. he was indicted on drug charges in florida
the panama canal commision, which supervises operation of the 50-mile waterway between the atlantic and pacific oceans, said dockworkers' strikes and an electricity shutoff had not impeded ship passage. the canal has its own electrical generating capacity
but operations stopped on the trans-panama pipeline, which carries about 650,000 barrels of alaskan crude oil a day across the isthmus for delivery to gulf of mexico and east coast markets. the pipeline relies on local power and the u.s. embassy in panama city said the line lacked electricity to drive the pumps
bp america inc. and its subsidiary sohio oil own up to three-quarters of the oil that flows through the line and exxon co. usa owns the rest, comprising about 10 percent of total u.s. production
washington has put pressure on noriega, and president reagan said tuesday the united states wants him ``out of there.'' sanctions such as freezing panamanian accounts in u.s. banks and withholding panama canal fees created a cash shortage that makes it impossible to pay the 130,000 public employees
flaming barricades blocked hundreds of streets on the third day of the latest public protest. by midafternoon, police and military units began reappearing in the city
many protesters identified themselves as ``civilistas'' _ members of the national civic crusade, a coalition of about 200 business, professional, labor, student and opposition groups
the crusade was formed last june to lead the campaign to oust noriega as chief of the defense forces, which include the military and police
by midafternoon, the demonstrators were dispersed, buses and taxis stopped running and the city was virtually deserted, with most shops closed. widespread looting broke out downtown, mostly by youths
reporters said men in civilian clothes fired pistols and rifles at demonstrators from four-wheel-drive vehicles. opponents have accused the government of using hired thugs or plainclothes security agents to break up protests
electricity went out in most of the country after workers at the state power company joined the protests at midday. local telephone service was sporadic
protesters chanted ``noriega must go!'' and ``noreiga, tyrant, your end is near!''
residents near the defense forces headquarters heard the clatter of light arms fire inside the walled compound beginning at about 8:15 a.m. it continued for at least half an hour
an hour after the shooting stopped, noriega appeared on the stairs on one side of the building, dressed in civilian clothes and accompanied by members of his high command
they were kisses,'' he said when asked about the shooting
to questions from reporters about what had happened, he replied: ``what happened is that you are visiting us here.''
a communique by the defense forces said ``an attempt by several officers to take over the headquarters of our institution was foiled. the attempt was an isolated action that was repressed by the officers, non-commissioned officers and soldiers of the institution.''
among those arrested, the communique said, were macias; majs. fernando quezada, aristedes valdonedo and jaime benitez and capt. humberto macias
the statement said ``most of the officers involved in this attempt were returned recently to the country after taking specialized courses in different military installations of the united states, where they were influenced and compromised into betraying the oath they had given to the defense forces and the fatherland
troops loyal to the commander in in chief, in a quick action, repressed and controlled the situation, thus avoiding bloodshed.''
earlier, soldiers stopped associated press reporters eloy o. aguilar and pauline jelinek and photographer diana smith as they drove up to the heavily guarded headquarters, forced them from the car at gunpoint and marched them into the compound
they saw guards lead an officer with his hands behind his head into a barracks
a captain told the journalists, who were later released, that the man was taking part ``in a simulated exercise'' of taking prisoners
the captain would not identify himself
hundreds of soldiers surrounded the headquarters in one of the older, poorer sections of panama city. residents were kept away
the u.s. southern command put its 10,000 military personnel and their dependents on the highest security alert, ordering americans ``not to go into public areas except for essential business.''
officials of the canal commission said in washinton that roads to the canal were blocked and the panamanian military closed the entrance to a u.s. air base near the canal administrative headquarters in balboa
dennis p. mcauliffe, administrator of the commission, said he ``would not regard (the blockade) as a hostile act at this moment.''
about 6,000 nicaraguan soldiers used helicopters and heavy artillery in a major offensive against contra rebel forces, but the government denied reports that its troops had crossed the border into honduras
honduran officials also denied contra claims that sandinista troops fighting in northern nicaragua on tuesday had entered honduran territory
heavy fighting was reported throughout nicaragua's 5th military region, which includes the provinces of boaco, chontales, rio san juan and zelaya south. the contras said sandinista troops had overrun some rebel positions
