perhaps he couldn't perform because he had too many tequilas and beers,'' assistant district attorney linda fairstein said of 21-year-old robert chambers
whatever the exact words were, only two human beings know what triggered the fight. it was an argument that escalated and became physical,'' she said
three decades after the irish government evacuated his weeping father and the few other people who remained on the tiny blasket islands, mike carney says the exiles are flourishing in their landlocked new home
there's more of us here than in ireland,'' said the happy emigrant from the harsh life that ended abruptly in 1955 with the closing of the islands off the western tip of the dingle peninsula
carney, 67, is among the last surviving natives of the five-mile-long main island that preserved 18th-century language and customs into the middle of the 20th century, when the government deemed the land too dangerous to inhabit
a 94-year-old man's offer of $10,000 to anyone who can end his 65 years of hiccuping has drawn some exotic nostrums _ dill seed, magnesium phosphate, holy water, indian hemp, among them _ but the man hiccups on
unbelievable,'' lucretia peterson of rural aitkin said as she sifted through some of the more than 5,000 letters, cassettes, and parcels that have poured into her home from europe and north america since her father, charlie osborne, offered the reward in january
people really care. even though the $10,000 is a big deal to some of them, a lot say keep the money and spend it in good health. it's unbelievable for that many people to write in this day and age,'' she said
munusamy gunasekaran sleeps on the job, but his boss doesn't mind
gunasekaran is one of 34 volunteers hired by the health department to act as ``human bait'' to attract and catch mosquitoes as part of a program that helps keep this city of 1 million people free of malaria
the volunteers are paid between $120 and $160 a month to sleep in small huts on a bed surrounded by mosquito netting
the mosquitoes are attracted by the scent of the men inside the hut and the light from small hurricane lamps hanging by the doors, said muthuthamby balakrishnan, a senior assistant in the city's public health department
jan kinast left his post at the polish embassy in washington 20 years ago little dreaming he would return this winter trying to mend relations shattered by martial law and a foreign debt that is still rising
i keep pretty busy,'' says kinast, a junior diplomat at the polish embassy in washington 1964-68 and poland's first ambassador to the united states since the military crackdown against the independent solidarity trade union in december 1981. kinast's predecessor, romuald spasowski, defected to protest martial law
so far, kinast is having better luck winning friends for poland among america's officials than its businessmen and bankers
we are delighted with ambassador kinast,'' said deputy secretary of state john whitehead, who has traveled twice to poland since martial law was lifted in 1983. whitehead, in a telephone interview, described kinast's immediate previous post, deputy foreign minister, as analagous to his own job as no. 2 in the state department
kinast, like many poles, is a chain smoker, and nicotine stains the thick glasses through which he pores over reams of finanicial statistics
poland's foreign debt, which was $25.5 billion in 1981, rose to $39. billion by dec. 31, 1987, driven higher by the collapsing dollar and a lack of quality exports
the reagan administration has lifted the freeze it imposed on new credits to poland during martial law, but poland is still such a bad risk that western bankers balk at offering any new loans
john davis jr., who just became the first u.s. ambassador to poland since 1982, said in a televised interview last week that polish authorities appeared genuinely interested in economic reforms
if economic reform is in place, and we see that it is in place, it may be that there are some opportunities for joint ventures, or other means of being helpful,'' said davis
poland took one step toward better relations with the united states by closing down a business enterprise affiliated with the abu nidal terrorist organization last fall and ordering the two men in charge to leave poland in january. u.s. anti-terrorism experts say they are watching the situation carefully
and u.s. officials say more american help might be forthcoming if polish leader gen. wojciech jaruzelski reached political accommodation with solidarity and poland's roman catholic church
i think that u.s. help would follow liberalization,'' davis said in an interview broadcast from warsaw by abc-tv
the billions of dollars poland received in credit in the 1970's, davis said, ``went down the drain through a combination of bad luck and bad management,'' creating the economic crisis that spawned solidarity in august 1980
but kinast said in a recent interview in his washington office that poland is looking not for new long-term credits but for short-term commercial credits to facilitate transactions
ninety-five percent of our (foreign) purchases are cash,'' he said. ``no other country in the world is buying machines and durable goods for cash.''
a polish trade delegation which visited washington feb. 14 for the 10th session of the joint american-polish trade commission _ the first such meeting since 1981 _ went home with friendly words instead of dollars
one deal under discussion is the purchase or rental by poland's state-owned lot airlines of two or three jets from boeing corp. the planes would fly between u.s. cities and warsaw, and money from tickets sold in the united states would pay for the planes, say polish officials
there are geopolitical overtones in poland's latest turn toward the west. lot grounded its fleet of eight soviet-made ilyushin 62 jets, the best moscow has to offer, after one crashed last may near warsaw, killing all 183 people aboard
a government commission blamed a faulty roller bearing for the crash, poland's worst, and the weekly przeglad tygodniowy recently complained that the il-62 is more costly to operate, and requires more maintenance, than other jetliners
kinast said that poland, like other soviet bloc countries, is seeking joint ventures with the west, and may be willing to waive previous requirements, allowing private polish firms to take part, allowing the western firm to own more than half the joint venture, and relaxing rules and taking hard currency out of poland
poland is seeking western help in the agricultural sector, as well. on feb. 20, the the foundation for the development of polish agriculture, created with the help of the rockefeller brothers' fund, was opening up a $2.4 million-line of credit for private farmers in poland to stimulate the export of hams
two weeks after he became pastor of a southern baptist church in west-central illinois, the rev. gerald price said he knew the congregation might end up firing him
it did
getting along with a congregation is a common challenge for clergy, particularly in the baptist system
the congregation which ousted price, he found later, had fired five previous staff members. it was plagued with financial problems and had split over the issue of speaking in tongues
price, who now is minister of education at park avenue baptist church here, said being fired devastated him and his family. but he said he found comfort in scripture and help from friends and family in relocating
the southern baptist convention, in which churches have local autonomy and can simply fire a pastor, has concluded the problem is severe enough to set up a special program to help fired pastors
other denominations have found that maintaining good relations between the pastor and congregation, as well as among members, often takes some effort. but in most denominations, a pastor can't simply be fired by the congregation
the southern baptist sunday school board research department discovered in 1984 that 88 ministers were fired by their churches each month, said norris smith, who coordinates a program to help fired ministers
we found that pastors who had been terminated had great need, both for a job and emotional support,'' smith said. ``being terminated does not change that pastor's internal spiritual awareness that god has called him into the ministry.''
previously, he said, there was no clear place for pastors to turn for financial or emotional help
smith tries to make sure they receive counseling if they need it, and seeks to put them in touch with others who can help in finding another job, if it appears they were unjustly fired. state conventions have funds to help with financial needs
smith works with churches such as highview baptist in louisville, ky., and first baptist church of orlando, fla., which have established temporary paid staff positions to help terminated ministers rebuild their careers
in the methodist, episcopal, roman catholic and lutheran churches, severe problems between a pastor and church are referred to the bishop or someone else within the church hierarchy. those churches have structures to investigate problems and work to remedy them
in the united methodist church, problems can be referred to a pastor-parish relations committee, or the bishop. a methodist pastor can be transferred, or suspended, if convicted in a church trial of some serious offense, such as immorality
in the episcopal church, pastors can be removed only through joint action of the parish governing body, the vestry, and diocesan bishop
the rev. patrick connor, vicar general of the nashville catholic diocese, said problems between priest and congregation would go to a parish-pastoral council and then the bishop, but a parish by itself can't fire a priest
the lutheran church-missouri synod has a full-time consultant on a ``peace in the parish'' program, aimed at improving relations between pastors and congregations and among members
the rev. norman grotelusuhen, president of the denomination's mid-south district, said a congregation can fire a pastor for particular causes, but he would investigate
if you can get in early enough, you usually can defuse it; if you come in late, it will more likely lead to a termination,'' he said
sometimes it's the pastor's fault, sometimes the church,'' he said. problems can arise over the pastor not spending enough time visiting the sick and bereaved, or having difficulty administering congregational affairs
the rev. james qualben, a lutheran, has for three years conducted sessions on such problems with church officials and ministers from lutheran, episcopal and methodist churches
he said that when he is asked to help resolve a problem in a congregation, he starts by reviewing its value system, and how past difficulties may come back as old angers and old hurts operating within the congregation
i went to one church that had split over slavery in 1872,'' he said. ``the descendants of the slavery congregation still sit on one side of the church, while the descendants of the non-slavery congregation still sit on the other side.''
qualben said he tries to help the church get a longer range perspective for making wise decisions and coping with the past without hoarding hurts
but eliminating all conflict doesn't square with human nature, he said. ``if the absence of conflict is the mark of a successful church then the disciples never qualified.''
but he said conciliating efforts often bring ``new life, new vitality of mutual ministry in the church.''
an official team of lutheran and roman catholic scholars says it is working toward agreements on the role of mary and the saints in christian faith
a key issue of the protestant reformation was roman catholic belief in prayers ``invoking the intercession'' of mary and the saints. protestants contended this obscured the primacy of christ as mediator for humanity
at a meeting here, members of the lutheran-catholic dialogue team said they expected to publish their conclusions in 1989. the team previously agreed that mary was a model of faith, devotion and spirituality
the assemblies of god reports that its number of congregations rose last year from 10,886 to 11,004, up 118
earth day'' comes this sunday _ at the spring equinox _ with an appeal for ringing of church bells at noon, and for people to pause for two minutes to pray for peace
lutheran john mcconnell of brooklyn, promoter of the day dedicated to peaceful care of the planet, says participation has been increasing since the annual observance began in 1970
the new international version of the bible, on its 10th birthday, has more than a million copies in print, reports its publisher, zondervan publishers
the version was produced by conservative scholars
company official bruce e. ryskamp cites sale figures indicating that nearly a third of new bibles sold are the niv version, putting it near the best-selling spot. he says,``this is an amazing feat in merely 10 years.''
the u.s. department of defense is distributing a 96-page booklet titled ``days of remembrance'' to assist members of the armed forces in organizing education programs and ceremonies in remembrance of the nazi slaughter of 6 million jews during world war ii
special observances are to take place april 10-17. the booklet was produced with assistance of the international center for holocaust studies of the anti-defamation league of b'nai b'rith
the church of the brethren has urged the u.s. congress to make further foreign aid to israel conditional on ending of its occupation of the west bank, gaza and the golan heights
we are outraged by the regular and sustained killing and injuring of unarmed palestinians who live under military occupation,'' the 165,000-member denomination's general board said in a resolution
southern baptists want to send their missionaries back to lebanon, but the u.s. state department says it's still too unsafe
that word was received here by the denomination's foreign mission board, which had ask that its 24 missionaries, forced to leave lebanon last year because of risky conditions, be allowed to return
the rev. keith parks, head of the mission board, expressed disappointment at the new ruling. he said that in other equally dangerous places of the world, the state department has not banned u.s. citizens
he said ``we long for the time'' when the missionaries can ``re-establish a presence and a ministry in lebanon.''  
when three whooping cranes flew out of a tidal marsh, sounds of awe mixed with the clicking of cameras on the deck of the lucky day
the three birds made up nearly 2 percent of the entire population of their kind
flying whooping cranes at 9 o'clock,'' capt. harry sloat told the 80 passengers, his second tour group of the day on the gulf intracoastal waterway. ``they're showing off their wing tips for you.''
each year, it gets a little easier to spot the birds at the aransas national wildlife refuge, which is celebrating its 50th aniversary
there are about 195 whoopers in the world today; in 1941, the population had dwindled to 15. the decline came as habitats were developed for farms and cities, while hunters helped to nearly finish off the species
whooping cranes made aransas famous, but when congress created the coastal preserve in 1937, the legislation did not mention the bird known scientifically as grus americana
this refuge was not established to protect whooping cranes,'' said refuge biologist tom stehn. ``it was established to protect waterfowl habitat.''
the government saw the need to protect less spectacular game birds, such as ducks and geese. whooping cranes just happened to be lucky enough to share the same area during the winter
their precarious situation by 1945 prompted the u.s. fish and wildlife service and national audubon society to work on rescuing the birds from extinction
without the aransas refuge, i think it's pretty evident the whooping crane would have become extinct,'' stehn said, while observing an unusual gathering of 14 whoopers in the same field
he called it ``just phenomenal to be able to see that many whooping cranes from one location, to think that at one point there were only 15 in the entire flock.''
scientists don't think the whooping crane population ever exceeded 5,000, he said
only about 8,000 acres on the refuge provide the marshy winter habitat whooping cranes use to look for food including plants, clams, snakes, crabs, snails, fish, worms and insects
several other endangered species make the refuge their home. they include the bald eagle, brown pelican, peregrine falcon, attwater's prairie chicken, jaguarundi and eskimo curlew
the texas whooping crane flock numbers 132 this year, a 79 percent increase in four years. virtually all are on or near the 54,829-acre refuge
they migrate each winter to texas from canada's wood buffalo national park 2,400 miles away
eighteen to 20 whoopers live among sandhill cranes that migrate between gray's lake national wildlife refuge in idaho and new mexico's bosque del apache national wildlife refuge. they were introduced as chicks into the sandhill families, but none have started breeding
a third group of 41 lives in captivity at the fish and wildlife service's patuxent wildlife research center in maryland. lone specimens of whooping crane also live at the san antonio zoo and the international crane foundation in baraboo, wis
with their population steadily growing, the texas whoopers have started spreading to a 44,000-acre state park and refuge on nearby matagorda island. the u.s. fish and wildlife service is buying an additional 11,502 acres at the southern end of matagorda from the nature conservancy. that will add important new habitat as the territorial whooping cranes spread out
we're really encouraged by the land that they're adding'' because wildlife is rapidly losing ground, said jesse grantham, biologist and manager for the national audubon society's texas sanctuaries. ``we're not creating habitat. we're just saving little pieces of what's left.''
whooper pairs, mated for life, stake out winter territories and return to the same claims each year
the birds stand nearly 5 feet tall and have wings spanning about 7{ feet. adults are snowy white, with black wingtips and red crowns on their heads. immature whooping cranes are rusty red and white with black wing tips. males breed at about the age 3, while females wait until they're about 5
in rockport, where sloat's lucky day and four other whooping crane tour boats are based, the endangered bird means money for the local economy
just a couple of years ago, only two whooping crane boats were operating
you have people that are staying in motels and eating and seeing other things while they are here'' to see the whooping cranes, said bob lynch, executive vice president of the rockport-fulton chamber of commerce. ``it has an economic impact on our community, there's no doubt.''
some estimate the refuge brings up to $5 million to the local economy
refuge officials, however, worry about its location on the gulf intracoastal waterway, a man-made channel that cuts right through the whooping crane habitat
some 1,485 acres of habitat have been lost since 1941 due to construction of the canal and erosion caused by boat wakes
regular barge traffic leaves oil, grease, cadmium, arsenic, nickel and mercury, while many of the barges carry deadly cargo
there is some nasty stuff going through that canal,'' said refuge manager brent giezentanner. ``you're carrying very toxic chemicals within 100 yards of the cranes. if we have one barge break open some time, we potentially could have a major portion of the whooping crane habitat contaminated.''
remember 20 years ago? black-and-white television, the vietnam war, the assassinations of martin luther king jr. and robert kennedy, campus unrest, sexual revolution, hippies, flower children?
other events shook the earth, too. growing up, for instance
in abc's ``the wonder years,'' kevin arnold is 12 years old in 1968. he has to be careful of the neighborhood bully, namely his older brother. his father is a distant figure who shows up now and then to straighten him out. the offstage narrator is kevin as a grownup, looking back and remembering. of course, remembering it in his own fashion
the wonder years,'' simply put, is wonderful. every adult out there who has ever grown up will identify with this awkward age
fred savage stars as kevin, jason hervey is his older brother, wayne, and olivia d'abo is his sister, karen. the midseason replacement series being given a limited trial by abc has been given a tuesday night spot between ``who's the boss'' and ``moonlighting.''
1968 was a year when a lot of amazing things took place,'' said carol black, creator and executive producer with her husband, neal marlens. marlens also created abc's ``growing pains.''
we were about that age that year. there were a lot of really disruptive events in the background of a kid's life.''
marlens said, ``it's different when you're 12. you know things are happening, but you're not quite sure about them. it struck us as an interesting time. there were already retrospectives about people who were a little older, like `the big chill.'''
when you're young you don't have a context in which to place things,'' black added. `it's just part of the world. it's a time when you get your first impression of life.''
it's also a time when a self-conscious 12-year-old is more interested in figuring out how he fits in. you can put it into context later. at 12 you just want to blend in
black admits ``the wonder years'' is not really about the 1960s. `it's the problems a kid has with his older brother, his father, his girlfriend,'' she said. ``the period is more of a backdrop than the essence of the show.''
black and marlens share common backgrounds. both were raised in the suburbs, he outside new york city and she outside washington, d.c. both had older brothers. they met while students at swarthmore college in pennsylvania
they started writing together about 6 years ago. he was working as a newspaper reporter in massachusetts and she was a graduate student
we wrote a spec script for `barney miller,' which had just gone off the air,'' said marlens. ``we felt it was better to write for a show that wasn't on the air. it got good response.''
marlens wrote for ``oh madeline'' and ``newhart.'' then he created ``growing pains'' while black wrote the movie ``soul man.'' actually, they worked together on both projects, but thought it best to separate the credit
they also stress that ``the wonder years'' is not autobiographical
i was never a 12-year-old boy,'' said black. ``and neal was never this particular 12-year-old boy.''
we make up the specifics,'' said marlens, ``but we do use incidents from our lives and those of our friends. it's the story of a family, but it's seen from the viewpoint of the boy
we didn't set out to do anything deep. `leave it to beaver' in its day was well thought out. but i think audiences today want to be challenged by something more substantial. we grew up in a controversial period and we're more prone to writing that way. but there are some things about growing up that never change. things that happened to the cleavers could happen to the arnolds, too.''
elsewhere in television:
hope acts _ bob hope makes a rare appearance on an episodic television show when he plays an angel dispatcher in nbc's ``highway to heaven'' on wednesday, march 30. he mistakenly reincarnates a man to disrupt his son's marriage and calls on jonathan (michael landon) to straighten it out. his character is called syncopomp. john pleshette and bill macy also guest star in the show. ..
lonesome dove _ robert duvall, tommy lee jones and anjelica houston will star in `lonesome dove,'' the eight-hour cbs miniseries based on the pulitzer prize-winning novel by larry mcmurtry. it tells of an epic cattle drive and the lives it changed. simon wincer will direct from a screenplay by bill witliff
as they file their tax returns this year, many savers and investors are making a decision by omission _ skipping any contribution for 1987 to their individual retirement accounts
a recent study commissioned by fidelity investments found that less than half the respondents with iras from previous years planned to add any money to them this time around
their reasoning isn't hard to understand. the tax deduction for contributions has been eliminated for anybody covered by an employer's retirement plan who has income of $35,000 or more ($50,000 for married couples filing joint returns)
in the $25,000-$35,000 income range ($40,000 to $50,000 for married couples), only part of the contribution is deductible
all working americans are still eligible to put up to $2,000 each year in an ira, whether they can claim the deduction or not. the interest, dividends or capital gains their money earns can still compound without being taxed until withdrawals from the account begin
however, money invested in an ira _ including non-deductible contributions _ can't be withdrawn before the year in which you reach age 59{ without incurring a penalty tax
why tie the money up, people seem to be concluding, if the incentive of the up-front deduction no longer exists? besides, the new rules have taken the simplicity of the old system and replaced it with a lot of paperwork hassles
what's the point of spending extra time or professional preparers' fees on a venture whose after-tax value is less than it was before?
these are sensible questions, to be sure. but some advisers suggest that many people who are no longer eligible for ira deductions give the matter some extra consideration
after all, they say, no matter what happens with the tax law, the need to save and plan for retirement hasn't changed
the discipline of automatic, annual contributions is especially useful to people who spend instead of save,'' says wallace head, tax partner at the accounting firm of arthur andersen &amp; co
they need only ask themselves if they can afford to invest cash for many years. if the answer is yes, iras should be considered an effective investment.''
for anyone who does make non-deductible contributions, good record-keeping is a must to avoid paying taxes on that money twice _ now, and again when you make withdrawals from the account
the internal revenue service requires that any non-deductible contributions be reported on the new form 8606, which the taxpayer attaches to his or her return for the year in question
you will probably want to save a file of extra copies of form 8606s for 1987 and subsequent years, or start a notebook, to serve as documentation for when you start taking money out of your ira
although this paperwork may be burdensome, it can make a big difference in the taxes you will have to pay in the future
suppose at some point around the year 2000 you have accumulated $100,000 in an ira, of which $25,000 came from non-deductible contributions, and you want to withdraw $20,000 from the account
since 25 percent of the total value of your ira is money that has already been taxed, having the proper records will enable you to establish that you owe taxes on only $15,000 of the distribution, rather than the full $20,000
americans are accustomed to hearing federal reserve chiefs discourse on the threat of inflation, but some might have been mystified by alan greenspan's reference to it this week
greenspan told congress that a further decline in the jobless rate, now 5.7 percent, might produce upward pressure on wages _ and, since wages are a large constituent of prices, the probability of inflation
how can that be, many americans are asking?
how can there be a worker shortage when 7 million members of the labor force are without jobs? how can there be a labor shortage when the jobless rate is so much above the old 4 percent ``full employment'' standard?
and how can inflation, which is usually associated with a boiling economy, be a threat at a time when expansion is so sluggish at times it takes the most sophisticated statistical measures to catch any movement at all?
greenspan's reference to the subject is bound to be passed off by some as a mere requirement of the office, a ritual expression that is now expected of a fed chairman, since his predecessor had made it the no. 1 enemy
but there is more to it than that
the most significant ``more'' involves a better understanding of market forces than existed back in the 1960s, when it was generally believed that unemployment could drop to 4 percent before inflation flared
experience taught otherwise, as witness the decade of inflation that followed in the 1970s
the second ``more'' involves the makeup of the labor force
in the 1960s, the economy had lots of younger workers to fill the beginning jobs. in the 1980s there are fewer labor-force entrants. and congress is considering sharp increases in the minimum wage
stated differently, most of those who are available to take jobs today are older and more experienced and thus come at higher prices. you don't need a decline to 4 percent before worrying about inflation. you worry at 5 percent
in truth, there is no certainty among economists on the point at which a falling jobless rate becomes inflationary. clearly, they were wrong in putting it at 4 percent in the 1960s, because double-digit inflation ensued
it can be argued, therefore, that it is merely wisdom and responsibility that causes a fed chief always to be vigilant, and for him to act on the theory it is wiser to ward off inflation than to treat the infection later
greenspan told congress that in his opinion the country is getting close to the point at which inflation could be ignited
certainly it's less than a percentage point,'' he said, adding that it was his impression that the flare point was ``closer to a half, and maybe somewhat less than that.''
is he premature in his concern?
hardly, if you consider that the last big bout of inflation was one of the worst and longest the country has ever experienced, and that it took a harsh recession to defeat it
consider also that a case of inflation in the range of 6 percent _ mild, when compared with the double-digit disasters of the 1970s _ can cut in half the value of everyone's money in a dozen years
the destruction of millions of acres of tropical jungles each year by peasant farmers and others is a problem for the developed nations as well as the third world and requires economic and educational solutions, say scientists at a leading plant research institution
the missouri botanical garden, known for its man-made tropical atmosphere in the so-called ``climatron'' designed by buckminster fuller, is working to halt the decimation of the world's real tropical jungles
the outlook is pretty grim,'' said biologist peter h. raven, director of the garden. ``although tropical forests once covered at least 12 percent of the globe _ an area about twice the size of europe _ they have already been reduced to about half that.''
currently, the forests are being cleared or degraded at the rate of about 60 million acres a year. that's an area about half the size of california.''
raven said roughly half of all known plant and animal species on earth are found in the tropical forests. at the current rate of destruction, as many as 60,000 species of plants will be extinct by the year 2020
the plant-rich tropics supply man with a wealth of food crops, medicines and other useful products,'' said dr. enrique forero, director of research at the garden. ``but they are being destroyed rapidly.''
the chief culprits, forero said, are loggers and slash-and-burn peasant farmers. the loggers obviously need the trees to stay in business and the farmers often have to destroy the forests to feed themselves and their families
and the scientists say the situation can only get worse unless something is done to stop it
at present, over half the people in the world live in countries that are at least partly tropical, excluding china,'' forero said. ``nearly a third of these people are already living in extreme poverty and with current rates of growth, the human population of these countries will double in less than 30 years.''
how can you tell these starving people that you are going to save the very things they have to destroy in order to sustain their already meager existence,'' asked raven. ``education and political and economic stability are obviously the keys. that and understanding.''
which is why, raven said, the garden has committed itself to an all-out effort to explore, document and save the forests
with a staff of 70 researchers and technicians, including many who live permanently in the tropics, the garden makes up one of the world's largest active field research programs in tropical botany
the goals, the scientists said, are to collect the plant species before they become extinct and to teach the impoverished farmers how to live in the forest without destroying it
with the growing knowledge of genetics, they said, it is important that the genes, the biological blueprints, of the endangered species be saved
to lose this genetic capital through massive extinctions just as we are developing our capabilities to explore its potential would indeed be a tragedy,'' raven said. ``the developments in genetics make the specter of extinction even worse,'' raven said. ``for each species of plant or animal lost to extinction, you're losing the potential for another 20,000 to 30,000 variants in the future.''
many of the plants, scientists say, could almost certainly be developed into cheaper, easy-to-grow sources of highly nutritious food. others could be converted into abundant sources of new medicines
another important part of the garden's program is to lend technical assistance to and train scientists from developing tropical countries through cooperative agreements
unfortunately, only 6 percent of the scientists working on the problem live in the countries involved,'' raven said. ``we must change that. momentum to implement the innovative conservation and development strategies needed to deal with these urgent problems ultimately must come from the affected countries themselves,'' raven said
the backbone of the garden's research, the scientists said, is its herbarium, or plant collection. along with the new york botanical garden and the smithsonian institution, the missouri herbarium is one of the three largest in the united states and among the 12 largest in the world
started by garden founder henry shaw in the 1850s, the missouri herbarium now contains samples of more than 3.5 million species and is expected to expand to 4.5 million within the next decade
pointing to a large map showing the locations of the garden's researchers in central and south america and africa, raven said of the encroachment on the forests: ``it won't be stopped soon
but there are encouraging signs. what people have to learn is that conservation and development are really two sides of the same coin.''
producers and consumers have to learn that they have a common problem. it can all be done, but it won't be easy.''
twenty years after a sniper's bullet felled martin luther king jr., his dream of equality and prosperity for american blacks still shines like a beacon. despite some remarkable progress, however, for too many it remains only a dream. the first story of three in a series that assesses black progress in economics, politics and social influence looks at a poor west side chicago neighborhood where king lived in 1966 to wage war on slums and poverty
this is truly an island of poverty in the midst of an ocean of plenty.''
_ martin luther king jr. in his 1967 book, ``where do we go from here: chaos or community?''
bonnet hampton knows what it's like to huddle in bed with a baseball bat at hand, wondering how to protect her babies from rats scurrying across the rotting wooden floor of her tenement flat
she knows how to sidestep young men strung out on drugs huddled in dingy hallways, and she's no longer shocked by dead bodies _ even at her doorstep
you don't get used to it,'' she said, ``but it's not a nightmare. if you see someone get shot or stabbed today _ usually you'd be nervous for days. it's not like that. ... it's just another one. you don't lose any rest over that.''
hampton lives in north lawndale. a generation ago, martin luther king jr. lived here in a four-room flat. king had come north to wage war on poverty and inequality, but 20 years after his death, the slums and disparity remain. so do dreams of a better life
this poor black community he adopted has become even poorer _ and that, say those who knew him, would grieve king if he were alive today
if king were to look at lawndale ... he'd think that his worst nightmare had come true,'' said gary orfield, a university of chicago political science professor who did volunteer work with king
some residents reluctantly agree
i think he was great enough to know and powerful enough to know his dream is not being fulfilled,'' said cleodia dawkins o'quinn, who welcomed king to her home. ``he would know we have stepped backward.''
black poverty is a bleak fact of life. nearly one in three blacks _ 31.1 percent _ lived below the poverty line in 1986, compared with 11 percent of whites, according to federal statistics
and 20 years after the kerner commission examined inner-city problems following the mid '60s riots and warned the united states was moving toward two societies, ``one black, one white _ separate and unequal,'' the gap remains
life for inner-city blacks has worsened, scholars said in a follow-up study this year, partly because of industrial decline. over 35 years, rust belt cities have lost almost half their manufacturing force, according to a report by the university of chicago's william julius wilson and loic wacquant
chicago, the report said, lost half its manufacturing blue-collar workers from 1967-82. and that's taken its toll on north lawndale. the neighborhood's misery index is high. according to federal, city and state records:
_ four of ten people lived in poverty in 1980, an increase of a third over a decade earlier
_ more than a third of the housing is uninhabitable or so deteriorated it's beyond rehabilitation
_ eight of 10 children are born out of wedlock. the 1986 infant mortality rate, 27.2 per 1,000 live births, was more than 2{ times the u.s. average
_ women headed 61 percent of the households in 1980
_ one in five people was out of work in 1980. unemployment, some activists say, may now be as high as 30 percent
much of north lawndale has simply vanished. since 1960, more than half the residents, thousands of jobs and most industries have fled. gangs are more vicious, drugs more common
still, optimists remain, proud, hard-working folks fighting to turn things around. ``we have been at the lowest of low,'' said jesse miller, head of the lawndale peoples planning and action conference, an activist group. ``the citizens of this community are facing up to the problems.''
but reversing those fortunes is a formidable task. north lawndale has block after block of weed-filled lots, gutted buildings and men in their prime who while away their days loitering on street corners or huddled around fires in garbage cans
you can't envision how it looked before,'' mrs. o'quinn said, shaking her head sadly. ``it's a wilderness now.''
once a largely jewish community with gray stone houses, stores, factories and banks, north lawndale turned from white to mostly black in the 1950s. absentee landlords and political neglect had contributed to its decline by 1966 when king moved into a $90-a-month, third-floor flat, with inadequate heat and halls reeking of urine
you can't really get close to the poor without living and being here with them,'' he said. king lived in the building, since torn down, on and off for several months that year
king tried to fight slumlords, build tenant unions, end discrimination. he led open-housing marches in all-white neighborhoods and tried to be peacemaker when riots flared in the summer of 1966
king, folks say, brought hope to north lawndale. his assassination brought destruction. riots that tore apart u.s. cities after king's death in 1968 unleashed a storm of rage here as well _ the skies were ablaze, the streets filled with looters, blocks of businesses turned to rubble, houses to ashes and dreams to despair
the riots killed or ... almost mortally wounded the hope of the community,'' said primus mootry, executive vice president of the local better boys foundation
there was no marshall plan for this war-torn community. it was as if someone decided to let them sit there in the mess that they made and let them stew,'' he said. ``the consequences have been devastating. the community has been damned from the outside.''
today, north lawndale has 61,000 residents, less than half the population of almost 125,000 in 1965. much of the middle-class has fled
if i had somewhere to go, i would have run, too,'' said 33-year resident mildred hunter
tens of thousands of jobs also disappeared. seventy-five percent of businesses were lost from 1960 to 1970. international harvester co. (now navistar) closed a plant. sears roebuck &amp; co. later moved its world headquarters out of north lawndale, keeping only a distribution and planning center
the main shopping strip, roosevelt road, remains a burned-out shell. a proposal by a national organization of planners, builders, bankers and others to build a $9.5 million shopping mall has been postponed
after 25 years of ``uninterrupted decline, north lawndale resembles a war zone,'' wilson and wacquant said in their study
today, the neighborhood has some food and liquor stores. to buy anything else, ``you have to go an area you're not wanted to spend your money,'' said isabelle burrell. ``it's insulting.''
shopping, however, seems like a minor problem against the drug dealing, gangs and violence
hampton, for example, a 30-year-old with three teen-agers and a baby, has survived four apartments and 14 years of horror stories: she's fended off giant rats slurping out of her toilet, been forced out by an arsonist, witnessed a robbery, faced drug users shooting up in the hallway and seen murder victims, including a decapitated man
i've seen a lot of disaster,'' she said, adding that she carries a knife by day, a gun at night. ``we have a lot of lunatics out here.''
hampton talks about returning to her native mississippi. in the meantime, she attends church with her children, visits their schools and preaches against drugs
they understand it,'' she said. ``they have seen it.''
others have, too. residents can rattle off the corners where drugs are sold like newspapers, customers pulling up in cars day and night
the only game left is the drug game,'' said leon farley, an unemployed counselor. ``to survive, to eat, to pay the rent. we don't have a lot of jobs.''
drug trafficking wasn't always a problem, and the gangs of decades past directed their violence at each other
they didn't bother those of us doing good things,'' said mrs. o'quinn, who with her husband runs a drum and bugle corps for youths. `the gangs don't respect anything now.''
mootry confirmed gangs are more lethal: zip guns, knives and chains have been replaced by uzi submachine guns and other sophisticated weapons
yet the biggest problem, he said, may be a perception among youths that north lawndale is ``an island ... a walled city (where) nothing comes in and nothing comes out. that is the way in which they are socialized. that's a great tragedy.''
mootry's organization tries to broaden horizons, offering recreational and education programs, including scholarships that have sent teens to harvard and the university of chicago. block clubs, slum-busting projects and infant health programs also have been started
because people live in the ghetto, you don't got to be dealing in dope, be a prostitute or on public aid,'' said hunter, the long-time north lawndale resident. ``you can live anywhere and be what you want to be.''
some businesses have stayed afloat, too. the community bank of lawndale, which opened in 1977 with $2 million in assets, now has $25 million
but jim hadley, senior vice president, said investors still question the neighborhood's viability, despite its prime location and good transportation
a main reason is housing shortages. only 727 units have been built since 1969, city officials say. some federally subsidized housing has been built and almost $7 million has been spent to improve 5,000 units since 1983, they add
as long as you don't have any housing, you're not going to have desirable residents,'' said resident edward manning. ``this community is not going to be the way you'd like it to be anytime soon.''
manning and others say a comeback depends on folks flexing political muscle. for years, ``we didn't demand nothing and we didn't get anything,'' he said
that, many say, changed with the 1983 election of harold washington, the city's first black mayor who died last year and is regarded in the same revered tones as king
miller, who last tuesday defeated the incumbent for the democratic ward committeeman post, says north lawndale's problems may be the same as they were a generation ago, except for one difference: ``the political maturity is there now.''
lawndale was and is a very poor community,'' he said. if king were alive, ``i think he'd be proud of the attitude of the residents. there's still hope. there are still efforts ... to bring lawndale into the 20th century. i think we're very close.''
sharon cohen is the ap midwest regional reporter, based in chicago
the rev. martin luther king jr. wrote of his experiences in north lawndale in his book ``where do we go from here: chaos or community?'' it was published in 1967
here are a few excerpts:
the phone rings daily with countless stories of man's inhumanity to man, and i find myself struggling constantly against the depression and hopelessness which the hearts of our cities pump into the spiritual bloodstream of our lives.''
the children's clothes are too skimpy to protect them from the chicago wind, and a closer look reveals the mucus in the corners of their bright eyes, and you are reminded that vitamin pills and flu shots are luxuries which they can ill afford. the `runny noses' of ghetto children become a graphic symbol of medical neglect in a society which has mastered most of the diseases from which they will too soon die. there is something wrong in a society that allows this to happen.''
on his children's summertime experiences in the community:
their tempers flared and they sometimes reverted to almost infantile behavior. ... it (the apartment) was just too hot, too crowded, too devoid of creative forms of recreation. ... and i understood anew the conditions which make of the ghetto an emotional pressure cooker.''
on higher prices charged in the local stores:
once confined to this isolated community, one no longer participates in a free economy, but is subject to price-fixing and wholesale robbery by many of the merchants in the area.''
the ritual of the poor is conducted almost every day at the southern christian leadership conference's headquarters here
they walk in and sit quietly on battered chairs, their eyes scanning walls lined with photographs of martin luther king jr. marching along alabama roads
they wait, sometimes for hours, hoping for help to find a job, a home or a lost welfare check
they helped my sister last year when her lights was off, so i was thinking they would help me find another place to stay _ you know, a cheaper one,'' said betty mitchell, who works at a fast-food restaurant and was waiting at the sclc offices last week
but trying to meet such demands strains the financially strapped organization and its skeleton crew, which struggles both to treat the symptoms of poverty and find a cure for the disease
oh, lord, we get more requests than we can handle,'' said the rev. joseph lowery, sclc president. ``we do what we can, but we just don't have the staff to respond to all the cases.''
the poor bring complaints about everything from police brutality to housing and hiring practices, lowery said
the major incidents, for example, are the violence of minimum-wage jobs, or no jobs at all,'' lowery said. ``the violence of homelessness. the violence of being the last hired and first fired
most poor people are working; they simply don't earn enough to get out of poverty.''
the sclc has tied itself to the needs of the needy since 1957, when it was founded by king, lowery and the revs. ralph abernathy and fred shuttlesworth to expand the non-violent movement against legal segregation. its eventual victory over discriminatory laws earned the sclc a reputation of militancy that holds to this day
we are the activist arm of the movement. when you do that, you step on toes and you don't become the most popular kid on the block,'' lowery said. ``we know it's not as popular to give us support as it is some other groups that are not as controversial.''
the nation heard from the sclc frequently last year as it spoke out on issues it felt could jeopardize human rights. it organized marches in virtually all-white forsyth county, ga.; helped establish a biracial committee on race relations there; opposed judge robert bork's nomination to the u.s. supreme court; condemned statements about blacks in sports made by al campanis and jimmy ``the greek'' snyder, and negotiated with major league groups to move blacks into upper management
we still believe in the efficacy of conscience-working and consciousness-raising and, if necessary, civil disobedience,'' lowery said. ``we're going to have to continue to have advocacy groups to keep pressure on _ creative, non-violent pressure. we have to keep that alive.''
the group, which lacks solid corporate support, operates from a dingy brownstone in atlanta's historic auburn avenue district. the building has changed little since it was first occupied in 1962
this is martin's desk,'' lowery said, running his hand over the cluttered, chipped wooden desk in his office. ``we have not put thick carpets on the floor or lined the walls and ceilings with chandeliers because that's not where our priorities are.''
on april 4, the 20th anniversary of king's assassination, the group will kick off its 1988 poor people's crusade with hearings on homelessness and unemployment. it will also hold rallies, starting in memphis, tenn., then sweeping through alabama, georgia and mississippi
the sclc was ready to start a similar campaign when king was gunned down at a memphis hotel in 1968. days later, sclc members dried their tears and marched on washington, d.c., carrying thousands of the nation's poor with them to dramatize poverty
this time around, the sclc wants more than a display of what's gone wrong with efforts to wipe out poverty, lowery said
the crusade is trying to get poverty on the national agenda,'' lowery said. ``whoever comes into office (as president), we want them to have a commitment to eliminating poverty and look at it as the urgent, critical problem that it is.''
lowery said he hopes the campaign will change the recent tendency to celebrate the national king holiday in january with glitzy, ceremonial events that ignore the issues that dominated king's life
we're beginning to honor martin as a orator, as a dreamer, but we're not honoring the message,'' lowery said, glancing at a large photograph of him talking with king in a church pulpit
you've got people now who are paying honor to him on that holiday who are not doing anything about helping the poor or working for economic justice
they say, `dr. king this, dr. king that,' then they don't register to vote, they don't join a boycott, they don't work for peace and human dignity.''
here are some statistics on black poverty and related issues:

poverty:
_ the national poverty rate for blacks in 1986 was 31.1 percent, compared with 11 percent for whites, according to the census bureau. the poverty rate is based on those people whose income falls below a level determined by the federal government; the level is $8,737 for a three-person family, and $11,203 for a four-person family
_ in 1968, the year martin luther king jr. was assassinated, the black poverty rate was 34.7 percent, compared with 10 percent for whites
_ the midwest had the highest proportion of blacks living below the poverty line, 34.5 percent, in 1986, according to the state of black america, a series of reports published by the national urban league
unemployment:
_ the black unemployment rate in 1987 was 13 percent, 2{ times the 5.3 percent for whites, the census bureau said
_ in 1968, before statistics were broken down for specific racial or ethnic groups, all minority unemployment was 6.7 percent. the white jobless rate was 3.2 percent
income:
_ median family income for blacks has increased every year since the recession-fueled low point of 1982, the urban league said. however, the average median black family income throughout the 1980s is $16,476, compared with $17,765 for the 1970s
_ in a single year, 1986, median black family income was $17,604, compared with $30,809 for whites
_ in 1986, 44.2 percent of black families had incomes of less than $10,000, compared with 13.7 percent of white families
children:
_ in 1986, 42.7 percent of all black children under 18 years of age were officially classified as poor. the comparable figure for white children was 15.3
cities:
_ from 1970 to 1980, the number of people living below the poverty line in the cores of the nation's 10 largest cities increased by 19 percent, from 3.1 million to 3.8 million, according to a university of chicago study by loic wacquant and william julius wilson
the increase, the study said, was due entirely to increased poverty among minorities. the cities measured were the largest as of 1970 _ new york, chicago, philadelphia, detroit, baltimore, dallas, cleveland, indianapolis, los angeles and houston
_ in the 1970-80 decade, the number of poor people rose 30 percent in los angeles, 24 percent in chicago, 20 percent in new york city and 16 percent in philadelphia, the study said
the proportion of blacks living in extremely poor neighborhoods doubled in chicago and tripled in new york city from 1970 to 1980
