first city bancorporation of texas inc. again has extended its deadline to dissident debt holders who have been asked to redeem their securities at a discount under a federal bailout plan for the institution
only about 51 percent of the holders of first city notes totaling $225.9 million had tendered their securities as of lare tuesday afternoon
texas' fourth-largest bank holding company had sought 90 percent of those securities, which were to be redeemed at less than face value as part of a buyout plan contained in a $1.5 billion bailout led by the federal deposit insurance corp
if completed, it would be the second-biggest u.s. bank rescue ever
the low response prompted first city to extend tuesday's 5 p.m. est deadline to march 29. it was the second extension given by the houston-based company _ the first being last week after only 41.4 percent, or $93.6 million, of the notes had been redeemed for cash
chicago investor a. robert abboud, who would become chairman of first city under the bailout plan, said actions were being taken to complete the transaction by alternate means but did not elaborate
under a buyout plan that was made a condition of the federal bailout, holders of first city's debt securities wre offered from 35 cents to 45 cents on the dollar for their notes
abboud, who said debt holders would fare worse if the bank were liquidated, told federal regulators in washington last weekend that not enough of the note holders had agreed to sell at those prices. he also has contended there was no intention to raise the amount of the offer
however, some industry analysts have indicated that some debt holders who don't tender their notes might end up getting a better deal once first city is recapitalized. depending on the strength of the recapitalized institution, the bonds could trade at significantly higher prices than abboud is offering
still other analysts have said the fdic could refuse to raise the offer for fear of setting a precedent for future bank bailouts
some of the alternatives being discussed for first city included dropping the participation threshold below 90 percent or terminating the tender offer
other options available to the fdic, analysts said, include canceling the abboud deal and reopening bidding for the bank, or having the fdic itself take over first city. the fdic did just that in 1984, pumping $4.5 billion into continental illinois bank and trust of chicago during the largest u.s. bank bailout ever
another plan calls for first city's 59 banks in texas and one in south dakota to fail and merge into a ``bridge bank'' until a new buyer is found. still another option is for the holding company, with $11 billion in assets, to enter voluntary bankruptcy proceedings
first city grew quickly during the texas oil boom, but was hammered by energy and real estate losses when oil prices plummeted. for 1987, the company posted a $1.1 billion loss
the bailout plan calls for $970 million in federal assistance, a $500 million infusion of capital raised privately by an investor group headed by abboud and a spinoff of $1.79 billion in book value of poorly performing assets
on march 4, more than 71 percent of the bank holding company's 37 million shareholders approved the controversial bailout
the united states, angry over european subsidies for the airbus aircraft-manufacturing consortium, is increasing pressure on airbus nations to abolish or at least reduce the payments, say diplomatic sources
the americans at a minimum want the europeans to give a signal that they are willing to accept some effective discipline in regard to subsidies,'' an informed diplomatic source, who asked not to be identified further, said tuesday
the united states estimates that the four countries involved in airbus industrie _ france, britain, west germany and spain _ have pumped $10 billion into the consortium since it was created 17 years ago
ministers of the four airbus countries are to meet with u.s. trade officials in the southern west german resort city of constance on friday to continue discussions on the dispute
willy de clercq, the european economic community's external relations commissioner, said last week that there was a ``realistic chance'' of settling the dispute, but said eec governments could not entirely renounce state aid payments to airbus
he predicted an agreement would require ``further rounds of very difficult negotiations.''
the united states maintains that subsidies to airbus are unfair to u.s. aircraft makers in the wide-body, long-haul passenger jet market
the airbus nations contend the subsidies do not distort trade and are allowed under the civil aircraft provisions of the general agreements on tariffs and trade
the eec also contends u.s. aircraft manufacturers long have enjoyed huge, indirect subsidies through military contracts from the pentagon and millions in government research grants
the united states has threatened to retaliate against airbus if the negotiations fail, despite a recent decision by the four airbus ministers to have airbus managers enter into direct negotiations with mcdonnell douglas corp. on a possible joint project
the aim of the talks is to see whether the two sides could collaborate on one or more new airplanes. under the prosposal, the new aircraft would not compete with existing models
but diplomatic sources told the associated press that the move was unlikely to reduce tensions over the subsidy issue
it may well be helpful for airbus and mcdonnell douglas to agree on a joint project, but that will not solve the core problem of the current subsidies,'' said another diplomatic source, who also declined to be identified further
a spokesman for u.s. trade representative clayton yeutter in washington declined comment on the upcoming meeting. yeutter is expected to attend the talks. week</head>
the announcement tuesday that weekend office hours will end next year for the nation's postal savings system could mean an effective move to a five-day work week
japan's posts and telecommunications minister, a top banking official and the president of the tokyo stock exchange all indicated separately on tuesday that they favored moving toward a nationwide five-day work week beginning february 1989
such moves by the concerned parties would eliminate saturday business hours for the postal savings system, banks and stock trading
japan's banks and stock market currently only close on the second and third saturdays of each month, while keeping half-day hours for the remaining saturdays. a six-day work week still is routine for many japanese
the proposal is designed to promote a less workaholic and a more leisure-based society commensurate with japan's higher standard of living. such a trend, proponents argue, could indirectly stimulate domestic demand by increasing personal consumption and the growth of service and other non-export industries
the movement toward a five-day work week has drawn increased support from financial and government groups for the past several years
posts and telecommunications minister masaaki nakayama touched off a flurry of comments tuesday by announcing he had decided to terminate weekend office hours for the postal savings system beginning next february
the ministry oversees the system _ one of the largest savings networks in the world _ where cash deposits have been declining due to higher interest rates on other investment instruments
in response to nakayama's decision, kenichi kamiya, chairman of the federation of bankers' associations of japan said, ``it is important for all large participants to be in agreement.''
a federation spokesman said kamiya's comments, made at a separate press conference, meant to suggest major banks and securities houses would be willing to fall in line with the savings ministry's move
in another separate comment, tokyo stock exchange president michio takeuchi said he favored the five-day work week in the wake of nakayama's decision
kamiya, who also is president of mitsui bank ltd., added the banking federation, which represents the interests of major japanese banking institutions, has been working on the concept of creating a five-day work week since november of last year
japan's banking industry had hoped to shift toward the five-day week as early as october 1988, but postponed its action until early 1989 in order to overlap with the anticipated weekend closing of government postal savings offices, industry sources said
e.w. scripps co., the privately held parent corporation of the scripps howard media group, says it plans to sell some of its limited-voting common stock to the public
the newspaper publishing company said tuesday that the number of shares to be sold had not been determined but that control of the company would remain with the founding scripps family
it said the required paperwork was expected to be filed with the federal securities and exchange commission next month
lawrence a. leser, president and chief executive officer, said the stock sale was intended to pay off debt incurred for the company's acquisition program begun in 1986 and to finance further growth
leser said it also would provide liquidity for members of the scripps family who will control the company after the termination of the edward w. scripps trust, the present controlling shareholder
the trust is to terminate upon the death of the last of the four eldest children of robert p. scripps, son of company founder e.w. scripps. at termination, the assets of the trust are to be distributed to 28 great-grandchildren of e.w. scripps
during its existence, the trust is required to maintain voting control of e.w. scripps co
the company has an 80 percent-owned subsidiary, scripps howard broadcasting co., which has public ownership and is traded over-the-counter. the stock sale will not affect the status of that company, the announcement said
e.w. scripps co. owns 21 daily newspapers, nine television stations, five radio stations and cable systems nationwide that serve approximately 400,000 cable tv subscribers. it also owns united media, a new york-based syndicator of newspaper columns and comic strips
e.w. scripps co. was reincorporated in delaware in 1987 and has two classes of common stock outstanding: regular common and class a common, which has limited voting power. the capital structure is similar to that of other media companies that seek to retain control within the founding family, leser said
the edward w. scripps trust now owns 73 percent of the regular common shares and 90 percent of the class a shares
holders of the class a common shares to be sold to the public will be entitled to elect a third of the company directors, but will not have other voting rights
in all other respects, the class a stock is comparable to the regular common shares, the company said
charles e. scripps, board chairman of the e.w. scripps co. and chairman of the trustees of the trust, said: ``my grandfather, through the trust, perpetuated family control for as long as was legally possible. the present capitalization, with a public market for the class a common shares, will permit the next generation of the family to retain control of the company after the termination of the trust and provide liquidity for their holdings.''
the majority of the shares to be offered will be newly issued stock. the trust will sell a portion of its holding, but it will continue to hold a majority of both the regular common and class a shares after the sale
first republicbank corp.'s attempt to seek federal assistance comes as the nation's 13th-largest banking company tries to bolster the waning confidence of its depositors and the financial markets
first republicbank indicated tuesday it was seeking federal aid to keep from failing, and had held preliminary discussions with the federal deposit insurance corp
we seek some assistance, yet to be defined. we will be putting together, over the next few weeks, a plan that we can submit to the fdic for assistance,'' said gerald w. fronterhouse, chairman and chief executive officer
it was important that we initiate those discussions in order to provide a more stable environment for our company,'' he said
shaken by the slumping real estate and energy sectors and a loss of confidence in the institution by wall street, first republicbank suffered a loss of about $600 million in deposits over a five-day period last month, prompting the decision to seek federal help
certainly two or three weeks ago we didn't believe this would be necessary,'' said joseph c. bowles, a spokesman for the company
first republicbank officials tried last month to combat rumors that the bank was considering merging with another financial institution, taking the unusual step of buying full-page newspaper ads to assure customers their deposits were safe
bowles said he didn't believe the latest development would lead more depositors to withdraw their money because ``we expect our customers will understand that their money is protected.''
first republicbank is discussing whether to pursue open-bank assistance from the fdic, generally used only if the agency finds keeping a bank open would be less costly to the government than letting it fail
an fdic bailout of that kind would require regulators to determine that the bank would fail without help
disclosure of the talks with the government _ and the company's suspension of payment of preferred stock dividends _ were greeted with pessimism by wall street
first republicbank's stock fell 25 cents to $1.50 a share tuesday on the new york stock exchange _ a 14.3 percent drop
furthermore, standard &amp; poor's corp. downgraded first republicbank's senior debt rating to its lowest level short of default. the wall street credit rating form also downgraded the bank holding company's certificate of deposit and commercial paper ratings
fronterhouse contended the company would continue to thrive and remain an important institution in the state for years
but financial analysts said the request for federal aid could foretell a buyout or merger for first republicbank, which was created by the merger of dallas rivals interfirst corp. and republicbank corp. in 1987
the real estate market turned down, i think, much more rapidly than the bank had thought and it just turned into a snowball effect,'' said frank anderson, a dallas independent bank consultant. ``and they got into a situation where news was being leaked from meetings of some of their top-level officials to various news media
and whereas that did not cause the problem, it surely exacerbated the problem,'' said anderson
first republicbank lost $656 million in 1987, mainly because a staggering 17 percent of its $15 billion loan portfolio was either past due or renegotiated
reports indicate the holding company stands to lose another $450 million this year. the company has 73 affiliate banks in texas and assets of $33.2 billion, and employs 15,188 people
separately, houston-based first city bancorporation of texas inc. extended a tuesday deadline for debt holders to redeem their securities at a discount under a rescue plan representing the second-largest bank bailout in u.s. history
first city granted a second extension, to 5 p.m. est march 29, after the required 90 percent of debt holders failed to tender their the securities
some industry analysts contended that first republicbank's decision to seek federal aid could help texas banking
it should lend further stability to the banking system in the state,'' said sandy flannigan, an analyst and vice president of painewebber inc. ``there has been a great deal of negative press, and the fact that they are seeking some kind of fdic assistance should create some additional confidence in the system.''
john r. torrell iii's surprise resignation as president of manufacturers hanover corp. comes as the bank holding company is on the verge of an expected rebound from recent financial setbacks
torell resigned ``at his initiative'' to pursue other business opportunities, according to spokesman john stefans. the resignation is effective at the end of this month
the board accepted it with deepest regret,'' stefans said
recent speculation on wall street about a possible management shakeup at the bank had focused not on torell but on john f. mcgillicuddy, manufacturers hanover's chairman and chief executive, according to analysts
in his most recent position, torell was the company's no. 2 executive behind mcgillicuddy and widely was considered his heir apparent
analysts have said torell played a key role in helping the banking company emerge from its recent earnings problems and was largely responsible for developing its successful consumer finance business
in its annual report released earlier this month, manufacturers hanover said it expected a profit of at least $807 million this year. like other big money-center banks, manufacturers hanover established a huge loan-loss reserve to cover shaky foreign debts in 1987, which was largely responsible for a $1.14 billion loss that year
torell, 48, said in a news release from the bank that after a 27-year career at manufacturers hanover, including 10 years as a director, ``it is time for a change.''
torell joined the bank fresh from graduation from princeton university. he became vice chairman in 1978, president of the bank in 1982 and president of the holding company in 1985, stefans said
manufacturers hanover is the nation's sixth largest bank holding company with assets totaling $73.3 billion
a search committee of the board will be convened to choose a successor for torell. candidates from inside and outside the institution will be considered, according to mcgillicuddy
citibank says it is retreating from a policy that denied credit cards to some university students because they majored in humanities, after receiving complaints from around the country
in the latest fallout from the policy, students at the university of california who said they were denied cards because of their humanities majors called for the bank to change the policy or get its representatives off campus
it doesn't take people from college to see that their reasoning that a humanities major is more of a financial risk than an engineering major is pretty weak,'' said student kennedy yip, 22
yip _ a rhetoric major _ received a visa last year while attending a different college as a mathematics major. yip's rejection letter for a citibank mastercard dated feb. 13 listed ``field of study'' as the cause
other liberal arts majors who say citibank rejected their credit applications include some studying italian and history
bill mcguire, a citibank spokesman in new york, said the bank was ``moving away'' from the policy, which would be discontinued by the end of june. he admitted the company had received complaints from students at other universities around the country but he would not identify the schools
mcguire, in an interview tuesday with the oakland tribune, would not describe how the policy was applied
some students with humanities majors at berkeley reported they had received citibank credit cards
furthermore, a spokesman for the u.s. comptroller of the currency in kansas city, mo. said tuesday that the equal credit opportunity act does not prohibit using a student's academic major in a credit application system
nevertheless, some of the students turned down for credit at berkeley are seeking to have citibank denied access to the campus, where its representatives set up tables around the student union to accept credit applications
the humanities policy surfaced last week when irene chang, a reporter for the independent campus newspaper, the daily californian, asked a campus bank-card canvasser how to apply
i told her i had heard a rumor that english majors were being turned down, and she said i should give her a student photo identification instead of my registration card, which lists my major,'' chang said tuesday in an interview
she then told me to fill in the application by putting in business administration or electrical engineering as my major, instead of english, which she said was what students (at another university) were doing,'' chang said
matt denn, berkeley student body president, said he doesn't want to threaten citibank but believes student government's right to regulate groups at the student union building gives him ``leverage to suggest a policy change.''
molly sorkin, 22, an art history major rejected last fall for a visa from citibank because of her major, says she supports punitive action against citibank
it's obvious discrimination, and i don't think they should be allowed to get away with thinking that some majors are the ones that are going to be making all the money,'' she said
what i study says nothing about my responsibility or whether or not i can pay my bills,'' said sorkin, who graduated in december and now works in retail sales
aggregate overseas equity investment by south korean companies since 1962 totaled $1 billion as of the end of february, the finance ministry reported wednesday
ministry officials said it was the first time the cumulative tally topped the $1 billion mark since 1962 korean companies began investing abroad in 1962
they said about one-third of the total went to the united states for manufacturing and other projects
officials also said korean investment abroad had shown marked rises in the past two years, reflecting the country's growing current account surplus, with $157 million invested in 1986 and $397 million in 1987
ministry statistics indicated foreign equity investment in south korea since 1962 was a cumulative $3.92 billion as of the end of january, after deducting withdrawals over the period
the dollar gained ground against all major foreign currencies except the canadian dollar in thin european trading early today despite some profit-taking
gold prices were mixed
foreign currency dealers said market attention was focused on thursday's scheduled release of u.s. trade figures for january. analysts are divided on whether the figures will show an expanding or shrinking trade deficit
in tokyo, where trading ends as europe's business day begins, the dollar rose 0.24 yen to 127.49. later, in london, it was quoted at 127.40 yen
the yen is easing against the dollar ... but everyone is waiting for the latest u.s. trade data,'' said an exchange dealer at a major commercial bank in tokyo
a trader with a major italian commercial bank in milan, italy, said his bank was predicting a january shortfall of $13.5 billion, wider than $12.2 billion in december. but he said ``it shouldn't hurt the dollar too much.''
other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late tuesday's rates, included: 1.6683 west german marks, up from 1.6650; 1.3802 swiss francs, up from 1.3760; 5.6770 french francs, up from 5.6605; 1.8734 dutch guilders, up from 1.8705; 1,237.50 italian lire, up from 1,232.40; and 1.2540 canadian dollars, down from 1.2564
in london, one british pound cost $1.8505, cheaper for buyers than late tuesday's $1.8570
gold was firming in london at midmorning amid reports of swiss buying
gold opened in london at a bid price of $445 a troy ounce, compared with late tuesday's $443.50. at midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $447.15
in zurich, the bid price was $442, down from $442.50 late tuesday
earlier, in hong kong, gold rose $4.52 to close at a bid $447.79
silver was quoted in london today at a bid price of $6.36 a troy ounce, up from tuesday's $6.25
tokyo's leading stock index surged today to its highest level since last october's crash, while the u.s. dollar rose slightly as traders awaited the release of u.s. trade deficit figures for january
the dollar closed at 127.49 yen, up 0.24 yen from tuesday's close. it opened at 127.38, and ranged between 127.32 yen and 127.55 yen
on the tokyo stock exchange, the nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues, which climbed 42.16 points tuesday, closed today at 25,704.43 points, up 228.76 points, or 0.90 percent
today's closing was the highest since stock prices plunged in october. the previous post-crash high was 25,682.82 points, on march 2
volume in the first section was estimated at 1.6 billion shares, roughly the same as tuesday, but 1.1 billion shares changed hands during the morning session alone in what traders were calling exceptionally heavy trading
heavy industrials, steel and electronics were leading the surge, said one broker
investors were spurred by u.s. payments data for the final quarter of 1987 showing the invisible trade balance in the black, one analyst said
in the foreign exchange market, traders continued their attitude of wait and see
the yen is easing against the dollar ... but everyone is waiting for the latest u.s. trade data,'' said an exchange dealer at a major commercial bank in tokyo
the u.s. commerce department is scheduled to release the nation's foreign trade figures for january on thursday. also moved on general news wires.</note>
president reagan was poised today to veto a major piece of civil rights legislation and call for an alternative giving corporations and religious schools more exemptions from anti-discrimination laws
a top civil rights leader said the veto would leave ``a terrible and lasting stain on the reagan presidency'' and democratic leaders predicted that congress would quickly override the president's action
today was the deadline for action on the sweeping measure, designed to overcome the effects of a 1984 supreme court decision that has allowed institutions to receive federal aid even when some of their departments discriminate illegally
the bill would require all parts of any institution receiving federal aid to obey anti-discrimination laws
we have said all along we would veto,'' white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said tuesday
fitzwater said the president believes the supreme court's decision, which involved grove city college in pennsylvania, was a mistake but that the corrective legislation goes too far in seeking to correct the problem
the bill became an issue in tuesday's illinois presidential primary when vice president george bush refused to say whether he would veto or sign the legislation if he were president
fitzwater said the administration has ``a very positive alternative bill'' but he declined to give details
an administration official, however, speaking on condition he not be identified, said the alternative was expected to be ``very much like'' a gop substitute that the house rejected by a 266-146 vote on march 2
that measure would have scaled back the bill's impact on corporations and allowed more schools to avoid compliance with civil rights laws on religious grounds
reagan wrote to house republicans that he objected to the bill that eventually passed because it ``dramatically expands the scope of federal jurisdiction over state and local governments and the private sector'' and ``poses a particular threat to religious liberty.''
the senate passed the bill 75-14 and the house passed it 315-98, margins substantially greater than the two-thirds majority of both houses needed to override a presidential veto
house majority leader thomas s. foley, d-wash., said tuesday that he expected the senate to override reagan's veto later this week and the house to follow suit next week
ralph neas, executive director of the 200-group leadership conference on civil rights, said that by vetoing the bill reagan would be ``favoring federal subsidies to discrimination.''
a presidential veto of a bill to end federal funding of discrimination would be unconscionable,'' he said. ``it will leave a terrible and lasting stain on the reagan presidency.''
the administration official who spoke anonymously said the white house strategy would be to try to get house members who voted for the gop substitute to vote to sustain the veto. since 146 _ the number of legislators who supported the house gop substitute _ is slightly more than one-third of the full house membership of 435, that could be enough to sustain
the civil rights bill would require entire colleges, school systems, government agencies and private entities to comply with anti-discrimination laws if any program or activity within them receives federal money. institutions that did not comply would lose their federal funding
the supreme court's grove city decision limited the penalty to the specific program or activity that violated the law
stock prices fell wednesday amid concerns about british monetary policy following tuesday's fiscal 1989 budget announcement
the financial times-stock exchange index of 100 stocks was down 9 points, or 0.5 percent, at 1,830.9 at midday
volume was a moderate 314.1 million shares, compared with 241.3 million shares the same time tuesday
concerns focused on the strength of the pound and perceptions that the next move in british interest rates likely would be higher
the pound's recent rise has spurred worries about lower corporate profitability. the budget announcement did little to dispel these fears, dealers said
also hitting share prices was profit-taking following strong gains posted in the run-up to the budget announcement, dealers said
they added that prices were being marked down amid light volume as the market awaits thursday's release of u.s. trade figures for january
with u.s. trade figures tomorrow, i don't think i'd be an aggressive buyer either,'' said nicholas knight, an equities strategist at james capel and co. others</head>
chrysler corp. has boosted buyer incentives on six models, offering as much as $1,500 in rebates, and one analyst said a ``fire sale'' seemed to be under way at the no. 3 u.s. automaker
chrysler said tuesday it was raising rebates on five 1987 and 1988 dodge cars and trucks and one jeep model. the incentive program has no expiration date
the automaker also said it planned to reduce rebates on three other models after the weekend
analysts credit the aggressive use of incentives with spurring sales. in early march, chrysler's domestic car sales were up 18.3 percent and its light truck sales were up 24.1 percent from a year ago
chrysler has the most generous incentives of any automaker. it's really running a fire sale on its left-over '87s,'' said ronald glantz, analyst with montgomery securities inc. in san francisco
rebates rose to $1,500 from $750 on the daytona pacifica; to $1,000 from $750 on daytona shelby z and standard ram pickups; to $1,000 from $500 on standard ram b150, b250 and b350 passenger vans; and to $750 from $500 on dakota mid-size pickups and jeep comanche pickup
chrysler said it also added its 1987 and 1988 chrysler lebaron convertible to the program with a $750 rebate
on monday, rebates on three other models will be reduced. the rebate on the 1987 and 1988 lebaron coupe will drop to $750 from $1,500; to $1,000 from $1,500 on the dodge ramcharger sport-utility vehicle; and to $500 from $750 on the dodge daytona highline
instead of rebates, buyers can opt for low-rate financing with interest rates of 3.8 percent on loans up to 48 months and 8.8 percent on loans up to 60 months, chrysler said
meanwhile, general motors corp.'s gmc truck division said it was extending its $500 rebate campaign through the end of the month on 1987 and 1988 s-15 compact pickups and sport-utility vehicles
gm also added its new 1988 sierra full-size pickup and 1987 and 1988 rally passenger vans and vandura cargo vans to the program, also with $500 rebates
the rebates may be used in addition to continuous option discounts
analysts said gm sales fell in early march because buyers took advantage of widespread incentives in february. rights.''</note>
the publisher of a canadian computer magazine says he was trying to show the dangers of software piracy when he wrote a rogue computer program that has popped up in software developed by seattle's aldus corp
but to aldus and others, the so-called computer ``virus'' _ apparently the first to appear in commercial software _ has caused consternation
viruses are programs created by computer operators for secret insertion into other programs as jokes or as acts of vandalism. they can spread from computer to computer when operators share contaminated software
consequences of the ``disease'' can range from a surprise message that pops up on a computer screen, as happened with the aldus virus, to the destruction of information stored in computer memories
until now, personal computer viruses were thought to reside only in non-commercial software, such as that available free or at low cost on computerized bulletin boards or on software disks shared by computer users
experts had thought viruses could be avoided if users used only commercial, off-the-shelf programs
richard brandow, publisher of montreal-based macmag, acknowledged tuesday in an interview that he wrote the so-called ``peace message'' that popped up on thousands of apple macintosh computer screens
brandow claimed that besides calling for world peace, the virus was intended to discourage software piracy or unauthorized copying and to encourage computer users to buy original copies
the virus was discovered in freehand, a new program developed by aldus for macintosh computers, said aldus spokeswoman laury bryant said. the message flashed when the program was loaded in the computer, ms. bryant said
although it ``was a very benign incident,'' aldus officials are angry and ``are talking with our attorneys to understand what our legal rights are in this instance,'' ms. bryant said
we feel that richard brandow's actions deserve to be condemned by every member of the macintosh community,'' she said
the incident resulted in aldus having to recall or rework thousands of packages of the new software. ms. bryant declined to say how much the recall or reworking of software would cost
the incident also sent a scare through the computer industry, because several of the nation's largest software companies also are clients of a macromind inc. of chicago, a subcontractor that inadvertently spread the virus to aldus
macromind president marc canter said in a telephone interview tuesday that he believed aldus was the only customer that received the virus
among canter's clients are the nation's three largest software producers _ microsoft corp. of redmond, ashton-tate, and lotus development corp. _ and apple
ashton-tate declined comment, but officials at microsoft, apple and lotus all said none of their software was infected
canter said the virus apparently was in a packet of software he obtained from brandow. unaware of the infection, canter ran the progam once and when he used the same computer to work on aldus software, the disk eventually sent to aldus became infected, he said
the computer virus then inadvertently was copied onto disks sold to customers and infected their computers, he said
brandow said he met canter, but denied giving him software
brandow said the virus program was written and tested for a year on a number of macintosh computers, and was left for two days in december on a macintosh at the magazine's offices
the publisher said he had expected that people making unauthorized copies of programs on the machine would spread the virus in the montreal area and possibly a few other areas of canada and the united states
instead, brandow said, an estimated 350,000 people in north america and europe had the message pop up on their computers on march 2
brandow said neither he nor his employees put the message on a computer billboard or information network, but he did not rule out the possibility that others who copied it without permission placed programs containing the message on such services
ms. bryant and brandow both said the virus died out after march 2
the full message, according to brandow, read: ``richard brandow, the publisher of macmag, and its entire staff would like to take this opportunity to convey their universal message of peace to all macintosh users around the world.'' beneath that was a graphic of the globe. fares</head>
northwest airlines has lowered the advance purchase requirement, to three days, on a discount fare used by business travelers
the change took effect tuesday as major airlines, including northwest, raised full coach fares and ended some discount fares, sharply increasing the cost of travel for people who cannot make plans in advance
northwest's change, which its competitors are expected to match, will make it easier for travelers to take advantage of some discount fares. the fare, available on a limited number of seats on most routes, carries no cancellation penalty and has no other restrictions
under the changes that took effect tuesday, most discount fares generally require a seven-day advance purchase and carry a cancellation penalty of 25 percent
if other airlines match the northwest fare, it would be the first modification of a series of fare increases proposed this month by continental airlines and matched by all leading carriers
william wren, vice president for public relations at northwest, said the airline was joining its competitors in extending to seven days from two the advance purchase requirement on maxsaver fares, the lowest fares available
in addition, wren said some carriers were proposing a 14-day advance purchase requirement, but that northwest did not support the idea
the stock market showed a small gain today, continuing the sluggish pattern of the past two sessions
the dow jones average of 30 industrials rose .83 to 2,048.24 in the first half hour
gainers slightly outnumbered losers in the overall tally of new york stock exchange-listed issues, with 468 up, 446 down and 578 unchanged
volume on the big board came to 19.47 million shares as of 10 a.m. on wall street
the market has been in a holding pattern since the start of the week as traders await thursday's report on the nation's trade balance for january
most economists look for a modest increase in the trade deficit after two months of pronounced declines. if the figures match those expectations, analysts believe the market wouldn't feel any great shock effects
but traders apparently are sticking with a cautious approach until then so as not to be caught off guard by any surprise either way
after the trade report, the market is also faced with a quarterly ``triple witching hour'' involving a series of stock index options and futures that will be settled friday
that too may pass quietly, brokers say, but until it is over it adds an additional element of uncertainty for investors
among actively traded blue chips, union carbide rose | to 25 and coca-cola was up | at 39[, but american telephone &amp; telegraph dropped \ to 28]
