housing construction posted the biggest increase in more than a year as new projects climbed by 8.9 percent in february, while industrial production edged up 0.2 percent, the government reported today
the commerce department said last month's gain in housing construction raised activity to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.49 million units. the increase followed declines of 1.9 percent in january and 15.8 percent in december
the unexpectedly strong february report was likely to ease worries about a possible recession. the 8.9 percent rise in housing starts in february was the sharpest monthly gain since a 12.7 percent rise in december 1986
the increase in february industrial production represented the fifth consecutive monthly gain, according to the federal reserve. the fed said the advance followed a 0.3 percent increase in january and left american industry operating at a rate 5.8 percent above a year ago
analysts said the report was consistent with their view that the economy will continue to move forward this year, but at a slower pace than in 1987
on tuesday, a jump in early march auto sales and news of a record 1987 trade deficit failed to wield much influence in the financial markets
major automakers said tuesday that sales of domestic cars and light trucks rose 6.3 percent in the first 10 days of march compared with a year earlier, led by surging sales of vehicles made by ford motor co. and chrysler corp. industry leader general motors corp. reported weaker results
in washington, the commerce department said the deficit in the broadest measure of foreign trade surged to a record $160.7 billion in 1987, a reflection of america's deepening debt to the rest of the world
the deficit in the u.s. current account was 13.7 percent higher than the 1986 deficit of $141.4 billion and marked the fifth consecutive year that this trade deficit has hit a new record
the reagan administration has sought to downplay the significance of the trade deficits, but private economists contend the rapid buildup of foreign debt could cause a further weakening in the dollar's value and a recession
the current account measures not only the flow of merchandise across u.s. borders but also the flow of services, primarily investment earnings
net debtor status means americans own less investments abroad than foreigners do in this country
despite the latest trade statistics, federal reserve board chairman alan greenspan said tuesday that americans shouldn't be overly concerned and that foreign investors make ``good corporate citizens.''
we will find that foreign investment in the united states will be a plus,'' even at present record levels, greenspan told the house-senate joint economic committee
neither the auto sales or foreign trade figures had much impact on wall street, where stocks were mixed in light trading. the dow jones average of 30 industrials fell 2.66 points to 2,047.41
prices in the bond market, a sensitive barometer of interest rates and the economy, also ended little changed. economists' comment after 6th graf pvs, however, the</note>
housing construction posted the biggest increase in more than a year as new projects climbed by 8.9 percent in february, the government reported today
the commerce department said the increase last month pushed construction activity to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.49 million units
the increase followed declines of 1.9 percent in january and 15.8 percent in december
those back-to-back monthly declines, which left housing starts at their slowest pace since the end of the last recession, had raised fears of a possible new economic downturn in the wake of the record collapse of the stock market in october
pessimists noted that housing is often the first sector to turn down at the onset of a new recession
however, the big jump in housing activity in february, which was much stronger than expected, was likely to ease worries about a possible recession this year, especially since other business barometers including employment gains, have shown strength since the oct. 19 stock market collapse
in another report today, the government said that production at u.s. factories, mines and utilities rose 0.2 percent in february following a 0.3 percent january gain. it was the fifth consecutive increase and left american industry producing at a 5.8 percent higher level than a year ago
economists said the increase in housing starts, while still leaving them well below the level of a year ago, was a good sign that the industry's two-month skid had been halted
the rebound in housing is yet another sign of an economy that is growing slowly but is far from a recession,'' said john a. tuccillo, chief economist of the national association of realtors. ``the lower interest rates enjoyed by the mortgage market in late january through february have revived what had seemed to be a dying housing sector.''
james christian, chief economist of the u.s. league of savings institutions, said he expected that mortgage rates, which are currently at an average of 9.96 percent for 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages, will not likely fall further but should stay around that level for the next several months
the 8.9 percent rise in housing starts in february was the sharpest monthly gain since a 12.7 percent rise in december 1986
housing permits, considered a good sign of future economic activity, also rose sharply in february, jumping 11.5 percent to an annual rate of 1.40 million units, also the biggest monthly gain since december 1986
many economists had been predicting a rebound in housing, given the fact that mortgage rates have fallen sharply since the first of the year and are again in the single-digit range
the strength in starts last month came in the construction of both single-family and multi-family housing
construction of single-family homes rose 9.3 percent in february to a seasonally adjusted 1.10 million units
construction of multi-family units was up 7.8 percent to an annual rate of 399,000 units
the strength was widespread in all sections of the country except the west, where starts fell 9 percent
housing starts rose 25.6 percent in the south, 13.8 percent in the midwest and 2.7 percent in the northeast
sears, roebuck and co. announced today it has agreed to buy a majority interest in western auto supply co. and will make a tender offer for the remainder of western auto's outstanding shares in a $402 million deal
sears said in a statement it will pay $19 a share for 52.3 percent of western auto's stock held by certain stockholders, including officers and directors
sears said it will offer the same cash price for all remaining stock if it can win the approval of western auto's board of directors this week
western auto's stock, which is traded on the over-the-counter market, was up $6 to $18.50 a share in early trading today
the stock buyout would cost sears $250 million and the retailer also would assume the auto supply company's $152 million debt
western auto is a kansas city-based marketer of auto supplies, tires, appliances and lawn and garden equipment. it has 6,600 employees and operates 278 company-owned retail stores. it also sells at wholesale to 1,570 independently owned western auto stores nationwide
the acquisition would represent sears' further expansion into specialty marketing. the nation's largest retailer previously bought apparel store and optical center chains
last year, western auto had a profit of $10.5 million on sales of $930.8 million. sears earned $1.65 billion and had revenues of $48.44 billion
sears said it reserved the right to cancel the deal if the western auto board fails to give its approval by friday
