sears, roebuck and co. is expanding its role in specialty retailing with a plan announced wednesday to buy western auto supply co. in a $402 million deal
sears said it was buying 52.3 percent of western auto stock from officers, directors and others for $19 a share and will make a tender offer for the remainder of the stock at the same price
the acquisition will cost the nation's biggest retailer $250 million. it also will assume the auto supply company's $152 million debt
western auto's stock, traded on the over-the-counter market, rose $5.87{ a share to $18.37{ by wednesday afternoon
john landschultz, a financial analyst in chicago with mesirow financial corp., said this was probably the first of several steps sears would take to increase its presence in the specialty field
this move does several things that were needed,'' said landschultz
first, he said, it gets sears out of the major malls where it has had a dominent influence and into the smaller markets. it also capitalizes on sears' strength in automotive parts and equipment
western auto sells auto supplies, tires, appliances and lawn and garden equipment through nearly 2,000 stores nationwide
the kansas city-based company operates 278 retail stores it owns, and sells wholesale to 1,570 independently owned western auto outlets
sears said john t. lundegard, western auto's chairman and chief executive officer, will remain as head of the auto supply unit and will report to alfred g. goldstein, president of sears' specialty merchandising
these personnel decisions are significant, said landschultz
it's very important that (lundegard) stays in place,'' he said, adding that goldstein has been extremely successful in the specialty field
the acquisition would represent sears' further expansion into specialty marketing. it previously bought apparel and optical chains
but the western auto deal is the first significant move in this direction, said landschultz
last year, western auto earned $10.5 million on sales of $930.8 million. sears earned $1.65 billion and had revenues of $48.44 billion
a former vice president of continental illinois national bank &amp; trust co. exceeded his authority and improperly approved risky loans in the years before the bank's near-collapse, a former lending officer testified
john lytle, accused of misusing bank funds, exceeded a limit of $5 million on the amount of loans he could approve by granting extensions on a loan, the former lending officer, anne liddell, testified tuesday
and she said lytle's initials appeared on a credit reporting form that was submitted in her name but that she did not fill out. the form listed the history of a prospective borrower
my name was misspelled,'' she said
ms. liddell's statements came during the second day of testimony in the five-day-old u.s. district court trial of lytle and two other men
lytle headed energy lending in oklahoma for contintental. the government has accused him of buying high-risk loans from the now-defunct penn square bank in oklahoma city in exchange for nearly $600,000 in kickbacks between 1980 and 1982
defendant william patterson, former head of energy lending at penn square, gave the kickbacks to lytle in the form of unsecured personal loans, the government contends
a third defendant, tulsa oil driller jere sturgis, is accused of purchasing oil-well investments from lytle at inflated prices in hopes of getting future loans from continental
all three are charged with multiple counts of wire fraud. lytle and patterson are also charged with misapplication of bank funds
the 1982 failure of penn square bank jolted continental, which was rescued in a massive bailout by the federal deposit insurance corp. two years later
wickes cos. inc. said wednesday it is negotiating to sell the kayser-roth hosiery group to members of the unit's management and narragansett capital inc. of new york
the hosiery unit, based in greensboro, n.c., is one of the world's leading manufacturers of men's and women's hosiery, including such brands as no nonsense, liz clairborne, calvin klein, burlington and supp-hose
it has 9,600 workers at 16 manufacturing plants and four distribution centers in the united states and europe
the kayser-roth units were part of gulf &amp; western industries' consumer and industrial products segment that was acquired by wickes for $1 billion in 1985
the hosiery group was one of three units put on the auction block by wickes last october. the others are its kayser-roth apparel group and wickes lumber
none of the three has been sold. wickes had tentatively agreed to sell the lumber segment to members of management, but that deal was called off in january because of financing problems. the lumber unit's management group is seeking other financing and wickes is looking at other possible buyers
the three units last year had sales of $1.8 billion and operating income of $80 million. of that, the hosiery group accounted for $500 million in sales, but no operating income figures were disclosed
wickes has said that proceeds from the asset sales will be used to buy back stock, pay debt and possibly fund acquisitions to expand continuing operations
the management group leading the buyout talks includes james i. spiegel, who was president of the consumer and industrial products units and corporate senior executive vice president at gulf &amp; western and later at wickes, and michael c. proies, president of no nonsense fashions inc. spiegel retired from wickes in early 1986
narragansett is a private investment firm that manages over $500 million in risk capital. industrial companies that make up its investment portfolio have sales of about $1 billion a year. narragansett also owns several radio and television stations and cable tv systems serving more than 350,000 subscribers
business took precedence over brotherhood in a suit that ended in u.s. district court when michael b. shane was awarded $1.3 million after suing his brother and partners six years ago
michael shane is the founder of leading edge products inc. of canton, a leading supplier of asian-made clones of ibm personal computers, in 1980
the case decided by a jury tuesday involved appendagez, a company founded in 1973 that sold a popular brand of blue jeans called faded glory
michael shane was 25 and had made $1 million selling wigs when james ip, a hong kong businessman, approached him about selling blue jeans. they were joined by shane's brother, james shane, and charles lee, a hong kong businessman
ip owned 14.5 percent of the hong kong company that made the jeans
appendagez at its peak sold $50 million to $60 million in jeans a year, said michael b. keating, lawyer for michael shane
michael shane was president and majority stockholder of appendagez until 1979 when he sold his stock in the company in two transactions
in january 1979, he sold 30 shares for $1.3 million. in november, he agreed with his three partners to sell his remaining 26 shares for $50,000 and ended all business relations
three years later he sued his brother and his other two former partners, charging them with securities fraud
he claimed that between the times of the two transactions, the three conspired to deceive him about the condition of appendagez so they could buy him out for less than his remaining shares were worth
tiger international inc. said wednesday it has paid off, at a substantial discount, $132 million in debt from its failed north american car rail-car leasing unit
the debt was paid off using proceeds from a new $100 million debt offering and an unspecified amount of internally generated cash, the company said
tiger, parent of the world's oldest and largest air-cargo concern, flying tiger line inc., wrote off its entire $132 million investment in north american car in 1984
in january, tiger said it had reached an agreement with holders of the north american car debt to repay them at a discount
tiger wouldn't say wednesday how much the discount was, other than that it was substantial
the $100 million in new debt is in notes that are due no later than 1993 and are secured by a pledge of 51 percent of flying tiger's stock
most grain and soybean futures prices turned weaker today on the chicago board of trade
hedge selling from south america put pressure on the soybean market from the start, said jerry gidel, an analyst with g.h. miller &amp; co
this was compounded by industry data putting the soybean crush figure for february at 3.7 million tons, substantially lower than a month earlier and the year-agofigure
the implication is that soybean processors still have large supplies of beans
a lack of export interest in corn and wheat weighed on those markets, said gidel
