a group of venture capitalists recently polled will have an average of $44.8 million to invest in growing companies this year, up 11 percent from the average earmarked for investments last year, according to a study released wednesday
grant thornton, the accounting and management consulting firm that conducted the survey, notedthat 93 percent of the 183 venture capital firms that responded said they anticipate receiving more requests from young companies seeking funds for expansion this year compared with the previous year
forty-seven percent of the venture capitalists polled said they would invest in more companies this year, the study said
only 13 percent of the respondents said they have shifted investment strategies since the october stock market crash, with several noting they prefer ``later-stage'' companies that may present less risk
a full 96 percent said they expect going public will be a more difficult and lengthy process in the post-crash environment
grant thornton mailed questionnaires to 501 venture capital firms across the country in january. the 183 completed surveys represent at 36 percent response rate
