news corp., an international media company controlled by publisher rupert murdoch, said wednesday it had arranged to buy nearly all the shares of australian associated press pty
that company, which is no relation to the associated press in the united states, distributes news and photographs throughout australia. it owns a 7.75 percent voting stake in reuters holdings plc, the large british news and information service
if murdoch's acquisition succeeds, his company would become the biggest single shareholder in reuters because news corp. already owns a 6.8 percent voting stake in reuters
news corp., which had owned 44.65 percent of the australian associated press, said it had acquired another 8.3 percent from bell group ltd., a concern controlled by australian investor robert holmes a court
news corp. said it also had agreed to acquire a 44.65 percent stake from john fairfax ltd., one of australia's major media companies
prices weren't disclosed
murdoch, a native australian who became a u.s. citizen in 1985, already controls about 60 percent of australia's press and has encountered government resistance to an expansion from government antitrust officials
it was not immediately clear whether murdoch's arrangement to effectively acquire the australian associated press would be blocked by the government. but an official of the trade practices commission, which regulates such transactions, said it would investigate
the official, who declined to be identified by name, said elements of the sale appeared to conflict with an order issued last year that prevented murdoch from acquiring the parent company of the australian associated press, the australian associated press information services ltd. second graf; uppicks 3rd graf pvs: the $100...</note>
a federal judge approved the a.h. robins co.'s merger pact with american home products corp. on wednesday after robins agreed to put $100 million toward dalkon shield claims before its chapter 11 bankruptcy case is completed
u.s. district judge robert r. merhige jr., who earlier in the day had raised questions about the merger deal, signed an order to execute the agreement in the wake of the pharmaceutical company's offer, said roscoe e. puckett jr., a robins spokesman
the $100 million would cover administrative costs to set up a dalkon shield trust fund that eventually will grow to $2.475 billion, the amount merhige said is needed to pay claims against the intrauterine birth-control device
the claims covered by the initial funding would be smaller amounts to women who show minimal proof of dalkon shield use and injury, said puckett, the robins spokesman
earlier wednesday, merhige, citing years of delay in paying dalkon shield claims, refused to ratify the merger unless it allowed some compensation before the company's reorganization became final
the surprise ruling sent attorneys in the 2{-year-old bankruptcy case back to the drawing board to hammer out a compromise that would allow payments of some claims pending expected appeals of the reorganization
you know it's coming. i know it's coming,'' merhige told the attorneys of expected court challenges. ``but we can't wait any longer.''
merhige's objection involved a section of the merger agreement that would allow the new york-based american home products, which plans to acquire robins through a $700 million exchange of stock, to back out after one year, if appeals of the court's confirmation order for robins' reorganization plan are still pending
putting off payments of injury claims against the intrauterine device until all appeals are resolved and a final order approving the reorganization is entered would be unacceptable, the judge said
instead, the judge suggested that american home products put up $100 million to begin paying claims pendig appeal. if the reorganization is later voided, he said, then ahp could recover the money from robins
i'm not going to delay this any more,'' he said. ``these women have waited and waited and waited.''
under the agreement reached later wednesday, robins will put up the $100 million instead of ahp, puckett said
until the hearing before merhige and u.s. bankruptcy judge blackwell n. shelley, there were no known hitches with the merger, except for a $25 million breakup claim against robins filed by the rorer group inc
robins and rorer, a suburban philadelphia drug manufacturer, had reached a tentative merger pact late last year. but in subsequent talks involving rorer, ahp and a third potential robins' buyer, france's sanofi sa, officials of robins accepted the american home offer
merhige said he would conduct a hearing on the rorer claim at a later time
the american home deal, reached jan. 19, had been endorsed by attorneys for 195,000 women with dalkon shield claims and by robins stockholders. in addition to the $2.475 billion dalkon shield trust fund, robins' trade creditors would receive full payment of claims
when the merger proposal came up in court, robins' attorney dennis drebsky said the plan ``happily is largely consensual.''
but merhige surprised attorneys by announcing, ``i have a problem.''
the judge said ahp's withdrawal option put an unnecessary delay on paying claims unless the appeals court ordered a freeze on payments pending a resolution of the case
robins filed for chapter 11 protection from creditors in august 1985 as millions of dollars in claims mounted against the dalkon shield. the company distributed about 4.5 million of the iuds in the united states and abroad in the early 1970s
at the time it entered bankruptcy court, robins had settled 9,500 of 15,000 dalkon shield lawsuits with payments of about $530 million. injury claims have ranged from pelvic infections to sterility
the dollar firmed slightly against most major currencies wednesday, but traders remained cautious in advance of new trade data to be released thursday
gold prices edged lower in domestic trading after climbing overseas. republic national bank of new york said gold was bid at $445 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. est, down $1 from late tuesday
analysts said the foreign-exchange markets remained relatively quiet in anticipation of the government's january trade figures, which are expected to show a small increase in the monthly trade deficit
although estimates have varied, most traders now expect the deficit for january to total somewhere between $13 billion and $14 billion, compared with $12.2 billion in december
a figure at the low end of the range would be a boon to the u.s. currency; a high-end number would revive the downward pressure on the dollar, they said
the dollar has been pressured lower in the past by trade reports showing a growing imbalance of imports over exports. but as recent reports have shown improvement in the trade gap, the currency has stabilized
in advance of the latest report, traders were reluctant ``to step up and buy the dollar,'' according to karen gibbs of the investment firm dean witter reynolds inc. in chicago
the currency managed its slight gains in response to better-than-expected government reports on housing construction and industrial production. the commerce department said housing starts jumped 8.9 percent in february, while the federal reserve said output at the nation's factories, mines and utilities rose 0.2 percent during the month. both appeared to be positive signs for the u.s. economy
because it is viewed as a safe haven in times of international turmoil, the dollar also drew strength from reports of an attempted coup in panama and of a nicaraguan attack on contra rebels in honduras
in tokyo, where the trading day begins, the dollar rose 0.24 yen to a closing 127.49. later, in london, it was quoted at 127.37 yen. in new york, the dollar traded at 127.455 yen, up from 127.375 late tuesday
in london, the british pound slipped to $1.8505, cheaper for buyers than late tuesday's $1.8570. in new york, the pound fetched $1.84925, up from $1.8455 late tuesday
other dollar rates late wednesday in new york, compared with late trading tuesday, included: 1.67395 west german marks, up from 1.66985; 1.3854 swiss francs, up from 1.3805; 1.2535 canadian dollars, down from 1.25385; 5.6894 french francs, up from 5.6660; and 1,242.00 italian lire, up from 1,232.40
late dollar rates in europe compared with late tuesday included: 1.6690 west german marks, up from 1.6650; 1.3810 swiss francs, up from 1.3760; 5.6782 french francs, up from 5.6605; 1.8750 dutch guilders, up from 1.8705; 1,238.45 italian lire, up from 1,232.40; 1.2518 canadian dollars, down from 1.2564
gold climbed to a late price of $446.20 a troy ounce in london, compared with late tuesday's $443.50. in zurich, the late bid price was $447, up from $442.50 late tuesday. earlier, in hong kong, gold rose $4.52 to close at a bid $447.79
on the new york commodity exchange, gold bullion for current delivery eased back to $445.30 a troy ounce, from $446.30 tuesday
silver was quoted in london late wednesday at a bid price of $6.36 a troy ounce, up from tuesday's $6.25. at the comex, silver bullion for current delivery traded at $6.327 a troy ounce, down from $6.365
energy futures prices spurted upward wednesday on the new york mercantile exchange, reponding to a drop in oil inventories and to turmoil in central america
on other markets, copper futures moved sharply higher; cattle prices were a little higher while other livestock and meat declined; grain and soybean prices retreated
oil traders said an unsuccessful coup attempt in panama against the regime of gen. manuel antonio noriega set the oil market on edge
and there were rumors that workers on the panama oil pipeline went on strike,'' said richard kane, an analyst in new york with merrill lynch capital markets
the pipeline is the primary means of moving crude oil shipped from alaska across panama to other tankers that take it to gulf coast
there also were rumors that the panama military cut off roads to the u.s. military base in the panama canal zone and fears that the canal could be closed, kane said
all this helped people to make up their minds to cover'' their ``short'' positions, kane said
there has been an unusually large number of open contracts on crude oil, with many traders having sold contracts with the idea of buying them back later in hopes prices would fall in the interval _ a practice known as ``selling short.''
fearing the events in panama could drive prices up instead, many people who were short felt it was wise to buy now to offset their earlier sales, kane said
the reports out of panama topped a market that opened bullish on industry data released tuesday
the american petroleum industry said crude oil, gasoline and heating oil stocks were all down in the latest week. gasoline was down 3.59 million barrels from the previous week and heating oil was reduced by 5.6 million barrels
these are very good product drawdowns,'' said kane
prices for west texas intermediate crude oil rose 19 cents to 32 cents a barrel, with the contract for delivery in april settling at $16. heating oil was .43 cent to .66 cent higher, with april at 44.08 cents a gallon; and unleaded gasoline was .40 cent to .89 cent higher, with april at 45.24 cents a gallon
copper futures rallied strongly after suffering sharp declines the previous day on the commodity exchange in new york
the recovery was triggered by a reversal in outlook for the size of stockpiles in the exchange warehouses
the inventory expectations went from the plus side to the minus side,'' said bette raptopoulos, an analyst in new york with prudential-bache securities inc
the expectations wednesday, she said, was that there would be further drawdowns in stocks
trading of precious metals, meanwhile, was quiet as the market awaited the government's report thursday on the nation's foreign trade balance during january
copper settled .30 cent lower to 3.05 cents higher, with the may contract at 97.55 cents a pound
gold was $1 lower, with march at $445.30 a troy ounce; and silver was 3.8 cents to 4 cents lower, with march at $6.327 a troy ounce
grain and soybean futures prices turned weaker on the chicago board of trade
selling from south america put pressure on the soybean market from the start, said jerry gidel, an analyst with g.h. miller &amp; co
this was compounded by industry data putting the amount of soybeans processed in mills during february at 3.7 million tons, substantially lower than a month earlier and the year-ago figure
the implication is that soybean processors still have large supplies of beans
gidel said the corn and wheat prices were depressed by a lack of export interest
