henley group inc., a two-year-old holding company, on wednesday announced plans to split into two public companies and buy back 22 percent of its stock
the stock buy-back would cost about $512 million at current prices. henley jumped $1.75 a share to close at $25.625 a share in over-the-counter trading
henley is an amalgam of 35 construction, environmental, energy, chemcial, manufacturing and finance businesses spun off in april 1986 by allied-signal inc., which itself was formed by a $5 billion merger in 1985
henley has gained a reputation for tightening operations to boost profits in individual units and then taking those units public. the current market value of henley's investments in its subsidiaries that have publicly traded shares and its other long-term investment securities is $2 billion
in recent months henley has been involved in a so-far unsuccessful bid for santa fe southern pacific corp., the chicago-based railroad, land and natural resources giant
under the restructuring, which was approved in principle by the company's board on wednesday, henley's assets would be divided between two public companies:
_wheelabrator group inc., which already is publicly traded, would take over henley's stake in its successful wheelabrator technologies inc. subsidiary and other assets related to the refuse-to-energy business
wheelabrator group would have the flexibility and resources to speed up the expansion of its businesses through mergers, acquisitions and joint ventures
_a newly created entity, to be called henley group inc., would own signal capital corp., signal landmark holdings inc., henley manufacturing corp. and henley's stake in fisher scientific group inc., plus other assets
this program will enable our shareholders to participate directly in henley's $650 million investment in wheelabrator technologies, the nation's leading refuse-to-energy business,'' said michael dingman, henley's chairman and chief executive
shares of the new entity that will be created for henley's other holdings will be distributed to stockholders as a partially taxable special dividend, the company said
henley's board also authorized the repurchase of 20 million of the company's 90 million outstanding shares. the number of outstanding shares peaked at 129 million in november 1986 before the company initiated a series of stock buy-backs
after the buy-back is completed, henley will have repurchased nearly 43 percent of its stock
separately, henley said it decided to waive protection under a recently enacted delaware statute providing that a holder of 15 percent of a company's stock is prohibited from merging with the company or undertaking certain other actions for three years
we do not believe it is in the best interests of shareholders to impose these restrictions,'' dingman said. ``we prefer to give investors a free hand to make those decisions.''
henley's top management owns about 6.5 million of the company's shares. that stake would rise to 9.3 percent with the completion of the stock repurchase
henley spokesman norman ritter said management wasn't considering a bid to take the company private
henley also said it intends to raise $1 billion by issuing notes, then using the proceeds to pay off its current $980 million in bank debt. that will allow the company to arrange $2.5 billion in new bank credit, henley said
the car rental company avis suddenly reversed a five-year policy forbidding employees to wear cornrows after two black workers filed a racial discrimination complaint tuesday
in a memorandum filed with the philadelphia commission on human relations, longterm employees linda holman, 43, and wanda williams, 35, contended a ban against the small, tight braids injected ``racial considerations into the employment process.''
they argued the ban targeted blacks because the hair style was worn predominantly by blacks, often as an affirmation of their african heritage
just hours after the memorandum was filed by the american civil liberties union, the avis headquarters in garden city, n.y., notified the philadelphia branch the ban had been lifted
i am delighted that avis is in fact trying harder,'' aclu attorney stephan presser said. ``the ... office tells me i am to inform my clients that they are free to wear their cornrows proudly to work tomorrow. this is the fastest victory i ever had in my life. i'm just delighted. my clients won.''
john britton, a spokesman for avis rent a car systems inc., said the company was in the process of ``formalizing'' new standards allowing cornrows before the employees' filed their complaint. the new grooming guidelines will appear in a brochure that will be issued to avis' 1,400 national branches in may, he said
cornrows were banned in a written circular in 1983 along with ``extreme'' bouffant hairdos and unkempt layered cuts
but things are modified, hairstyles are modified and attitudes are modified,'' britton said. ``in the '60s, we used to require women behind the counter to wear girdles, and we had rules governing hair length and facial hair. all those things have changed over time.''
when the ban was implemented, cornrows were not predominantly considered a sign of black pride, he said
my first awareness of cornrows was with a (white) movie actress, bo derek,'' he said
avis reversed its position as part of an effort to respect cultural differences, he said
according to presser, ms. holman and ms. williams were warned that they would be fired when they began wearing cornrows in july. the rental agents wore wigs over the cornrows ``until they literally became a headache'' and then gave up the hairstyle, he said
their memorandum charged that the ban on cornrows violated city, state and federal job discrimination laws. had the philadelphia commission on human relations concurred, the agency could have taken avis to court, presser said
presser said he will wait a few weeks to see how the women fare before withdrawing the charges
the federal energy regulatory commission decided wednesday that 71 applications to construct new natural gas pipelines serving the northeast really amount to 31 projects, and the staff has warned two that they are in danger of rejection already
the analysis was necessary because a single project may require more than one request to the commission to proceed. if a new pipeline would use a segment of an existing line in the middle, it might mean three applications _ one for the middle and one for each end
the commission attracted the applications during an ``open season'' ending in january for new pipeline applications to serve new england, new york, pennsylvania and new jersey, where demand for gas is rising
as is its custom, the commission declined to release immediately the text of what it had voted on, but staff lawyer susan court told reporters afterward the commission wanted public comment on its analysis and how to proceed, and would request market data from the applicants and schedule technical conferences in the next step
chairman martha hesse told her four fellow commissioners she would propose a schedule in the next few days
without the text of what the commission voted, it was impossible to tell which companies fell in what class. but the commission was told in a staff briefing that of the 31 projects, 20 appear to be competitive, requiring hearings comparing one proposal against another
court said later it was not clear yet whether all 20 would be in one hearing, or whether separate competitions were involved and the hearings could be held in groups, perhaps according to the market that would be served
seven projects have no competition and can proceed on their own, and backers of four were sent ``deficiency letters,'' warning that their applications were inadequate
two of those letters went to anr corp., whose erie subsidiary has one project, and to panhandle eastern pipeline co., whose indiana-ohio subsidiary has another
the two companies were among three applying for permission under an optional procedure whereby the applicant assumes the economic risk of building the line and is forbidden from spreading those costs among other other lines and customers if its expectations don't pan out
the commission, however, has limited such applications to pipelines promising to transport gas for anybody _ and has denied such applications from ``open access'' companies it judged mere extensions of a ``closed'' company
that is the case with anr and panhandle, court said. streamlining</head>
chrysler corp. will try to meet its foreign competition by trimming executive-suite jobs and stepping up teamwork on the plant floor, a chrysler vice president said tuesday
by year's end, the no. 3 automaker will begin cutting its eight-level organizational chart to a six-tier plan similar to japanese auto company structures, said anthony st. john, vice president of human resources and chrysler's chief labor negotiator
the company also plans a new dispute-resolution system for management employees in addition to opening early negotiations with the united auto workers union on a contract for some 60,000 union employees
contract talks could begin as early as the third week in april, st. john said. the uaw agreed last week to chrysler's request for early negotiations on a contract to replace a three-year contract expiring sept. 14
st. john said chrysler needs to find ways to inspire employee commitment and loyalty while keeping the company's employment costs at competitive levels
the outcome may well be determined by our ability to provide meaningful assurances of employee security,'' st. john said at a labor-management seminar at oakland university's ken morris labor studies center
chrysler's request for an early start of talks was part of an effort to return to a teamwork labor-management approach, he said. talks normally begin in mid-july
tension already is running high in response to chrysler's decision to close down operations in kenosha, wis., and its plan, since reversed in the face of bitter uaw opposition, to sell its acustar inc. parts subsidiary
our goal is to reach a strike-free settlement,'' st. john said. ``it is going to then put the adversarial action behind us.''
chrysler already has begun talks with the uaw on a contract covering 800 employees who will continue engine assembly work at kenosha and a closing agreement to cover 5,500 employees losing their jobs in assembly and stamping operations at the former american motors corp. factory
in addition to the contract talks, st. john said, the company will be attempting to negotiate additional modern operating agreements such as those set up in six of its plants since 1985
the agreements involve a teamwork concept, also found in japanese auto plants, involving workers in decisions, cutting the number of supervisors by about 30 percent, and eliminating artificial barriers such as separate management dining rooms and parking
it puts into practice the simple but long neglected truth that people exist from their shoulders up as well as from their shoulders down,'' st. john said
the 1985 contract established a six-member joint activities board with three members each from the company and union. the board has organized training to bring employees up to date in areas such as computers, new technology, robotics
training programs will be stepped up, along with such modern operating agreement features such as higher pay for workers mastering additional skills
roughly 25 percent of our hourly work force is illiterate,'' st. john said
st. john did not say how many jobs would be involved in the upper-level cuts, but said most are expected to be accomplished through retirements and other normal departures
stronger industrial production and a rebound in housing construction were reported by the government wednesday, but the financial markets had mixed reactions in advance of a more potent statistic, the trade deficit
the federal reserve said industrial production edged up 0.2 percent in february despite output reductions at auto factories and coal mines. economists said the gain, although slower than the january level, represented good news for the economy and further dampened concerns about a severe slowdown
the commerce department said the housing industry, after staggering for two months following the october stock crash, enjoyed a sharp 8.9 percent increase in construction activity in february, the biggest gain in more than a year
the department said the increase pushed construction of single-family homes and apartments up to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.49 million units last month following declines of 15.8 percent in december and 1.9 percent in january
those setbacks, coupled with three consecutive monthly declines in new home sales, had raised concerns because housing is often the first industry to weaken at the onset of a recession. economists feared that home buyers had grown wary following the record collapse of the stock market in october
but the february upturn in construction starts was seen as an encouraging sign that while housing activity will be slower this year, it will not weaken so much that it threatens overall economic growth
housing is on the rebound,'' said warren lasko, executive vice president of the mortgage bankers association. ``with interest rates at low levels and the economy growing and no recession in sight, we think we have all the ingredients in place to generate a strong spring building season.''
nevertheless, the news hurt the bond market, a barometer of interest rates and the economy. since stronger growth implies future inflation, which erodes the value of fixed-income investments, bond prices tumbled
the treasury's key 30-year issue fell $10 per $1,000 in face amount. its yield, which moves inversely to price, jumped from 8.51 percent to 8.60 percent, its highest level since late january
on the other hand, the stock market closed largely higher. the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks, which sat for most of the day with a modest loss, ended with a 16.91 point gain at 2,064.32, though trading was slow
analysts said the markets remained preoccupied with what the commerce department would report thursday on the january trade deficit. that monthly statistic has become one of the most important influences because of its implications for american monetary and trade policy
the deficit declined in november and december, suggesting that the dollar's depreciation over the past two years has made american products more competitive. three straight monthly declines would provide further confirmation of that trend and lessen pressure for more devaluation of the u.s. currency
conversely, if the deficit significantly widened in january, the dollar likely would fall, raising fears of inflation and foreign flight from u.s. investments. 6,000, sted in addition to; also moving on general news wires</note>
the u.s. labor department agreed tuesday to let some north and south carolina school districts continue to use 17-year-old bus drivers through the end of the school year
the agreement supersedes a labor department order that had required both states to end the use of 17-year-old school bus drivers by april 1
the department had told the two states it was ending an exemption allowing the 17-year-old drivers because the states had violated the terms of the exemption, primarily by using drivers who had moving violations
officials in both states had protested that some districts had been unable to find qualified replacements, and that abruptly replacing experienced 17-year-olds with new drivers could create safety problems
under the agreement announced by labor secretary ann mclaughlin, school districts that have had the most problems finding new drivers can use 17-year-old drivers through june 15, and all districts may use drivers who will turn 18 before that time
all 17-year-old drivers must have been hired and trained before the school year began and must have clean driving records, the agreement said
south carolina gov. carroll campbell called the compromise a ``fair agreement.''
this agreement was essential to provide the safest possible situation for our children for the remainder of the school year, as well as prevent major disruptions in the 12 districts unable to find qualified adults,'' campbell said
the state of south carolina will not seek another extension,'' campbell said. ``we will have an all-adult force in place by the beginning of the next school year.''
campbell and state education superintendent charlie williams said they support state budget proposals that would raise minimum bus driver pay from $3.47 to $4.75 an hour and fund some fringe benefits
north carolina gov. jim martin said he would seek a $24 million budget amendment during the june session of the general assembly to increase drivers' pay to enable the state to attract and hire additional adult drivers. the state has 2,085 drivers under age 18, officials said
during our discussions with secretary mclaughlin, i think it became apparent that our school children would be a lot safer riding with 17-year-olds with seven or eight months of bus driving experience than it would be to have them riding with drivers who have little or no experience driving a school bus,'' martin said
williams said the agreement leaves south carolina with about 350 adult positions to fill by next year. after beginning the year with 2,250 17-year-old drivers, the state now has 808 17-year-olds among its 6,000 drivers, deputy superintendent of education carl garris said
the 17-year-olds have been permitted to drive in the two states under an exemption to the fair labor standards act. but that was repealed after labor department investigations during january and february found north carolina had violated the act 80 times, and south carolina had recorded 200 violations during the two-month period
the investigation was triggered when a 4-year-old boy in west columbia was struck and killed by a 17-year-old bus driver with a bad driving record. pickup</note>
a federal judge wednesday blocked a moved by an italian tire maker to stop an ohio law from hampering its attempted takeover of firestone tire &amp; rubber co
u.s. district judge alice m. batchelder ruled that the ohio control share acquisition act does not violate federal law by discriminating against interstate commerce, or causing inconsistent state regulation
the statute requires a corporate raider to wait up to 50 days for shareholders to vote before purchasing tendered shares. federal law requires that any tender offer remain open for no less than 20 business days
pirelli societe generale sa of italy made a tender offer of $58 a share last week for firestone, which has its corporate offices in chicago and its north american tire headquarters in akron
the $1.9 billion offer is contingent on firestone dropping its plans to enter into a joint tire venture with bridgestone corp. of japan
firestone officials said pirelli's offer killed earlier plans to sell most of the firestone tire-making business to bridgestone, but the firestone board met monday and decided to explore other options. firestone said it is again talking with bridgestone, adding that the talks concern ``what course of action bridgestone may now wish to pursue.''
the u.s. tire maker said it would advise shareholders by friday on the pirelli offer
firestone attorney patrick f. mccarton opposed pirelli's attempt to win a preliminary injunction during a court hearing monday, saying ``control is one of the most valuable assets a shareholder can possess. it is a collective asset and should be (given up) in a collective manner.''
dennis orr, an attorney representing pirelli-owned veere inc. of delaware, argued the law is a burden on interstate commerce and could hurt shareholders by giving firestone time to defeat pirelli's tender offer
ms. batchelder said it is possible for companies to comply with both ohio and federal law
the ohio act ... by allowing the shareholders collectively to evaluate the fairness of the tender offer and to vote as a group, ... furthers the policy of investor protection,'' ms. batchelder wrote, in a 14-page opinion
the ohio statute does not discriminate against interstate commerce or cause inconsistent state regulation because it has the same effects on raiders from inside and outside of ohio, she said. picks up 5th graf, shearson's equity...</note>
koppers co. said wednesday it was studying a cash payout to shareholders, asset sales or a recapitalization plan to battle a takeover attempt by a british investor and a new york investment bank
koppers did not disclose the options it was studying, but investor brian beazer, who has joined with shearson lehman hutton inc. in making the $45 a share, or $1.3 billion, takeover offer, criticized the company's disclosure
beazer said that if koppers decided to undertake a recapitalization, the case the company essentially was bidding for itself. as such, koppers was obligated to give beazer's group access to the same confidential corporate information koppers would use to formulate such a plan
you now have a duty to provide us with a `level playing field,' to meet with us, and to furnish us with the same information you would provide to potential lenders or investors in any recapitalization or asset sale program that koppers is considering,'' beazer said in a public letter issued wednesday
in addition to disclosing possible alternatives to thwart beazer, koppers likely will launch a publicity campaign criticizing shearson, according to one securities analyst
i would expect the first thing you'll see ... will be some newspaper advertising that'll peel the hide off shearson,'' said donald a. pattison of cyrus j. lawrence inc. of new york
pattison said shearson is vulnerable to criticism for owning 46 percent of bns inc., the company formed with beazer to attempt the takeover of the pittsburgh building materials and chemical company
shearson's equity participation is a more aggressive variation of investment bankers' traditional role as adviser and financier in hostile takeovers
koppers alleged in a federal lawsuit filed march 11 that shearson violated disclosure requirements of securities laws and that it offered to sell koppers its services defending the company against hostile takeovers after laying plans with beazer to raid the company
pittsburgh filed suit in federal court wednesday alleging that shearson, as underwriter of city bonds, violated its duty not to do anything to hurt the pittsburgh economy, said david welty, spokesman for mayor richard caliguiri
under beazer's plan to sell koppers' chemical business, about 1,100 jobs could disappear in pittsburgh, city officials contend
caliguiri also ordered city department heads to exclude shearson from consideration as an underwriter of future financing, welty said
a koppers spokesman said the board set no timetable for settling details of any recapitalization offer
the question is what's it worth'' to shareholders, said securities analyst gregory drahuschak of butcher &amp; singer of pittsburgh. ``until that happens you wait around
pattison said he expects koppers to defeat the tender offer through the lawsuit and an offer to common shareholders of cash and securities worth up to $60
i don't see a third party out there that would be a competitor to beazer,'' said drahuschak. ``i tried to find one and couldn't even scare up a good rumor.''
pattison, however, said aggregates, the crushed stone used in roadbeds and mixed with cement to make concrete, are tightly controlled in britain, enhancing interest in u.s. producers like koppers. the weak u.s. dollar and accounting rule differences in britain and the united states might also attract other bidders for koppers
koppers' board believes that the company remaining independent would, over the long term, be a superior alternative to accepting the bns offer,'' which is inadequate, the company said
koppers common stock jumped $2.75 a share tuesday to $54.50 on the new york stock exchange, apparently in anticipation of wednesday's deadline for the company to respond to the tender offer. the announcement sent the stock down 87{ cents to $53.62{ wednesday in heavy trading
koppers chairman charles r. pullin said management will explore the possible sale of an equity interest in all or part of the construction materials and services business or portions of the business and the proceeds used to sweeten the payments to common shareholders
beazer has said it probably would sell koppers' chemicals business if it gained control
the bns offer of $107 for each preferred share is adequate, koppers said, while declining to advise holders whether to tender their stock
koppers said it is being advised by the first boston corp
